{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Nepal}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal\n| map1            = Nepal COVID-19 outbreak map (17 April 2020).svg<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in Nepal (as of 17 April) {{legend|#d40000|Confirmed cases reported}}<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Nepal\n| first_case      = [[Kathmandu District | Kathmandu]], [[Bagmati Pradesh]]\n| arrival_date    = 5 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 31<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| recovery_cases  = 4<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| active_cases    = 27<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| deaths          = 0<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| territories     = {{ublist|[[Baglung District|Baglung]], [[Chitwan District|Chitwan]], [[Kathmandu District|Kathmandu]], [[Kailali District|Kailali]], [[Kanchanpur District|Kanchanpur]], [[Parsa District|Parsa]], [[Rautahat District|Rautahat]], [[Udayapur District|Udayapur]]}}\n<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| website         = {{url|covid19.mohp.gov.np|Corona Info}} ([[Ministry of Health and Population (Nepal)|MOHP]]; Nepali)<br/>{{url|covid19.ndrrma.gov.np|COVID-19 dashboard}} ([[Ministry of Home Affairs (Nepal)|MOHA]]; English)\n}}\n\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], in [[Nepal]] was reported on 24 January 2020 in [[Kathmandu]]. The patient showed mild symptoms and had been discharged a week earlier with instructions to self-quarantine at home; he was subsequently confirmed to have completely recovered. Between January and March, Nepal took steps to prevent a widespread outbreak of the disease, while preparing for it by procuring essential supplies, equipment and medicine, upgrading health infrastructure, training medical personnel, and spreading public awareness. The second case was confirmed on 23 March 2020 in Kathmandu. {{as of|2020|04|17}}, 28 additional cases have been confirmed, one each in Rautahat and Kanchanpur, two each in Baglung and Chitwan, three each in Parsa and Kathmandu, four in Kailali and 12 in Udayapur district.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> 13 of the cases involved people who had recently returned from abroad, and 15 of them were Indian nationals residing in Nepal; the first case of local transmission was confirmed on 4 April in a 34-year-old woman from Kailali.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> A second complete recovery was confirmed on 18 April, bringing the number of active cases to 28. As of the 19th April, 4 patients in total have recovered.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> A country-wide lockdown came into effect on 24 March, and is scheduled to end on 27 April.<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n\nNepal established health-desks at the international airport as well as on border checkpoints with India, starting in mid-January. Land borders with India as well as China were later completely sealed off, and all international flights suspended. All academic examinations were cancelled, and schools and colleges were closed. Quarantine centres and temporary hospitals are being setup across the country. Laboratory facilities are being upgraded and expanded. Hospitals have been setting up [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] units and [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] beds. The [[SAARC]] countries have pledged to cooperate in controlling the disease in the region. India, the United States and Germany have increased their support to Nepali health sector.\n\nNepal cancelled its international promotional activities related to ''Visit Nepal Year 2020''. Its economy is expected to be severely affected by the pandemic due its impact on foreign employment, tourism, manufacturing, construction and trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/govt-to-carry-out-impact-assessment-of-coronavirus-on-economy/|title=Govt to carry out impact assessment of coronavirus on economy|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131059/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/govt-to-carry-out-impact-assessment-of-coronavirus-on-economy/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Wikipedia-VideoWiki-Coronavirus disease 2019.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:02|upright=1.4|left|Video summary ([[Wikipedia:VideoWiki/Coronavirus disease 2019|script]]) on the coronavirus disease.]]\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nThe ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) is caused by <!--NO DEFINITE ARTICLE (\"THE\") AS PER VIRUS'S ARTICLE--> [[SARS-COV-2|severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130202553/https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The outbreak was first identified in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei, China]], in December 2019 and recognised as a pandemic by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=11 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311212521/https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> {{as of|{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}|post=,}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic cases|more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|conround|editlink=|ref=no}} cases]]{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} of COVID-19 have been reported in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|{{Territories affected by the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}} countries and territories]],<ref name=\"WOM\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) |work=Worldometer |date=2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195657/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |archive-date=29 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> resulting in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic deaths/WHO situation reports|more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|dround|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths]]. More than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recround|editlink=|ref=no}} people have recovered,{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} although there may be a possibility of reinfection.<ref name=\"SLT-202004112\">{{cite news |last=Politi |first=Daniel |title=WHO Investigating Reports of Coronavirus Patients Testing Positive Again After Recovery |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/who-reports-coronavirus-testing-positive-recovery.html |date=11 April 2020 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"NPR-20200327\">{{cite news |last=Feng |first=Emily |title=Mystery In Wuhan: Recovered Coronavirus Patients Test Negative ... Then Positive |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/27/822407626/mystery-in-wuhan-recovered-coronavirus-patients-test-negative-then-positive |date=27 March 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 }}</ref> <section end=\"intro-cases\"/>The [[case fatality rate]] was estimated to be 4{{nbsp}}percent in China,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Estimating case fatality rates of COVID-19|first1=Piotr|last1=Spychalski|first2=Agata|last2=B\u0142a\u017cy\u0144ska-Spychalska|first3=Jarek|last3=Kobiela|date=10 March 2020|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|doi=10.1016/s1473-3099(20)30246-2|pmid = 32243815}}</ref> but varies significantly between countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cebm.net/covid-19/global-covid-19-case-fatality-rates/|title=Global Covid-19 Case Fatality Rates|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=[[Centre for Evidence-Based Medicine]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCommon symptoms include [[fever]], [[cough]] and [[shortness of breath]].<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/symptoms.html |title=Symptoms of Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |date=10 February 2020 |work=CDC.gov |publisher=US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]) |access-date=11 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130202038/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/symptoms.html |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Complications may include [[pneumonia]] and [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]].<ref name=\"WxJWu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/clinical-guidance-management-patients.html|title=Interim Clinical Guidance for Management of Patients with Confirmed Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19)|last=|first=|date=4 April 2020|website=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The [[incubation period|time from exposure to onset of symptoms]] is typically around five days, but may range from two to fourteen days.<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|author-last1=Velavan |author-first1=T. P. |author-last2=Meyer |author-first2=C. G. |title=The COVID-19 epidemic |journal=Tropical Medicine & International Health |volume=n/a |issue=n/a |pages=278\u201380 |doi=10.1111/tmi.13383 |doi-access=free |pmid=32052514 |date=March 2020}}</ref> There is [[COVID-19 vaccine|no known vaccine]] or [[COVID-19 drug development|specific]] [[Antiviral drug|antiviral treatment]].<ref name=\"WHO2020QA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses |title=Q&A on coronaviruses |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |work=WHO.int |date=11 February 2020 |access-date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120174649/https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses |archive-date=20 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><!--Quote=To date, there is no vaccine and no specific antiviral medicine to prevent or treat COVID-2019--> Primary treatment is [[Symptomatic treatment|symptomatic]] and [[supportive therapy]].<ref name=\"APVG0\">{{cite web |title=Caring for Yourself at Home |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/if-you-are-sick/caring-for-yourself-at-home.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n<!--Quote=People with COVID-19 should receive supportive care to help relieve symptoms. For severe cases, treatment should include care to support vital organ functions.-->\n\nRecommended [[Preventive healthcare|preventive measures]] include [[hand washing]], covering one's mouth when coughing, [[physical distancing|maintaining distance from other people]], and monitoring and [[self-isolation]] for people who suspect they are infected.<ref name=\"WHO2020QA\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://covid19.govt.nz/|title=Unite against COVID-19|last=|first=|date=|website=Unite against COVID-19|publisher=[[Government of New Zealand]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Authorities worldwide have [[National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|responded]] by implementing [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]], quarantines, curfews, [[Workplace hazard controls for COVID-19|workplace hazard controls]], and [[List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|facility closures]].\n\nThe pandemic has led to [[Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|severe global socioeconomic disruption]],<ref name=\"NYT-20200229\">{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Here Comes the Coronavirus Pandemic: Now, after many fire drills, the world may be facing a real fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/opinion/sunday/corona-virus-usa.html |date=29 February 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020 |department=Editorial}}</ref> [[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the postponement or cancellation of sporting, religious, political and cultural events]],<ref name=\"NYTcancellations\">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/cancelled-events-coronavirus.html|title=A List of What's Been Canceled Because of the Coronavirus|date=1 April 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and widespread shortages of supplies exacerbated by [[panic buying]].<ref name=\"W7Y6Y\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/18/supply-chain-experts-foods-that-could-be-less-available-in-pandemic.html |title=Why there will soon be tons of toilet paper, and what food may be scarce, according to supply chain experts |last=Scipioni |first=Jade |date=18 March 2020 |publisher=CNBC|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"c5kOh\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cfr.org/in-brief/coronavirus-disrupt-us-drug-supply-shortages-fda |title=The Coronavirus Outbreak Could Disrupt the U.S. Drug Supply |website=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education|Schools, universities and colleges have closed]] either on a nationwide or local basis in {{Education statistics on the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|total}} countries, affecting approximately {{Education statistics on the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|percentage}} <!--This information seems wrong compared to the source, but it is actually not. The UNESCO source states the amount of learners affected by nationwide closures, not the amount affected by both nationwide and local. Hover over the graph and you can see the number of total closures. By using cross multiplication, the correct answer is achieved. (1.576/91.3 is equal to 1.716/x)-->percent of the world's student population.<ref name=\"UNESCO2020\">{{cite web |url=https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |title=COVID-19 Educational Disruption and Response |date=4 March 2020 |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Misinformation about the virus]] has spread online.<ref name=\"EZGH5\">{{cite news|last1=Perper|first1=Rosie|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-death-toll-global-gdp-loss-australian-national-university-study-2020-3|title=As the coronavirus spreads, one study predicts that even the best-case scenario is 15 million dead and a $2.4 trillion hit to global GDP|date=5 March 2020|work=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"r7xem\">{{cite web |last=Clamp |first=Rachel |title=Coronavirus and the Black Death: spread of misinformation and xenophobia shows we haven't learned from our past |work=[[The Conversation]] |date=5 March 2020 |url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-and-the-black-death-spread-of-misinformation-and-xenophobia-shows-we-havent-learned-from-our-past-132802 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Due to reduced travel and closures of heavy industry, there [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the environment|has been a decrease]] in [[air pollution]] and [[carbon emissions]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Watts |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/23/coronavirus-pandemic-leading-to-huge-drop-in-air-pollution |title=Coronavirus pandemic leading to huge drop in air pollution |date=23 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=8 April 2020 |last2=Kommenda |first2=Niko  |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter |title=Analysis: Coronavirus temporarily reduced China's CO2 emissions by a quarter |date=19 February 2020 |website=Carbon Brief |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\n[[File:20200326 - United Nations in Nepal - CORONA PSA.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:24|Awareness video on prevention of COVID-19 from the United Nations (in [[Nepali language|Nepali]])]]\nNepal is a landlocked country with China in the northern side and India in the east, west and south. Nepal shares a {{convert|1414|km|mi}} border with China's autonomous region of Tibet, in the Himalayas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85919/|title=Nepal-China Rasuwagadhi border point to be sealed for 15 days from Wednesday|last=DEVKOTA|first=HIMNATH|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060457/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85919/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> China is Nepal's second-largest trading partner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2015/09/09/nepal-has-trade-surplus-with-32-countries|title=Nepal has trade surplus with 32 countries|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060500/https://kathmandupost.com/money/2015/09/09/nepal-has-trade-surplus-with-32-countries|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal has an 1,800-km open border with India in the east, west and south. Nepal lies in South Asia, one of the least developed and most densely populated world regions, that performs poorly in education as well as health care and sanitation metrics, and is therefore considered one of the highest risk areas for the pandemic, and also one of the least prepared.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ranks-111th-in-health-security-index/|title=Nepal ranks 111th in health security index|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092931/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ranks-111th-in-health-security-index/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/28/south-asia-prepared-wuhan-virus-china-nepal-india-health/|title=Is South Asia Prepared for the Wuhan Virus?|last=Salam|first=Ravi Agrawal, Kathryn|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328083944/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/28/south-asia-prepared-wuhan-virus-china-nepal-india-health/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=tht116>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-vulnerable-to-new-china-virus-warn-doctors/|title=Nepal vulnerable to new China virus, warn doctors|date=2020-01-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131119/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-vulnerable-to-new-china-virus-warn-doctors/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21150529/italy-coronavirus-south-korea|title=How to travel during the international coronavirus outbreak|last=Belluz|first=Julia|date=2020-02-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229002300/https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21150529/italy-coronavirus-south-korea|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ill-prepared-for-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Nepal ill-prepared for coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-02-26|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115126/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ill-prepared-for-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'', before the pandemic, hospitals in Nepal had few ICU beds (just three in Teku Hospital) which were almost always occupied, with people in critical condition usually having to wait for the beds to become empty. It reported doctors as saying that it would be next to impossible to admit new patients to ICU as soon as they need them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/12/nepal-s-hospitals-have-no-icus-to-treat-coronavirus-patients-doctors-say|title=Nepal's hospitals have no ICUs to treat coronavirus patients, doctors say|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314082423/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/12/nepal-s-hospitals-have-no-icus-to-treat-coronavirus-patients-doctors-say|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Teku Hospital, the only one designated for handling infectious disease, had built an isolation ward during the [[avian influenza]] outbreak a decade ago, but had never brought it into use, as it did not have experts to evaluate or maintain the required standards.<ref name=two/>\n\nAs news of a new infectious disease in China broke, concerns were raised in Nepal over the high potential risk, the need to implement preventive measures and a severe lack of necessary medical equipment and infrastructure. According to Baburam Marasini, former director of [[Epidemiology and Disease Control Division]], Nepal does not have any double cab ambulances to transport highly infectious patients safely, isolation wards in hospitals, or biosafety level-3 or better laboratories needed to test for highly infectious diseases.<ref name=tht116/>\n\n==Epidemiological overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|Confirmed COVID-19 cases in Nepal by district}}\n! rowspan=2; |District\n! rowspan=2; |Cases\n! colspan=2; |Recovered\n! colspan=2; |Deaths\n! colspan=2; |Active cases\n|-\n! #\n! %\n! #\n! %\n! #\n! %\n|-\n!Baglung\n|'''2'''\n|1\n|50%\n|0\n|0%\n|1\n|50%\n|-\n!Chitwan\n|'''2'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|2\n|100%\n|-\n!Kailali\n|'''4'''\n|1\n|25%\n|0\n|0%\n|3\n|75%\n|-\n!Kathmandu\n|'''5'''\n|2\n|40%\n|0\n|0%\n|3\n|60%\n|-\n!Kanchanpur\n| '''1'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|1\n|100%\n|-\n!Parsa\n| '''3'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|3\n|100%\n|-\n!Rautahat\n| '''1'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|1\n|100%\n|-\n!Udaypur\n|'''13'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|13\n|100%\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''31'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''4'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''12.90%'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0%'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''27'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''87.10%'''\n|}<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\nAs of 17 April 2020, Nepal has confirmed 30 cases of COVID-19 disease, 13 of them in persons who had recently returned from abroad, and 15 in Indian nationals residing in Nepal.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> The first case was confirmed on 24 January in a 32-year-old man who had recently returned from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=India Times |first1=The Economic Times |title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms |accessdate=Jan 24, 2020 |publisher=The Economic Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309215130/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The patient had shown mild symptoms, and was completely cured by the end of January.<ref name=paper/> The second case was confirmed on 23 March in a 19-year-old woman who had recently returned from France via Qatar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323070621/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She is being treated in Teku hospital, Kathmandu. Her family has been put in quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/23/15849466024353731.html|title=Second confirmed case of covid-19 in Nepal|url-status=live|language=ne|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323082104/https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/23/15849466024353731.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The third case was confirmed on 25 March, in a person who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=25 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325071210/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth case, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed on 27 March, in a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the Middle East. He is being treated in Seti Provincial Hospital in [[Dhangadhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fourth-covid-19-positive-case-confirmed-by-health-ministry/|title=Fourth case of Covid-19 in Nepal|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327134451/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fourth-covid-19-positive-case-confirmed-by-health-ministry/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The fifth case was confirmed in Baglung on 28 March, in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from Belgium via Qatar. She had shared a flight from Doha to Kathmandu with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth case of covid-19 cofirmed in Nepal|last=|first=|date=28 March 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328111230/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The sixth case was confirmed on 2 April in a woman from Baglung.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|title=One more person tests positive for Covid-19, Nepal's sixth confirmed case|date=2020-04-02|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Three new cases were confirmed on 4 April, two of them were men who had recently returned from India and one was a 34-year woman, a relative of one of the previously confirmed patients. She was also the first instance of local transmission within Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/nepal-confirms-3-new-coronavirus-cases/articleshow/74981586.cms|title=Nepal confirms 3 new coronavirus cases - Times of India|last=Apr 4|first=PTI {{!}}|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12|last3=Ist|first3=15:48}}</ref> On 11 April, three more cases were confirmed, in Indian nationals who had been stranded in [[Birgunj]] of Parsa District.<ref name=tkpthree/> On 13 April, a 65-year-old woman from Kailali and a 19-year-old man from Rautahat tested positive.<ref name=rnd14/> On 14 April, two new cases were confirmed in a family from Kathmandu which had returned from the United Kingdom four weeks prior. On 17 April, 14 new cases were confirmed, 12 of them, Indian nationals from Delhi, quarantined in Udaypur, and two, Nepalis from Chitwan who had recently returned from abroad, taking the total number of cases to 30.<!--GETS OUTDATED--><ref name=mr16>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/92625/|title=COVID-19 cases jump to 16 in Nepal as two more patients tested positive|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> On 18 April, a second complete recovery was confirmed in Kathmandu, bringing the total number of active cases to 28.<ref name=18apr>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/second-person-infected-with-covid-19-returns-home-after-recovery/|title=Second person infected with COVID-19 returns home after recovery|date=2020-04-18|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n\nSukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital is the designated primary hospital for the treatment of COVID-19; isolation wards, makeshift hospitals and quarantine centres have been established throughout the country. [[Nepal Public Health Laboratory]] in Kathmandu was the only laboratory capable of testing for the disease {{as of|lc=y|2020|03|15}}; laboratory capabilities were later expanded to other major cities.\n\n===Nepalis abroad===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|COVID-19 cases in Nepalis abroad}}\n! Country/Territory\n! Cases\n! Deaths\n|-\n!Australia\n|9\n|0\n|-\n!Bahrain\n|3\n|0\n|-\n!Germany\n|4\n|0\n|-\n!Hong Kong\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Japan\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Kuwait\n|5\n|0\n|-\n!Malaysia\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Myanmar\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Portugal\n|8\n|0\n|-\n!Saudi Arabia\n|4\n|0\n|-\n!Spain\n|18\n|0\n|-\n!United Arab Emirates\n|10\n|1\n|-\n!United Kingdom\n|100\n|8\n|-\n!United States\n|500\n|5\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''665'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''14'''\n|}\n\nAccording to data compiled by the [[Non Resident Nepali Association|Non-Resident Nepali Association (NRNA)]], published on 13 April by ''[[The Himalayan Times]]'', 14 Nepalis abroad have died from the disease\u2014eight in the United Kingdom, five in the United States and one in the United Arab Emirates. At least 662 Nepalis abroad have tested positive\u2014500 of them in the United States, 100 in the United Kingdom, 18 in Spain, 10 in the United Arab Emirates, nine in Australia, eight in Portugal, five in Kuwait, four each in Germany and Saudi Arabia, and one each in Hong Kong, Japan, Malaysia and Myanmar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-claims-14-nepalis-abroad/|title=Virus claims 14 Nepalis abroad|date=2020-04-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Three Nepalis have been independently reported to have tested positive in Bahrain, two of them on 21 March and one on 22 March; three more were put into 14-day quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-nepalis-contract-covid-19/|title=Three nepalis contract covid-19|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151951/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-nepalis-contract-covid-19/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===January===\nA 31-year-old student of [[Wuhan University of Technology|Wuhan University]] who had returned home on 5 January,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms|title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309215130/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> was admitted with mild symptoms on 13 January and discharged on 17 January with instructions to self-quarantine at home after preliminary tests showed he may not be infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-test-on-china-returnee-shows-negative-result.html|title=Coronavirus test on China returnee shows negative result \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060455/https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-test-on-china-returnee-shows-negative-result.html|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Although Nepal had the laboratories and the skilled manpower to test for the disease, Nepal did not have the [[reagent]]s required. The reagents cost around [[Nepalese rupee|Rs]] 17,000 per test and need to be bought in bulk, sufficient for about 200 tests. As there were no other suspected cases needing testing, the officials decided to send the samples to [[Hong Kong]] instead of buying the reagents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/corona-virus-infection-suspected-in-capital/|title=Corona virus infection suspected in capital|date=2020-01-18|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200118145317/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/corona-virus-infection-suspected-in-capital/|archive-date=18 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The samples were sent to Hong Kong on 21 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/blood-throat-swab-sent-to-hk-for-diagnosis-2/|title=Blood, throat swab sent to HK for diagnosis|date=2020-01-22|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060504/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/blood-throat-swab-sent-to-hk-for-diagnosis-2/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 January, the [[Health ministry (Nepal)|Health ministry]] confirmed that the test had come back positive. The ministry said the patient was under surveillance, those who came into close contact with him were being investigated, and health information on all passengers returning from China was being sought.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|title=Nepal confirms first case of new coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205163702/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|archive-date=5 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' quoted officials at the Epidemiology and Disease Control Division as saying that no one knew of the patient's activity since he was discharged and that they were looking for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/24/officials-confirm-novel-coronavirus-in-nepali-man-who-returned-from-wuhan-earlier-this-month|title=Officials confirm coronavirus in Nepali man who returned from Wuhan|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313045742/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/24/officials-confirm-novel-coronavirus-in-nepali-man-who-returned-from-wuhan-earlier-this-month|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, they said that they had only spoken to the patient on phone; he had reported being in good health and was not asked to come in for check-up or monitoring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060518/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The patient was confirmed completely treated when [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|RT-PCR]] throat swabs returned negative for [[COVID-19]] in followup assessments of 29 and 31 January.<ref name=paper>{{Cite journal|last=Bastola|first=Anup|last2=Sah|first2=Ranjit|last3=Rodriguez-Morales|first3=Alfonso J.|last4=Lal|first4=Bibek Kumar|last5=Jha|first5=Runa|last6=Ojha|first6=Hemant Chanda|last7=Shrestha|first7=Bikesh|last8=Chu|first8=Daniel K. W.|last9=Poon|first9=Leo L. M.|last10=Costello|first10=Anthony|last11=Morita|first11=Kouichi|date=2020-03-01|title=The first 2019 novel coronavirus case in Nepal|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(20)30067-0/abstract|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=20|issue=3|pages=279\u2013280|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(20)30067-0|issn=1473-3099|pmid=32057299|pmc=7130048}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|title=Nepali man suspected to have been infected with the new strain of coronavirus discharged|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128151035/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> None of the people known to have come in contact with the patient showed any symptoms after three weeks of the patient's return to Nepal, and it was therefore presumed that he had not transmitted the disease to anyone else in Nepal.<ref name=two/>\n\nOn 17 January, urged by the WHO, Nepal began screening passengers arriving in [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] from China, Thailand and Japan, the three countries with multiple confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/sri-lankan-president-thanks-pm-modi-for-saarc-conference-promises-colombos-support-to-combat-covid-1920200316075726/|title=Sri Lankan President thanks PM Modi for SAARC conference; promises Colombo's support to combat COVID-19|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060456/https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/sri-lankan-president-thanks-pm-modi-for-saarc-conference-promises-colombos-support-to-combat-covid-1920200316075726/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Eight persons manned the health desk. The airport did not have infrared scanners and was therefore using thermal scanners as preparations were being made to install the infrared ones. The passengers who showed fever were being asked to remain in contact and contact the hospitals if they showed additional symptoms.<ref name=thermal>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-has-no-boundaries-says-minister-of-health-and-population-bhanubhakta-dhakal/|title=Coronavirus has no boundaries, says Health Minister Dhakal|date=2020-01-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060558/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-has-no-boundaries-says-minister-of-health-and-population-bhanubhakta-dhakal/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, Dr. Bashudev Pandey, director of Teku Hospital, was quoted as saying that the hospital was on high alert, while three other hospitals \u2013 Nepal Police Hospital, [[Patan Hospital]] and [[Tribhuvan University Teaching Hospital]] \u2013 would also treat the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85487/|title=Nepal is untouched by coronavirus so far, say govt authorities|last=Hyolmo|first=Kunga|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060459/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85487/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Six beds in Teku Hospital had been allocated for isolation of suspected patients.<ref name=thermal/>\n\nOn 25 January, a day after the first case was confirmed, the Health Ministry informed that two other suspected patients were in [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] at Teku Hospital.<ref name=two>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|title=Two more coronavirus cases suspected but government agencies are woefully prepared to combat its spread|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201130018/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The hospital discharged them in the morning of 27 January without waiting for test results even though the results were due later that same day, raising concerns over its handling of the crisis. The tests which confirmed a negative result for both patients were conducted at the bio-safety level-2 labs of the National Public Health Laboratory, the first such tests to be performed in Nepal. Reagents sufficient for 100 tests were borrowed from the Centre for Molecular Dynamics and test kits were provided by the World Health Organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060518/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A woman was in isolation awaiting test results as of 27 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/testing-for-coronavirus-starts-in-nepal/|title=Testing for coronavirus starts in Nepal|date=2020-01-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060546/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/testing-for-coronavirus-starts-in-nepal/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, Nepal closed down the [[Rasuwagadhi]] border with China, bringing Nepal-China trade to a complete halt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-hits-nepal-china-trade/|title=Coronavirus hits Nepal-China trade|date=2020-02-03|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060651/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-hits-nepal-china-trade/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Bordering districts of India were reported to be in high alert, and medical personnel had been deployed to various entry points along the Indo-Nepal border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/indo-nepal-border-put-on-high-alert-due-to-corona-virus/videoshow/73683956.cms|title=Indo-Nepal border put on high alert due to corona virus {{!}} News - Times of India Videos|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131210/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/indo-nepal-border-put-on-high-alert-due-to-corona-virus/videoshow/73683956.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February===\nBy the first week of February, Nepal reported a shortage of face masks, as people hurried to buy them following reports of the first confirmed case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/03/nepalis-rush-to-buy-face-masks-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-but-there-are-none-available|title=Nepalis rush to buy face masks amidst coronavirus outbreak but there are none available|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131213/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/03/nepalis-rush-to-buy-face-masks-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-but-there-are-none-available|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Districts bordering India began setting up health desks at border crossings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86597/|title='Corona health desk' set up in Mahottari|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092645/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86597/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86513/|title=Corona virus prevention health desk set up at Jamunaha|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092647/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86513/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Epidemiology and Disease Control Division reported that it had devised its own treatment protocol based on the one developed by UN Health Agency and directed all private hospitals to strictly follow the guidelines in handling any suspected new cases.<ref name=two/> By 1 February, Teku Hospital had handled five suspected cases all of whom tested negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/five-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative|title=Five coronavirus suspects test negative|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092646/https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/five-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 4 February, the Minister for Health informed that three hospitals had been made capable of testing for the virus, and 43 beds had been made available for patients of the possible outbreak. He also informed that health desks had been setup in Pokhara, Chitwan and Bhairahawa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86669/|title=Coronavirus not yet seen in Nepal, government preparing for high alertness|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060457/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86669/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 February, Nepal donated 100,000 protective masks to China as a gesture of friendship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-crisis-nepal-donates-100000-masks-to-china.html|title=Coronavirus crisis: Nepal donates 100,000 masks to China \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060456/https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-crisis-nepal-donates-100000-masks-to-china.html|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA village in [[Sindhupalchok District]] reported hundreds of cases with fever, cough and difficulty breathing, starting on 10 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/government-allays-fear-of-coronavirus-in-sindhupalchowk/|title=Govt allays fear of coronavirus in Sindhupalchowk|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092841/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/government-allays-fear-of-coronavirus-in-sindhupalchowk/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 February, the district ruled out the possibility that it could be COVID-19 based on travel history of people in the village.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/87396/|title=Coronavirus infection ruled out in Sindhupalchowk|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092651/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/87396/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/gumba-village-not-affected-by-coronavirus|title=Gumba village not affected by coronavirus|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092644/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/gumba-village-not-affected-by-coronavirus|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Laboratory testing later confirmed that the outbreak was influenza but not COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sindhupalchowk-patients-suffer-from-influenza-test-negative-for-covid-19/|title=Sindhupalchowk patients suffer from influenza, test negative for COVID-19|date=2020-02-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092653/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sindhupalchowk-patients-suffer-from-influenza-test-negative-for-covid-19/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 13 February, Nepal had conducted tests on 19 suspected patients. A [[Saudi Arabia]]n national who only spoke Arabic and appeared to object to being kept in the hospital, fled from isolation, and could not be located. The health ministry said it would start using police to guard suspected patients at the hospital.<ref name=fled>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|title=Coronavirus suspect goes missing|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215183546/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, the government was reported to have devised contingency plans to tackle the virus. Under Plan A, the government was preparing to evacuate Nepali citizens stranded in Hubei and keep them in isolation in Bhaktapur. Plan B included educating the people and distributing protective kits. The details of Plan C which would be implemented in case the disease actually spread and started killing people were not shared.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|title=Three coronavirus suspects test negative|date=2020-02-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311200934/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNepal evacuated 175, mostly students, who had been stranded across Hubei,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/17/nasal-throat-swabs-collected-from-nepalis-evacuated-from-china-s-wuhan-tests-to-be-conducted-today|title=Nasal, throat swabs collected from Nepalis evacuated from China's Wuhan; tests to be conducted today|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131236/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/17/nasal-throat-swabs-collected-from-nepalis-evacuated-from-china-s-wuhan-tests-to-be-conducted-today|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on 16 February 2020, using a Nepal Airlines chartered aeroplane<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/na-plane-carrying-175-nepalis-enroute-to-ktm-from-wuhan/|title=NA plane carrying 175 Nepalis enroute to Ktm from Wuhan|date=2020-02-15|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092653/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/na-plane-carrying-175-nepalis-enroute-to-ktm-from-wuhan/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and placed them in a 14-day quarantine at Kharipati in [[Bhaktapur]]. Six other Nepalis were prevented from leaving by the Chinese government, while four of the applicants who had requested rescue later changed their minds. Although 180 Nepalis had applied for immediate evacuation from China by 2 February; the effort took almost two weeks, as the government struggled to meet WHO's evacuation standards, and find a suitable venue for quarantine. The government was criticised for its slow response; a [[Public interest litigation]] was filed at the Supreme Court demanding immediate action,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/pil-filed-against-govt-demanding-nepalis-in-china-be-brought-home/|title=PIL filed against govt demanding Nepalis in China be brought home|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092716/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/pil-filed-against-govt-demanding-nepalis-in-china-be-brought-home/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while the locals around the designated quarantine site in Bhaktapur protested the government's decision which the viewed as endangering to the local community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepalis-in-china-make-frantic-pleas-to-return-home/|title=Nepalis in China make frantic pleas to return home|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092924/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepalis-in-china-make-frantic-pleas-to-return-home/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/immediately-evacuate-nepalis-from-china-national-human-rights-commission/|title=Immediately evacuate Nepalis from China: NHRC|date=2020-02-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092725/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/immediately-evacuate-nepalis-from-china-national-human-rights-commission/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/mps-flay-laxity-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-china/|title=MPs flay laxity to evacuate Nepalis from China|date=2020-02-05|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092913/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/mps-flay-laxity-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-china/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-likely-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-chinas-hubei-on-saturday/|title=Govt likely to evacuate Nepalis from China's Hubei on Saturday|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092654/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-likely-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-chinas-hubei-on-saturday/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 February, the Health Ministry reported that all of the evacuees had tested negative.<ref name=evac>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88095/|title=Initial tests show Wuhan evacuees free of coronavirus|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88049/|title=175 Nepali nationals evacuated from China tested negative for coronavirus, says MoHP|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115119/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88049/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February, the Chinese Embassy in Nepal criticised ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' for republishing a ''[[The Korea Herald|Korea Herald]]'' piece critical of China's handling of the pandemic, accusing editor-in-chief Anup Kaphle of anti-China bias. In response, 17 editors from Nepalese mainstream press released a joint statement expressing concern about the singling out of the editor, and reminding the Chinese Embassy of diplomatic norms and constitutionally guaranteed freedom of the Press in Nepal; ''The Kathmandu Post'' published an editorial criticising the Embassy's actions. The Chinese embassy's actions were seen as uncharacteristic and surprising as China is known for non-interference in Nepal's internal matters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3051648/nepalese-newspaper-accuses-china-veiled-threats-against-editor|title=Nepalese newspaper accuses China of 'veiled threats against editor'|date=2020-02-20|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225094250/https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3051648/nepalese-newspaper-accuses-china-veiled-threats-against-editor|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/nepal-media-feels-chinas-wrath-in-coronavirus-fallout/|title=Nepal media feels China's wrath in coronavirus fallout|last=Dixit|first=Kunda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134400/https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/nepal-media-feels-chinas-wrath-in-coronavirus-fallout/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/china-cannot-dictate-terms-to-a-free-media-in-nepal-can-pm-oli-resist-analysis/story-F4KTSO7XH5dqcrObjPYtsN.html|title=China cannot dictate terms to a free media in Nepal. Can PM Oli resist?{{!}} Analysis|date=2020-02-26|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115120/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/china-cannot-dictate-terms-to-a-free-media-in-nepal-can-pm-oli-resist-analysis/story-F4KTSO7XH5dqcrObjPYtsN.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of February, the health desk at Tribhuvan International Airport was screening passengers from China, South Korea, Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Japan and Saudi Arabia, but did not have sufficient manpower and equipment to screen all new arrivals. A total of six infrared scanners had been setup; the only thermal scanner had yet to be repaired, but plans were underway to purchase three more.<ref name=thtscan>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/samples-collected-for-second-time-from-quarantined-nepalis/|title=Samples collected for second time from quarantined Nepalis|date=2020-03-01|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115118/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/samples-collected-for-second-time-from-quarantined-nepalis/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Passengers were not being asked to fill locator forms that would make it possible to track them down later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/01/as-un-health-agency-raises-covid-19-outbreak-risk-to-the-highest-level-nepal-scrambles-go-step-up-measures|title=As UN health agency raises Covid-19 outbreak risk to the highest level, Nepal scrambles to step up measures|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131255/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/01/as-un-health-agency-raises-covid-19-outbreak-risk-to-the-highest-level-nepal-scrambles-go-step-up-measures|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also reported that the government was seeking help from the UN having failed to procure masks and protective gear due to global shortages.<ref name=tkp227/> On 29 February, the government formed a high level committee to prevent and control the spread of COVID-19 under the leadership of Deputy Prime Minister [[Ishwor Pokhrel]].<ref name=thtscan/> The government also decided to suspend promotional activities for Visit Nepal 2020.<ref name=mr31>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89188/|title=Govt urges one and all to avoid public gathering to prevent outbreak of coronavirus|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115121/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89188/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal suspended labour migration to South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/07/as-covid-19-spreads-to-malaysia-and-the-persian-gulf-countries-uncertainty-looms-over-nepal-s-labour-migration|title=As Covid-19 spreads to Malaysia and the Persian Gulf countries, uncertainty looms over Nepal's labour migration|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323124826/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/07/as-covid-19-spreads-to-malaysia-and-the-persian-gulf-countries-uncertainty-looms-over-nepal-s-labour-migration|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> India started screening passengers from Nepal and making masks compulsory for all visiting Nepalis.<ref name=tkp227>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/27/as-covid-19-spreads-public-health-officials-consider-plans-for-a-worst-case-scenario|title=As Covid-19 spreads, public health officials consider plans for a worst-case scenario|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115118/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/27/as-covid-19-spreads-public-health-officials-consider-plans-for-a-worst-case-scenario|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also screening Nepalis travelling into India by land, at various checkpoints at the border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88395/|title=India to start screening all air passengers from KTM starting from Monday|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115122/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88395/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n'''1 March:''' Nepal announced suspension of [[Visa on arrival|visa-on-arrival]] service for nationals of five countries badly affected by COVID-19 \u2013 China, South Korea, Japan,Italy and Iran \u2013 to be enforced from 7 to 30 March.{{efn|The implementation date was later reported to be 10 March.<ref name=tkp33/>}}<ref name=\"Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival\">{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival for nationals of countries badly affected by COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/02/c_138836161.htm |website=Xinhua |accessdate=2020-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303171539/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/02/c_138836161.htm |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89193/|title=Nepal announces temporary suspension of visa on arrival from March 7 to prevent coronavirus outbreak|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115118/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89193/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=tkp32>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/02/all-175-nepalis-evacuated-from-hubei-province-test-negative-for-covid-19|title=All 175 Nepalis evacuated from Hubei Province test negative for Covid-19|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115121/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/02/all-175-nepalis-evacuated-from-hubei-province-test-negative-for-covid-19|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It also urged the general public to avoid large gatherings.<ref name=mr31/> The passengers and crew involved in the evacuation of Nepalis from Hubei were released from quarantine after all tests again came back negative following a two-week quarantine.<ref name=tkp32/>\n\n'''2 March:''' The Supreme Court issued an interim order to suspend flights to and from countries affected by the disease, in response to a public interest litigation. The government issued a travel advisory against non-essential travel to countries hardest hit by the disease, including China, Iran, South Korea, Japan and Italy.<ref name=tkp33>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/03/aviation-authority-urges-government-to-implement-stringent-travel-restrictions|title=Aviation authority urges government to implement stringent travel restrictions|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324153558/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/03/aviation-authority-urges-government-to-implement-stringent-travel-restrictions|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The visitors coming from or via these countries would be required to submit a health certificate. Health checkpoints were to be established at all major entry points from India and third country citizens would be allowed to cross from select border check-points only. The [[Sagarmatha Sambaad|Sagarmatha Sambad]] programme scheduled for April was also postponed.<ref name=tkp33/>\n\n'''4\u20135 March:''' Due to a severe shortage of face-masks and protective gear as well as increase in price following a ban on export in China and India, some hospitals were reported to be sewing plain clothes masks as a precaution.<ref name=tkp34>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/04/hospitals-urge-ministry-to-arrange-for-face-masks-gloves-and-other-protective-gear|title=Hospitals urge ministry to arrange for face masks, gloves and other protective gear|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115122/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/04/hospitals-urge-ministry-to-arrange-for-face-masks-gloves-and-other-protective-gear|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A shortage of hand sanitisers was also reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/04/hand-sanitisers-in-short-supply-due-to-buying-rush-sparked-by-outbreak-fears|title=Hand sanitisers in short supply due to buying rush sparked by outbreak fears|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131320/https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/04/hand-sanitisers-in-short-supply-due-to-buying-rush-sparked-by-outbreak-fears|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Everest Premier League]], the domestic T20 cricket tournament was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fallout-everest-premier-league-postponed|title=COVID-19 fallout: Everest Premier League postponed|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323163819/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fallout-everest-premier-league-postponed|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''8 March:''' Qatar imposed a temporary ban on arrivals from Nepal and other countries, affecting almost 40,000 labour migrants with valid work permits who were yet to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/09/qatar-places-temporary-ban-on-entry-of-people-from-14-countries-including-nepal|title=Thousands of Nepali workers affected as Qatar imposes temporary entry ban amidst Covid-19 outbreak|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131326/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/09/qatar-places-temporary-ban-on-entry-of-people-from-14-countries-including-nepal|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal Airlines and Himalaya Airlines suspended their flights to Doha indefinitely following the ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|title=NAC and Himalaya Airlines suspend flights to Doha|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131329/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''9 March:''' The government expanded the suspension of visa-on-arrival service to include three additional countries \u2014 France, Germany and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89928/|title=Nepal temporarily suspends on-arrival visa for nationals of France, Germany and Spain|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131330/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89928/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''10 March:''' Seventy one Chinese workers employed in the construction of Pokhara Airport who had returned from China after undergoing a 14-day quarantine were put into quarantine for another 14 days. They were being closely monitored and everyone was reported to be in normal health. Previously, 36 Chinese workers working for the project had also gone through a similar quarantine upon return to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/71-chinese-workers-in-pokhara-quarantined/|title=71 Chinese workers in Pokhara quarantined|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311124017/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/71-chinese-workers-in-pokhara-quarantined/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''12\u201315 March:''' Nepal decided to suspend on-arrival tourist visa for all countries, with an exception to diplomatic and official visas, to last from 14 March till 30 April. The government closed land border entry points for third country nationals, and cancelled all mountain climbing expeditions including on [[Mount Everest]], to be enforced from 14 March to 30 April. It also declared two-week mandatory self- and home-quarantines for everyone visiting Nepal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends on arrival tourist visa, closes land routes and cancels mountain climbing expeditions |url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/12/nepal-government-puts-all-tourist-visas-on-hold-and-cancels-all-spring-climbing-expeditions |website=Kathmandu Post |accessdate=2020-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315233926/https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/12/nepal-government-puts-all-tourist-visas-on-hold-and-cancels-all-spring-climbing-expeditions |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-announces-sweeping-travel-restrictions/|title=Govt announces sweeping travel restrictions|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151649/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-announces-sweeping-travel-restrictions/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Labour permits for all countries were suspended indefinitely, including to workers who were only back home on holiday. The government also suspended issuance of no objection letters to students going for abroad study until 30 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/on-arrival-visas-scrapped-till-april-30/|title=On-arrival visas scrapped till April 30|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151700/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/on-arrival-visas-scrapped-till-april-30/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Province No. 1]] government unveiled plans for two quarantine sites in the province, including one on a [[Koshi River]] island. It also assured plans were underway to provide additional equipment to health personnel, to set up health desks on border-crossings with India, to keep ambulances in standby and to maintain isolation wards in three major hospitals \u2013 [[B.P. Koirala Memorial Cancer Hospital|BP Koirala Institute Of Health Science]] in [[Dharan]], Koshi Hospital in [[Biratnagar]] and Mechi Hospital in [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-quarantine-centres-to-be-established-in-province-1/|title=Two quarantine centres to be established in Province 1|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060503/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-quarantine-centres-to-be-established-in-province-1/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/28-isolation-wards-prepared-in-province-1/|title=28 isolation wards prepared in Province 1|date=2020-03-05|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060506/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/28-isolation-wards-prepared-in-province-1/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> BP Koirala Institute of Health sciences in Dharan reported that a suspected patient had refused to remain in hospital and returned home. He had promised to return the following day for testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/14/man-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-refuses-to-stay-in-isolation-ward-and-returns-home|title=Man suspected of having coronavirus refuses to stay in isolation ward and returns home|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060457/https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/14/man-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-refuses-to-stay-in-isolation-ward-and-returns-home|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, Bihar transport department suspended Patna-Nepal bus services with immediate effect, to be enforced until 31 March, in an effort to contain the virus, after many cases emerged throughout India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/15/operation-of-patna-nepal-buses-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-2116837.html|title=Operation of Patna-Nepal buses postponed due to coronavirus outbreak|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316131254/https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/15/operation-of-patna-nepal-buses-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-2116837.html|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> India declared a suspension of all passenger movement through Indo-Nepal border, except a few designated checkpoints \u2013 Banbasa, Raxaul, Ranigunj and Sunauli<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90832/|title=Govt mulls complete closure of border with India|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191649/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90832/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \u2013 with intensified health inspections, effective from 15 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/coronavirus-passenger-movements-through-pak-bdesh-nepal-bhutan-myanmar-border-points-suspended-55426|title=Coronavirus: Passenger movements through Pak, B'desh, Nepal, Bhutan, Myanmar border points suspended|last=Tribune News Service|website=Tribuneindia News Service|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060458/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/coronavirus-passenger-movements-through-pak-bdesh-nepal-bhutan-myanmar-border-points-suspended-55426|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The land-border checkpoints with China began releasing imported goods following quarantine procedures as cases in China began to drop.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/containers-stalled-at-rasuwagadi-start-entering-nepal/|title=Containers stalled at Rasuwagadi start entering Nepal|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151627/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/containers-stalled-at-rasuwagadi-start-entering-nepal/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi proposed starting the COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC region; he also said India could share a Disease Surveillance Software with SAARC partners, and hinted at the possibility of conducting coordinated research on controlling epidemic diseases in the SAARC region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90492/|title=Indian PM Modi proposes COVID-19 Emergency Fund to combat coronavirus in South Asia|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151617/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90492/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''17 March:''' A meeting of the high-level coordination committee for prevention and control of COVID-19 decided to add 115 ICU and 1,000 isolation beds in the Kathmandu Valley. It also instructed the provincial governments to setup a total of 120 ICU beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90596/|title=Govt to set up 235 ICU beds amid coronavirus fears|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130313/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90596/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''18\u201319 March:''' The government declared suspension of all classes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90755/|title=Govt takes sweeping measures to contain spread of COVID-19|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182558/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90755/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and postponement of all academic examinations including the [[Secondary Education Examination (Nepal)|Secondary Education Examination]] until 12 April, the end of the Month of [[Chaitra]], the last month of Nepali calendar year when all schools hold the [[final examination]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/govt-postpones-all-examinations-till-12-april|title=Govt postpones all examinations till 12 April|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182559/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/govt-postpones-all-examinations-till-12-april|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Tribhuvan University and the Public Service Commission also postponed all their examinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90797/|title=Amid COVID-19 fears, PSC halts scheduled exams until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182602/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90797/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government banned all passengers, including Nepalis, from EU and the UK, West Asia and the Middle East as well as Malaysia, South Korea and Japan, effective from 20 March until 15 April. It also decided to shut down all cinema halls, gymnasiums,museums and cultural centres, and ban gathering of more than 25 people in any public spaces including at places of worship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/18/government-bans-entry-of-all-passengers|title=Government bans entry of all passengers, including Nepalis, from midnight March 20|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322024729/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/18/government-bans-entry-of-all-passengers|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal began to see a significant influx of people from India to Nepal as India saw increase in new cases throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/sudurpaschim-province/2020/03/18/amid-covid-19-threat-banbasa-border-sees-a-sudden-influx-of-people-returning-home-from-india|title=Amid Covid-19 threat, Banbasa border sees a sudden influx of people returning home from India|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130129/https://kathmandupost.com/sudurpaschim-province/2020/03/18/amid-covid-19-threat-banbasa-border-sees-a-sudden-influx-of-people-returning-home-from-india|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A noticeable outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley was reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/number-of-people-leaving-kathmandu-valley-increases/|title=Number of people leaving Kathmandu Valley increases|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182556/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/number-of-people-leaving-kathmandu-valley-increases/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The House of Representatives meeting was postponed until 26 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/govts-measures-to-fight-covid-19-inadequate-say-mps/|title=Govt's measures to fight COVID-19 inadequate, say MPs|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182558/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/govts-measures-to-fight-covid-19-inadequate-say-mps/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Province No. 1 government established quarantine centres throughout the province with a total capacity of 440 beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/440-bed-quarantine-centres-in-province-1/|title=440-bed quarantine centres in Province 1|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182557/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/440-bed-quarantine-centres-in-province-1/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''20 March:''' The National Assembly was suspended indefinitely.<ref name=mr319>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90872/|title=National Assembly put off until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184416/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90872/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health Ministry instructed public employees to report on weekends as well, and not leave the Kathmandu Valley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/health-ministry-bars-employees-from-leaving-kathmandu-valley|title=Health ministry bars employees from leaving Kathmandu valley|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182559/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/health-ministry-bars-employees-from-leaving-kathmandu-valley|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All weekly newspapers published from the Kathmandu Valley ceased their print editions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90891/|title=COVID-19 fear: Weekly newspapers from Kathmandu cease their print version|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182605/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90891/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The US government pledged $1.8&nbsp;million to Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/us-government-pledges-1-8-million/|title=US government pledges $1.8&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182649/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/us-government-pledges-1-8-million/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Prime Minister Oli addressed the nation for the first time since the start of the pandemic and announced a list of preventative measures. All international flights would be stopped from 22 March to 31 March and vehicular movement on long routes would be closed from 23 March. All government services and private offices except those providing essential services would be closed until 3 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southasia-idUSKBN217117|title=Sri Lanka imposes curfew as South Asia steps up coronavirus battle|date=2020-03-20|agency=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325122959/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southasia-idUSKBN217117|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u0947\u0936\u092d\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092f\u093e\u0924\u093e\u092f\u093e\u0924 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926, \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940\u092f \u0938\u0940\u092e\u093e \u0928\u093e\u0915\u093e \u0916\u0941\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e !036 |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846036 |website=Onlinekhabar |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=ne |trans-title=Indian border crossing open, traffic closed within country |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321030805/https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846036 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A notice from Nepal Tourism Board announced the suspension of issuance of trekking permits for tourists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends issuance of trekking permits for foreign trekkers |url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2020-03/20/content_75840039.htm |website=China.org.cn |accessdate=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321031001/http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2020-03/20/content_75840039.htm |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley intensified; almost 300,000 people had left in the preceding three days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/people-leaving-kathmandu-on-the-rise-photo-feature|title=People leaving Kathmandu on the rise (Photo Feature)|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182603/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/people-leaving-kathmandu-on-the-rise-photo-feature|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health Ministry decided to halt non-urgent health check-ups and surgeries until 12 April in hospitals in the Kathmandu Valley with 50 or more beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/big-hospitals-to-stop-non-urgent-health-check-up-surgeries|title=Big hospitals to stop non-urgent health check-up, surgeries|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182600/https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/big-hospitals-to-stop-non-urgent-health-check-up-surgeries|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A full bench meeting of the Supreme Court presided over by the Chief Justice decided to halt all non-urgent proceedings in courts across the country until 4 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/supreme-court-to-halt-non-urgent-proceedings/|title=Supreme Court to halt non-urgent proceedings|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/supreme-court-to-halt-non-urgent-proceedings/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90877/|title=Courts across the country to be closed for two weeks|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182555/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90877/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal government pledged Rs 100 Million to the [[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90907/|title=Nepal to contribute Rs 100 million to SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90907/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''21 March:''' Kathmandu city launched a central help desk and a toll-free 24-hour hotline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/dial-1180-in-case-of-covid-19-suspicion-kmc/|title=Dial 1180 in case of COVID-19 suspicion: KMC|date=2020-03-22|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323165223/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/dial-1180-in-case-of-covid-19-suspicion-kmc/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Germany pledged an additional one million Euros to its existing health programmes in Nepal to help combat the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/german-aid-to-nepal/|title=German aid to Nepal|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210145/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/german-aid-to-nepal/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Around sixty passengers from COVID-19 affected countries that landed on Tribhuvan Interantional Airport were sent to quarantine at Kharipati, Bhaktapur; they had not presented any symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/63-people-sent-to-kharipati-quarantine|title=63 people sent to Kharipati Quarantine|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130222/https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/63-people-sent-to-kharipati-quarantine|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was reported that Gandaki Province had set up 111 isolation beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/111-isolation-beds-in-gandaki-province|title=111 isolation beds in Gandaki province|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210116/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/111-isolation-beds-in-gandaki-province|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Metropolitan Traffic Police Division suspended breathalyser tests as well as educational classes for drivers found breaking traffic rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/police-put-off-drink-and-drive-operation|title=Police put off 'drink and drive' operation|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210112/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/police-put-off-drink-and-drive-operation|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It also deployed 200 of its personnel to display placards with awareness messages about the disease by the roadside.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/traffic-police-generate-awareness-about-covid-19|title=Traffic police generate awareness about Covid-19|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/traffic-police-generate-awareness-about-covid-19|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nepal Police]] established coronavirus response units in all its stations and decided not to make arrests for minor offences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/21/police-set-up-coronavirus-response-unit-at-every-station|title=Police set up coronavirus response unit at every station|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210114/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/21/police-set-up-coronavirus-response-unit-at-every-station|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health Ministry informed that private hospitals with more than 100 beds would not be allowed to refer patients to other hospitals; they were required to treat suspected patients, wait for test results and provide free treatment if the disease were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/21/158475695256349344.html|title=\u0938\u092f \u092c\u0947\u0921\u092e\u093e\u0925\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0905\u0938\u094d\u092a\u0924\u093e\u0932\u0932\u0947 \u092c\u093f\u0930\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0930\u0947\u092b\u0930 \u0917\u0930\u094d\u0928 \u0928\u092a\u093e\u0909\u0928\u0947|website=ekantipur.com|language=ne|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210115/https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/21/158475695256349344.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''22 March:''' Nepal decided to close its land border with India and China for a week effective from 23 March. The government also declared a Rs 500 million fund with contributions of a month's salary from government ministers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/government-to-close-down-border-with-india-and-china-for-a-week|title=Government to close down border with India and China for a week|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130127/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/government-to-close-down-border-with-india-and-china-for-a-week|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It also increased the allowances for health workers working at the front desks of hospitals by 50\u2013100%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846585 |title=\u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0932\u093e\u0908 \u092a\u0940\u092a\u0940\u0908 \u0930 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0938\u093e\u0939\u0928 \u092d\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0926\u093f\u0928\u0947 \u0928\u093f\u0930\u094d\u0923\u092f |work=onlinekhabar.com |access-date=22 March 2020 |language=ne |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322192028/https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846585 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Kanchanpur District|Kanchanpur]] and [[Banke District]]s declared lockdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/kanchanpur-nepalgunj-under-indefinite-lockdown/|title=Kanchanpur, Nepalgunj under indefinite lockdown|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130752/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/kanchanpur-nepalgunj-under-indefinite-lockdown/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March:''' COVID-19 was confirmed in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from France on 17 March via Qatar, the first case in two months, second overall. She was admitted into isolation at Teku Hospital. Her family is said to be in quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web |title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/ |website=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323070621/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Office of the attorney General was reported to have asked the Police to release people held for minor crimes under bail or parole to reduce crowding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/opinion/editorial-inadequate-testing/|title=EDITORIAL: Inadequate testing|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151128/https://thehimalayantimes.com/opinion/editorial-inadequate-testing/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Minister of Health declared that all patients of COVID-19 would be rescued as necessary and provided free treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/govt-will-rescue-provide-free-treatment-to-infected-people-health-minister-dhakal|title=Govt will rescue, provide free treatment to infected people: Health minister Dhakal|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130130/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/govt-will-rescue-provide-free-treatment-to-infected-people-health-minister-dhakal|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kailali District]] was reported to have declared an indefinite lock-down effective from 2&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/91136/|title=Curfew clamped in Kailali to prevent COVID-19|last=RSS|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133650/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/91136/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Arghakhanchi District]] also declared an indefinite lock-down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/arghakhanchi-district-to-be-locked-down-from-midnight|title=Arghakhanchi district to be locked down from midnight|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130159/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/arghakhanchi-district-to-be-locked-down-from-midnight|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''24 March:''' The country-wide lockdown came into effect.<ref name=four/>\n\n'''25 March:''' The third case in Kathmandu was confirmed. The patient had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates and was staying in a hotel in Kathmandu. They are being treated in Teku Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325071210/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''26 March:''' Rescue of tourists stranded throughout Nepal was initiated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/more-stranded-tourists-evacuated-from-nepal/|title=More stranded tourists evacuated from Nepal|last=Times|first=Nepali|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329200539/https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/more-stranded-tourists-evacuated-from-nepal/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 28 March, hundreds of tourists had been rescued and brought to Kathmandu; many were being repatriated via chartered flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/rescue-flights-continue-on-saturday/|title=Rescue flights continue on Saturday|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329205325/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/rescue-flights-continue-on-saturday/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''27 March:''' Fourth case nationally, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed. It involved a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates. He is being treated at Seti Provincial Hospital in Dhangadhi.<ref name=four>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/27/fourth-nepali-tests-positive-for-covid-19-case|title=Fourth Nepali tests positive for Covid-19|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131517/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/27/fourth-nepali-tests-positive-for-covid-19-case|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''28 March:''' A 19-year-old woman who had recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium via Doha tested positive, bringing the total to five in the country. She had shared a flight from Doha with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March. She had since travelled to her home in Baglung; she was admitted for treatment at Dhaulagiri Zonal Hospital after the test came back positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fifth-patient-moved-freely-in-her-village-for-5-days-got-admitted-to-dhaulagiri-hospital-7-hours-after-being-confirmed|title=COVID-19 fifth patient moved freely in her village for 5 days, got admitted to Dhaulagiri hospital 7 hours after being confirmed !|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329205329/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fifth-patient-moved-freely-in-her-village-for-5-days-got-admitted-to-dhaulagiri-hospital-7-hours-after-being-confirmed|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328111230/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March:''' The government decided to extend the suspension of international flights to until 15 April. The country-wide lockdown was extended to until 8 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/29/nationwide-lockdown-extended-until-april-8-ban-on-international-flights-until-april-15|title=Nationwide lockdown extended until April 8, ban on international flights until April 15|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329205329/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/29/nationwide-lockdown-extended-until-april-8-ban-on-international-flights-until-april-15|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n'''2 April:''' A 65-year-old woman who recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium who accompanied the 19-year-old woman on 17 March tested positive bringing the total to six in the country. Health minister confirmed that she was staying at her home in Baglung. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|title=One more person tests positive for Covid-19, Nepal's sixth confirmed case|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404055356/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/02/health-ministry-confirms-sixth-covid-19-case|title=Health Ministry confirms sixth Covid-19 case|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404064438/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/02/health-ministry-confirms-sixth-covid-19-case|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''4 April:''' Three new positive cases were confirmed in the far-western region of Nepal. Among the three are a 21-year-old male of Kailali who had returned from Mumbai in India, 41-year-old male of Kanchanpur who had returned from Uttarakhand in India, and a 34-year-old female from Kailali who is known be a relative of one of the earlier infected persons. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/temp/three-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=Three new positive cases for Covid-19 in Nepal|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> This is the first local transmission in Nepal. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/covid-19-first-locally-transmitted-case-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=First person-to-person Covid-19 transmission in Nepal|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406221237/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/covid-19-first-locally-transmitted-case-confirmed-in-nepal/|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Four Nepalese died in New York <ref>{{cite web|author=\u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0916\u092c\u0930 |url=https://nepalkhabar.com/global/23816-2020-04-05-15-02-44 |title=\u0905\u092e\u0947\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0915\u094b \u0915\u094b\u0930\u094b\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0947\u0928\u094d\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u0928\u094d\u092f\u0941\u092f\u094b\u0930\u094d\u0915\u092e\u093e \u096a \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0943\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0941 |publisher=Nepalkhabar.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''11 April:''' Three Indian nationals residing in [[Parsa District]] tested positive.<ref name=tkpthree>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/04/12/three-indian-nationals-in-birgunj-test-positive-for-covid-19|title=Three Indian nationals in Birgunj test positive for Covid-19|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n'''13 April:''' A 65-year-old woman from Kailali and a 19-year-old man from Rautahat tested positive for the disease.<ref name=rnd14>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/mohp-confirms-2-more-covid-19-cases-number-reaches-14|title=MoHP confirms 2 more COVID-19 cases, number reaches 14|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n'''14 April:''' Two members of a family in Kathmandu which had returned from the United Kingdom four weeks earlier tested positive for the disease.<ref name=mr16/> The countrywide lockdown was extended until 27 April, citing an increase in the number of new cases. The border closures and suspension of international flights were extended until 1 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/04/14/lockdown-extended-by-12-more-days-until-april-27|title=Lockdown extended by 12 more days until April 27|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n'''17 April:''' 12 Indian nationals from Delhi who had been quarantined in [[Udayapur District]] of [[Province No. 1]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/friday-sees-14-new-cases-spiking-nepals-covid-19-count-to-30/ |title=Friday sees 14 new cases, spiking Nepal\u2019s Covid-19 count to 30 |date=17 April 2020 |website= |publisher= |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> Two [[United Kingdom|UK]] returnees, a mother and her son from [[Chitwan district]] in [[Bagmati Pradesh]], also tested positive on the same day, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 30.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/17/with-14-new-cases-nepal-s-covid-19-tally-doubles-in-a-single-day |title=With 14 new cases, Nepal\u2019s Covid-19 tally doubles in a single day |date=17 April 2020 |website= |publisher= |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n'''18 April:''' One more Indian National aged 65 years old tested positive today for corona virus. He was one of 16 people who was quarantined in [[Udayapur District]] where 12 people tested positive yesterday. <ref>{{cite web |url= |title= |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=}}</ref> The second coronavirus patient, hospitalised since 23 March, was confirmed completely recovered<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/nepals-second-covid-19-patient-recovered-health-ministry20200418181641/ |title=Nepal's second COVID-19 patient recovered: Health Ministry |date=18 April 2020 |website= |publisher=ANI |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and a 65 years old woman from [[Baglung District]] who tested positive on 2 April 2020 recovered today and discharged from Dhaulagiri Zonal Hospital. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://ekantipur.com/pradesh-4/2020/04/18/158721747338121993.html |title=\u092c\u093e\u0917\u094d\u0932\u0941\u0919\u0915\u0940 \u096c\u096b \u0935\u0930\u094d\u0937\u0940\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u094b\u0930\u094b\u0928\u093e\u0932\u093e\u0908 \u091c\u093f\u0924\u093f\u0928\u094d, \u0924\u0940\u0928 \u0938\u093e\u0924\u093e\u092e\u093e \u092d\u0907\u0928\u094d \u0921\u093f\u0938\u094d\u091a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091c |date=18 April 2020 |website= |publisher=Kantipur Publication |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> With this, the number of recoveries reached three and the number of active cases 28.<ref name=18apr/><!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n\n==Impact and response==\nThe tourism sector has been reported to be suffering due to the absence of Chinese tourists, as well as the various travel restrictions imposed on travel globally. Manufacturing sector is experiencing a shortage of raw materials, most of which used to come from China. The situation is exacerbated by spread of the pandemic to the Middle-east which is the main source of remittance that makes up more than half of Nepal's [[GDP]]. Remittances were expected to sharply drop after Nepal suspended issuance of workers permit to Nepalis for all countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/15/nepal-s-remittance-dependent-economy-braces-for-upheaval-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Nepal's remittance-dependent economy braces for upheaval amid Covid-19 pandemic|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329025536/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/15/nepal-s-remittance-dependent-economy-braces-for-upheaval-amid-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The wholesale and retail sector has also been affected due to fall of imports from China. The construction sector which imports most of its building materials from China has slowed down. As the Chinese contractors and workers who went home for the Chinese new year could not return, the public construction projects have also been affected.<ref name=econ>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/04/nepali-economy-starts-to-feel-the-pinch-as-coronavirus-spreads|title=Nepali economy starts to feel the pinch as coronavirus spreads|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48830-coronavirus-chills-nepal-infrastructure-construction?v=preview|title=Coronavirus Chills Nepal Infrastructure Construction|website=www.enr.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131538/https://www.enr.com/articles/48830-coronavirus-chills-nepal-infrastructure-construction?v=preview|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-outbreak-could-shave-off-nepals-economy-by-36-78-million/|title=Coronavirus outbreak could shave off Nepal's economy by $36.78&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-07|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013531/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-outbreak-could-shave-off-nepals-economy-by-36-78-million/|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The domestic airlines were reported to be struggling for survival as ticket prices dropped to half or a third of normal following a sharp decline in demand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/11/domestic-airfares-hit-rock-bottom-amidst-coronavirus-travel-advisory|title=Domestic airfares hit rock bottom amidst coronavirus travel advisory|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131541/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/11/domestic-airfares-hit-rock-bottom-amidst-coronavirus-travel-advisory|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Number of international flights to and from Nepal had decreased by more than 50% by 13 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/international-flights-drop-significantly-at-tia/|title=International flights drop significantly at TIA|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151616/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/international-flights-drop-significantly-at-tia/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal's import-dependent economy is also vulnerable to depreciation of Indian currency to which its currency is permanently pegged, as Indian economy suffers the impact of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/weakening-nepali-currency-to-hit-economy/|title=Weakening Nepali currency to hit economy|date=2020-03-12|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151617/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/weakening-nepali-currency-to-hit-economy/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 20,000 tour, trek and mountaineering guides lost their livelihood when mountaineering was suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/14/suspension-of-climbing-permits-and-on-arrival-visas-entails-losses-of-thousands-of-jobs-and-millions-of-dollars|title=Suspension of climbing permits and on-arrival visas entails losses of thousands of jobs and millions of dollars|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131548/https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/14/suspension-of-climbing-permits-and-on-arrival-visas-entails-losses-of-thousands-of-jobs-and-millions-of-dollars|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/18/experts-call-for-measures-to-ease-the-impact-of-coronavirus-on-the-economy|title=Experts call for measures to ease the impact of coronavirus on the economy|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe annual [[Holi]] celebrations, which fell on 9 and 10 March in 2020 saw decreased activities, low business and cancellation of organised celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-scare-dampens-holi-spirit-businesses-hit/|title=Coronavirus scare dampens Holi spirit, businesses hit|date=2020-03-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311153307/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-scare-dampens-holi-spirit-businesses-hit/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNepal had declared 2020 as the Visit Nepal Year and aimed to bring in two million foreign tourists, almost double the figure from previous year. As the pandemic spread and Nepal had to suspend air travel to and from China, the biggest source of international tourists arriving by air, Nepal suspended its promotional campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/01/c_138831984.htm|title=Nepal postpones int'l tourism promotion amid coronavirus outbreak - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe temporary blanket ban on animal markets imposed by China as a response to the pandemic is expected to curb wildlife poaching and trafficking through Nepal, as the Chinese traditional medicine which uses various body parts of endangered animals as its ingredients has been the biggest challenge to wildlife conservation in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|title=Coronavirus outbreak may curb wildlife trafficking|last=Awale|first=Sonia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211183345/https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|archive-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Market regulation===\nThe department of Commerce, Supplies and Consumer Protection conducted raids on 161 firms and fined 57 of them, a total of around four million Rupees in the month of [[Falgun]] (February\u2013March).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/20/government-launches-coordinated-inspections-to-curb-black-marketeering-of-essential-goods|title=Government launches coordinated inspections to curb black marketeering of essential goods|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182557/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/20/government-launches-coordinated-inspections-to-curb-black-marketeering-of-essential-goods|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It inspected multiple pharmacies and surgical shops in Kathmandu on 5 March and fined a total of Rs 430,000 for hiking prices and other offences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/05/government-cracks-down-on-price-gouging-by-pharmacies-and-surgical-shops|title=Government cracks down on price-gouging by pharmacies and surgical shops|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 10 March, four pharmacies were fined a total of Rs 800,000 after they were caught charging 1000% of normal price for surgical masks. Some groceries and LPG stores were also inspected. One million units of face masks were confiscated from a warehouse in Kathmandu and the owner arrested on 18 March, bringing the total of masks confiscated in the week past to 2.3&nbsp;million. Around 50,000 units of hand-sanitisers were also confiscated from the black market. Around two dozen black marketeers had been arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/police-seize-one-million-masks/|title=Police seize one million masks|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182722/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/police-seize-one-million-masks/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As the outflux of people from Kathmandu intensified, 23 transport entrepreneurs and workers were arrested on 20 March for overcharging the passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/23-persons-held-for-fleecing-passengers/|title=23 persons held for fleecing passengers|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/23-persons-held-for-fleecing-passengers/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Essential drugs===\nNepal's pharmaceutical industry has been impacted due to lack of raw materials as a number of essential ingredients were previously imported from Hubei.<ref name=econ/> Nepal faced the prospect of a potential shortage of essential medicines when India imposed restrictions on export of 26 types of raw materials including of essential medicine citing disruption in the supply chain from Hubei; however India later agreed to relax restrictions in case of Nepal, and asked the Nepalese government to provide a list of names and quantities of essential medicines that it needed to supply to Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|title=India seeks list of essential drugs that Nepal needs|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307141100/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation===\nOn 21 March a 20-year-old man was arrested on charges of spreading misinformation online through an unregistered [[fake news website]] and causing public fear, after audio tapes alleging cover-up of COVID-19 cases were found circulating online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/youth-arrested-for-spreading-romours-of-covid-19-cases/|title=Youth arrested for spreading romours of COVID-19 cases|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130304/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/youth-arrested-for-spreading-romours-of-covid-19-cases/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, [[Nepal Army]] dispelled rumours circulating in social media that claimed Army helicopters were being used to spray disinfectants over settlements at midnight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/army-dismisses-helicopter-spraying-disifectant-at-midnight-rumours/|title=Army dismisses 'helicopter spraying disinfectant at midnight' rumours|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130814/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/army-dismisses-helicopter-spraying-disifectant-at-midnight-rumours/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Poaching===\n[[Poachers]] in Nepal took advantage of slack monitoring and sparse public movement during the Covid-19 lockdown and the country saw a surge in killing of wildlife under the shadow of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dpa-international.com/topic/nepal-sees-surge-wildlife-poaching-due-covid-19-lockdown-urn%3Anewsml%3Adpa.com%3A20090101%3A200404-99-589875/|title=Nepal sees surge in wildlife poaching due to Covid-19 lockdown|date=2020-04-04|website=[[Deutsche Presse-Agentur|DPA International]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|state=expanded}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Nepal|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Nepal|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Nepal]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Nepal]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Nepal}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal\n| map1            = Nepal COVID-19 outbreak map (17 April 2020).svg<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in Nepal (as of 17 April) {{legend|#d40000|Confirmed cases reported}}<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Nepal\n| first_case      = [[Kathmandu District | Kathmandu]], [[Bagmati Pradesh]]\n| arrival_date    = 5 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 31<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| recovery_cases  = 4<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| active_cases    = 27<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| deaths          = 0<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| territories     = {{ublist|[[Baglung District|Baglung]], [[Chitwan District|Chitwan]], [[Kathmandu District|Kathmandu]], [[Kailali District|Kailali]], [[Kanchanpur District|Kanchanpur]], [[Parsa District|Parsa]], [[Rautahat District|Rautahat]], [[Udayapur District|Udayapur]]}}\n<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n| website         = {{url|covid19.mohp.gov.np|Corona Info}} ([[Ministry of Health and Population (Nepal)|MOHP]]; Nepali)<br/>{{url|covid19.ndrrma.gov.np|COVID-19 dashboard}} ([[Ministry of Home Affairs (Nepal)|MOHA]]; English)\n}}\n\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], in [[Nepal]] was reported on 24 January 2020 in [[Kathmandu]]. The patient showed mild symptoms and had been discharged a week earlier with instructions to self-quarantine at home; he was subsequently confirmed to have completely recovered. Between January and March, Nepal took steps to prevent a widespread outbreak of the disease, while preparing for it by procuring essential supplies, equipment and medicine, upgrading health infrastructure, training medical personnel, and spreading public awareness. The second case was confirmed on 23 March 2020 in Kathmandu. {{as of|2020|04|17}}, 28 additional cases have been confirmed, one each in Rautahat and Kanchanpur, two each in Baglung and Chitwan, three each in Parsa and Kathmandu, four in Kailali and 12 in Udayapur district.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> 13 of the cases involved people who had recently returned from abroad, and 15 of them were Indian nationals residing in Nepal; the first case of local transmission was confirmed on 4 April in a 34-year-old woman from Kailali.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> A second complete recovery was confirmed on 18 April, bringing the number of active cases to 28.As for now (19 April) 4 of them have recovered.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> A country-wide lockdown came into effect on 24 March, and is scheduled to end on 27 April.<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n\nNepal established health-desks at the international airport as well as on border checkpoints with India, starting in mid-January. Land borders with India as well as China were later completely sealed off, and all international flights suspended. All academic examinations were cancelled, and schools and colleges were closed. Quarantine centres and temporary hospitals are being setup across the country. Laboratory facilities are being upgraded and expanded. Hospitals have been setting up [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] units and [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] beds. The [[SAARC]] countries have pledged to cooperate in controlling the disease in the region. India, the United States and Germany have increased their support to Nepali health sector.\n\nNepal cancelled its international promotional activities related to ''Visit Nepal Year 2020''. Its economy is expected to be severely affected by the pandemic due its impact on foreign employment, tourism, manufacturing, construction and trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/govt-to-carry-out-impact-assessment-of-coronavirus-on-economy/|title=Govt to carry out impact assessment of coronavirus on economy|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131059/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/govt-to-carry-out-impact-assessment-of-coronavirus-on-economy/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Wikipedia-VideoWiki-Coronavirus disease 2019.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:02|upright=1.4|left|Video summary ([[Wikipedia:VideoWiki/Coronavirus disease 2019|script]]) on the coronavirus disease.]]\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nThe ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) is caused by <!--NO DEFINITE ARTICLE (\"THE\") AS PER VIRUS'S ARTICLE--> [[SARS-COV-2|severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130202553/https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The outbreak was first identified in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei, China]], in December 2019 and recognised as a pandemic by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=11 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311212521/https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> {{as of|{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}|post=,}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic cases|more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|conround|editlink=|ref=no}} cases]]{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} of COVID-19 have been reported in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|{{Territories affected by the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}} countries and territories]],<ref name=\"WOM\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) |work=Worldometer |date=2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195657/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |archive-date=29 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> resulting in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic deaths/WHO situation reports|more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|dround|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths]]. More than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recround|editlink=|ref=no}} people have recovered,{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} although there may be a possibility of reinfection.<ref name=\"SLT-202004112\">{{cite news |last=Politi |first=Daniel |title=WHO Investigating Reports of Coronavirus Patients Testing Positive Again After Recovery |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/who-reports-coronavirus-testing-positive-recovery.html |date=11 April 2020 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"NPR-20200327\">{{cite news |last=Feng |first=Emily |title=Mystery In Wuhan: Recovered Coronavirus Patients Test Negative ... Then Positive |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/27/822407626/mystery-in-wuhan-recovered-coronavirus-patients-test-negative-then-positive |date=27 March 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 }}</ref> <section end=\"intro-cases\"/>The [[case fatality rate]] was estimated to be 4{{nbsp}}percent in China,<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Estimating case fatality rates of COVID-19|first1=Piotr|last1=Spychalski|first2=Agata|last2=B\u0142a\u017cy\u0144ska-Spychalska|first3=Jarek|last3=Kobiela|date=10 March 2020|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|doi=10.1016/s1473-3099(20)30246-2|pmid = 32243815}}</ref> but varies significantly between countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cebm.net/covid-19/global-covid-19-case-fatality-rates/|title=Global Covid-19 Case Fatality Rates|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=[[Centre for Evidence-Based Medicine]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCommon symptoms include [[fever]], [[cough]] and [[shortness of breath]].<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/symptoms.html |title=Symptoms of Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |date=10 February 2020 |work=CDC.gov |publisher=US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]) |access-date=11 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130202038/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/symptoms.html |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Complications may include [[pneumonia]] and [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]].<ref name=\"WxJWu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/clinical-guidance-management-patients.html|title=Interim Clinical Guidance for Management of Patients with Confirmed Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19)|last=|first=|date=4 April 2020|website=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The [[incubation period|time from exposure to onset of symptoms]] is typically around five days, but may range from two to fourteen days.<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|author-last1=Velavan |author-first1=T. P. |author-last2=Meyer |author-first2=C. G. |title=The COVID-19 epidemic |journal=Tropical Medicine & International Health |volume=n/a |issue=n/a |pages=278\u201380 |doi=10.1111/tmi.13383 |doi-access=free |pmid=32052514 |date=March 2020}}</ref> There is [[COVID-19 vaccine|no known vaccine]] or [[COVID-19 drug development|specific]] [[Antiviral drug|antiviral treatment]].<ref name=\"WHO2020QA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses |title=Q&A on coronaviruses |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |work=WHO.int |date=11 February 2020 |access-date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120174649/https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses |archive-date=20 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><!--Quote=To date, there is no vaccine and no specific antiviral medicine to prevent or treat COVID-2019--> Primary treatment is [[Symptomatic treatment|symptomatic]] and [[supportive therapy]].<ref name=\"APVG0\">{{cite web |title=Caring for Yourself at Home |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/if-you-are-sick/caring-for-yourself-at-home.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n<!--Quote=People with COVID-19 should receive supportive care to help relieve symptoms. For severe cases, treatment should include care to support vital organ functions.-->\n\nRecommended [[Preventive healthcare|preventive measures]] include [[hand washing]], covering one's mouth when coughing, [[physical distancing|maintaining distance from other people]], and monitoring and [[self-isolation]] for people who suspect they are infected.<ref name=\"WHO2020QA\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://covid19.govt.nz/|title=Unite against COVID-19|last=|first=|date=|website=Unite against COVID-19|publisher=[[Government of New Zealand]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Authorities worldwide have [[National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|responded]] by implementing [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]], quarantines, curfews, [[Workplace hazard controls for COVID-19|workplace hazard controls]], and [[List of public venues and institutions closed during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|facility closures]].\n\nThe pandemic has led to [[Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|severe global socioeconomic disruption]],<ref name=\"NYT-20200229\">{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Here Comes the Coronavirus Pandemic: Now, after many fire drills, the world may be facing a real fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/opinion/sunday/corona-virus-usa.html |date=29 February 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020 |department=Editorial}}</ref> [[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the postponement or cancellation of sporting, religious, political and cultural events]],<ref name=\"NYTcancellations\">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/cancelled-events-coronavirus.html|title=A List of What's Been Canceled Because of the Coronavirus|date=1 April 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and widespread shortages of supplies exacerbated by [[panic buying]].<ref name=\"W7Y6Y\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/18/supply-chain-experts-foods-that-could-be-less-available-in-pandemic.html |title=Why there will soon be tons of toilet paper, and what food may be scarce, according to supply chain experts |last=Scipioni |first=Jade |date=18 March 2020 |publisher=CNBC|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"c5kOh\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cfr.org/in-brief/coronavirus-disrupt-us-drug-supply-shortages-fda |title=The Coronavirus Outbreak Could Disrupt the U.S. Drug Supply |website=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education|Schools, universities and colleges have closed]] either on a nationwide or local basis in {{Education statistics on the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|total}} countries, affecting approximately {{Education statistics on the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|percentage}} <!--This information seems wrong compared to the source, but it is actually not. The UNESCO source states the amount of learners affected by nationwide closures, not the amount affected by both nationwide and local. Hover over the graph and you can see the number of total closures. By using cross multiplication, the correct answer is achieved. (1.576/91.3 is equal to 1.716/x)-->percent of the world's student population.<ref name=\"UNESCO2020\">{{cite web |url=https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |title=COVID-19 Educational Disruption and Response |date=4 March 2020 |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Misinformation about the virus]] has spread online.<ref name=\"EZGH5\">{{cite news|last1=Perper|first1=Rosie|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-death-toll-global-gdp-loss-australian-national-university-study-2020-3|title=As the coronavirus spreads, one study predicts that even the best-case scenario is 15 million dead and a $2.4 trillion hit to global GDP|date=5 March 2020|work=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"r7xem\">{{cite web |last=Clamp |first=Rachel |title=Coronavirus and the Black Death: spread of misinformation and xenophobia shows we haven't learned from our past |work=[[The Conversation]] |date=5 March 2020 |url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-and-the-black-death-spread-of-misinformation-and-xenophobia-shows-we-havent-learned-from-our-past-132802 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Due to reduced travel and closures of heavy industry, there [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the environment|has been a decrease]] in [[air pollution]] and [[carbon emissions]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Watts |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/23/coronavirus-pandemic-leading-to-huge-drop-in-air-pollution |title=Coronavirus pandemic leading to huge drop in air pollution |date=23 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=8 April 2020 |last2=Kommenda |first2=Niko  |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter |title=Analysis: Coronavirus temporarily reduced China's CO2 emissions by a quarter |date=19 February 2020 |website=Carbon Brief |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\n[[File:20200326 - United Nations in Nepal - CORONA PSA.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:24|Awareness video on prevention of COVID-19 from the United Nations (in [[Nepali language|Nepali]])]]\nNepal is a landlocked country with China in the northern side and India in the east, west and south. Nepal shares a {{convert|1414|km|mi}} border with China's autonomous region of Tibet, in the Himalayas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85919/|title=Nepal-China Rasuwagadhi border point to be sealed for 15 days from Wednesday|last=DEVKOTA|first=HIMNATH|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060457/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85919/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> China is Nepal's second-largest trading partner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2015/09/09/nepal-has-trade-surplus-with-32-countries|title=Nepal has trade surplus with 32 countries|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060500/https://kathmandupost.com/money/2015/09/09/nepal-has-trade-surplus-with-32-countries|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal has an 1,800-km open border with India in the east, west and south. Nepal lies in South Asia, one of the least developed and most densely populated world regions, that performs poorly in education as well as health care and sanitation metrics, and is therefore considered one of the highest risk areas for the pandemic, and also one of the least prepared.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ranks-111th-in-health-security-index/|title=Nepal ranks 111th in health security index|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092931/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ranks-111th-in-health-security-index/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/28/south-asia-prepared-wuhan-virus-china-nepal-india-health/|title=Is South Asia Prepared for the Wuhan Virus?|last=Salam|first=Ravi Agrawal, Kathryn|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328083944/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/28/south-asia-prepared-wuhan-virus-china-nepal-india-health/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=tht116>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-vulnerable-to-new-china-virus-warn-doctors/|title=Nepal vulnerable to new China virus, warn doctors|date=2020-01-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131119/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-vulnerable-to-new-china-virus-warn-doctors/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21150529/italy-coronavirus-south-korea|title=How to travel during the international coronavirus outbreak|last=Belluz|first=Julia|date=2020-02-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229002300/https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21150529/italy-coronavirus-south-korea|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ill-prepared-for-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Nepal ill-prepared for coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-02-26|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115126/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ill-prepared-for-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'', before the pandemic, hospitals in Nepal had few ICU beds (just three in Teku Hospital) which were almost always occupied, with people in critical condition usually having to wait for the beds to become empty. It reported doctors as saying that it would be next to impossible to admit new patients to ICU as soon as they need them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/12/nepal-s-hospitals-have-no-icus-to-treat-coronavirus-patients-doctors-say|title=Nepal's hospitals have no ICUs to treat coronavirus patients, doctors say|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314082423/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/12/nepal-s-hospitals-have-no-icus-to-treat-coronavirus-patients-doctors-say|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Teku Hospital, the only one designated for handling infectious disease, had built an isolation ward during the [[avian influenza]] outbreak a decade ago, but had never brought it into use, as it did not have experts to evaluate or maintain the required standards.<ref name=two/>\n\nAs news of a new infectious disease in China broke, concerns were raised in Nepal over the high potential risk, the need to implement preventive measures and a severe lack of necessary medical equipment and infrastructure. According to Baburam Marasini, former director of [[Epidemiology and Disease Control Division]], Nepal does not have any double cab ambulances to transport highly infectious patients safely, isolation wards in hospitals, or biosafety level-3 or better laboratories needed to test for highly infectious diseases.<ref name=tht116/>\n\n==Epidemiological overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|Confirmed COVID-19 cases in Nepal by district}}\n! rowspan=2; |District\n! rowspan=2; |Cases\n! colspan=2; |Recovered\n! colspan=2; |Deaths\n! colspan=2; |Active cases\n|-\n! #\n! %\n! #\n! %\n! #\n! %\n|-\n!Baglung\n|'''2'''\n|1\n|50%\n|0\n|0%\n|1\n|50%\n|-\n!Chitwan\n|'''2'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|2\n|100%\n|-\n!Kailali\n|'''4'''\n|1\n|25%\n|0\n|0%\n|3\n|75%\n|-\n!Kathmandu\n|'''5'''\n|2\n|40%\n|0\n|0%\n|3\n|60%\n|-\n!Kanchanpur\n| '''1'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|1\n|100%\n|-\n!Parsa\n| '''3'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|3\n|100%\n|-\n!Rautahat\n| '''1'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|1\n|100%\n|-\n!Udaypur\n|'''13'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|13\n|100%\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''31'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''4'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''12.90%'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0%'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''27'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''87.10%'''\n|}<!--GETS OUTDATED-->\nAs of 17 April 2020, Nepal has confirmed 30 cases of COVID-19 disease, 13 of them in persons who had recently returned from abroad, and 15 in Indian nationals residing in Nepal.<!--GETS OUTDATED--> The first case was confirmed on 24 January in a 32-year-old man who had recently returned from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=India Times |first1=The Economic Times |title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms |accessdate=Jan 24, 2020 |publisher=The Economic Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309215130/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The patient had shown mild symptoms, and was completely cured by the end of January.<ref name=paper/> The second case was confirmed on 23 March in a 19-year-old woman who had recently returned from France via Qatar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323070621/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She is being treated in Teku hospital, Kathmandu. Her family has been put in quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/23/15849466024353731.html|title=Second confirmed case of covid-19 in Nepal|url-status=live|language=ne|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323082104/https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/23/15849466024353731.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The third case was confirmed on 25 March, in a person who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=25 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325071210/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth case, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed on 27 March, in a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the Middle East. He is being treated in Seti Provincial Hospital in [[Dhangadhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fourth-covid-19-positive-case-confirmed-by-health-ministry/|title=Fourth case of Covid-19 in Nepal|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327134451/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fourth-covid-19-positive-case-confirmed-by-health-ministry/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The fifth case was confirmed in Baglung on 28 March, in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from Belgium via Qatar. She had shared a flight from Doha to Kathmandu with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth case of covid-19 cofirmed in Nepal|last=|first=|date=28 March 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328111230/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The sixth case was confirmed on 2 April in a woman from Baglung.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|title=One more person tests positive for Covid-19, Nepal's sixth confirmed case|date=2020-04-02|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Three new cases were confirmed on 4 April, two of them were men who had recently returned from India and one was a 34-year woman, a relative of one of the previously confirmed patients. She was also the first instance of local transmission within Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/nepal-confirms-3-new-coronavirus-cases/articleshow/74981586.cms|title=Nepal confirms 3 new coronavirus cases - Times of India|last=Apr 4|first=PTI {{!}}|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12|last3=Ist|first3=15:48}}</ref> On 11 April, three more cases were confirmed, in Indian nationals who had been stranded in [[Birgunj]] of Parsa District.<ref name=tkpthree/> On 13 April, a 65-year-old woman from Kailali and a 19-year-old man from Rautahat tested positive.<ref name=rnd14/> On 14 April, two new cases were confirmed in a family from Kathmandu which had returned from the United Kingdom four weeks prior. On 17 April, 14 new cases were confirmed, 12 of them, Indian nationals from Delhi, quarantined in Udaypur, and two, Nepalis from Chitwan who had recently returned from abroad, taking the total number of cases to 30.<!--GETS OUTDATED--><ref name=mr16>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/92625/|title=COVID-19 cases jump to 16 in Nepal as two more patients tested positive|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> On 18 April, a second complete recovery was confirmed in Kathmandu, bringing the total number of active cases to 28.<ref name=18apr>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/second-person-infected-with-covid-19-returns-home-after-recovery/|title=Second person infected with COVID-19 returns home after recovery|date=2020-04-18|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n\nSukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital is the designated primary hospital for the treatment of COVID-19; isolation wards, makeshift hospitals and quarantine centres have been established throughout the country. [[Nepal Public Health Laboratory]] in Kathmandu was the only laboratory capable of testing for the disease {{as of|lc=y|2020|03|15}}; laboratory capabilities were later expanded to other major cities.\n\n===Nepalis abroad===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|COVID-19 cases in Nepalis abroad}}\n! Country/Territory\n! Cases\n! Deaths\n|-\n!Australia\n|9\n|0\n|-\n!Bahrain\n|3\n|0\n|-\n!Germany\n|4\n|0\n|-\n!Hong Kong\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Japan\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Kuwait\n|5\n|0\n|-\n!Malaysia\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Myanmar\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Portugal\n|8\n|0\n|-\n!Saudi Arabia\n|4\n|0\n|-\n!Spain\n|18\n|0\n|-\n!United Arab Emirates\n|10\n|1\n|-\n!United Kingdom\n|100\n|8\n|-\n!United States\n|500\n|5\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''665'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''14'''\n|}\n\nAccording to data compiled by the [[Non Resident Nepali Association|Non-Resident Nepali Association (NRNA)]], published on 13 April by ''[[The Himalayan Times]]'', 14 Nepalis abroad have died from the disease\u2014eight in the United Kingdom, five in the United States and one in the United Arab Emirates. At least 662 Nepalis abroad have tested positive\u2014500 of them in the United States, 100 in the United Kingdom, 18 in Spain, 10 in the United Arab Emirates, nine in Australia, eight in Portugal, five in Kuwait, four each in Germany and Saudi Arabia, and one each in Hong Kong, Japan, Malaysia and Myanmar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-claims-14-nepalis-abroad/|title=Virus claims 14 Nepalis abroad|date=2020-04-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Three Nepalis have been independently reported to have tested positive in Bahrain, two of them on 21 March and one on 22 March; three more were put into 14-day quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-nepalis-contract-covid-19/|title=Three nepalis contract covid-19|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151951/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-nepalis-contract-covid-19/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===January===\nA 31-year-old student of [[Wuhan University of Technology|Wuhan University]] who had returned home on 5 January,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms|title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309215130/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> was admitted with mild symptoms on 13 January and discharged on 17 January with instructions to self-quarantine at home after preliminary tests showed he may not be infected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-test-on-china-returnee-shows-negative-result.html|title=Coronavirus test on China returnee shows negative result \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060455/https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-test-on-china-returnee-shows-negative-result.html|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Although Nepal had the laboratories and the skilled manpower to test for the disease, Nepal did not have the [[reagent]]s required. The reagents cost around [[Nepalese rupee|Rs]] 17,000 per test and need to be bought in bulk, sufficient for about 200 tests. As there were no other suspected cases needing testing, the officials decided to send the samples to [[Hong Kong]] instead of buying the reagents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/corona-virus-infection-suspected-in-capital/|title=Corona virus infection suspected in capital|date=2020-01-18|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200118145317/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/corona-virus-infection-suspected-in-capital/|archive-date=18 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The samples were sent to Hong Kong on 21 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/blood-throat-swab-sent-to-hk-for-diagnosis-2/|title=Blood, throat swab sent to HK for diagnosis|date=2020-01-22|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060504/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/blood-throat-swab-sent-to-hk-for-diagnosis-2/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 January, the [[Health ministry (Nepal)|Health ministry]] confirmed that the test had come back positive. The ministry said the patient was under surveillance, those who came into close contact with him were being investigated, and health information on all passengers returning from China was being sought.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|title=Nepal confirms first case of new coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205163702/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|archive-date=5 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' quoted officials at the Epidemiology and Disease Control Division as saying that no one knew of the patient's activity since he was discharged and that they were looking for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/24/officials-confirm-novel-coronavirus-in-nepali-man-who-returned-from-wuhan-earlier-this-month|title=Officials confirm coronavirus in Nepali man who returned from Wuhan|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313045742/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/24/officials-confirm-novel-coronavirus-in-nepali-man-who-returned-from-wuhan-earlier-this-month|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, they said that they had only spoken to the patient on phone; he had reported being in good health and was not asked to come in for check-up or monitoring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060518/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The patient was confirmed completely treated when [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|RT-PCR]] throat swabs returned negative for [[COVID-19]] in followup assessments of 29 and 31 January.<ref name=paper>{{Cite journal|last=Bastola|first=Anup|last2=Sah|first2=Ranjit|last3=Rodriguez-Morales|first3=Alfonso J.|last4=Lal|first4=Bibek Kumar|last5=Jha|first5=Runa|last6=Ojha|first6=Hemant Chanda|last7=Shrestha|first7=Bikesh|last8=Chu|first8=Daniel K. W.|last9=Poon|first9=Leo L. M.|last10=Costello|first10=Anthony|last11=Morita|first11=Kouichi|date=2020-03-01|title=The first 2019 novel coronavirus case in Nepal|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(20)30067-0/abstract|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=20|issue=3|pages=279\u2013280|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(20)30067-0|issn=1473-3099|pmid=32057299|pmc=7130048}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|title=Nepali man suspected to have been infected with the new strain of coronavirus discharged|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128151035/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> None of the people known to have come in contact with the patient showed any symptoms after three weeks of the patient's return to Nepal, and it was therefore presumed that he had not transmitted the disease to anyone else in Nepal.<ref name=two/>\n\nOn 17 January, urged by the WHO, Nepal began screening passengers arriving in [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] from China, Thailand and Japan, the three countries with multiple confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/sri-lankan-president-thanks-pm-modi-for-saarc-conference-promises-colombos-support-to-combat-covid-1920200316075726/|title=Sri Lankan President thanks PM Modi for SAARC conference; promises Colombo's support to combat COVID-19|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060456/https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/sri-lankan-president-thanks-pm-modi-for-saarc-conference-promises-colombos-support-to-combat-covid-1920200316075726/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Eight persons manned the health desk. The airport did not have infrared scanners and was therefore using thermal scanners as preparations were being made to install the infrared ones. The passengers who showed fever were being asked to remain in contact and contact the hospitals if they showed additional symptoms.<ref name=thermal>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-has-no-boundaries-says-minister-of-health-and-population-bhanubhakta-dhakal/|title=Coronavirus has no boundaries, says Health Minister Dhakal|date=2020-01-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060558/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-has-no-boundaries-says-minister-of-health-and-population-bhanubhakta-dhakal/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, Dr. Bashudev Pandey, director of Teku Hospital, was quoted as saying that the hospital was on high alert, while three other hospitals \u2013 Nepal Police Hospital, [[Patan Hospital]] and [[Tribhuvan University Teaching Hospital]] \u2013 would also treat the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85487/|title=Nepal is untouched by coronavirus so far, say govt authorities|last=Hyolmo|first=Kunga|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060459/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85487/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Six beds in Teku Hospital had been allocated for isolation of suspected patients.<ref name=thermal/>\n\nOn 25 January, a day after the first case was confirmed, the Health Ministry informed that two other suspected patients were in [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] at Teku Hospital.<ref name=two>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|title=Two more coronavirus cases suspected but government agencies are woefully prepared to combat its spread|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201130018/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The hospital discharged them in the morning of 27 January without waiting for test results even though the results were due later that same day, raising concerns over its handling of the crisis. The tests which confirmed a negative result for both patients were conducted at the bio-safety level-2 labs of the National Public Health Laboratory, the first such tests to be performed in Nepal. Reagents sufficient for 100 tests were borrowed from the Centre for Molecular Dynamics and test kits were provided by the World Health Organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060518/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A woman was in isolation awaiting test results as of 27 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/testing-for-coronavirus-starts-in-nepal/|title=Testing for coronavirus starts in Nepal|date=2020-01-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060546/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/testing-for-coronavirus-starts-in-nepal/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, Nepal closed down the [[Rasuwagadhi]] border with China, bringing Nepal-China trade to a complete halt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-hits-nepal-china-trade/|title=Coronavirus hits Nepal-China trade|date=2020-02-03|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060651/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-hits-nepal-china-trade/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Bordering districts of India were reported to be in high alert, and medical personnel had been deployed to various entry points along the Indo-Nepal border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/indo-nepal-border-put-on-high-alert-due-to-corona-virus/videoshow/73683956.cms|title=Indo-Nepal border put on high alert due to corona virus {{!}} News - Times of India Videos|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131210/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/indo-nepal-border-put-on-high-alert-due-to-corona-virus/videoshow/73683956.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February===\nBy the first week of February, Nepal reported a shortage of face masks, as people hurried to buy them following reports of the first confirmed case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/03/nepalis-rush-to-buy-face-masks-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-but-there-are-none-available|title=Nepalis rush to buy face masks amidst coronavirus outbreak but there are none available|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131213/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/03/nepalis-rush-to-buy-face-masks-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-but-there-are-none-available|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Districts bordering India began setting up health desks at border crossings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86597/|title='Corona health desk' set up in Mahottari|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092645/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86597/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86513/|title=Corona virus prevention health desk set up at Jamunaha|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092647/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86513/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Epidemiology and Disease Control Division reported that it had devised its own treatment protocol based on the one developed by UN Health Agency and directed all private hospitals to strictly follow the guidelines in handling any suspected new cases.<ref name=two/> By 1 February, Teku Hospital had handled five suspected cases all of whom tested negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/five-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative|title=Five coronavirus suspects test negative|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092646/https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/five-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 4 February, the Minister for Health informed that three hospitals had been made capable of testing for the virus, and 43 beds had been made available for patients of the possible outbreak. He also informed that health desks had been setup in Pokhara, Chitwan and Bhairahawa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86669/|title=Coronavirus not yet seen in Nepal, government preparing for high alertness|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060457/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86669/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 February, Nepal donated 100,000 protective masks to China as a gesture of friendship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-crisis-nepal-donates-100000-masks-to-china.html|title=Coronavirus crisis: Nepal donates 100,000 masks to China \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060456/https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-crisis-nepal-donates-100000-masks-to-china.html|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA village in [[Sindhupalchok District]] reported hundreds of cases with fever, cough and difficulty breathing, starting on 10 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/government-allays-fear-of-coronavirus-in-sindhupalchowk/|title=Govt allays fear of coronavirus in Sindhupalchowk|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092841/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/government-allays-fear-of-coronavirus-in-sindhupalchowk/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 February, the district ruled out the possibility that it could be COVID-19 based on travel history of people in the village.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/87396/|title=Coronavirus infection ruled out in Sindhupalchowk|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092651/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/87396/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/gumba-village-not-affected-by-coronavirus|title=Gumba village not affected by coronavirus|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092644/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/gumba-village-not-affected-by-coronavirus|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Laboratory testing later confirmed that the outbreak was influenza but not COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sindhupalchowk-patients-suffer-from-influenza-test-negative-for-covid-19/|title=Sindhupalchowk patients suffer from influenza, test negative for COVID-19|date=2020-02-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092653/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sindhupalchowk-patients-suffer-from-influenza-test-negative-for-covid-19/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 13 February, Nepal had conducted tests on 19 suspected patients. A [[Saudi Arabia]]n national who only spoke Arabic and appeared to object to being kept in the hospital, fled from isolation, and could not be located. The health ministry said it would start using police to guard suspected patients at the hospital.<ref name=fled>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|title=Coronavirus suspect goes missing|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215183546/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, the government was reported to have devised contingency plans to tackle the virus. Under Plan A, the government was preparing to evacuate Nepali citizens stranded in Hubei and keep them in isolation in Bhaktapur. Plan B included educating the people and distributing protective kits. The details of Plan C which would be implemented in case the disease actually spread and started killing people were not shared.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|title=Three coronavirus suspects test negative|date=2020-02-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311200934/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNepal evacuated 175, mostly students, who had been stranded across Hubei,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/17/nasal-throat-swabs-collected-from-nepalis-evacuated-from-china-s-wuhan-tests-to-be-conducted-today|title=Nasal, throat swabs collected from Nepalis evacuated from China's Wuhan; tests to be conducted today|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131236/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/17/nasal-throat-swabs-collected-from-nepalis-evacuated-from-china-s-wuhan-tests-to-be-conducted-today|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on 16 February 2020, using a Nepal Airlines chartered aeroplane<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/na-plane-carrying-175-nepalis-enroute-to-ktm-from-wuhan/|title=NA plane carrying 175 Nepalis enroute to Ktm from Wuhan|date=2020-02-15|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092653/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/na-plane-carrying-175-nepalis-enroute-to-ktm-from-wuhan/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and placed them in a 14-day quarantine at Kharipati in [[Bhaktapur]]. Six other Nepalis were prevented from leaving by the Chinese government, while four of the applicants who had requested rescue later changed their minds. Although 180 Nepalis had applied for immediate evacuation from China by 2 February; the effort took almost two weeks, as the government struggled to meet WHO's evacuation standards, and find a suitable venue for quarantine. The government was criticised for its slow response; a [[Public interest litigation]] was filed at the Supreme Court demanding immediate action,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/pil-filed-against-govt-demanding-nepalis-in-china-be-brought-home/|title=PIL filed against govt demanding Nepalis in China be brought home|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092716/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/pil-filed-against-govt-demanding-nepalis-in-china-be-brought-home/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while the locals around the designated quarantine site in Bhaktapur protested the government's decision which the viewed as endangering to the local community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepalis-in-china-make-frantic-pleas-to-return-home/|title=Nepalis in China make frantic pleas to return home|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092924/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepalis-in-china-make-frantic-pleas-to-return-home/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/immediately-evacuate-nepalis-from-china-national-human-rights-commission/|title=Immediately evacuate Nepalis from China: NHRC|date=2020-02-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092725/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/immediately-evacuate-nepalis-from-china-national-human-rights-commission/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/mps-flay-laxity-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-china/|title=MPs flay laxity to evacuate Nepalis from China|date=2020-02-05|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092913/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/mps-flay-laxity-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-china/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-likely-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-chinas-hubei-on-saturday/|title=Govt likely to evacuate Nepalis from China's Hubei on Saturday|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324092654/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-likely-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-chinas-hubei-on-saturday/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 February, the Health Ministry reported that all of the evacuees had tested negative.<ref name=evac>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88095/|title=Initial tests show Wuhan evacuees free of coronavirus|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88049/|title=175 Nepali nationals evacuated from China tested negative for coronavirus, says MoHP|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115119/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88049/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February, the Chinese Embassy in Nepal criticised ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' for republishing a ''[[The Korea Herald|Korea Herald]]'' piece critical of China's handling of the pandemic, accusing editor-in-chief Anup Kaphle of anti-China bias. In response, 17 editors from Nepalese mainstream press released a joint statement expressing concern about the singling out of the editor, and reminding the Chinese Embassy of diplomatic norms and constitutionally guaranteed freedom of the Press in Nepal; ''The Kathmandu Post'' published an editorial criticising the Embassy's actions. The Chinese embassy's actions were seen as uncharacteristic and surprising as China is known for non-interference in Nepal's internal matters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3051648/nepalese-newspaper-accuses-china-veiled-threats-against-editor|title=Nepalese newspaper accuses China of 'veiled threats against editor'|date=2020-02-20|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225094250/https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3051648/nepalese-newspaper-accuses-china-veiled-threats-against-editor|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/nepal-media-feels-chinas-wrath-in-coronavirus-fallout/|title=Nepal media feels China's wrath in coronavirus fallout|last=Dixit|first=Kunda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134400/https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/nepal-media-feels-chinas-wrath-in-coronavirus-fallout/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/china-cannot-dictate-terms-to-a-free-media-in-nepal-can-pm-oli-resist-analysis/story-F4KTSO7XH5dqcrObjPYtsN.html|title=China cannot dictate terms to a free media in Nepal. Can PM Oli resist?{{!}} Analysis|date=2020-02-26|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115120/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/china-cannot-dictate-terms-to-a-free-media-in-nepal-can-pm-oli-resist-analysis/story-F4KTSO7XH5dqcrObjPYtsN.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of February, the health desk at Tribhuvan International Airport was screening passengers from China, South Korea, Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Japan and Saudi Arabia, but did not have sufficient manpower and equipment to screen all new arrivals. A total of six infrared scanners had been setup; the only thermal scanner had yet to be repaired, but plans were underway to purchase three more.<ref name=thtscan>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/samples-collected-for-second-time-from-quarantined-nepalis/|title=Samples collected for second time from quarantined Nepalis|date=2020-03-01|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115118/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/samples-collected-for-second-time-from-quarantined-nepalis/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Passengers were not being asked to fill locator forms that would make it possible to track them down later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/01/as-un-health-agency-raises-covid-19-outbreak-risk-to-the-highest-level-nepal-scrambles-go-step-up-measures|title=As UN health agency raises Covid-19 outbreak risk to the highest level, Nepal scrambles to step up measures|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131255/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/01/as-un-health-agency-raises-covid-19-outbreak-risk-to-the-highest-level-nepal-scrambles-go-step-up-measures|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also reported that the government was seeking help from the UN having failed to procure masks and protective gear due to global shortages.<ref name=tkp227/> On 29 February, the government formed a high level committee to prevent and control the spread of COVID-19 under the leadership of Deputy Prime Minister [[Ishwor Pokhrel]].<ref name=thtscan/> The government also decided to suspend promotional activities for Visit Nepal 2020.<ref name=mr31>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89188/|title=Govt urges one and all to avoid public gathering to prevent outbreak of coronavirus|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115121/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89188/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal suspended labour migration to South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/07/as-covid-19-spreads-to-malaysia-and-the-persian-gulf-countries-uncertainty-looms-over-nepal-s-labour-migration|title=As Covid-19 spreads to Malaysia and the Persian Gulf countries, uncertainty looms over Nepal's labour migration|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323124826/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/07/as-covid-19-spreads-to-malaysia-and-the-persian-gulf-countries-uncertainty-looms-over-nepal-s-labour-migration|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> India started screening passengers from Nepal and making masks compulsory for all visiting Nepalis.<ref name=tkp227>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/27/as-covid-19-spreads-public-health-officials-consider-plans-for-a-worst-case-scenario|title=As Covid-19 spreads, public health officials consider plans for a worst-case scenario|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115118/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/27/as-covid-19-spreads-public-health-officials-consider-plans-for-a-worst-case-scenario|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also screening Nepalis travelling into India by land, at various checkpoints at the border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88395/|title=India to start screening all air passengers from KTM starting from Monday|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115122/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88395/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n'''1 March:''' Nepal announced suspension of [[Visa on arrival|visa-on-arrival]] service for nationals of five countries badly affected by COVID-19 \u2013 China, South Korea, Japan,Italy and Iran \u2013 to be enforced from 7 to 30 March.{{efn|The implementation date was later reported to be 10 March.<ref name=tkp33/>}}<ref name=\"Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival\">{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival for nationals of countries badly affected by COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/02/c_138836161.htm |website=Xinhua |accessdate=2020-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303171539/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/02/c_138836161.htm |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89193/|title=Nepal announces temporary suspension of visa on arrival from March 7 to prevent coronavirus outbreak|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115118/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89193/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=tkp32>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/02/all-175-nepalis-evacuated-from-hubei-province-test-negative-for-covid-19|title=All 175 Nepalis evacuated from Hubei Province test negative for Covid-19|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115121/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/02/all-175-nepalis-evacuated-from-hubei-province-test-negative-for-covid-19|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It also urged the general public to avoid large gatherings.<ref name=mr31/> The passengers and crew involved in the evacuation of Nepalis from Hubei were released from quarantine after all tests again came back negative following a two-week quarantine.<ref name=tkp32/>\n\n'''2 March:''' The Supreme Court issued an interim order to suspend flights to and from countries affected by the disease, in response to a public interest litigation. The government issued a travel advisory against non-essential travel to countries hardest hit by the disease, including China, Iran, South Korea, Japan and Italy.<ref name=tkp33>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/03/aviation-authority-urges-government-to-implement-stringent-travel-restrictions|title=Aviation authority urges government to implement stringent travel restrictions|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324153558/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/03/aviation-authority-urges-government-to-implement-stringent-travel-restrictions|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The visitors coming from or via these countries would be required to submit a health certificate. Health checkpoints were to be established at all major entry points from India and third country citizens would be allowed to cross from select border check-points only. The [[Sagarmatha Sambaad|Sagarmatha Sambad]] programme scheduled for April was also postponed.<ref name=tkp33/>\n\n'''4\u20135 March:''' Due to a severe shortage of face-masks and protective gear as well as increase in price following a ban on export in China and India, some hospitals were reported to be sewing plain clothes masks as a precaution.<ref name=tkp34>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/04/hospitals-urge-ministry-to-arrange-for-face-masks-gloves-and-other-protective-gear|title=Hospitals urge ministry to arrange for face masks, gloves and other protective gear|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324115122/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/04/hospitals-urge-ministry-to-arrange-for-face-masks-gloves-and-other-protective-gear|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A shortage of hand sanitisers was also reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/04/hand-sanitisers-in-short-supply-due-to-buying-rush-sparked-by-outbreak-fears|title=Hand sanitisers in short supply due to buying rush sparked by outbreak fears|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131320/https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/04/hand-sanitisers-in-short-supply-due-to-buying-rush-sparked-by-outbreak-fears|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Everest Premier League]], the domestic T20 cricket tournament was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fallout-everest-premier-league-postponed|title=COVID-19 fallout: Everest Premier League postponed|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323163819/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fallout-everest-premier-league-postponed|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''8 March:''' Qatar imposed a temporary ban on arrivals from Nepal and other countries, affecting almost 40,000 labour migrants with valid work permits who were yet to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/09/qatar-places-temporary-ban-on-entry-of-people-from-14-countries-including-nepal|title=Thousands of Nepali workers affected as Qatar imposes temporary entry ban amidst Covid-19 outbreak|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131326/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/09/qatar-places-temporary-ban-on-entry-of-people-from-14-countries-including-nepal|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal Airlines and Himalaya Airlines suspended their flights to Doha indefinitely following the ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|title=NAC and Himalaya Airlines suspend flights to Doha|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131329/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''9 March:''' The government expanded the suspension of visa-on-arrival service to include three additional countries \u2014 France, Germany and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89928/|title=Nepal temporarily suspends on-arrival visa for nationals of France, Germany and Spain|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131330/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89928/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''10 March:''' Seventy one Chinese workers employed in the construction of Pokhara Airport who had returned from China after undergoing a 14-day quarantine were put into quarantine for another 14 days. They were being closely monitored and everyone was reported to be in normal health. Previously, 36 Chinese workers working for the project had also gone through a similar quarantine upon return to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/71-chinese-workers-in-pokhara-quarantined/|title=71 Chinese workers in Pokhara quarantined|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311124017/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/71-chinese-workers-in-pokhara-quarantined/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''12\u201315 March:''' Nepal decided to suspend on-arrival tourist visa for all countries, with an exception to diplomatic and official visas, to last from 14 March till 30 April. The government closed land border entry points for third country nationals, and cancelled all mountain climbing expeditions including on [[Mount Everest]], to be enforced from 14 March to 30 April. It also declared two-week mandatory self- and home-quarantines for everyone visiting Nepal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends on arrival tourist visa, closes land routes and cancels mountain climbing expeditions |url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/12/nepal-government-puts-all-tourist-visas-on-hold-and-cancels-all-spring-climbing-expeditions |website=Kathmandu Post |accessdate=2020-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315233926/https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/12/nepal-government-puts-all-tourist-visas-on-hold-and-cancels-all-spring-climbing-expeditions |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-announces-sweeping-travel-restrictions/|title=Govt announces sweeping travel restrictions|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151649/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-announces-sweeping-travel-restrictions/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Labour permits for all countries were suspended indefinitely, including to workers who were only back home on holiday. The government also suspended issuance of no objection letters to students going for abroad study until 30 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/on-arrival-visas-scrapped-till-april-30/|title=On-arrival visas scrapped till April 30|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151700/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/on-arrival-visas-scrapped-till-april-30/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Province No. 1]] government unveiled plans for two quarantine sites in the province, including one on a [[Koshi River]] island. It also assured plans were underway to provide additional equipment to health personnel, to set up health desks on border-crossings with India, to keep ambulances in standby and to maintain isolation wards in three major hospitals \u2013 [[B.P. Koirala Memorial Cancer Hospital|BP Koirala Institute Of Health Science]] in [[Dharan]], Koshi Hospital in [[Biratnagar]] and Mechi Hospital in [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-quarantine-centres-to-be-established-in-province-1/|title=Two quarantine centres to be established in Province 1|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060503/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-quarantine-centres-to-be-established-in-province-1/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/28-isolation-wards-prepared-in-province-1/|title=28 isolation wards prepared in Province 1|date=2020-03-05|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060506/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/28-isolation-wards-prepared-in-province-1/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> BP Koirala Institute of Health sciences in Dharan reported that a suspected patient had refused to remain in hospital and returned home. He had promised to return the following day for testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/14/man-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-refuses-to-stay-in-isolation-ward-and-returns-home|title=Man suspected of having coronavirus refuses to stay in isolation ward and returns home|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060457/https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/14/man-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-refuses-to-stay-in-isolation-ward-and-returns-home|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, Bihar transport department suspended Patna-Nepal bus services with immediate effect, to be enforced until 31 March, in an effort to contain the virus, after many cases emerged throughout India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/15/operation-of-patna-nepal-buses-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-2116837.html|title=Operation of Patna-Nepal buses postponed due to coronavirus outbreak|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316131254/https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/15/operation-of-patna-nepal-buses-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-2116837.html|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> India declared a suspension of all passenger movement through Indo-Nepal border, except a few designated checkpoints \u2013 Banbasa, Raxaul, Ranigunj and Sunauli<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90832/|title=Govt mulls complete closure of border with India|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324191649/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90832/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \u2013 with intensified health inspections, effective from 15 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/coronavirus-passenger-movements-through-pak-bdesh-nepal-bhutan-myanmar-border-points-suspended-55426|title=Coronavirus: Passenger movements through Pak, B'desh, Nepal, Bhutan, Myanmar border points suspended|last=Tribune News Service|website=Tribuneindia News Service|access-date=2020-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060458/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/coronavirus-passenger-movements-through-pak-bdesh-nepal-bhutan-myanmar-border-points-suspended-55426|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The land-border checkpoints with China began releasing imported goods following quarantine procedures as cases in China began to drop.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/containers-stalled-at-rasuwagadi-start-entering-nepal/|title=Containers stalled at Rasuwagadi start entering Nepal|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151627/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/containers-stalled-at-rasuwagadi-start-entering-nepal/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi proposed starting the COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC region; he also said India could share a Disease Surveillance Software with SAARC partners, and hinted at the possibility of conducting coordinated research on controlling epidemic diseases in the SAARC region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90492/|title=Indian PM Modi proposes COVID-19 Emergency Fund to combat coronavirus in South Asia|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151617/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90492/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''17 March:''' A meeting of the high-level coordination committee for prevention and control of COVID-19 decided to add 115 ICU and 1,000 isolation beds in the Kathmandu Valley. It also instructed the provincial governments to setup a total of 120 ICU beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90596/|title=Govt to set up 235 ICU beds amid coronavirus fears|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130313/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90596/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''18\u201319 March:''' The government declared suspension of all classes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90755/|title=Govt takes sweeping measures to contain spread of COVID-19|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182558/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90755/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and postponement of all academic examinations including the [[Secondary Education Examination (Nepal)|Secondary Education Examination]] until 12 April, the end of the Month of [[Chaitra]], the last month of Nepali calendar year when all schools hold the [[final examination]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/govt-postpones-all-examinations-till-12-april|title=Govt postpones all examinations till 12 April|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182559/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/govt-postpones-all-examinations-till-12-april|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Tribhuvan University and the Public Service Commission also postponed all their examinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90797/|title=Amid COVID-19 fears, PSC halts scheduled exams until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182602/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90797/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government banned all passengers, including Nepalis, from EU and the UK, West Asia and the Middle East as well as Malaysia, South Korea and Japan, effective from 20 March until 15 April. It also decided to shut down all cinema halls, gymnasiums,museums and cultural centres, and ban gathering of more than 25 people in any public spaces including at places of worship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/18/government-bans-entry-of-all-passengers|title=Government bans entry of all passengers, including Nepalis, from midnight March 20|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322024729/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/18/government-bans-entry-of-all-passengers|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal began to see a significant influx of people from India to Nepal as India saw increase in new cases throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/sudurpaschim-province/2020/03/18/amid-covid-19-threat-banbasa-border-sees-a-sudden-influx-of-people-returning-home-from-india|title=Amid Covid-19 threat, Banbasa border sees a sudden influx of people returning home from India|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130129/https://kathmandupost.com/sudurpaschim-province/2020/03/18/amid-covid-19-threat-banbasa-border-sees-a-sudden-influx-of-people-returning-home-from-india|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A noticeable outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley was reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/number-of-people-leaving-kathmandu-valley-increases/|title=Number of people leaving Kathmandu Valley increases|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182556/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/number-of-people-leaving-kathmandu-valley-increases/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The House of Representatives meeting was postponed until 26 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/govts-measures-to-fight-covid-19-inadequate-say-mps/|title=Govt's measures to fight COVID-19 inadequate, say MPs|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182558/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/govts-measures-to-fight-covid-19-inadequate-say-mps/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Province No. 1 government established quarantine centres throughout the province with a total capacity of 440 beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/440-bed-quarantine-centres-in-province-1/|title=440-bed quarantine centres in Province 1|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182557/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/440-bed-quarantine-centres-in-province-1/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''20 March:''' The National Assembly was suspended indefinitely.<ref name=mr319>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90872/|title=National Assembly put off until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184416/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90872/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health Ministry instructed public employees to report on weekends as well, and not leave the Kathmandu Valley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/health-ministry-bars-employees-from-leaving-kathmandu-valley|title=Health ministry bars employees from leaving Kathmandu valley|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182559/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/health-ministry-bars-employees-from-leaving-kathmandu-valley|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All weekly newspapers published from the Kathmandu Valley ceased their print editions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90891/|title=COVID-19 fear: Weekly newspapers from Kathmandu cease their print version|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182605/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90891/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The US government pledged $1.8&nbsp;million to Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/us-government-pledges-1-8-million/|title=US government pledges $1.8&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182649/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/us-government-pledges-1-8-million/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Prime Minister Oli addressed the nation for the first time since the start of the pandemic and announced a list of preventative measures. All international flights would be stopped from 22 March to 31 March and vehicular movement on long routes would be closed from 23 March. All government services and private offices except those providing essential services would be closed until 3 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southasia-idUSKBN217117|title=Sri Lanka imposes curfew as South Asia steps up coronavirus battle|date=2020-03-20|agency=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325122959/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southasia-idUSKBN217117|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u0947\u0936\u092d\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092f\u093e\u0924\u093e\u092f\u093e\u0924 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926, \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940\u092f \u0938\u0940\u092e\u093e \u0928\u093e\u0915\u093e \u0916\u0941\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e !036 |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846036 |website=Onlinekhabar |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=ne |trans-title=Indian border crossing open, traffic closed within country |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321030805/https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846036 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A notice from Nepal Tourism Board announced the suspension of issuance of trekking permits for tourists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends issuance of trekking permits for foreign trekkers |url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2020-03/20/content_75840039.htm |website=China.org.cn |accessdate=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321031001/http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2020-03/20/content_75840039.htm |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley intensified; almost 300,000 people had left in the preceding three days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/people-leaving-kathmandu-on-the-rise-photo-feature|title=People leaving Kathmandu on the rise (Photo Feature)|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182603/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/people-leaving-kathmandu-on-the-rise-photo-feature|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health Ministry decided to halt non-urgent health check-ups and surgeries until 12 April in hospitals in the Kathmandu Valley with 50 or more beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/big-hospitals-to-stop-non-urgent-health-check-up-surgeries|title=Big hospitals to stop non-urgent health check-up, surgeries|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182600/https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/big-hospitals-to-stop-non-urgent-health-check-up-surgeries|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A full bench meeting of the Supreme Court presided over by the Chief Justice decided to halt all non-urgent proceedings in courts across the country until 4 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/supreme-court-to-halt-non-urgent-proceedings/|title=Supreme Court to halt non-urgent proceedings|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/supreme-court-to-halt-non-urgent-proceedings/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90877/|title=Courts across the country to be closed for two weeks|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182555/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90877/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal government pledged Rs 100 Million to the [[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90907/|title=Nepal to contribute Rs 100 million to SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90907/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''21 March:''' Kathmandu city launched a central help desk and a toll-free 24-hour hotline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/dial-1180-in-case-of-covid-19-suspicion-kmc/|title=Dial 1180 in case of COVID-19 suspicion: KMC|date=2020-03-22|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323165223/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/dial-1180-in-case-of-covid-19-suspicion-kmc/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Germany pledged an additional one million Euros to its existing health programmes in Nepal to help combat the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/german-aid-to-nepal/|title=German aid to Nepal|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210145/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/german-aid-to-nepal/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Around sixty passengers from COVID-19 affected countries that landed on Tribhuvan Interantional Airport were sent to quarantine at Kharipati, Bhaktapur; they had not presented any symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/63-people-sent-to-kharipati-quarantine|title=63 people sent to Kharipati Quarantine|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130222/https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/63-people-sent-to-kharipati-quarantine|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was reported that Gandaki Province had set up 111 isolation beds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/111-isolation-beds-in-gandaki-province|title=111 isolation beds in Gandaki province|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210116/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/111-isolation-beds-in-gandaki-province|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Metropolitan Traffic Police Division suspended breathalyser tests as well as educational classes for drivers found breaking traffic rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/police-put-off-drink-and-drive-operation|title=Police put off 'drink and drive' operation|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210112/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/police-put-off-drink-and-drive-operation|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It also deployed 200 of its personnel to display placards with awareness messages about the disease by the roadside.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/traffic-police-generate-awareness-about-covid-19|title=Traffic police generate awareness about Covid-19|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/traffic-police-generate-awareness-about-covid-19|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nepal Police]] established coronavirus response units in all its stations and decided not to make arrests for minor offences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/21/police-set-up-coronavirus-response-unit-at-every-station|title=Police set up coronavirus response unit at every station|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210114/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/21/police-set-up-coronavirus-response-unit-at-every-station|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health Ministry informed that private hospitals with more than 100 beds would not be allowed to refer patients to other hospitals; they were required to treat suspected patients, wait for test results and provide free treatment if the disease were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/21/158475695256349344.html|title=\u0938\u092f \u092c\u0947\u0921\u092e\u093e\u0925\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0905\u0938\u094d\u092a\u0924\u093e\u0932\u0932\u0947 \u092c\u093f\u0930\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0930\u0947\u092b\u0930 \u0917\u0930\u094d\u0928 \u0928\u092a\u093e\u0909\u0928\u0947|website=ekantipur.com|language=ne|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210115/https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/21/158475695256349344.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''22 March:''' Nepal decided to close its land border with India and China for a week effective from 23 March. The government also declared a Rs 500 million fund with contributions of a month's salary from government ministers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/government-to-close-down-border-with-india-and-china-for-a-week|title=Government to close down border with India and China for a week|website=Kathmandu Post|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130127/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/government-to-close-down-border-with-india-and-china-for-a-week|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It also increased the allowances for health workers working at the front desks of hospitals by 50\u2013100%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846585 |title=\u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0932\u093e\u0908 \u092a\u0940\u092a\u0940\u0908 \u0930 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0938\u093e\u0939\u0928 \u092d\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0926\u093f\u0928\u0947 \u0928\u093f\u0930\u094d\u0923\u092f |work=onlinekhabar.com |access-date=22 March 2020 |language=ne |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322192028/https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846585 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Kanchanpur District|Kanchanpur]] and [[Banke District]]s declared lockdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/kanchanpur-nepalgunj-under-indefinite-lockdown/|title=Kanchanpur, Nepalgunj under indefinite lockdown|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130752/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/kanchanpur-nepalgunj-under-indefinite-lockdown/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March:''' COVID-19 was confirmed in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from France on 17 March via Qatar, the first case in two months, second overall. She was admitted into isolation at Teku Hospital. Her family is said to be in quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web |title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/ |website=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323070621/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Office of the attorney General was reported to have asked the Police to release people held for minor crimes under bail or parole to reduce crowding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/opinion/editorial-inadequate-testing/|title=EDITORIAL: Inadequate testing|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151128/https://thehimalayantimes.com/opinion/editorial-inadequate-testing/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Minister of Health declared that all patients of COVID-19 would be rescued as necessary and provided free treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/govt-will-rescue-provide-free-treatment-to-infected-people-health-minister-dhakal|title=Govt will rescue, provide free treatment to infected people: Health minister Dhakal|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130130/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/govt-will-rescue-provide-free-treatment-to-infected-people-health-minister-dhakal|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kailali District]] was reported to have declared an indefinite lock-down effective from 2&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/91136/|title=Curfew clamped in Kailali to prevent COVID-19|last=RSS|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133650/https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/91136/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Arghakhanchi District]] also declared an indefinite lock-down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/arghakhanchi-district-to-be-locked-down-from-midnight|title=Arghakhanchi district to be locked down from midnight|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130159/https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/arghakhanchi-district-to-be-locked-down-from-midnight|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''24 March:''' The country-wide lockdown came into effect.<ref name=four/>\n\n'''25 March:''' The third case in Kathmandu was confirmed. The patient had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates and was staying in a hotel in Kathmandu. They are being treated in Teku Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325071210/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''26 March:''' Rescue of tourists stranded throughout Nepal was initiated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/more-stranded-tourists-evacuated-from-nepal/|title=More stranded tourists evacuated from Nepal|last=Times|first=Nepali|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329200539/https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/more-stranded-tourists-evacuated-from-nepal/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 28 March, hundreds of tourists had been rescued and brought to Kathmandu; many were being repatriated via chartered flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/rescue-flights-continue-on-saturday/|title=Rescue flights continue on Saturday|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329205325/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/rescue-flights-continue-on-saturday/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''27 March:''' Fourth case nationally, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed. It involved a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates. He is being treated at Seti Provincial Hospital in Dhangadhi.<ref name=four>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/27/fourth-nepali-tests-positive-for-covid-19-case|title=Fourth Nepali tests positive for Covid-19|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131517/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/27/fourth-nepali-tests-positive-for-covid-19-case|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''28 March:''' A 19-year-old woman who had recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium via Doha tested positive, bringing the total to five in the country. She had shared a flight from Doha with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March. She had since travelled to her home in Baglung; she was admitted for treatment at Dhaulagiri Zonal Hospital after the test came back positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fifth-patient-moved-freely-in-her-village-for-5-days-got-admitted-to-dhaulagiri-hospital-7-hours-after-being-confirmed|title=COVID-19 fifth patient moved freely in her village for 5 days, got admitted to Dhaulagiri hospital 7 hours after being confirmed !|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329205329/https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fifth-patient-moved-freely-in-her-village-for-5-days-got-admitted-to-dhaulagiri-hospital-7-hours-after-being-confirmed|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328111230/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March:''' The government decided to extend the suspension of international flights to until 15 April. The country-wide lockdown was extended to until 8 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/29/nationwide-lockdown-extended-until-april-8-ban-on-international-flights-until-april-15|title=Nationwide lockdown extended until April 8, ban on international flights until April 15|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329205329/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/29/nationwide-lockdown-extended-until-april-8-ban-on-international-flights-until-april-15|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n'''2 April:''' A 65-year-old woman who recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium who accompanied the 19-year-old woman on 17 March tested positive bringing the total to six in the country. Health minister confirmed that she was staying at her home in Baglung. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|title=One more person tests positive for Covid-19, Nepal's sixth confirmed case|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404055356/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/02/health-ministry-confirms-sixth-covid-19-case|title=Health Ministry confirms sixth Covid-19 case|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404064438/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/02/health-ministry-confirms-sixth-covid-19-case|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''4 April:''' Three new positive cases were confirmed in the far-western region of Nepal. Among the three are a 21-year-old male of Kailali who had returned from Mumbai in India, 41-year-old male of Kanchanpur who had returned from Uttarakhand in India, and a 34-year-old female from Kailali who is known be a relative of one of the earlier infected persons. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/temp/three-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=Three new positive cases for Covid-19 in Nepal|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> This is the first local transmission in Nepal. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/covid-19-first-locally-transmitted-case-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=First person-to-person Covid-19 transmission in Nepal|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406221237/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/covid-19-first-locally-transmitted-case-confirmed-in-nepal/|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Four Nepalese died in New York <ref>{{cite web|author=\u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0916\u092c\u0930 |url=https://nepalkhabar.com/global/23816-2020-04-05-15-02-44 |title=\u0905\u092e\u0947\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e\u0915\u094b \u0915\u094b\u0930\u094b\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0947\u0928\u094d\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u0928\u094d\u092f\u0941\u092f\u094b\u0930\u094d\u0915\u092e\u093e \u096a \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940\u0915\u094b \u092e\u0943\u0924\u094d\u092f\u0941 |publisher=Nepalkhabar.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n'''11 April:''' Three Indian nationals residing in [[Parsa District]] tested positive.<ref name=tkpthree>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/04/12/three-indian-nationals-in-birgunj-test-positive-for-covid-19|title=Three Indian nationals in Birgunj test positive for Covid-19|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n'''13 April:''' A 65-year-old woman from Kailali and a 19-year-old man from Rautahat tested positive for the disease.<ref name=rnd14>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/mohp-confirms-2-more-covid-19-cases-number-reaches-14|title=MoHP confirms 2 more COVID-19 cases, number reaches 14|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n'''14 April:''' Two members of a family in Kathmandu which had returned from the United Kingdom four weeks earlier tested positive for the disease.<ref name=mr16/> The countrywide lockdown was extended until 27 April, citing an increase in the number of new cases. The border closures and suspension of international flights were extended until 1 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/04/14/lockdown-extended-by-12-more-days-until-april-27|title=Lockdown extended by 12 more days until April 27|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n'''17 April:''' 12 Indian nationals from Delhi who had been quarantined in [[Udayapur District]] of [[Province No. 1]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/friday-sees-14-new-cases-spiking-nepals-covid-19-count-to-30/ |title=Friday sees 14 new cases, spiking Nepal\u2019s Covid-19 count to 30 |date=17 April 2020 |website= |publisher= |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> Two [[United Kingdom|UK]] returnees, a mother and her son from [[Chitwan district]] in [[Bagmati Pradesh]], also tested positive on the same day, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 30.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/17/with-14-new-cases-nepal-s-covid-19-tally-doubles-in-a-single-day |title=With 14 new cases, Nepal\u2019s Covid-19 tally doubles in a single day |date=17 April 2020 |website= |publisher= |access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n'''18 April:''' One more Indian National aged 65 years old tested positive today for corona virus. He was one of 16 people who was quarantined in [[Udayapur District]] where 12 people tested positive yesterday. <ref>{{cite web |url= |title= |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=}}</ref> The second coronavirus patient, hospitalised since 23 March, was confirmed completely recovered<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/nepals-second-covid-19-patient-recovered-health-ministry20200418181641/ |title=Nepal's second COVID-19 patient recovered: Health Ministry |date=18 April 2020 |website= |publisher=ANI |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and a 65 years old woman from [[Baglung District]] who tested positive on 2 April 2020 recovered today and discharged from Dhaulagiri Zonal Hospital. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://ekantipur.com/pradesh-4/2020/04/18/158721747338121993.html |title=\u092c\u093e\u0917\u094d\u0932\u0941\u0919\u0915\u0940 \u096c\u096b \u0935\u0930\u094d\u0937\u0940\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0939\u093f\u0932\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u094b\u0930\u094b\u0928\u093e\u0932\u093e\u0908 \u091c\u093f\u0924\u093f\u0928\u094d, \u0924\u0940\u0928 \u0938\u093e\u0924\u093e\u092e\u093e \u092d\u0907\u0928\u094d \u0921\u093f\u0938\u094d\u091a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091c |date=18 April 2020 |website= |publisher=Kantipur Publication |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> With this, the number of recoveries reached three and the number of active cases 28.<ref name=18apr/><!--GETS OUTDATED-->\n\n==Impact and response==\nThe tourism sector has been reported to be suffering due to the absence of Chinese tourists, as well as the various travel restrictions imposed on travel globally. Manufacturing sector is experiencing a shortage of raw materials, most of which used to come from China. The situation is exacerbated by spread of the pandemic to the Middle-east which is the main source of remittance that makes up more than half of Nepal's [[GDP]]. Remittances were expected to sharply drop after Nepal suspended issuance of workers permit to Nepalis for all countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/15/nepal-s-remittance-dependent-economy-braces-for-upheaval-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Nepal's remittance-dependent economy braces for upheaval amid Covid-19 pandemic|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329025536/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/15/nepal-s-remittance-dependent-economy-braces-for-upheaval-amid-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The wholesale and retail sector has also been affected due to fall of imports from China. The construction sector which imports most of its building materials from China has slowed down. As the Chinese contractors and workers who went home for the Chinese new year could not return, the public construction projects have also been affected.<ref name=econ>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/04/nepali-economy-starts-to-feel-the-pinch-as-coronavirus-spreads|title=Nepali economy starts to feel the pinch as coronavirus spreads|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48830-coronavirus-chills-nepal-infrastructure-construction?v=preview|title=Coronavirus Chills Nepal Infrastructure Construction|website=www.enr.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131538/https://www.enr.com/articles/48830-coronavirus-chills-nepal-infrastructure-construction?v=preview|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-outbreak-could-shave-off-nepals-economy-by-36-78-million/|title=Coronavirus outbreak could shave off Nepal's economy by $36.78&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-07|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325013531/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-outbreak-could-shave-off-nepals-economy-by-36-78-million/|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The domestic airlines were reported to be struggling for survival as ticket prices dropped to half or a third of normal following a sharp decline in demand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/11/domestic-airfares-hit-rock-bottom-amidst-coronavirus-travel-advisory|title=Domestic airfares hit rock bottom amidst coronavirus travel advisory|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131541/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/11/domestic-airfares-hit-rock-bottom-amidst-coronavirus-travel-advisory|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Number of international flights to and from Nepal had decreased by more than 50% by 13 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/international-flights-drop-significantly-at-tia/|title=International flights drop significantly at TIA|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151616/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/international-flights-drop-significantly-at-tia/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nepal's import-dependent economy is also vulnerable to depreciation of Indian currency to which its currency is permanently pegged, as Indian economy suffers the impact of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/weakening-nepali-currency-to-hit-economy/|title=Weakening Nepali currency to hit economy|date=2020-03-12|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324151617/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/weakening-nepali-currency-to-hit-economy/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 20,000 tour, trek and mountaineering guides lost their livelihood when mountaineering was suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/14/suspension-of-climbing-permits-and-on-arrival-visas-entails-losses-of-thousands-of-jobs-and-millions-of-dollars|title=Suspension of climbing permits and on-arrival visas entails losses of thousands of jobs and millions of dollars|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131548/https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/14/suspension-of-climbing-permits-and-on-arrival-visas-entails-losses-of-thousands-of-jobs-and-millions-of-dollars|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/18/experts-call-for-measures-to-ease-the-impact-of-coronavirus-on-the-economy|title=Experts call for measures to ease the impact of coronavirus on the economy|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe annual [[Holi]] celebrations, which fell on 9 and 10 March in 2020 saw decreased activities, low business and cancellation of organised celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-scare-dampens-holi-spirit-businesses-hit/|title=Coronavirus scare dampens Holi spirit, businesses hit|date=2020-03-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311153307/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-scare-dampens-holi-spirit-businesses-hit/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNepal had declared 2020 as the Visit Nepal Year and aimed to bring in two million foreign tourists, almost double the figure from previous year. As the pandemic spread and Nepal had to suspend air travel to and from China, the biggest source of international tourists arriving by air, Nepal suspended its promotional campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/01/c_138831984.htm|title=Nepal postpones int'l tourism promotion amid coronavirus outbreak - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe temporary blanket ban on animal markets imposed by China as a response to the pandemic is expected to curb wildlife poaching and trafficking through Nepal, as the Chinese traditional medicine which uses various body parts of endangered animals as its ingredients has been the biggest challenge to wildlife conservation in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|title=Coronavirus outbreak may curb wildlife trafficking|last=Awale|first=Sonia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211183345/https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|archive-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Market regulation===\nThe department of Commerce, Supplies and Consumer Protection conducted raids on 161 firms and fined 57 of them, a total of around four million Rupees in the month of [[Falgun]] (February\u2013March).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/20/government-launches-coordinated-inspections-to-curb-black-marketeering-of-essential-goods|title=Government launches coordinated inspections to curb black marketeering of essential goods|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182557/https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/20/government-launches-coordinated-inspections-to-curb-black-marketeering-of-essential-goods|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It inspected multiple pharmacies and surgical shops in Kathmandu on 5 March and fined a total of Rs 430,000 for hiking prices and other offences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/05/government-cracks-down-on-price-gouging-by-pharmacies-and-surgical-shops|title=Government cracks down on price-gouging by pharmacies and surgical shops|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 10 March, four pharmacies were fined a total of Rs 800,000 after they were caught charging 1000% of normal price for surgical masks. Some groceries and LPG stores were also inspected. One million units of face masks were confiscated from a warehouse in Kathmandu and the owner arrested on 18 March, bringing the total of masks confiscated in the week past to 2.3&nbsp;million. Around 50,000 units of hand-sanitisers were also confiscated from the black market. Around two dozen black marketeers had been arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/police-seize-one-million-masks/|title=Police seize one million masks|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324182722/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/police-seize-one-million-masks/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As the outflux of people from Kathmandu intensified, 23 transport entrepreneurs and workers were arrested on 20 March for overcharging the passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/23-persons-held-for-fleecing-passengers/|title=23 persons held for fleecing passengers|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324210113/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/23-persons-held-for-fleecing-passengers/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Essential drugs===\nNepal's pharmaceutical industry has been impacted due to lack of raw materials as a number of essential ingredients were previously imported from Hubei.<ref name=econ/> Nepal faced the prospect of a potential shortage of essential medicines when India imposed restrictions on export of 26 types of raw materials including of essential medicine citing disruption in the supply chain from Hubei; however India later agreed to relax restrictions in case of Nepal, and asked the Nepalese government to provide a list of names and quantities of essential medicines that it needed to supply to Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|title=India seeks list of essential drugs that Nepal needs|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307141100/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation===\nOn 21 March a 20-year-old man was arrested on charges of spreading misinformation online through an unregistered [[fake news website]] and causing public fear, after audio tapes alleging cover-up of COVID-19 cases were found circulating online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/youth-arrested-for-spreading-romours-of-covid-19-cases/|title=Youth arrested for spreading romours of COVID-19 cases|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130304/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/youth-arrested-for-spreading-romours-of-covid-19-cases/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, [[Nepal Army]] dispelled rumours circulating in social media that claimed Army helicopters were being used to spray disinfectants over settlements at midnight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/army-dismisses-helicopter-spraying-disifectant-at-midnight-rumours/|title=Army dismisses 'helicopter spraying disinfectant at midnight' rumours|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323130814/https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/army-dismisses-helicopter-spraying-disifectant-at-midnight-rumours/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Poaching===\n[[Poachers]] in Nepal took advantage of slack monitoring and sparse public movement during the Covid-19 lockdown and the country saw a surge in killing of wildlife under the shadow of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dpa-international.com/topic/nepal-sees-surge-wildlife-poaching-due-covid-19-lockdown-urn%3Anewsml%3Adpa.com%3A20090101%3A200404-99-589875/|title=Nepal sees surge in wildlife poaching due to Covid-19 lockdown|date=2020-04-04|website=[[Deutsche Presse-Agentur|DPA International]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|state=expanded}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Nepal|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Nepal|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Nepal]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Nepal]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "Naypta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Nepal"}
{"title_page": "Chewing tobacco", "text_new": "[[File:Tuggtobak.jpg|thumb|right|American [[Red Man]] loose leaf and Danish [[Oliver Twist Tobacco|Oliver Twist]] tobacco bits are two leading chewing tobacco brands.]]\n\n'''Chewing tobacco''' is a type of [[smokeless tobacco]] [[tobacco product|product]] consumed by placing a portion of the tobacco between the cheek and gum or upper lip teeth and chewing. Unlike [[dipping tobacco]], it is not ground and must be manually crushed with the teeth to release flavour and [[nicotine]]. Unwanted juices are then spat.\n\nChewing tobacco is typically manufactured as several varieties of product \u2013 most often as loose leaf (or scrap), pellets (tobacco \"bites\" or \"bits\"), and \"plug\" (a form of loose leaf tobacco condensed with a binding sweetener). Nearly all modern chewing tobaccos are produced via a process of leaf curing, cutting, fermentation and processing or sweetening. Historically, a lot of American chewing tobacco brands (which were popular during the [[American Civil War]] era) were made with [[cigar]] clippings.\n\n==Health issues==\nOral and spit tobacco increase the risk for [[leukoplakia]], a precursor to [[oral cancer]].<ref>[http://www.cancer.org/docroot/CRI/content/CRI_2_4_3X_What_are_the_signs_and_symptoms_of_cancer.asp ''Detailed Guide: Cancer (General Information) Signs and Symptoms of Cancer''].</ref> Chewing tobacco has been known to cause [[cancer]], particularly of the mouth and throat.<ref name=\"IARC\" /> According to [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]], \"Some health scientists have suggested that smokeless tobacco should be used in smoking cessation programs and have made implicit or explicit claims that its use would partly reduce the exposure of smokers to carcinogens and the risk for cancer. These claims, however, are not supported by the available evidence.\"<ref name=\"IARC\">{{cite journal |year=2007 |title=Smokeless Tobacco and Some Tobacco-specific N-Nitrosamines |journal=IARC Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans |volume=87 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/n/iarcmono89/pdf/}} </ref>\n\n== History ==\nChewing is one of the oldest methods of consuming tobacco. [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas]] in both North and South America chewed the leaves of the plant long before the arrival of Europeans, frequently mixed with the mineral [[Lime (mineral)|lime]], in the same way as [[coca]] leaves.{{citation needed|date=October 2010}}\n\nThe southern United States was distinctive for its production of tobacco, which earned premium prices from around the world. Most farmers grew a little for their own use, or traded with neighbours who grew it. Commercial sales became important in the late 19th century as major tobacco companies rose in the South, becoming one of the largest employers in cities like [[Winston-Salem, NC]], [[Durham, NC]], and [[Richmond, VA]]. Southerners dominated the tobacco industry in the United States; even a concern as large as the [[Bloch Brothers Tobacco Company|Helme Tobacco Company]], headquartered in [[New Jersey]], was headed by former Confederate officer [[George Washington Helme]]. In 1938, [[R.J. Reynolds]] marketed eighty-four brands of chewing tobacco, twelve brands of smoking tobacco, and the top-selling [[Camel cigarettes|Camel brand of cigarettes]]. Reynolds sold large quantities of chewing tobacco, though that market peaked about 1910.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalink.org/tobacco/trg/Chapter17/Chap17_SmokelessPage5.html|title=globalink|accessdate=30 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926020900/http://www.globalink.org/tobacco/trg/Chapter17/Chap17_SmokelessPage5.html|archivedate=26 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nA historian of the American South in the late 1860s reported on typical usage in the region where it was grown, paying close attention to class and gender:<ref>''A History of the United States since the Civil War'' Volume: 1. by [[Ellis Paxson Oberholtzer]]; 1917. p. 93.</ref>\n{{bquote|The chewing of tobacco was well-nigh universal. This habit had been widespread among the agricultural population of America both North and South before the war. Soldiers had found the quid a solace in the field and continued to revolve it in their mouths upon returning to their homes. Out of doors where his life was principally led the chewer spat upon his lands without offence to other men, and his homes and public buildings were supplied with spittoons. Brown and yellow parabolas were projected to right and left toward these receivers, but very often without the careful aim which made for cleanly living. Even the pews of fashionable churches were likely to contain these familiar conveniences. The large numbers of Southern men, and these were of the better class (officers in the Confederate army and planters, worth $20,000 or more, and barred from general amnesty) who presented themselves for the pardon of President Johnson, while they sat awaiting his pleasure in the ante-room at the White House, covered its floor with pools and rivulets of their spittle. An observant traveller in the South in 1865 said that in his belief seven-tenths of all persons above the age of twelve years, both male and female, used tobacco in some form. Women could be seen at the doors of their cabins in their bare feet, in their dirty one-piece cotton garments, their chairs tipped back, smoking pipes made of corn cobs into which were fitted reed stems or goose quills. Boys of eight or nine years of age and half-grown girls smoked. Women and girls \"dipped\" in their houses, on their porches, in the public parlours of hotels and in the streets.}}\n\nChewing tobacco is still used, predominantly by young males in some parts of the American Southeast, but also in other areas and age groups. In September 2006 both the Republican and Democratic candidates for Senator from Virginia admitted to chewing tobacco and agreed that it sets a bad example for children.<ref>[https://archive.today/20070811044721/http://home.hamptonroads.com/stories/story.cfm?story=111171&ran=197946 home.hamptonroads.com]</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century, during the peak in popularity of chewing tobacco in the western United States, a device known as the [[spittoon]] was a ubiquitous feature throughout places both private and public (e.g. [[parlour]]s and [[Passenger car (rail)|passenger cars]]). The purpose of the spittoon was to provide a receptacle for excess juices and spittle accumulated from the oral use of tobacco. As chewing tobacco's popularity declined throughout the years, the spittoon became merely a relic of the Old West and is rarely seen outside museums. Spittoons are still present on the floor of the [[U.S. Senate]]'s old chamber, honored as tradition.\n\n==Types==\nChewing tobacco comes in several different varieties.\n\n===Loose leaf===\nLoose leaf chewing tobacco is the most widely available and most frequently used type of chewing tobacco.  It consists of shredded tobacco leaf, usually sweetened and sometimes flavored, and often sold in a sealed pouch weighing on average 3oz.  Loose leaf chewing tobacco has a sticky texture due to the sweeteners added.  Common loose leaf chewing tobaccos include [[Red Man]], [[Levi Garrett]], Beechnut, and Stoker's.\n\n===Plug===\n[[File:Plug Chewing Tobaccos.JPG|thumb|200px|A selection of plug chewing tobaccos from the United States.]]\nPlug chewing tobacco is pressed tobacco leaves into a square, brick-like mass of tobacco called a plug.  From this, pieces are bitten off or cut from the plug and then chewed.  Plug tobacco is declining in popularity and is thus less readily available than loose leaf chewing tobacco. Historically, plug tobacco could be either smoked in a pipe or chewed, but today these are two distinct products.\n\n===Twist===\nTwist chewing tobacco is a rope-like piece of tobacco twisted together.  Unlike most loose leaf tobaccos, twist chewing tobacco is usually not sweetened.  Pieces of twist are either bitten off or cut and then chewed. Twist chewing tobacco is not widely available and is mostly found in [[Appalachia]].  Historically, twists could also be smoked in a pipe, or ground up into nasal [[Snuff (tobacco)|snuff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pipesmagazine.com/python/tag/how-to-smoke-rope-twist-tobacco/|title=How To Smoke Rope & Twist Tobacco \u2013 With Pipe and Pen|publisher=|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Chew bags===\nChew bags are traditional cut tobacco in a small bag containing between 0.5 and 1 gram each. Chew bags are used in much the same way as other chewing tobaccos although they have the appearance of snus portions. Chew bags are defined by European Commission, European Binding Tariff Information (EBTI) as cut or fine cut tobacco flakes (between 1-2 mm wide and 2-6 mm long) packed in sachets. By varying the sachet between the upper lip and by chewing, the consumer controls the release of flavor or nicotine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chadizzy1.blogspot.se/2017/01/general-cut-original-extra-strong-chew.html|title=General Cut (Original & Extra Strong) Chew Bags - Review.  20 January 2017.|author=|date=|website=chadizzy1.blogspot.se|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/dds2/ebti/ebti_details.jsp?Lang=en&selectedReference=&reference=SE2015-00330&refcountry=&valstartdate=&valstartdateto=&valenddate=&valenddateto=&suppldate=&nomenc=2403991000&nomencto=&keywordsearch=&descript=&orderby=0&totalRecords=17&linkVal=&viewVal=&keywordmatchrule=OR&specialkeyword|title=BTI Details|author=|date=|website=ec.europa.eu|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Chewing tobacco and baseball==\nWhen the rules of baseball were first written in 1845, the carcinogenic potential of chewing tobacco was unknown. At that time, it was commonly used by players and coaches alike.<ref>Bird, Patrick J.. \"Chewing Tobacco the Spitting Image of Baseball\". Ocala Star-Banner April 11, 1989: 7C.</ref> Smokeless tobacco use became rampant by players by the early 1900s. They liked chewing tobacco because it kept their mouths (and their mitts) moist on the dusty infield.<ref name=\"Palmer09\">Palmer, Brian. [http://www.slate.com/id/2234341/ \"Why Do So Many Baseball Players Chew Tobacco?\"]. Slate November 2, 2009.</ref> The use of chewing tobacco in baseball steadily increased until the mid-20th century, when cigarettes became popular and took the place of some players' smokeless tobacco habit.  Today, however, more baseball players are actually using dipping tobacco, not chewing tobacco.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Notable players affected by chewing tobacco===\nAs shown below, a number of notable players have died of oral cancer as a result. [[Joe Garagiola]], who quit, warns about chewing tobacco: \n{{quote|\"I tell these guys, 'You may not like what I say, but with lung cancer you die of lung cancer,{{'\"}} ... \"With oral cancer, you die one piece at a time. They operate on your neck, they operate on your jaw, they operate on your throat.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/30/sports/baseball/30vecsey.html?ref=health \"Garagiola, Who Quit, Warns About Chewing Tobacco\"], Sports of ''The Times'' By George Vecsey Published: May 29, 2010</ref>}}\n\n[[Bill Tuttle]] was a Major League player who made a big name for himself both through baseball and his anti-chewing-tobacco efforts. Tuttle was an outfielder for the [[Detroit Tigers]], [[Kansas City Athletics]], and the [[Minnesota Twins]]. He was an avid tobacco chewer; even his [[baseball card]]s pictured him with a bulge in his cheek from the tobacco. Nearly forty years after he began using smokeless tobacco, Tuttle developed a tumor in his mouth so severe it protruded through his skin. A few years before he died, Tuttle had many of his teeth, his jawbone, his gums, and his right cheekbone removed. He also had his taste buds removed.<ref>\"Smokeless Tobacco\". [http://kidshealth.org/teen/drug_alcohol/tobacco/smokeless.html KidsHealth.org]. April 28, 2010.</ref> Tuttle dedicated the last years of his life to speaking with Major League teams about not using chewing tobacco where television cameras could see the players so that children could not witness and be influenced by it. He also dedicated time to the National Spit Tobacco Education Program, which was being run by friend and former Major League player, Joe Garagiola. Tuttle died July 27, 1998, after a five-year battle with cancer.<ref name=\"No-Smoking.org\">Goldstein, Richard. \"Big League Anti-Tobacco Advocate Dies\". [http://no-smoking.org/july98/07-30-98-1.html No-Smoking.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927095440/http://no-smoking.org/july98/07-30-98-1.html |date=2007-09-27 }} July 30, 1998.</ref>\n\n[[Babe Ruth]], perhaps the most famous player of all time, also died of throat cancer. In the mid-1940s, Ruth was diagnosed with [[nasopharyngeal carcinoma]] (cancer of the upper throat). The top two causes of this disease are alcohol and tobacco; Ruth was a heavy user of both.<ref name=\"Babe Ruth\">[http://www.oralcancerfoundation.org/people/sports_figures.htm \"Sports Figures \u2013 Babe Ruth\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220064717/http://www.oralcancerfoundation.org/people/sports_figures.htm |date=2013-12-20 }}. Oral Cancer Foundation. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Rex Barney]], who began his career at age 19 pitching for the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]], later recounted that his coach told him he had to begin chewing tobacco if he ever wanted to be a Major League pitcher. Barney contracted a sickness from chewing and was unable to play in the first game he was supposed to start in.<ref name=\"QuitNet\">[http://www.quitnet.com/library/guides/Beat_The_Habit/BTH_History.jtml \"Smokeless Tobacco and Baseball: A Short History\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421161029/http://www.quitnet.com/library/guides/Beat_The_Habit/BTH_History.jtml |date=April 21, 2009 }}. QuitNet. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n\nHall of fame outfielder [[Tony Gwynn]] died of salivary cancer on June 16, 2014. He claimed the cancer was linked to his lifetime use of chewing and [[dipping tobacco]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lawrence|first1=Andrew|title=Tony Gwynn's last days: Cancer, tobacco and the death of a legend|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/06/02/tony-gwynn-cancer-san-diego-padres|website=SI.com|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Timeline===\n\n* '''1845:''' Baseball rules written, chewing tobacco use among players already rampant.<ref name=\"Borio10\">Borio, Gene. \"Tobacco Timeline: The Nineteenth Century\u2014The Age of the Cigar\". [http://www.tobacco.org/resources/history/Tobacco_History19.html Tobacco.org]: Tobacco News and Information. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n* '''1890:''' Dr. [[Robert Koch]] shows that the spitting of chewing tobacco was leading to a spread of tuberculosis. This leads to a downturn in use of chewing tobacco among the general population, but baseball players continue use.<ref name=\"Palmer09\" />\n* '''1909:''' [[Honus Wagner]], a well-known American baseball player, tells [[American Tobacco Company]] to take his picture off of their cartons. He does not want to be responsible for influencing children to smoke.<ref name=\"Borio10\" />\n* '''1948:''' Babe Ruth dies of throat cancer at age 53.<ref name=\"Babe Ruth\" />\n* '''1950s:''' Use of smokeless tobacco decreases as players make the switch to cigarettes.<ref name=\"QuitNet\" />\n* '''1970:''' Players' use of smokeless tobacco increases once again when the U.S. Government begins to warn against the potential risks of smoking.<ref name=\"QuitNet\" />\n* '''1984:''' Sean Marsee, who won 28 track medals at Talihina High school, in Talihina, Oklahoma, dies of oral cancer at the age of 19 after dipping Copenhagen snuff for six years since age 12.<ref>http://www.ok.gov/okswat/documents/Sean%20Marsee%20Story.pdf</ref>\n* '''1986:''' Betty Ann Marsee, mother of the late Sean Marsee, lost her lawsuit in Federal court on June 20, 1986, against the United States Tobacco Company for $137 million plus $10 million for pain and suffering. Ms. Marsee testified during the trial her son believed snuff was safe because it carried no warning label, and because athletes like former Dallas Cowboy running back Walt Garrison advertised it. Dr. Carl Hook, who treated Marsee in the early stages of the disease, testified that the teenager's oral cancer was caused by snuff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1986-06-20/news/mn-11626_1_oral-cancer|title=Jury Rejects Claim That Snuff Caused Cancer Death|work=latimes|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n* '''1989:''' Betty Ann Marsee, mother of the late Sean Marsee, loses her appeal in the United States Court of Appeals, Tenth Circuit, on January 10, 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/866/319/205068/|title=Betty Ann Marsee, As Administratrix of the Estate of Marvinsean Marsee, Deceased, Plaintiff-appellant, v. United States Tobacco Company, a New Jersey Corporation, defendant-appellee, 866 F.2d 319 (10th Cir. 1989)|work=Justia Law|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n* '''1993:''' [[Minor league baseball|Minor League]] players, coaches, and staff prohibited from smokeless tobacco use during games.<ref>Borio, Gene. \"Tobacco Timeline: The Twentieth Century 1950\u20131999\u2014The Battle is Joined\". [http://www.tobacco.org/resources/history/Tobacco_History20-2.html Tobacco.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422095537/http://www.tobacco.org/resources/history/Tobacco_History20-2.html |date=2012-04-22 }}: Tobacco News and Information. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n* '''1998:''' Bill Tuttle, anti-chewing-tobacco spokesperson and former MLB player, dies at the age of 69 after a five-year battle with cancer.<ref name=\"No-Smoking.org\" />\n* '''2010:''' [[San Diego Padres]] HOFer [[Tony Gwynn]] is diagnosed with cancer of a salivary gland which he says is due to him still using chew.<ref>Friend, Tom (March 25, 2011). \"Tony Gwynn returns after facing cancer\". ESPN.com. Archived from the original on March 27, 2011.</ref> Gwynn died of the disease in 2014.\n* '''2011:''' New five-year labor deal prevents the use of smokeless tobacco during pre and post-game interviews. However does not ban the use during games as long as the can or pouch is out of sight.\n* '''2016:''' A new collective bargaining agreement prohibits all new [[Major League Baseball]] players from using smokeless tobacco.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report: CBA includes smokeless tobacco ban for new players|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/18177667/cba-includes-smokeless-tobacco-ban-new-mlb-players|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MLB takes a swing at smokeless tobacco|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/mlb-takes-a-swing-at-smokeless-tobacco/2016/12/27/c4d6f304-b8d5-11e6-b994-f45a208f7a73_story.html|website=WashingtonPost.com|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Effects==\n\n===Baseball players' use effect on youth===\nThere is debate over whether players should be banned from using tobacco products during the games. The [[Major League Baseball Players Association]] disagrees, claiming it is a legal substance and therefore is acceptable to be used during games. [[Harvard School of Public Health]] professor, [[Gregory Connolly]], however, says \"the use of smokeless tobacco by players has a powerful role model effect on youth particularly among young males in sport, some of whom remain addicted in future careers as professional athletes.\"<ref name=\"Smith10\">Smith, Donna. [https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE63D4QZ20100414 \"Smokeless Tobacco Use Rising Among Teens\"]. Reuters. April 28, 2010.</ref> According to Connolly, one quarter of Minor League players do not support allowing the use of chewing tobacco during games, and one third of Major League players support abolishing it.<ref name=\"Smith10\"/> Due to health concerns, the MLB was asked to ban the use of chewing tobacco during the [[2011 World Series]] between the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] and [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].\n\n===Statistics===\nMany believe that the widespread use of chewing tobacco by baseball players has led to a rampant increase in youth, and particularly teen, use.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} Additionally, teen use of smokeless tobacco has increased, while use of all tobacco products by teens has decreased. This is true especially among white and Hispanic males.<ref name=\"Smith10\"/> In 1970, five times as many 65-and-older males used smokeless tobacco as 18- to 24-year-olds did (12.7% of the population were 65+ male users, 2.2% of the population were 18\u201324 male users). More specifically, moist snuff use increased for males ages 18\u201324 from 1% of the population to 6.2% of the population, while 65+ male users decreased from 4% to 2.2%.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nA 2009 survey by The U.S. Center for Disease Control revealed that 8.9% of U.S. high school students had used smokeless tobacco on at least 1 day during the 30 days before the survey.<ref name=CDC2009/> Usage was more common among males (15.0%) than females (2.2%) and among whites (11.9%) than blacks (3.3%) or Hispanics (5.1%). The five states with the highest percentage of high school users were Wyoming (16.2%) North Dakota (15.3%) South Dakota (14.6%) Montana (14.6%) and West Virginia (14.4%).<ref name=CDC2009>[https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/ss5905a1.htm \"Youth Risk Behavior Surveillance --- United States, 2009\"]. Center for Disease Control \u2013 June 4, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Brands==\nNotable chewing tobacco brands include:\n<!-- Only add brands that have a Wikipedia page -->\n{{Div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Copenhagen (tobacco)|Copenhagen]]\n* [[Grizzly (tobacco)|Grizzly]]\n* [[Kodiak tobacco|Kodiak]]\n* [[Levi Garrett]]\n* [[Mail Pouch]]\n* [[Oliver Twist Tobacco|Oliver Twist]]\n* [[Red Man]]\n* [[Skoal (tobacco)|Skoal]]\n* [[Stoker's]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dipping tobacco]]\n* [[Herbal smokeless tobacco]]\n* [[Smokeless tobacco]]\n* [[Naswar]]\n* [[Big League Chew]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Drug use}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chewing Tobacco}}\n[[Category:Tobacco]]\n[[Category:Habits]]\n[[Category:Masticatories]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Tuggtobak.jpg|thumb|right|American [[Red Man]] loose leaf and Danish [[Oliver Twist Tobacco|Oliver Twist]] tobacco bits are two leading chewing tobacco brands.]]\n\n'''Chewing tobacco''' is a type of [[smokeless tobacco]] [[tobacco product|product]] consumed by placing a portion of the tobacco between the cheek and gum or upper lip teeth and chewing. Unlike [[dipping tobacco]], it is not ground and must be manually crushed with the teeth to release flavour and [[nicotine]]. Unwanted juices are then expectorated (spat).\n\nChewing tobacco is typically manufactured as several varieties of product \u2013 most often as loose leaf (or scrap), pellets (tobacco \"bites\" or \"bits\"), and \"plug\" (a form of loose leaf tobacco condensed with a binding sweetener). Nearly all modern chewing tobaccos are produced via a process of leaf curing, cutting, fermentation and processing or sweetening. Historically, a lot of American chewing tobacco brands (which were popular during the [[American Civil War]] era) were made with [[cigar]] clippings.\n\n==Health issues==\nOral and spit tobacco increase the risk for [[leukoplakia]], a precursor to [[oral cancer]].<ref>[http://www.cancer.org/docroot/CRI/content/CRI_2_4_3X_What_are_the_signs_and_symptoms_of_cancer.asp ''Detailed Guide: Cancer (General Information) Signs and Symptoms of Cancer''].</ref> Chewing tobacco has been known to cause [[cancer]], particularly of the mouth and throat.<ref name=\"IARC\" /> According to [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]], \"Some health scientists have suggested that smokeless tobacco should be used in smoking cessation programs and have made implicit or explicit claims that its use would partly reduce the exposure of smokers to carcinogens and the risk for cancer. These claims, however, are not supported by the available evidence.\"<ref name=\"IARC\">{{cite journal |year=2007 |title=Smokeless Tobacco and Some Tobacco-specific N-Nitrosamines |journal=IARC Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans |volume=87 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/n/iarcmono89/pdf/}} </ref>\n\n== History ==\nChewing is one of the oldest methods of consuming tobacco. [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas]] in both North and South America chewed the leaves of the plant long before the arrival of Europeans, frequently mixed with the mineral [[Lime (mineral)|lime]], in the same way as [[coca]] leaves.{{citation needed|date=October 2010}}\n\nThe southern United States was distinctive for its production of tobacco, which earned premium prices from around the world. Most farmers grew a little for their own use, or traded with neighbours who grew it. Commercial sales became important in the late 19th century as major tobacco companies rose in the South, becoming one of the largest employers in cities like [[Winston-Salem, NC]], [[Durham, NC]], and [[Richmond, VA]]. Southerners dominated the tobacco industry in the United States; even a concern as large as the [[Bloch Brothers Tobacco Company|Helme Tobacco Company]], headquartered in [[New Jersey]], was headed by former Confederate officer [[George Washington Helme]]. In 1938, [[R.J. Reynolds]] marketed eighty-four brands of chewing tobacco, twelve brands of smoking tobacco, and the top-selling [[Camel cigarettes|Camel brand of cigarettes]]. Reynolds sold large quantities of chewing tobacco, though that market peaked about 1910.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalink.org/tobacco/trg/Chapter17/Chap17_SmokelessPage5.html|title=globalink|accessdate=30 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926020900/http://www.globalink.org/tobacco/trg/Chapter17/Chap17_SmokelessPage5.html|archivedate=26 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nA historian of the American South in the late 1860s reported on typical usage in the region where it was grown, paying close attention to class and gender:<ref>''A History of the United States since the Civil War'' Volume: 1. by [[Ellis Paxson Oberholtzer]]; 1917. p. 93.</ref>\n{{bquote|The chewing of tobacco was well-nigh universal. This habit had been widespread among the agricultural population of America both North and South before the war. Soldiers had found the quid a solace in the field and continued to revolve it in their mouths upon returning to their homes. Out of doors where his life was principally led the chewer spat upon his lands without offence to other men, and his homes and public buildings were supplied with spittoons. Brown and yellow parabolas were projected to right and left toward these receivers, but very often without the careful aim which made for cleanly living. Even the pews of fashionable churches were likely to contain these familiar conveniences. The large numbers of Southern men, and these were of the better class (officers in the Confederate army and planters, worth $20,000 or more, and barred from general amnesty) who presented themselves for the pardon of President Johnson, while they sat awaiting his pleasure in the ante-room at the White House, covered its floor with pools and rivulets of their spittle. An observant traveller in the South in 1865 said that in his belief seven-tenths of all persons above the age of twelve years, both male and female, used tobacco in some form. Women could be seen at the doors of their cabins in their bare feet, in their dirty one-piece cotton garments, their chairs tipped back, smoking pipes made of corn cobs into which were fitted reed stems or goose quills. Boys of eight or nine years of age and half-grown girls smoked. Women and girls \"dipped\" in their houses, on their porches, in the public parlours of hotels and in the streets.}}\n\nChewing tobacco is still used, predominantly by young males in some parts of the American Southeast, but also in other areas and age groups. In September 2006 both the Republican and Democratic candidates for Senator from Virginia admitted to chewing tobacco and agreed that it sets a bad example for children.<ref>[https://archive.today/20070811044721/http://home.hamptonroads.com/stories/story.cfm?story=111171&ran=197946 home.hamptonroads.com]</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century, during the peak in popularity of chewing tobacco in the western United States, a device known as the [[spittoon]] was a ubiquitous feature throughout places both private and public (e.g. [[parlour]]s and [[Passenger car (rail)|passenger cars]]). The purpose of the spittoon was to provide a receptacle for excess juices and spittle accumulated from the oral use of tobacco. As chewing tobacco's popularity declined throughout the years, the spittoon became merely a relic of the Old West and is rarely seen outside museums. Spittoons are still present on the floor of the [[U.S. Senate]]'s old chamber, honored as tradition.\n\n==Types==\nChewing tobacco comes in several different varieties.\n\n===Loose leaf===\nLoose leaf chewing tobacco is the most widely available and most frequently used type of chewing tobacco.  It consists of shredded tobacco leaf, usually sweetened and sometimes flavored, and often sold in a sealed pouch weighing on average 3oz.  Loose leaf chewing tobacco has a sticky texture due to the sweeteners added.  Common loose leaf chewing tobaccos include [[Red Man]], [[Levi Garrett]], Beechnut, and Stoker's.\n\n===Plug===\n[[File:Plug Chewing Tobaccos.JPG|thumb|200px|A selection of plug chewing tobaccos from the United States.]]\nPlug chewing tobacco is pressed tobacco leaves into a square, brick-like mass of tobacco called a plug.  From this, pieces are bitten off or cut from the plug and then chewed.  Plug tobacco is declining in popularity and is thus less readily available than loose leaf chewing tobacco. Historically, plug tobacco could be either smoked in a pipe or chewed, but today these are two distinct products.\n\n===Twist===\nTwist chewing tobacco is a rope-like piece of tobacco twisted together.  Unlike most loose leaf tobaccos, twist chewing tobacco is usually not sweetened.  Pieces of twist are either bitten off or cut and then chewed. Twist chewing tobacco is not widely available and is mostly found in [[Appalachia]].  Historically, twists could also be smoked in a pipe, or ground up into nasal [[Snuff (tobacco)|snuff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pipesmagazine.com/python/tag/how-to-smoke-rope-twist-tobacco/|title=How To Smoke Rope & Twist Tobacco \u2013 With Pipe and Pen|publisher=|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Chew bags===\nChew bags are traditional cut tobacco in a small bag containing between 0.5 and 1 gram each. Chew bags are used in much the same way as other chewing tobaccos although they have the appearance of snus portions. Chew bags are defined by European Commission, European Binding Tariff Information (EBTI) as cut or fine cut tobacco flakes (between 1-2 mm wide and 2-6 mm long) packed in sachets. By varying the sachet between the upper lip and by chewing, the consumer controls the release of flavor or nicotine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chadizzy1.blogspot.se/2017/01/general-cut-original-extra-strong-chew.html|title=General Cut (Original & Extra Strong) Chew Bags - Review.  20 January 2017.|author=|date=|website=chadizzy1.blogspot.se|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/dds2/ebti/ebti_details.jsp?Lang=en&selectedReference=&reference=SE2015-00330&refcountry=&valstartdate=&valstartdateto=&valenddate=&valenddateto=&suppldate=&nomenc=2403991000&nomencto=&keywordsearch=&descript=&orderby=0&totalRecords=17&linkVal=&viewVal=&keywordmatchrule=OR&specialkeyword|title=BTI Details|author=|date=|website=ec.europa.eu|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Chewing tobacco and baseball==\nWhen the rules of baseball were first written in 1845, the carcinogenic potential of chewing tobacco was unknown. At that time, it was commonly used by players and coaches alike.<ref>Bird, Patrick J.. \"Chewing Tobacco the Spitting Image of Baseball\". Ocala Star-Banner April 11, 1989: 7C.</ref> Smokeless tobacco use became rampant by players by the early 1900s. They liked chewing tobacco because it kept their mouths (and their mitts) moist on the dusty infield.<ref name=\"Palmer09\">Palmer, Brian. [http://www.slate.com/id/2234341/ \"Why Do So Many Baseball Players Chew Tobacco?\"]. Slate November 2, 2009.</ref> The use of chewing tobacco in baseball steadily increased until the mid-20th century, when cigarettes became popular and took the place of some players' smokeless tobacco habit.  Today, however, more baseball players are actually using dipping tobacco, not chewing tobacco.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Notable players affected by chewing tobacco===\nAs shown below, a number of notable players have died of oral cancer as a result. [[Joe Garagiola]], who quit, warns about chewing tobacco: \n{{quote|\"I tell these guys, 'You may not like what I say, but with lung cancer you die of lung cancer,{{'\"}} ... \"With oral cancer, you die one piece at a time. They operate on your neck, they operate on your jaw, they operate on your throat.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/30/sports/baseball/30vecsey.html?ref=health \"Garagiola, Who Quit, Warns About Chewing Tobacco\"], Sports of ''The Times'' By George Vecsey Published: May 29, 2010</ref>}}\n\n[[Bill Tuttle]] was a Major League player who made a big name for himself both through baseball and his anti-chewing-tobacco efforts. Tuttle was an outfielder for the [[Detroit Tigers]], [[Kansas City Athletics]], and the [[Minnesota Twins]]. He was an avid tobacco chewer; even his [[baseball card]]s pictured him with a bulge in his cheek from the tobacco. Nearly forty years after he began using smokeless tobacco, Tuttle developed a tumor in his mouth so severe it protruded through his skin. A few years before he died, Tuttle had many of his teeth, his jawbone, his gums, and his right cheekbone removed. He also had his taste buds removed.<ref>\"Smokeless Tobacco\". [http://kidshealth.org/teen/drug_alcohol/tobacco/smokeless.html KidsHealth.org]. April 28, 2010.</ref> Tuttle dedicated the last years of his life to speaking with Major League teams about not using chewing tobacco where television cameras could see the players so that children could not witness and be influenced by it. He also dedicated time to the National Spit Tobacco Education Program, which was being run by friend and former Major League player, Joe Garagiola. Tuttle died July 27, 1998, after a five-year battle with cancer.<ref name=\"No-Smoking.org\">Goldstein, Richard. \"Big League Anti-Tobacco Advocate Dies\". [http://no-smoking.org/july98/07-30-98-1.html No-Smoking.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927095440/http://no-smoking.org/july98/07-30-98-1.html |date=2007-09-27 }} July 30, 1998.</ref>\n\n[[Babe Ruth]], perhaps the most famous player of all time, also died of throat cancer. In the mid-1940s, Ruth was diagnosed with [[nasopharyngeal carcinoma]] (cancer of the upper throat). The top two causes of this disease are alcohol and tobacco; Ruth was a heavy user of both.<ref name=\"Babe Ruth\">[http://www.oralcancerfoundation.org/people/sports_figures.htm \"Sports Figures \u2013 Babe Ruth\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220064717/http://www.oralcancerfoundation.org/people/sports_figures.htm |date=2013-12-20 }}. Oral Cancer Foundation. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Rex Barney]], who began his career at age 19 pitching for the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]], later recounted that his coach told him he had to begin chewing tobacco if he ever wanted to be a Major League pitcher. Barney contracted a sickness from chewing and was unable to play in the first game he was supposed to start in.<ref name=\"QuitNet\">[http://www.quitnet.com/library/guides/Beat_The_Habit/BTH_History.jtml \"Smokeless Tobacco and Baseball: A Short History\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421161029/http://www.quitnet.com/library/guides/Beat_The_Habit/BTH_History.jtml |date=April 21, 2009 }}. QuitNet. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n\nHall of fame outfielder [[Tony Gwynn]] died of salivary cancer on June 16, 2014. He claimed the cancer was linked to his lifetime use of chewing and [[dipping tobacco]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lawrence|first1=Andrew|title=Tony Gwynn's last days: Cancer, tobacco and the death of a legend|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/06/02/tony-gwynn-cancer-san-diego-padres|website=SI.com|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Timeline===\n\n* '''1845:''' Baseball rules written, chewing tobacco use among players already rampant.<ref name=\"Borio10\">Borio, Gene. \"Tobacco Timeline: The Nineteenth Century\u2014The Age of the Cigar\". [http://www.tobacco.org/resources/history/Tobacco_History19.html Tobacco.org]: Tobacco News and Information. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n* '''1890:''' Dr. [[Robert Koch]] shows that the spitting of chewing tobacco was leading to a spread of tuberculosis. This leads to a downturn in use of chewing tobacco among the general population, but baseball players continue use.<ref name=\"Palmer09\" />\n* '''1909:''' [[Honus Wagner]], a well-known American baseball player, tells [[American Tobacco Company]] to take his picture off of their cartons. He does not want to be responsible for influencing children to smoke.<ref name=\"Borio10\" />\n* '''1948:''' Babe Ruth dies of throat cancer at age 53.<ref name=\"Babe Ruth\" />\n* '''1950s:''' Use of smokeless tobacco decreases as players make the switch to cigarettes.<ref name=\"QuitNet\" />\n* '''1970:''' Players' use of smokeless tobacco increases once again when the U.S. Government begins to warn against the potential risks of smoking.<ref name=\"QuitNet\" />\n* '''1984:''' Sean Marsee, who won 28 track medals at Talihina High school, in Talihina, Oklahoma, dies of oral cancer at the age of 19 after dipping Copenhagen snuff for six years since age 12.<ref>http://www.ok.gov/okswat/documents/Sean%20Marsee%20Story.pdf</ref>\n* '''1986:''' Betty Ann Marsee, mother of the late Sean Marsee, lost her lawsuit in Federal court on June 20, 1986, against the United States Tobacco Company for $137 million plus $10 million for pain and suffering. Ms. Marsee testified during the trial her son believed snuff was safe because it carried no warning label, and because athletes like former Dallas Cowboy running back Walt Garrison advertised it. Dr. Carl Hook, who treated Marsee in the early stages of the disease, testified that the teenager's oral cancer was caused by snuff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1986-06-20/news/mn-11626_1_oral-cancer|title=Jury Rejects Claim That Snuff Caused Cancer Death|work=latimes|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n* '''1989:''' Betty Ann Marsee, mother of the late Sean Marsee, loses her appeal in the United States Court of Appeals, Tenth Circuit, on January 10, 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/866/319/205068/|title=Betty Ann Marsee, As Administratrix of the Estate of Marvinsean Marsee, Deceased, Plaintiff-appellant, v. United States Tobacco Company, a New Jersey Corporation, defendant-appellee, 866 F.2d 319 (10th Cir. 1989)|work=Justia Law|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n* '''1993:''' [[Minor league baseball|Minor League]] players, coaches, and staff prohibited from smokeless tobacco use during games.<ref>Borio, Gene. \"Tobacco Timeline: The Twentieth Century 1950\u20131999\u2014The Battle is Joined\". [http://www.tobacco.org/resources/history/Tobacco_History20-2.html Tobacco.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422095537/http://www.tobacco.org/resources/history/Tobacco_History20-2.html |date=2012-04-22 }}: Tobacco News and Information. April 28, 2010.</ref>\n* '''1998:''' Bill Tuttle, anti-chewing-tobacco spokesperson and former MLB player, dies at the age of 69 after a five-year battle with cancer.<ref name=\"No-Smoking.org\" />\n* '''2010:''' [[San Diego Padres]] HOFer [[Tony Gwynn]] is diagnosed with cancer of a salivary gland which he says is due to him still using chew.<ref>Friend, Tom (March 25, 2011). \"Tony Gwynn returns after facing cancer\". ESPN.com. Archived from the original on March 27, 2011.</ref> Gwynn died of the disease in 2014.\n* '''2011:''' New five-year labor deal prevents the use of smokeless tobacco during pre and post-game interviews. However does not ban the use during games as long as the can or pouch is out of sight.\n* '''2016:''' A new collective bargaining agreement prohibits all new [[Major League Baseball]] players from using smokeless tobacco.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report: CBA includes smokeless tobacco ban for new players|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/18177667/cba-includes-smokeless-tobacco-ban-new-mlb-players|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MLB takes a swing at smokeless tobacco|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/mlb-takes-a-swing-at-smokeless-tobacco/2016/12/27/c4d6f304-b8d5-11e6-b994-f45a208f7a73_story.html|website=WashingtonPost.com|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Effects==\n\n===Baseball players' use effect on youth===\nThere is debate over whether players should be banned from using tobacco products during the games. The [[Major League Baseball Players Association]] disagrees, claiming it is a legal substance and therefore is acceptable to be used during games. [[Harvard School of Public Health]] professor, [[Gregory Connolly]], however, says \"the use of smokeless tobacco by players has a powerful role model effect on youth particularly among young males in sport, some of whom remain addicted in future careers as professional athletes.\"<ref name=\"Smith10\">Smith, Donna. [https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE63D4QZ20100414 \"Smokeless Tobacco Use Rising Among Teens\"]. Reuters. April 28, 2010.</ref> According to Connolly, one quarter of Minor League players do not support allowing the use of chewing tobacco during games, and one third of Major League players support abolishing it.<ref name=\"Smith10\"/> Due to health concerns, the MLB was asked to ban the use of chewing tobacco during the [[2011 World Series]] between the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] and [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].\n\n===Statistics===\nMany believe that the widespread use of chewing tobacco by baseball players has led to a rampant increase in youth, and particularly teen, use.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} Additionally, teen use of smokeless tobacco has increased, while use of all tobacco products by teens has decreased. This is true especially among white and Hispanic males.<ref name=\"Smith10\"/> In 1970, five times as many 65-and-older males used smokeless tobacco as 18- to 24-year-olds did (12.7% of the population were 65+ male users, 2.2% of the population were 18\u201324 male users). More specifically, moist snuff use increased for males ages 18\u201324 from 1% of the population to 6.2% of the population, while 65+ male users decreased from 4% to 2.2%.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nA 2009 survey by The U.S. Center for Disease Control revealed that 8.9% of U.S. high school students had used smokeless tobacco on at least 1 day during the 30 days before the survey.<ref name=CDC2009/> Usage was more common among males (15.0%) than females (2.2%) and among whites (11.9%) than blacks (3.3%) or Hispanics (5.1%). The five states with the highest percentage of high school users were Wyoming (16.2%) North Dakota (15.3%) South Dakota (14.6%) Montana (14.6%) and West Virginia (14.4%).<ref name=CDC2009>[https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/ss5905a1.htm \"Youth Risk Behavior Surveillance --- United States, 2009\"]. Center for Disease Control \u2013 June 4, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Brands==\nNotable chewing tobacco brands include:\n<!-- Only add brands that have a Wikipedia page -->\n{{Div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Copenhagen (tobacco)|Copenhagen]]\n* [[Grizzly (tobacco)|Grizzly]]\n* [[Kodiak tobacco|Kodiak]]\n* [[Levi Garrett]]\n* [[Mail Pouch]]\n* [[Oliver Twist Tobacco|Oliver Twist]]\n* [[Red Man]]\n* [[Skoal (tobacco)|Skoal]]\n* [[Stoker's]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dipping tobacco]]\n* [[Herbal smokeless tobacco]]\n* [[Smokeless tobacco]]\n* [[Naswar]]\n* [[Big League Chew]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Drug use}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chewing Tobacco}}\n[[Category:Tobacco]]\n[[Category:Habits]]\n[[Category:Masticatories]]\n", "name_user": "Manu de hanoi", "label": "safe", "comment": "expectorate means taking off of the throat or lungs, but the juices are not there, they are in the mouth. Spat is the correct word", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chewing_tobacco"}
{"title_page": "Spamdexing", "text_new": "{{short description|Deliberate manipulation of search engine indexes}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\nIn [[digital marketing]] and [[online advertising]], '''spamdexing''' (also known as '''search engine spam''', '''search engine poisoning''', '''[[Black hat hacker|black-hat]] [[search engine optimization]] (SEO)''', '''search spam''' or '''web spam''')<ref>[http://searchengineland.com/what-is-search-engine-spam-the-video-edition-15202.php  ''SearchEngineLand'', Danny Sullivan's video explanation of Search Engine Spam, October 2008] . Retrieved 2008-11-13.</ref> is the deliberate manipulation of [[Web search engine|search engine]] [[Index (search engine)|indexes]]. It involves a number of methods, such as [[link building]] and repeating unrelated phrases, to manipulate the relevance or prominence of resources indexed, in a manner inconsistent with the purpose of the indexing system.<ref name=\"wspy\">\"Word Spy - spamdexing\" (definition), March 2003, webpage:[http://www.wordspy.com/words/spamdexing.asp WordSpy-spamdexing].</ref><ref name=Gyongyi>{{Citation | first=Zolt\u00e1n | last=Gy\u00f6ngyi | authorlink1=Zolt\u00e1n Gy\u00f6ngyi | first2=Hector | last2=Garcia-Molina | contribution=Web spam taxonomy | contribution-url=http://airweb.cse.lehigh.edu/2005/gyongyi.pdf | title=Proceedings of the First International Workshop on Adversarial Information Retrieval on the Web (AIRWeb), 2005 in The 14th International World Wide Web Conference (WWW 2005) May 10, (Tue)-14 (Sat), 2005, Nippon Convention Center (Makuhari Messe), Chiba, Japan. | year=2005 | publisher=ACM Press | place=New York, NY | isbn=1-59593-046-9 | authorlink2=Hector Garcia-Molina }}</ref>\n\nSpamdexing could be considered to be a part of [[search engine optimization]], although there are many search engine optimization methods that improve the quality and appearance of the content of web sites and serve content useful to many users.<ref name=Ntoulas>{{Citation | first=Alexandros | last=Ntoulas |author-link=Alexandros Ntoulas | first2=Mark | last2=Manasse | author2-link=Mark Manasse | first3=Marc | last3=Najork | author3-link=Marc Najork | first4=Dennis | last4=Fetterly | author4-link=Dennis Fetterly | contribution=Detecting Spam Web Pages through Content Analysis | title=The 15th International World Wide Web Conference (WWW 2006) May 23\u201326, 2006, Edinburgh, Scotland. | year=2006 | publisher=ACM Press | place=New York, NY | isbn=1-59593-323-9 }}</ref> \n  \nSearch engines use a variety of [[algorithm]]s to determine relevancy ranking. Some of these include determining whether the search term appears in the [[body text]] or [[Uniform Resource Locator|URL]] of a [[web page]]. Many search engines check for instances of spamdexing and will remove suspect pages from their indexes. Also, search-engine operators can quickly block the results listing from entire websites that use spamdexing, perhaps in response to user complaints of false matches. The rise of spamdexing in the mid-1990s made the leading search engines of the time less useful. Using unethical methods to make websites rank higher in search engine results than they otherwise would is commonly referred to in the SEO (search engine optimization) industry as \"black-hat SEO\". These methods are more focused on breaking the search-engine-promotion rules and guidelines. In addition to this, the perpetrators run the risk of their websites being severely penalized by the [[Google Panda]] and [[Google Penguin]] search-results ranking algorithms.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ann |last=Smarty |title=What Is BlackHat SEO? 5 Definitions |url=http://www.searchenginejournal.com/what-is-blackhat-seo-5-definitions/8151/ |work=Search Engine Journal |date=2008-12-17 |accessdate=2012-07-05 }}</ref>\n\nCommon spamdexing techniques can be classified into two broad classes: ''content spam''<ref name=\"Ntoulas\"/> (or ''term spam'') and ''link spam''.<ref name=Gyongyi/>\n\n==History==\nThe earliest known reference<ref name=\"wspy\"/> to the term ''spamdexing'' is by Eric Convey in his article \"Porn sneaks way back on Web,\" [[The Boston Herald]], May 22, 1996, where he said:\n\n<blockquote>The problem arises when site operators load their Web pages with hundreds of extraneous terms so search engines will list them among legitimate addresses.\nThe process is called \"spamdexing,\" a combination of [[spamming]] \u2014 the Internet term for sending users unsolicited information \u2014 and \"[[Web indexing|indexing]].\"<ref name=wspy/></blockquote>\n\n==Content spam==\nThese techniques involve altering the logical view that a search engine has over the page's contents. They all aim at variants of the [[vector space model]] for information retrieval on text collections.\n\n===Keyword stuffing===\nKeyword stuffing involves the calculated placement of keywords within a page to raise the keyword count, variety, and density of the page. This is useful to make a page appear to be relevant for a [[web crawler]] in a way that makes it more likely to be found. Example: A promoter of a [[Ponzi scheme]] wants to attract web surfers to a site where he advertises his scam. He places hidden text appropriate for a fan page of a popular music group on his page, hoping that the page will be listed as a fan site and receive many visits from music lovers. Older versions of indexing programs simply counted how often a keyword appeared, and used that to determine relevance levels. Most modern search engines have the ability to analyze a page for keyword stuffing and determine whether the frequency is consistent with other sites created specifically to attract search engine traffic. Also, large webpages are truncated, so that massive dictionary lists cannot be indexed on a single webpage.{{cn|date=December 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2012/03/21/dangers-of-keyword-stuffing|title=The Dangers of SEO Keyword Stuffing|last=Megan|first=Marrs|date=2017|website=https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2012/03/21/dangers-of-keyword-stuffing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19/4/2020}}</ref> (However, spammers can circumvent this webpage-size limitation merely by setting up multiple webpages, either independently or linked to each other.)\n  \n=== Hidden or invisible text ===\nUnrelated [[hidden text]] is disguised by making it the same color as the background, using a tiny font size, or hiding it within [[HTML]] code such as \"no frame\" sections, [[alt attribute]]s, zero-sized [[Span and div|DIVs]], and \"no script\" sections. People manually screening red-flagged websites for a search-engine company might temporarily or permanently block an entire website for having invisible text on some of its pages. However, hidden text is not always spamdexing: it can also be used to enhance [[web accessibility|accessibility]].\n\n===Meta-tag stuffing===\nThis involves repeating keywords in the [[meta tag]]s, and using meta keywords that are unrelated to the site's content. This tactic has been ineffective since 2005.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Doorway pages===\n\"Gateway\" or [[doorway page]]s are low-quality web pages created with very little content, but are instead stuffed with very similar keywords and phrases. They are designed to rank highly within the search results, but serve no purpose to visitors looking for information. A doorway page will generally have \"click here to enter\" on the page; autoforwarding can also be used for this purpose. In 2006, Google ousted vehicle manufacturer [[BMW]] for using \"doorway pages\" to the company's German site, BMW.de.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Segal |title=The Dirty Little Secrets of Search |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/business/13search.html?pagewanted=all |work=[[The NY Times]] |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2012-07-03 }}</ref>\n\n===Scraper sites===\n[[Scraper sites]] are created using various programs designed to \"scrape\" search-engine results pages or other sources of content and create \"content\" for a website.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} The specific presentation of content on these sites is unique, but is merely an amalgamation of content taken from other sources, often without permission. Such websites are generally full of advertising (such as [[pay per click|pay-per-click]] ads), or they redirect the user to other sites. It is even feasible for scraper sites to outrank original websites for their own information and organization names.\n\n===Article spinning===\n[[Article spinning]] involves rewriting existing articles, as opposed to merely scraping content from other sites, to avoid penalties imposed by search engines for [[duplicate content]]. This process is undertaken by hired writers or automated using a [[thesaurus]] database or a [[neural network]].\n\n===Machine translation===\nSimilarly to [[article spinning]], some sites use machine translation to render their content in several languages, with no human editing, resulting in unintelligible texts that nonetheless continue to be indexed by search engines, thereby attracting traffic.\n \n===Pages with no information related to page title===\n{{Confusing|section|date=July 2014}}\nPublishing web pages that contain information that is unrelated to the title is a misleading practice known as deception. Despite being a target for penalties from the leading search engines that rank pages, deception is a common practice in some types of sites, including dictionary and encyclopedia sites.\n\n==Link spam==\n'''Link spam''' is defined as links between pages that are present for reasons\nother than merit.<ref name=Davison>{{Citation\n  | first=Brian | last=Davison | author-link=Brian D. Davison\n  | contribution = Recognizing Nepotistic Links on the Web\n  | contribution-url = http://www.cse.lehigh.edu/~brian/pubs/2000/aaaiws/aaai2000ws.pdf\n  | title=AAAI-2000 workshop on Artificial Intelligence for Web Search\n  | year=2000 | pages=23\u201328 | publisher=AAAI Press | place=Boston\n}}</ref> Link spam takes advantage of link-based ranking algorithms, which gives [[websites]] higher rankings the more other highly ranked websites link to it. These techniques also aim at influencing other link-based ranking techniques such as the [[HITS algorithm]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n===Link farms===\n{{main|Link farm}}\nLink farms are tightly-knit networks of websites that link to each other for the sole purpose of gaming the search engine ranking algorithms. These are also known facetiously as ''mutual admiration societies''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.sims.berkeley.edu/courses/is141/f05/lectures/se-course-intro.pdf|title=Search Engines:Technology, Society, and Business - Marti Hearst, Aug 29, 2005|author=|date=|website=berkeley.edu}}</ref> Use of links farms has been greatly reduced after Google launched the first Panda Update in February 2011, which introduced significant improvements in its spam-detection algorithm.\n\n=== Private blog networks ===\nBlog networks (PBNs) are a group of authoritative websites used as a source of contextual links that point to the owner's main website to achieve higher search engine ranking. Owners of PBN websites use expired domains or [[Domain name auction|auction domains]] that have [[backlink]]s from high-authority websites. Google targeted and penalized PBN users on several occasions with several massive deindexing campaigns since 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-targets-sites-using-private-blog-networks-manual-action-ranking-penalties-204000|title=Google Targets Sites Using Private Blog Networks With Manual Action Ranking Penalties|date=2014-09-23|newspaper=Search Engine Land|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Hidden links===\nPutting [[hyperlink]]s where visitors will not see them to increase [[link popularity]]. Highlighted link text can help rank a webpage higher for matching that phrase.\n\n===Sybil attack===\nA [[Sybil attack]] is the forging of multiple identities for malicious intent, named after the famous [[multiple personality disorder]] patient \"[[Sybil (Schreiber book)|Sybil]]\". A spammer may create multiple web sites at different [[domain name]]s that all link to each other, such as fake blogs (known as [[spam blogs]]).\n\n===Spam blogs===\n{{main|Spam blog}}\nSpam blogs are blogs created solely for commercial promotion and the passage of link authority to target sites. Often these \"splogs\" are designed in a misleading manner that will give the effect of a legitimate website but upon close inspection will often be written using spinning software or be very poorly written and barely readable content. They are similar in nature to link farms.\n\n===Guest blog spam===\n\nGuest blog spam is the process of placing guest blogs on websites for the sole purpose of gaining a link to another website or websites. Unfortunately, these are often confused with legitimate forms of guest blogging with other motives than placing links. This technique was made famous by Matt Cutts, who publicly declared \"war\" against this form of link spam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mattcutts.com/blog/guest-blogging/|title=The decay and fall of guest blogging for SEO|author=|date=20 January 2014|website=mattcutts.com}}</ref>\n\n===Buying expired domains===\n{{See also|Domaining}}\nSome link spammers utilize expired domain crawler software or monitor DNS records for domains that will expire soon, then buy them when they expire and replace the pages with links to their pages. However, it is possible but not confirmed that Google resets the link data on expired domains. {{citation needed|date=June 2015}} To maintain all previous Google ranking data for the domain, it is advisable that a buyer grab the domain before it is \"dropped\". \n   \nSome of these techniques may be applied for creating a [[Google bomb]] \u2014 that is, to cooperate with other users to boost the ranking of a particular page for a particular query.\n\n===Cookie stuffing===\n[[Cookie stuffing]] involves placing an [[affiliate marketing|affiliate]] tracking cookie on a website visitor's computer without their knowledge, which will then generate revenue for the person doing the cookie stuffing. This not only generates fraudulent affiliate sales, but also has the potential to overwrite other affiliates' cookies, essentially stealing their legitimately earned commissions.\n\n=== Using world-writable pages ===\n{{main|Forum spam}}\nWeb sites that can be edited by users can be used by spamdexers to insert links to spam sites if the appropriate anti-spam measures are not taken.\n\nAutomated [[spambot]]s can rapidly make the user-editable portion of a site unusable.\nProgrammers have developed a variety of automated [[Forum spam#Spam prevention|spam prevention techniques]] to block or at least slow down spambots.\n\n====Spam in blogs====\n{{main|Spam in blogs}}\n[[Spam in blogs]] is the placing or solicitation of links randomly on other sites, placing a desired keyword into the hyperlinked text of the inbound link. Guest books, forums, blogs, and any site that accepts visitors' comments are particular targets and are often victims of drive-by spamming where automated software creates nonsense posts with links that are usually irrelevant and unwanted.\n\n====Comment spam====\nComment spam is a form of link spam that has arisen in web pages that allow dynamic user editing such as [[wikis]], [[blogs]], and [[guestbooks]]. It can be problematic because [[Software agent|agents]] can be written that automatically randomly select a user edited web page, such as a Wikipedia article, and add spamming links.<ref name=Mishne>{{cite conference\n  | first = Gilad | last = Mishne | authorlink = Gilad Mishne |author2=David Carmel |author3=Ronny Lempel\n  | title = Blocking Blog Spam with Language Model Disagreement\n  | booktitle = Proceedings of the First International Workshop on Adversarial Information Retrieval on the Web\n  | pages= | publisher= | year=2005 | url = http://airweb.cse.lehigh.edu/2005/mishne.pdf\n  | accessdate = 2007-10-24 }}</ref>\n\n====Wiki spam====\nWiki spam is a form of link spam on wiki pages. The spammer uses the open editability of wiki systems to place links from the wiki site to the spam site. The subject of the spam site is often unrelated to the wiki page where the link is added.\n\n====Referrer log spamming====\n[[Referrer spam]] takes place when a spam perpetrator or facilitator accesses a [[web page]] (the ''referee''), by following a link from another web page (the ''[[referrer]]''), so that the referee is given the address of the referrer by the person's Internet browser. Some [[website]]s have a referrer log which shows which pages link to that site. By having a [[Internet bot|robot]] randomly access many sites enough times, with a message or specific address given as the referrer, that message or Internet address then appears in the referrer log of those sites that have referrer logs. Since some [[Web search engine]]s base the importance of sites on the number of different sites linking to them, referrer-log spam may increase the search engine rankings of the spammer's sites.  Also, site administrators who notice the referrer log entries in their logs may follow the link back to the spammer's referrer page.\n\n==== Countermeasures ====\nBecause of the large amount of spam posted to user-editable webpages, Google proposed a nofollow tag that could be embedded with links. A link-based search engine, such as Google's [[PageRank]] system, will not use the link to increase the score of the linked website if the link carries a nofollow tag. This ensures that spamming links to user-editable websites will not raise the sites ranking with search engines. Nofollow is used by several major websites, including [[WordPress|Wordpress]], [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]] and [[Wikipedia]].{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Other types==\n\n===Mirror websites===\nA [[mirror website|mirror site]] is the hosting of multiple websites with conceptually similar content but using different [[Uniform Resource Locator|URLs]]. Some search engines give a higher rank to results where the keyword searched for appears in the URL.\n\n===URL redirection===\n[[URL redirection]] is the taking of the user to another page without his or her intervention, ''e.g.'', using [[META refresh]] tags, [[Adobe Flash|Flash]],  [[JavaScript]], [[Java (programming language)|Java]] or [[Server side redirect]]s. However, [[HTTP 301|301 Redirect]], or permanent redirect, is not considered as a malicious behavior.\n\n===Cloaking===\n[[Cloaking]] refers to any of several means to serve a page to the search-engine [[Web crawler|spider]] that is different from that seen by human users. It can be an attempt to mislead search engines regarding the content on a particular web site. Cloaking, however, can also be used to ethically increase accessibility of a site to users with disabilities or provide human users with content that search engines aren't able to process or parse. It is also used to deliver content based on a user's location; Google itself uses [[IP delivery]], a form of cloaking, to deliver results. Another form of cloaking is ''code swapping'', ''i.e.'', optimizing a page for top ranking and then swapping another page in its place once a top ranking is achieved. Google refers to these type of redirects as ''Sneaky Redirects''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/2721217?hl=en|title=Sneaky redirects - Search Console Help|author=|date=|website=support.google.com}}</ref>\n\n== Countermeasures ==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2017}}\n\n=== By search engine maintainer ===\nSpamdexed pages are sometimes eliminated from search results by the search engine.\n\n=== By search engine user ===\nUsers can craft at search keyword, for example, a keyword preceding \"-\" (minus) will eliminate sites that contains the keyword in their pages or in their domain of URL of the pages from search result. Example, search keyword \"-naver\" will eliminate sites that contains word \"naver\" in their pages and the pages whose domain of URL contains \"naver\".\n\n=== Google Chrome extension ===\n\nGoogle itself launched the [[Google Chrome]] extension \"Personal Blocklist (by Google)\" in 2011 as part of countermeasures against [[content farm]]ing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gigazine.net/news/20161129-personal-blocklist-by-google/|title=Google\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c\u306e\u60aa\u8cea\u306a\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8\u3092\u975e\u8868\u793a\uff06\u901a\u5831\u3057\u691c\u7d22\u54c1\u8cea\u30a2\u30c3\u30d7\u306b\u8ca2\u732e\u3067\u304d\u308bGoogle\u516c\u5f0fChrome\u62e1\u5f35\u6a5f\u80fd\u300cPersonal Blocklist\u300d|author=|date=|website=gigazine.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/googles-personal-blocklist-delete-google-search-results-on-chrome-64757|title=New: Block Sites From Google Results Using Chrome's \"Personal Blocklist\" - Search Engine Land|author=|date=14 February 2011|website=searchengineland.com}}</ref>  As of 2018, the extension only works with the [[Personal Computer|PC]] version of Google Chrome.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Adversarial information retrieval]]\n* [[Index (search engine)]] \u2013 overview of search engine indexing technology\n* [[TrustRank]]\n* [[Web scraping]]\n*[[Microsoft SmartScreen]]\n*[[Windows Defender]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n\n{{Spamming}}\n\n[[Category:Black hat search engine optimization]]\n[[Category:Spamming]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Deliberate manipulation of search engine indexes}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\nIn [[digital marketing]] and [[online advertising]], '''spamdexing''' (also known as '''search engine spam''', '''search engine poisoning''', '''[[Black hat hacker|black-hat]] [[search engine optimization]] (SEO)''', '''search spam''' or '''web spam''')<ref>[http://searchengineland.com/what-is-search-engine-spam-the-video-edition-15202.php  ''SearchEngineLand'', Danny Sullivan's video explanation of Search Engine Spam, October 2008] . Retrieved 2008-11-13.</ref> is the deliberate manipulation of [[Web search engine|search engine]] [[Index (search engine)|indexes]]. It involves a number of methods, such as [[link building]] and repeating unrelated phrases, to manipulate the relevance or prominence of resources indexed, in a manner inconsistent with the purpose of the indexing system.<ref name=\"wspy\">\"Word Spy - spamdexing\" (definition), March 2003, webpage:[http://www.wordspy.com/words/spamdexing.asp WordSpy-spamdexing].</ref><ref name=Gyongyi>{{Citation | first=Zolt\u00e1n | last=Gy\u00f6ngyi | authorlink1=Zolt\u00e1n Gy\u00f6ngyi | first2=Hector | last2=Garcia-Molina | contribution=Web spam taxonomy | contribution-url=http://airweb.cse.lehigh.edu/2005/gyongyi.pdf | title=Proceedings of the First International Workshop on Adversarial Information Retrieval on the Web (AIRWeb), 2005 in The 14th International World Wide Web Conference (WWW 2005) May 10, (Tue)-14 (Sat), 2005, Nippon Convention Center (Makuhari Messe), Chiba, Japan. | year=2005 | publisher=ACM Press | place=New York, NY | isbn=1-59593-046-9 | authorlink2=Hector Garcia-Molina }}</ref>\n\nSpamdexing could be considered to be a part of [[search engine optimization]], although there are many search engine optimization methods that improve the quality and appearance of the content of web sites and serve content useful to many users.<ref name=Ntoulas>{{Citation | first=Alexandros | last=Ntoulas |author-link=Alexandros Ntoulas | first2=Mark | last2=Manasse | author2-link=Mark Manasse | first3=Marc | last3=Najork | author3-link=Marc Najork | first4=Dennis | last4=Fetterly | author4-link=Dennis Fetterly | contribution=Detecting Spam Web Pages through Content Analysis | title=The 15th International World Wide Web Conference (WWW 2006) May 23\u201326, 2006, Edinburgh, Scotland. | year=2006 | publisher=ACM Press | place=New York, NY | isbn=1-59593-323-9 }}</ref> \n  \nSearch engines use a variety of [[algorithm]]s to determine relevancy ranking. Some of these include determining whether the search term appears in the [[body text]] or [[Uniform Resource Locator|URL]] of a [[web page]]. Many search engines check for instances of spamdexing and will remove suspect pages from their indexes. Also, search-engine operators can quickly block the results listing from entire websites that use spamdexing, perhaps in response to user complaints of false matches. The rise of spamdexing in the mid-1990s made the leading search engines of the time less useful. Using unethical methods to make websites rank higher in search engine results than they otherwise would is commonly referred to in the SEO (search engine optimization) industry as \"black-hat SEO\". These methods are more focused on breaking the search-engine-promotion rules and guidelines. In addition to this, the perpetrators run the risk of their websites being severely penalized by the [[Google Panda]] and [[Google Penguin]] search-results ranking algorithms.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ann |last=Smarty |title=What Is BlackHat SEO? 5 Definitions |url=http://www.searchenginejournal.com/what-is-blackhat-seo-5-definitions/8151/ |work=Search Engine Journal |date=2008-12-17 |accessdate=2012-07-05 }}</ref>\n\nCommon spamdexing techniques can be classified into two broad classes: ''content spam''<ref name=\"Ntoulas\"/> (or ''term spam'') and ''link spam''.<ref name=Gyongyi/>\n\n==History==\nThe earliest known reference<ref name=\"wspy\"/> to the term ''spamdexing'' is by Eric Convey in his article \"Porn sneaks way back on Web,\" [[The Boston Herald]], May 22, 1996, where he said:\n\n<blockquote>The problem arises when site operators load their Web pages with hundreds of extraneous terms so search engines will list them among legitimate addresses.\nThe process is called \"spamdexing,\" a combination of [[spamming]] \u2014 the Internet term for sending users unsolicited information \u2014 and \"[[Web indexing|indexing]].\"<ref name=wspy/></blockquote>\n\n==Content spam==\nThese techniques involve altering the logical view that a search engine has over the page's contents. They all aim at variants of the [[vector space model]] for information retrieval on text collections.\n\n===Keyword stuffing===\nKeyword stuffing involves the calculated placement of keywords within a page to raise the keyword count, variety, and density of the page. This is useful to make a page appear to be relevant for a [[web crawler]] in a way that makes it more likely to be found. Example: A promoter of a [[Ponzi scheme]] wants to attract web surfers to a site where he advertises his scam. He places hidden text appropriate for a fan page of a popular music group on his page, hoping that the page will be listed as a fan site and receive many visits from music lovers. Older versions of indexing programs simply counted how often a keyword appeared, and used that to determine relevance levels. Most modern search engines have the ability to analyze a page for keyword stuffing and determine whether the frequency is consistent with other sites created specifically to attract search engine traffic. Also, large webpages are truncated, so that massive dictionary lists cannot be indexed on a single webpage.{{cn|date=December 2019}} (However, spammers can circumvent this webpage-size limitation merely by setting up multiple webpages, either independently or linked to each other.)\n  \n=== Hidden or invisible text ===\nUnrelated [[hidden text]] is disguised by making it the same color as the background, using a tiny font size, or hiding it within [[HTML]] code such as \"no frame\" sections, [[alt attribute]]s, zero-sized [[Span and div|DIVs]], and \"no script\" sections. People manually screening red-flagged websites for a search-engine company might temporarily or permanently block an entire website for having invisible text on some of its pages. However, hidden text is not always spamdexing: it can also be used to enhance [[web accessibility|accessibility]].\n\n===Meta-tag stuffing===\nThis involves repeating keywords in the [[meta tag]]s, and using meta keywords that are unrelated to the site's content. This tactic has been ineffective since 2005.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Doorway pages===\n\"Gateway\" or [[doorway page]]s are low-quality web pages created with very little content, but are instead stuffed with very similar keywords and phrases. They are designed to rank highly within the search results, but serve no purpose to visitors looking for information. A doorway page will generally have \"click here to enter\" on the page; autoforwarding can also be used for this purpose. In 2006, Google ousted vehicle manufacturer [[BMW]] for using \"doorway pages\" to the company's German site, BMW.de.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Segal |title=The Dirty Little Secrets of Search |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/business/13search.html?pagewanted=all |work=[[The NY Times]] |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2012-07-03 }}</ref>\n\n===Scraper sites===\n[[Scraper sites]] are created using various programs designed to \"scrape\" search-engine results pages or other sources of content and create \"content\" for a website.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} The specific presentation of content on these sites is unique, but is merely an amalgamation of content taken from other sources, often without permission. Such websites are generally full of advertising (such as [[pay per click|pay-per-click]] ads), or they redirect the user to other sites. It is even feasible for scraper sites to outrank original websites for their own information and organization names.\n\n===Article spinning===\n[[Article spinning]] involves rewriting existing articles, as opposed to merely scraping content from other sites, to avoid penalties imposed by search engines for [[duplicate content]]. This process is undertaken by hired writers or automated using a [[thesaurus]] database or a [[neural network]].\n\n===Machine translation===\nSimilarly to [[article spinning]], some sites use machine translation to render their content in several languages, with no human editing, resulting in unintelligible texts that nonetheless continue to be indexed by search engines, thereby attracting traffic.\n \n===Pages with no information related to page title===\n{{Confusing|section|date=July 2014}}\nPublishing web pages that contain information that is unrelated to the title is a misleading practice known as deception. Despite being a target for penalties from the leading search engines that rank pages, deception is a common practice in some types of sites, including dictionary and encyclopedia sites.\n\n==Link spam==\n'''Link spam''' is defined as links between pages that are present for reasons\nother than merit.<ref name=Davison>{{Citation\n  | first=Brian | last=Davison | author-link=Brian D. Davison\n  | contribution = Recognizing Nepotistic Links on the Web\n  | contribution-url = http://www.cse.lehigh.edu/~brian/pubs/2000/aaaiws/aaai2000ws.pdf\n  | title=AAAI-2000 workshop on Artificial Intelligence for Web Search\n  | year=2000 | pages=23\u201328 | publisher=AAAI Press | place=Boston\n}}</ref> Link spam takes advantage of link-based ranking algorithms, which gives [[websites]] higher rankings the more other highly ranked websites link to it. These techniques also aim at influencing other link-based ranking techniques such as the [[HITS algorithm]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n===Link farms===\n{{main|Link farm}}\nLink farms are tightly-knit networks of websites that link to each other for the sole purpose of gaming the search engine ranking algorithms. These are also known facetiously as ''mutual admiration societies''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.sims.berkeley.edu/courses/is141/f05/lectures/se-course-intro.pdf|title=Search Engines:Technology, Society, and Business - Marti Hearst, Aug 29, 2005|author=|date=|website=berkeley.edu}}</ref> Use of links farms has been greatly reduced after Google launched the first Panda Update in February 2011, which introduced significant improvements in its spam-detection algorithm.\n\n=== Private blog networks ===\nBlog networks (PBNs) are a group of authoritative websites used as a source of contextual links that point to the owner's main website to achieve higher search engine ranking. Owners of PBN websites use expired domains or [[Domain name auction|auction domains]] that have [[backlink]]s from high-authority websites. Google targeted and penalized PBN users on several occasions with several massive deindexing campaigns since 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-targets-sites-using-private-blog-networks-manual-action-ranking-penalties-204000|title=Google Targets Sites Using Private Blog Networks With Manual Action Ranking Penalties|date=2014-09-23|newspaper=Search Engine Land|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Hidden links===\nPutting [[hyperlink]]s where visitors will not see them to increase [[link popularity]]. Highlighted link text can help rank a webpage higher for matching that phrase.\n\n===Sybil attack===\nA [[Sybil attack]] is the forging of multiple identities for malicious intent, named after the famous [[multiple personality disorder]] patient \"[[Sybil (Schreiber book)|Sybil]]\". A spammer may create multiple web sites at different [[domain name]]s that all link to each other, such as fake blogs (known as [[spam blogs]]).\n\n===Spam blogs===\n{{main|Spam blog}}\nSpam blogs are blogs created solely for commercial promotion and the passage of link authority to target sites. Often these \"splogs\" are designed in a misleading manner that will give the effect of a legitimate website but upon close inspection will often be written using spinning software or be very poorly written and barely readable content. They are similar in nature to link farms.\n\n===Guest blog spam===\n\nGuest blog spam is the process of placing guest blogs on websites for the sole purpose of gaining a link to another website or websites. Unfortunately, these are often confused with legitimate forms of guest blogging with other motives than placing links. This technique was made famous by Matt Cutts, who publicly declared \"war\" against this form of link spam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mattcutts.com/blog/guest-blogging/|title=The decay and fall of guest blogging for SEO|author=|date=20 January 2014|website=mattcutts.com}}</ref>\n\n===Buying expired domains===\n{{See also|Domaining}}\nSome link spammers utilize expired domain crawler software or monitor DNS records for domains that will expire soon, then buy them when they expire and replace the pages with links to their pages. However, it is possible but not confirmed that Google resets the link data on expired domains. {{citation needed|date=June 2015}} To maintain all previous Google ranking data for the domain, it is advisable that a buyer grab the domain before it is \"dropped\". \n   \nSome of these techniques may be applied for creating a [[Google bomb]] \u2014 that is, to cooperate with other users to boost the ranking of a particular page for a particular query.\n\n===Cookie stuffing===\n[[Cookie stuffing]] involves placing an [[affiliate marketing|affiliate]] tracking cookie on a website visitor's computer without their knowledge, which will then generate revenue for the person doing the cookie stuffing. This not only generates fraudulent affiliate sales, but also has the potential to overwrite other affiliates' cookies, essentially stealing their legitimately earned commissions.\n\n=== Using world-writable pages ===\n{{main|Forum spam}}\nWeb sites that can be edited by users can be used by spamdexers to insert links to spam sites if the appropriate anti-spam measures are not taken.\n\nAutomated [[spambot]]s can rapidly make the user-editable portion of a site unusable.\nProgrammers have developed a variety of automated [[Forum spam#Spam prevention|spam prevention techniques]] to block or at least slow down spambots.\n\n====Spam in blogs====\n{{main|Spam in blogs}}\n[[Spam in blogs]] is the placing or solicitation of links randomly on other sites, placing a desired keyword into the hyperlinked text of the inbound link. Guest books, forums, blogs, and any site that accepts visitors' comments are particular targets and are often victims of drive-by spamming where automated software creates nonsense posts with links that are usually irrelevant and unwanted.\n\n====Comment spam====\nComment spam is a form of link spam that has arisen in web pages that allow dynamic user editing such as [[wikis]], [[blogs]], and [[guestbooks]]. It can be problematic because [[Software agent|agents]] can be written that automatically randomly select a user edited web page, such as a Wikipedia article, and add spamming links.<ref name=Mishne>{{cite conference\n  | first = Gilad | last = Mishne | authorlink = Gilad Mishne |author2=David Carmel |author3=Ronny Lempel\n  | title = Blocking Blog Spam with Language Model Disagreement\n  | booktitle = Proceedings of the First International Workshop on Adversarial Information Retrieval on the Web\n  | pages= | publisher= | year=2005 | url = http://airweb.cse.lehigh.edu/2005/mishne.pdf\n  | accessdate = 2007-10-24 }}</ref>\n\n====Wiki spam====\nWiki spam is a form of link spam on wiki pages. The spammer uses the open editability of wiki systems to place links from the wiki site to the spam site. The subject of the spam site is often unrelated to the wiki page where the link is added.\n\n====Referrer log spamming====\n[[Referrer spam]] takes place when a spam perpetrator or facilitator accesses a [[web page]] (the ''referee''), by following a link from another web page (the ''[[referrer]]''), so that the referee is given the address of the referrer by the person's Internet browser. Some [[website]]s have a referrer log which shows which pages link to that site. By having a [[Internet bot|robot]] randomly access many sites enough times, with a message or specific address given as the referrer, that message or Internet address then appears in the referrer log of those sites that have referrer logs. Since some [[Web search engine]]s base the importance of sites on the number of different sites linking to them, referrer-log spam may increase the search engine rankings of the spammer's sites.  Also, site administrators who notice the referrer log entries in their logs may follow the link back to the spammer's referrer page.\n\n==== Countermeasures ====\nBecause of the large amount of spam posted to user-editable webpages, Google proposed a nofollow tag that could be embedded with links. A link-based search engine, such as Google's [[PageRank]] system, will not use the link to increase the score of the linked website if the link carries a nofollow tag. This ensures that spamming links to user-editable websites will not raise the sites ranking with search engines. Nofollow is used by several major websites, including [[WordPress|Wordpress]], [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]] and [[Wikipedia]].{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Other types==\n\n===Mirror websites===\nA [[mirror website|mirror site]] is the hosting of multiple websites with conceptually similar content but using different [[Uniform Resource Locator|URLs]]. Some search engines give a higher rank to results where the keyword searched for appears in the URL.\n\n===URL redirection===\n[[URL redirection]] is the taking of the user to another page without his or her intervention, ''e.g.'', using [[META refresh]] tags, [[Adobe Flash|Flash]],  [[JavaScript]], [[Java (programming language)|Java]] or [[Server side redirect]]s. However, [[HTTP 301|301 Redirect]], or permanent redirect, is not considered as a malicious behavior.\n\n===Cloaking===\n[[Cloaking]] refers to any of several means to serve a page to the search-engine [[Web crawler|spider]] that is different from that seen by human users. It can be an attempt to mislead search engines regarding the content on a particular web site. Cloaking, however, can also be used to ethically increase accessibility of a site to users with disabilities or provide human users with content that search engines aren't able to process or parse. It is also used to deliver content based on a user's location; Google itself uses [[IP delivery]], a form of cloaking, to deliver results. Another form of cloaking is ''code swapping'', ''i.e.'', optimizing a page for top ranking and then swapping another page in its place once a top ranking is achieved. Google refers to these type of redirects as ''Sneaky Redirects''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/2721217?hl=en|title=Sneaky redirects - Search Console Help|author=|date=|website=support.google.com}}</ref>\n\n== Countermeasures ==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2017}}\n\n=== By search engine maintainer ===\nSpamdexed pages are sometimes eliminated from search results by the search engine.\n\n=== By search engine user ===\nUsers can craft at search keyword, for example, a keyword preceding \"-\" (minus) will eliminate sites that contains the keyword in their pages or in their domain of URL of the pages from search result. Example, search keyword \"-naver\" will eliminate sites that contains word \"naver\" in their pages and the pages whose domain of URL contains \"naver\".\n\n=== Google Chrome extension ===\n\nGoogle itself launched the [[Google Chrome]] extension \"Personal Blocklist (by Google)\" in 2011 as part of countermeasures against [[content farm]]ing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gigazine.net/news/20161129-personal-blocklist-by-google/|title=Google\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c\u306e\u60aa\u8cea\u306a\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8\u3092\u975e\u8868\u793a\uff06\u901a\u5831\u3057\u691c\u7d22\u54c1\u8cea\u30a2\u30c3\u30d7\u306b\u8ca2\u732e\u3067\u304d\u308bGoogle\u516c\u5f0fChrome\u62e1\u5f35\u6a5f\u80fd\u300cPersonal Blocklist\u300d|author=|date=|website=gigazine.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/googles-personal-blocklist-delete-google-search-results-on-chrome-64757|title=New: Block Sites From Google Results Using Chrome's \"Personal Blocklist\" - Search Engine Land|author=|date=14 February 2011|website=searchengineland.com}}</ref>  As of 2018, the extension only works with the [[Personal Computer|PC]] version of Google Chrome.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Adversarial information retrieval]]\n* [[Index (search engine)]] \u2013 overview of search engine indexing technology\n* [[TrustRank]]\n* [[Web scraping]]\n*[[Microsoft SmartScreen]]\n*[[Windows Defender]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n\n{{Spamming}}\n\n[[Category:Black hat search engine optimization]]\n[[Category:Spamming]]\n", "name_user": "Benlow98", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spamdexing"}
{"title_page": "Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{More medical citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\n'''Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' consists of [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] and [[disinformation]] that emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention and treatment surrounding the [[COVID-19]] disease and the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ensuing pandemic]] related to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | access-date=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and [[misinformation]] can be spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of countries such as China, [[Iran]] and [[Turkmenistan]],<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/04/did-turkmenistan-really-ban-the-word-coronavirus/|title=Did Turkmenistan Really Ban the Word 'Coronavirus'?|last=Putz|first=Catherine| name-list-format = vanc |website=thediplomat.com|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> and they may be propagated by celebrities, politicians, or other prominent public figures.<ref name=20200408theguardian>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/apr/08/influencers-being-key-distributors-of-coronavirus-fake-news |title= Influencers among 'key distributors' of coronavirus misinformation |first=Jim |last=Waterson | name-list-format = vanc |date= April 8, 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=March 31, 2020|publisher=Reports Without Borders|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><section begin=\"Intro\" /> Medical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease has circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |access-date=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name = \"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse | name-list-format = vanc |title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy/><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\"/><ref name=RunningList/><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\"/><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |work=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |access-date=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Combative efforts==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref name=un1056672>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |access-date=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked several claims as false, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking large amounts of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water prevents infection.<ref name=20200317cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref name=20200206nytimes>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref name=20200201reuters>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for health products whose prices were \"significantly higher than recent prices offered on or off Amazon\", although numerous items were \"still being sold at unusually high prices\" as of February 28<ref>.{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|access-date = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation have occurred across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala | name-list-format = vanc |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China; many of them later spread to Korea and the United States, prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung| name-list-format = vanc |author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nThe media has praised Wikipedia's coverage of COVID-19 and its combating the inclusion of misinformation through efforts led by the [[meta:Wiki Project Med Foundation|Wiki Project Med Foundation]] and the English-language Wikipedia's [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Medicine|WikiProject Medicine]], among other groups.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.com/story/how-wikipedia-prevents-spread-coronavirus-misinformation/ | title = How Wikipedia Prevents the Spread of Coronavirus Misinformation | first=  Noam | last = Cohem | date = March 15, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/coronavirus-wikipedia-policies.html | title = The Coronavirus Is Stress-Testing Wikipedia's Policies | first= Stephan | last= Harrison | name-list-format = vanc | date = March 19, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Salon (magazine)|Salon]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium.MAGAZINE-why-wikipedia-is-immune-to-coronavirus-1.8751147 | title = Why Wikipedia Is Immune to Coronavirus | first = Omer | last = Benjakob | date = April 8, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Haaretz]] }}</ref>\n\nMany local newspapers have been severely affected by losses in advertising revenues from coronavirus; journalists have been laid off, and some have closed altogether.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hsu |first1=Tiffany |last2=Tracy |first2=Marc | name-list-format = vanc |title=Local News Outlets Dealt a Crippling Blow by This Biggest of Stories |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/business/media/coronavirus-local-news.html |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref><ref name=\"newspaywalls\">{{cite web |last1=Kottke |first1=Jason |title=Media Paywalls Dropped for COVID-19 Crisis Coverage |url=https://kottke.org/20/03/media-paywalls-dropped-for-covid-19-crisis-coverage |website=kottke.org |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n==Conspiracy theories==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm/> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included domestic and overseas Russian state media ([[Channel One Russia]] and [[RT (TV network)|RT]] ), the British tabloid the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', and conservative media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|last=Sharma|first=Gouri | name-list-format = vanc | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Bioengineered virus===\nIt has been repeatedly claimed that the virus was deliberately created by humans.\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Andersen KG, Rambaut A, Lipkin WI, Holmes EC, Garry RF | title = The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2 | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 26 | issue = 4 | pages = 450\u2013452 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32284615 | doi = 10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9?fbclid=IwAR0cOVC4i9wyLuODURmxAxWWGOUm9RyzHmzTBA98jI_SR-ou8v-8_MLJgP4 | doi-access = free }}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\"/> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of bats and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=[[Live Science]]| access-date =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson| name-list-format = vanc  | date=February 14, 2020 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" />\n\n===Chinese biological weapon===\n\n====United States====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020, [[BBC News]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that said the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"bbc51271037\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online |date=January 30, 2020 |access-date=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic.\"<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref name=20200131bloomberg>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that created the virus responsible for a [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. Posts online noted that \"{{sic|Racoon}}\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil'') was an anagram of \"Corona\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> [[Snopes]] noted that the logo was not from the WIV, but a company named Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd (located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai), and that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil was \"Raccoon City\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | name-list-format = vanc | date=January 29, 2020 | access-date=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon;<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | name-list-format = vanc | access-date=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> multiple medical experts have indicated there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese government was using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|access-date= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref name=go68807304>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| access-date=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, conducted a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|access-date= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=usatoday5065736002>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |access-date=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe | name-list-format = vanc |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |access-date= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref name=20200229telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that a member of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]], a government committee tasked with dealing with crisis, has stated while government intelligence does not dispute that the virus has a zoonotic origin, it also does not discount the idea of a leak from a Wuhan laboratory, saying that \"Perhaps it is no coincidence that there is that laboratory in Wuhan.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/wuhan-lab-virus-leak-no-longer-discounted-cobra/ |title=Wuhan lab virus leak 'no longer discounted': Cobra |first= Dave |last= Makichuk | name-list-format = vanc |work=Asia Times|date=April 6, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====India====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref name=scmp3075445>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Ukraine====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref name=20200318kyivpost>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===US biological weapon===\n====Russia====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\"/><ref name=yahoo171730161>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref name=bbc51599009>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] news agency was active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and making many other claims. Sputnik branches in countries including Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and in the middle east came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Iran====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref name=radiofarda30449087>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref name=bbc51677530>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref name=20200305alarabiya>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref name=20200316iranwire>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's 'Biological Attack' Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref> \nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaA>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the [[United Nations]] on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref name=20200309washingtonexaminer>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref name=20200319alarabiya>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref name=20200208economist>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref name=nbcnews1151291>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2013 and misinformation \u2013 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest government-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref name=20200326propublica>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|access-date=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref name=20200405telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=April 5, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=April 5, 2020|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles said that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref name=setn677313>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref name=xilu1000010001>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|access-date=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref name=szhgh221836>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|access-date=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" >{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=thehill487308>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |access-date=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaB>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Arab world====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n====Philippine====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=philstar1990332>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus was a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref name=20200307somostuvoz>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Muslim===\n\n{{further|2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|Islamophobia}}\nIn India, Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious gathering.<ref name=newsweek1496011>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref name=firstpost8231371>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back to a Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren't hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK, there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.<ref name=20200405theguardian>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen| name-list-format = vanc |title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n===Antisemitic===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\"/>\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref name=jpost617021>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref name=forward441421>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly| name-list-format = vanc |title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref name=20200314timesofisrael>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa| name-list-format = vanc |title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref name=jpost621230>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref name=jpost620900>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref name=jpost621393>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref name=go69737522>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Spy operation===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact/> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\"/> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted/> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in a [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public.\"<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref name=20200129besacenter>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham | name-list-format = vanc |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Population control scheme===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by [[Paleolibertarianism|right-wing libertarians]], [[New World Order (conspiracy theory)|NWO conspiracy theorists]], and [[Christian fundamentalism|Christian Fundamentalists]].<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accidental leakage===\nA number of allegations have emerged on the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology#Concerns as source|link]] between the virus and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV), among these is that the virus was an accidental leakage from WIV.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cyranoski D | title = Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens | journal = Nature | volume = 542 | issue = 7642 | pages = 399\u2013400 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28230144 | doi = 10.1038/nature.2017.21487 | bibcode = 2017Natur.542..399C | doi-access = free }}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nIn February 2020, it has been alleged that the first person infected may have been a researcher at the institute named Huang Yanling.<ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\" /> Rumours circulated on Chinese social media that the researcher had become infected and died, prompting a denial from WIV, saying that she was a graduate student enrolled in the Institute until 2015 and is not the patient zero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whiov.ac.cn/tzgg_105342/202002/t20200216_5500201.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u58f0\u660e |date=February 16, 2020 |work=Wuhan Institute of Virology }}</ref><ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3050872/chinese-research-lab-denies-rumours-links-first-coronavirus |title=Chinese research lab denies rumours of links to first coronavirus patient |date=16 February 2020|first=Jun |last= Mai | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> In April, the conspiracy theory started to circulate around on Youtube and got picked up by conservative media, ''National Review''.<ref name=20200403nationalreview>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/coronavirus-china-trail-leading-back-to-wuhan-labs/ |title= The Trail Leading Back to the Wuhan Labs |first= Jim |last=Geraghty | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|work=National Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/04/14/as-the-coronavirus-spreads-conspiracy-theories-are-going-viral-too/|title=As the Coronavirus Spreads, Conspiracy Theories Are Going Viral Too|website=Foreign Policy|date= 14 April 2020|first=Elise |last=Thomas | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' (SCMP) reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the SCMP to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 6, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref name=caixinglobal101512828>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 7, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Immunologist [[Vincent Racaniello]] stated that virus leaking theory \"reflect a lack of understanding of the genetic make-up of Sars-CoV-2 and its relationship to the bat virus\". He states that the bat virus researched in the institution \"would not have been able to infect humans \u2013 the human Sars-CoV-2 has additional changes that allows it to infect humans.\"<ref name=\"scmp0411\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3079391/bat-virus-bioweapon-what-science-says-about-covid-19-origins |title=Bat virus? Bioweapon? What the science says about Covid-19 origins |date=11 April 2020|first=Simone |last= McCarthy|first2=Stephen |last2=Chen | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, the US [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], General [[Mark A. Milley|Mark Milley]], in response to questions about the virus being manufactured in a lab, said \"... it\u2019s inconclusive, although the weight of evidence seems to indicate natural. But we don\u2019t know for certain.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/14/covid-19-origin-lab-general-mark-milley |title=US military chief: 'Weight of evidence' that Covid-19 did not originate in a lab |first=Julian |last=Borger | name-list-format = vanc |date= 14 April 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> Days later, multiple media outlets confirmed that U.S. intelligence officials were investigating the possibility that the virus started in the WIV.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |title=U.S. intel community examining whether coronavirus emerged accidentally from a Chinese lab |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/china/u-s-intel-community-examining-whether-coronavirus-emerged-accidentally-chinese-n1185371 |website=NBC News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren P. |title=U.S. Intelligence Sifts Evidence for Origins of Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-intelligence-sifts-evidence-for-origins-of-coronavirus-11587077170 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gazis |first1=Olivia |title=U.S. intelligence community still investigating origins of COVID-19 outbreak, including whether it was a lab accident |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-covid-19-origins-investigation-wuhan-lab-accident/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Campbell |first1=Josh |title=US explores possibility that coronavirus spread started in Chinese lab, not a market |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/15/politics/us-intelligence-virus-started-chinese-lab/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Age===\nDespite sufficient data gathered in regards of case fatality rates by age group,<ref name=\"covidstats\">{{cite web|url=https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus#what-do-we-know-about-the-risk-of-dying-from-covid-19|title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) \u2013 Statistics and Research}}</ref> rumours of young people with no premorbidities dying of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus were circulating social media and were even published by large daily newspapers.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52041709|title=Chloe Middleton: Woman, 21, died with 'no underlying health issues'|website=BBC|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"express\">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1260123/Chloe-Middleton-coronavirus-death-UK-latest-Facebook-video-COVID-19-symptoms|title=Heartbreak as healthy 21-year-old dies from coronavirus \u2013 'It's not just a virus'|website=Express|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> However, many of these media reports have proven to be false or misrepresented upon closer inspection - such cases included news about a 21-year old spanish football coach Francisco Garcia<ref name=\"yahoosport\">{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/spanish-football-coach-francisco-garcia-163153573.html|title=Spanish football coach Francisco Garcia dies of coronavirus aged 21|website=Sports Yahoo|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and British 21-year old woman Chloe Middleton.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20200329015127/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/chloe-middleton-death-21-year-old-not-recorded-nhs-covid-19-related|title=Chloe Middleton: death of 21-year-old not recorded as Covid-19|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"spiked\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2020/03/27/chloe-middleton-the-coronavirus-death-that-wasnt/|title=Chloe Middleton: the coronavirus death that wasn't|website=Spiked|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>{{MEDCN|date=April 2020}}<!--implication that young people without co-morbidities can't die-->\n\n===Nurse whistleblower===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Alleged leak of death toll===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref name=taiwannews3871594>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington | name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref name=inews1411992>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster | name-list-format = vanc |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation against Taiwan===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref name=cna2020022604>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref name=taipeitimes2003731764>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200229reuters>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref name=20200303reuters>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard | name-list-format = vanc |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref name=washingtonpost3400200>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref name=npr814709530>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref name=taiwannews3904042>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta | name-list-format = vanc |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline in cellphone subscriptions===\nThere was a decrease of nearly 21 million cellphone subscriptions among the three largest cellphone carriers in China, which led to the spread of misinformation that this is evidence for millions of deaths due to the coronavirus in China.<ref name=laj-dicu/> However, the decline in cellphone subscriptions is actually attributed to people cancelling phone services as a result of a downturn in the social and economic life during the outbreak.<ref name=laj-dicu>{{cite web |last1=Lajka |first1=Arijeta |title=Drop in cellphone users in China wrongly attributed to coronavirus deaths |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8717250566 |website=AP NEWS |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Medical misinformation==\n{{main|List of unproven methods against COVID-19}}\n<!--This article is becoming longer by the day. Please try to add new content in the :List of unproven methods against COVID-19\" page instead of doing so here-->\nWidely circulated posts on social media have made many unfounded claims of methods against coronavirus. Some of these claims are scams, and some promoted methods are dangerous and unhealthy.<ref name=WHO_myths/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Andrew |title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> For misinformation that is a direct claim of a method to prevent, diagnose, or treat COVID-19, see [[List of unproven methods against COVID-19]]. This section deals only with other misinformation or prevent/diagnose/treat claims with wider social consquences.\n\n===COVID-19 recovery===\nIt has been wrongly claimed that anyone infected with COVID-19 will have the virus in their bodies for life. While there is no curative treatment, infected individuals can recover from the disease, eliminating the virus from their bodies; getting supportive medical care early can help.<ref name=WHO_myths/>\n\n===Vaccine pre-existence===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref name=20200123politifact>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher | name-list-format = vanc |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref name=aljazeera2002020934>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |access-date=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocaine===\nCocaine does not protect against COVID-19. Several viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a public service announcement debunking this claim, saying \"No, cocaine does NOT protect against COVID-19. It is an addictive drug that causes serious side effects and is harmful to people\u2019s health.\" The [[World Health Organisation]] also debunked the claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |website=Pedestrian.TV|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ethnic resistance/susceptibilty===\n\nThere have been claims that specific [[ethnicities]] are more or less vulnerable to COVID-19. COVID-19 is a new [[zoonotic]] disease, so no population has yet had the time to develop [[population immunity]].{{medcn|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref name=20200212afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref name=20200313cnn>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke| name-list-format = vanc |publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This myth was cited as a contributing factor in the disproportionately high rates of infection and death observed among African Americans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poston |first1=Ben |last2=Barboza |first2=Tony |last3=Jennings |first3=Angel | name-list-format = vanc |title=L.A. releases first racial breakdown of coronavirus fatalities; blacks have higher death rate|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-07/l-a-releases-first-racial-breakdown-of-coronavirus-fatalities-african-americans-have-higher-death-rate}}</ref><ref name=usatoday2961323001>{{cite news|last=Barfield Berry |first=Deborah | name-list-format = vanc  |title=Black people dying from coronavirus at much higher rates in cities across the USA | newspaper=USA Today |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/04/07/who-dying-coronavirus-more-black-people-die-major-cities/2961323001/}}</ref>\n\nThere have been claims of \"Indian immunity\": that the people of India have more immunity to the COVID-19 virus due to living conditions in India. This idea was deemed \"absolute drivel\" by Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS). He said that there was no [[population immunity]] to the COVID-19 virus yet, as it is new, and it is not even clear whether people who have recovered from COVID-19 will have lasting immunity, as this happens with some viruses but not with others.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |work=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] claimed that the virus was genetically targeted at Iranians by the USA, and this is why it is [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|seriously affecting Iran]]. He did not offer any evidence.<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=france2420200322>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|publisher=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 xenophobic blaming by ethnicity===<!--not sure if this doesn't belong with some of the nationally-based blaming above-->\nCOVID-19-related [[xenophobic]] attacks have been made against people the attacker blamed for COVID-19 on the basis of their ethnicity. The [[Asian Australian Alliance]] did a survey on attacks against Asian Australians in April 2020; 81% of victims said they believed the attack against them was related to the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Naaman |title=Survey of Covid-19 racism against Asian Australians records 178 incidents in two weeks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/17/survey-of-covid-19-racism-against-asian-australians-records-178-incidents-in-two-weeks |work=The Guardian |date=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[White supremacist]] groups have blamed COVID-19 on non-whites and advocated deliberately infecting minorities they dislike, such as Jews.<ref>{{cite web |title=World - as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19 - News - msn |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19/ |website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n<!--On the basis of historical examples, there have been warnings about discriminating by immunity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olivarius |first1=Kathryn |title=The Dangerous History of Immunoprivilege |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/opinion/coronavirus-immunity-passports.html |website=The New York Times |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>-->\n\n===5G===\nThe theories linking 5G mobile phone networks to COVID-19 were described as the \"worst kind of fake news\" by Professor Steve Powis, national medical director of [[NHS England]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\"/> Viruses cannot be transmitted by [[radio waves]]. COVID-19 is spreading in many countries which do not have 5G networks.<ref name=WHO_myths/>\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC News]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> The video of his claims went viral and was recirculated by celebrities including [[Woody Harrelson]], [[John Cusack]], and singer [[Keri Hilson]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Satariano |first1=Adam |last2=Alba |first2=Davey | name-list-format = vanc |title=Burning Cell Towers, Out of Baseless Fear They Spread the Virus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/10/technology/coronavirus-5g-uk.html |work=The New York Times |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The claims may also have been recirculated by an alleged \"coordinated disinformation campaign\", similar to campaigns used by the [[Internet Research Agency]] in Saint Petersburg, Russia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Ryan |title=5G Virus Conspiracy Theory Fueled by Coordinated Effort |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-09/covid-19-link-to-5g-technology-fueled-by-coordinated-effort |access-date=12 April 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The claims were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref name=usatoday2873731001>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref name=20200313fullfact>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were the subject of arson attacks, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \"just nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\"<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref> [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-telecom-tower-fires/|title=5G-coronavirus conspiracy theory spurs rash of telecom tower arson fires|website=Fortune}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, 2020 at least 20 mobile phone masts in the UK had been vandalised since the previous Thursday.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims>{{Cite news|title=At least 20 UK phone masts vandalised over false 5G coronavirus claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/06/at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last2=Hern|first2=Alex}}</ref> Because of slow rollout of 5G in the UK, many of the damaged masts had only 3G and 4G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> Mobile phone and home broadband operators estimated there were at least 30 incidents of confronting engineers maintaining equipment in the week up to April 6.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> There have been eleven incidents of attempted arson at mobile phone masts in the Netherlands, including one case where \"Fuck 5G\" was written, as well as in Ireland and Cyprus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2330065-brand-bij-vier-zendmasten-heel-sterk-vermoeden-van-brandstichting.html|title=Brand bij vier zendmasten: 'Heel sterk vermoeden van brandstichting'|date=April 10, 2020|work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting]]|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live|language=nl}}</ref><!-- FT article not paywalled --><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fildes|first1=Nic|last2=Di Stefano|first2=Mark|last3=Murphy|first3=Hannah | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.ft.com/content/1eeedb71-d9dc-4b13-9b45-fcb7898ae9e1|title=How a 5G coronavirus conspiracy spread across Europe|work=Financial Times|date=16 April 2020|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Facebook has deleted multiple messages encouraging attacks on 5G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/>\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] posted pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/>\n\nYouTube announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 5, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> The discredited theories had been promoted by British conspiracy theorist [[David Icke]] in videos (subsequently removed) on YouTube and Vimeo, and an interview by [[London Live]] TV network, prompting calls for action by [[Ofcom]].<ref name=bbc52198946>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved April 7, 2020</ref><ref name=extremetech308888>{{Cite web|url=https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/308888-youtube-says-it-will-remove-5g-misinformation-as-frightened-people-burn-cell-towers|title=YouTube Says It Will Remove 5G Misinformation After People Burn Cell Towers \u2013 ExtremeTech|website=extremetech.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 2020, [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda\u00ed]] were investigating fires at 5G masts in [[County Donegal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal>{{Cite news|title=Garda\u00ed suspect fires at 5G masts were deliberate after coal found|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal-5073466-Apr2020/|last=Maguire|first=Stephen| name-list-format = vanc |date=13 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020|work=[[TheJournal.ie]]}}</ref> Garda\u00ed and fire services had attended the fires the previous night in an attempt to put them out.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal/> Although Garda\u00ed were awaiting results of tests they were treating the fires as deliberate.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal/>\n\nThere were 20 suspected arson attacks on phone masts in the UK over the [[Easter]] 2020 weekend.<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\">{{cite news |title=Mast fires surge in the UK over Easter weekend amid 5G-coronavirus conspiracy theories |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-994035.html |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=14 April 2020}}</ref> These included an incident in [[Dagenham]] where three men were arrested on suspicion of arson, a fire in [[Huddersfield]] that affected a mast used by emergency services and a fire in a mast that provides mobile connectivity to the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Birmingham]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\"/>\n\n===Vegetarian immunity===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}<!--this seems to be more complex tahn just a claim that if you dont' eat meat you will not get infected-->\nClaims that [[vegetarian]]s are immune to coronavirus spread online in India, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}} Eating meat does not have an effect on COVID-19 spread, except for people [[zoonosis|near where animals are slaughtered]], said Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |website=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Fisheries, Dairying and Animal Husbandry Minister Giriraj Singh said that the rumour had significantly affected industry, with the price of a chicken falling to a third of pre-pandemic levels. He also described efforts to improve the hygiene of the meat supply chain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Non-vegetarian food does not cause COVID-19, says Minister |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/non-vegetarian-food-does-not-cause-covid-19-says-minister/article31003791.ece |work=The Hindu |date=6 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n===Alcohol (ethanol and poisonous methanol)===\nContrary to some reports, drinking alcohol does not protect against COVID-19, and can increase health risks<ref name=WHO_myths/> ([[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption|short term]] and [[Long-term effects of alcohol|long term]]). [[Drinking alcohol]] is [[ethanol]]; other [[alcohols]], such as [[methanol]], which causes [[methanol poisoning]], are acutely poisonous, and may be present in badly-prepared alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beauchamp GA, Valento M | title = Toxic Alcohol Ingestion: Prompt Recognition And Management In The Emergency Department | journal = Emergency Medicine Practice | volume = 18 | issue = 9 | pages = 1\u201320 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 27538060 }}</ref>\n\nIran has reported incidents of methanol poisoning, caused by the false belief that drinking alcohol would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/> [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]], and [[bootleg alcohol]] may [[Bootleg alcohol#Safety|contain methanol]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\"/> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\"/> Iranian social media had circulated a story from British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/><ref name=mirror21418662>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of alcohol-based<!--not just ethanol!--> [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew| name-list-format = vanc  |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref name=20200325cnnturk>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref name=hurriyet41473161>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n===Efficacy of hand sanitiser, \"antibacterial\" soaps===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} does destroy the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Hand sanitizer]] is recommended against COVID-19,<ref name=WHO_myths/> though unlike soap, it is not effective against all types of germs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Show Me the Science \u2013 When & How to Use Hand Sanitizer in Community Settings |author=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/show-me-the-science-hand-sanitizer.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Washing in soap and water for at least 20 seconds is recommended by the US Centers for Disease Control as the best way to clean hands in most situations. However, if soap and water are not available, a hand sanitizer that is at least 60% alcohol can be used instead, unless hands are visibly dirty or greasy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/disinfecting-your-home.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |language=en-us |date=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=When and How to Wash Your Hands|author= Centers for Disease Control |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The US CDC and the Food and Drug Administration recommend plain soap; there is no evidence that \"[[antibacterial soap]]s\" are any better, and limited evidence that they might be worse long-term.<ref>{{cite web |author=Center for Drug Evaluation and Research |title=Q&A for Consumers: Hand Sanitizers and COVID-19 |url=https://www.fda.gov/drugs/information-drug-class/qa-consumers-hand-sanitizers-and-covid-19 |website=FDA |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Antibacterial Soap? You Can Skip It, Use Plain Soap and Water |url=https://www.fda.gov/consumers/consumer-updates/antibacterial-soap-you-can-skip-it-use-plain-soap-and-water |website=FDA |author=Office of the Commissioner |language=en |date=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Public use of face masks===\nSeveral governments and institutions have initially dismissed the use of face masks by the general population, often with misleading or incomplete information about the efficacy of masks.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\">{{cite web |title=Through all the misinformation, what is the truth of wearing face masks? |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18385472.misinformation-truth-wearing-face-masks/ |website=The National }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=T. A. |title=\"I Was Looking at Them in the Wrong Way\": Mask Misinformation and the Failure of the Elites |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/mask-misinformation-and-the-failure-of-the-elites |website=Vanity Fair |date=April 2020}}</ref> Professor Zeynep Tufekci, writing in ''The New York Times'', suggests that the authorities dismissed mask usage by the general public in their messaging to manage shortages of supplies rather than confronting the reality of the situation.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web |last1=Tufekci |first1=Zeynep |title=Why Telling People They Don\u2019t Need Masks Backfired |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/opinion/coronavirus-face-masks.html |website=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> She remarks that the public received contradictory pieces of information about the usage of face masks, unlike other measures such as hand washing and social distancing.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nEven though there is no evidence that non-medical masks are an effective means of respiratory protection, there is some evidence they may reduce the transmission of viruses.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\"/> For instance, Harvard epidemiologist Bill Hanage said about masks that \"You're not wearing them to stop yourself getting infected, but to stop someone else getting infected.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=T. A. |title=\"I Was Looking at Them in the Wrong Way\": Mask Misinformation and the Failure of the Elites |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/mask-misinformation-and-the-failure-of-the-elites |website=Vanity Fair |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Helicopter spraying===\nIn some Asian countries, it has been claimed that one should stay at home on particular days when helicopters spray disinfectant over homes for killing off COVID-19; no such spraying is taking place.<ref name=20200326afpA>{{cite news |title=False claim circulates online that certain countries in Asia are using helicopters to spray 'COVID-19 disinfectant' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330085147/https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19|archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320afp>{{cite news |title=Indian authorities refute 'fake' advisory which claimed disinfectant would be sprayed across India to tackle COVID-19 |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408121452/https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india|archive-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mosquitos===\nIt has been claimed that [[mosquitos]] transmit coronavirus. There is no evidence that this is true; coronavirus spreads through small droplets of saliva and snot.<ref name=WHO_myths/> Colder northern-hemisphere countries have had COVID-19 spread long before the first mosquitos of spring emerge.\n\n===Cruise ships safety from infection===\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map per Capita.svg|thumb|upright=1.8|Claims by cruise-ship operators notwithstanding, there are many cases of coronaviruses in hot climates; some countries on the [[Caribbean]], the [[Mediterranean]], and the [[Persian Gulf]] are severely affected.]]\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships}}\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFlu is seasonal (becoming less frequent in the summer) in some countries, but not in others. While it is possible that the COVID-19 coronavirus will also show some seasonality, it it not yet known.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on February 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} The COVID-19 coronavirus spread along international air travel routes, including to tropical locations.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Venkatesh S, Memish ZA | title = SARS: the new challenge to international health and travel medicine | journal = Eastern Mediterranean Health Journal = La Revue De Sante De La Mediterranee Orientale = Al-Majallah Al-Sihhiyah Li-Sharq Al-Mutawassit | volume = 10 | issue = 4-5 | pages = 655\u201362 | date = 25 January 2004 | pmid = 16335659 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref> [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|Outbreaks on cruise ships]], where an older population lives in close quarters, frequently touching surfaces which others have touched, were common.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Browne A, Ahmad SS, Beck CR, Nguyen-Van-Tam JS | title = The roles of transportation and transportation hubs in the propagation of influenza and coronaviruses: a systematic review | journal = Journal of Travel Medicine | volume = 23 | issue = 1 | pages = tav002 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26782122 | doi = 10.1093/jtm/tav002 | url = https://academic.oup.com/jtm/article/23/1/tav002/2635586 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mallapaty S | title = What the cruise-ship outbreaks reveal about COVID-19 | journal = Nature | volume = 580 | issue = 7801 | pages = 18 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32218546 | doi = 10.1038/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref>\n\nIt seems that COVID-19 can be transmitted in all climates.<ref name=WHO_myths>{{cite web |title=Myth busters |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters |website=www.who.int |publisher=World Health Organization |language=en}}</ref> It has seriously affected many warm-climate countries. For instance, [[Dubai]], with an [[Climate of Dubai|year-round average daily high of 28.0 Celsius (82.3\u00b0F)]] and [[Dubai International Airport|the airport said to have the world's most international traffic]], has had [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates|thousands of cases]].\n\n===Country-specific===\n\n====Australia====\n\nA warning, claiming to be from the [[Australia Department of Health]] said that coronavirus  spreads through petrol pumps  and that everyone should wear gloves when filling up petrol in their cars.<ref name=20200325afpA>{{cite news |title=Australia's Department of Health did not issue a warning that 'using petrol pumps can spread COVID-19' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331182810/https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19|archive-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Twitter post claimed that scientists from the \"Australian Medical University\" had developed a vaccine for the coronavirus. It accepted 0.1 [[Bitcoin]] as payment for a vaccination kit and promised shipping in 5\u201310 days. It was later removed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus|last=Taylor|first=Andrew | name-list-format = vanc |date=2020-03-28|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123958/https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|archive-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Brazil====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref name=20200304abril>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9 | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref name=otempo2307041>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine [[Tamiflu]], according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref name=20200304uol>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref name=20200313afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref name=bbc51485559>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref name=cctv200125>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |access-date=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref name=epochtimes11842894>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |access-date=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref name=sina2164147>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref name=xinhuanet1125720410>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims originating from China circulated, stating that saline solutions could kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|title=Saline solution kills China coronavirus? Experts refute online rumour|date=2020-01-24|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401153714/https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|archive-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Estonia====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Greece====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, on March 9, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, would continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | name-list-format = vanc | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\"/>\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis| name-list-format = vanc |website=heise online|language=de|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref name=dw52742226>{{cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | name-list-format = vanc | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ |access-date=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/>\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although the alleged miracle drug is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\n====India====\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref name=indiatimes73952691>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=firstpost8111021>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] criticised politicians incautiously spreading such misinformation without an evidence base.<ref name=20200303ndtv>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|access-date=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020|quote=\"Q: In a situation like this when we need scientific solution to a medical crisis, when you get in our country for examples, political leaders saying things like co''[sic]'' dung or cow urine can be beneficial in fixing something like coronavirus, do we end up taking a step back after such statements, as we need to deal with the issue in a modern scientific manner. <br/>A: I completely agree, I think all the public figures including politicians need to be extra careful when it comes to making such statements, because they have such a huge following. Its really important for them to say things that are based on some scientific evidence and rationing''[sic; probably \"reasoning\" typo]''.... when it comes to the claims of cures of this infection we should be extremely careful about our statements and it should be made by the people who know what they\u2019re talking about. And has to be baked''[sic]'' by evidence\"}}</ref> Dr Shailendra Saxena of the [[Indian Virological Society]] stated that there is no evidence that cow urine has any anti-viral effect, and eating cow dung might even create a new [[zoonosis]].<ref name=BBC_tea>{{Cite news|last=team| name-list-format = vanc |first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>{{medcn|date=April 2020}}<!--not clear if doc is a subject expert-->\n\nParliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=deccanherald811390>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref name=20200320hindustantimes>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref name=thenewsminute120844>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[Amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on 'clapping vibrations destroy virus potency' after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=March 23, 2020 }}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/>\n\nIn India, fake news circulated that the [[World Health Organization]] warned against eating cabbage to prevent coronavirus infection.<ref name=20200331afp>{{cite news |title=WHO did not warn against eating cabbage during the COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402070033/https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The poisonous fruit of the [[Datura]] plant as a preventive measure for COVID-19 resulted in eleven people being hospitalized in India. They ate the fruit, following the instructions from a [[TikTok]] video that propagated misinformation regarding the prevention of COVID-19.<ref name=thenewsminute122136>{{cite news |title=11 in AP hospitalised after following TikTok poisonous 'remedy' for COVID-19 |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/11-ap-hospitalised-after-following-tiktok-poisonous-remedy-covid-19-122136 |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com}}</ref><ref name=thehindu31282688>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Twelve taken ill after consuming 'coronavirus shaped' datura seeds |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/twelve-taken-ill-after-consuming-coronavirus-shaped-datura-seeds/article31282688.ece |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=April 7, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nAn \"anti-coronavirus\" mattress was advertised as being anti-fungal, anti-allergic, dustproof and waterproof and that it could fight the coronavirus.<ref name=\":0CVP\">{{Cite news|last=team|first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=March 25, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims of neem leaves or ''[[Azadirachta indica]]'' as remedies for COVID-19 were circulated in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|title=No scientific evidence neem can cure COVID-19 infection - Experts|website=[[Bernama]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408122745/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|archive-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndian politician [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body could cure coronavirus. He also stated that only Indian cows must be used.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that a 30 year-old Indian textbook lists aspirin, anti-histamines and nasal spray as treatments for COVID-19. The textbook actually talks about [[coronaviruses]] in general, as a family of viruses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hoax-circulates-online-old-indian-textbook-lists-treatments-covid-19|title=Hoax circulates online that an old Indian textbook lists treatments for COVID-19|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====Italy====\nThere are claims that wearing shoes at one's home is the reason behind the spread of the coronavirus in Italy.<ref name=20200409afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-wearing-shoes-indoors-main-reason-hike-covid-19-infections|title=Hoax circulates online that people wearing shoes indoors triggered hike in COVID-19 cases in Italy|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====Nigeria====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref name=qz1810219>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref name=20200221afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients |title=Anti-malaria drug has proven effective in treating coronavirus but has not cured 12,552 patients &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Pakistan====\nReligious and scientific misconceptions related to the coronavirus was widespread in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Only 38% Pakistanis can recall state helpline for coronavirus: report |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/282463-only-38-pakistanis-can-recall-state-helpline-for-coronavirus-report |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref> According to a survey research conducted by [[Ipsos]], 82% of people in Pakistan believed that performing [[wudu]]/ablution five times a day will keep them protected from contracting Coronavirus. Meanwhile 67% polled believed that jamaat (congregation prayer) cannot become a source of infection<ref name=\"thenews/1\">{{cite news |title=88pc Pakistanis aware of COVID-19 implications: poll |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/643643-88pc-pakistanis-aware-of-covid-19-implications-poll |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.thenews.com.pk |language=en}}</ref> and 48% people believed that shaking hands cannot infect anyone since it is [[Sunnah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2020/04/myths-pakistanis-believe-wuzu-protects-you-from-covid/|title=Myths: Pakistanis believe wuzu protects you from COVID {{!}} SAMAA|publisher=Samaa TV|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Philippines====\nPosts on social media claimed that volcanic ash from the eruption of the [[Taal Volcano]] on January 12, 2020 in the Philippines was the cause of low infection rates in the country, stating that it could kill the virus and had \"anti-viral\" and \"disinfectant qualities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|title=World Health Organization refutes misleading claim that volcanic ash can kill coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408104634/https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClaims from the Philippines circulated that sap from [[Tinospora|''tinospora crispa'']] plants could serve as an antibiotic against the coronavirus when used as an eye drop. It also made the claim that the coronavirus is from the skin and crawls to the eyes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|title=Philippine health experts dismiss misleading online claim that tinospora crispa plants can treat novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-05|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408105720/https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that an anti-viral injection was developed as a cure in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-authorities-warn-anti-viral-injection-has-not-yet-been-approved-treating-covid-19|title=Philippine authorities warn anti-viral injection has not yet been approved for treating COVID-19|date=April 15, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref name=scmp3075421>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=upi9881584365>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were also fake news of discovery of a vaccine against COVID-19.<ref name=20200325afpB>{{cite news |title=This photo shows a COVID-19 test kit developed by a South Korean company |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327125546/https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company|archive-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Senegal====\nOn Facebook, a widely shared post claimed that 7 Senegalese children had died because they had received a COVID-19 vaccine. No such vaccine exists, although some are in clinical trials.<ref name=20200408afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/senegalese-children-did-not-die-coronavirus-vaccine-which-does-not-yet-exist|title=Senegalese children did not die from a coronavirus vaccine (which does not yet exist)|date=April 8, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====Sri Lanka====\n\nA claim that [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] could protect against the coronavirus appeared on Youtube, along with a petition to legalize cannabis in Sri Lanka.<ref name=20200219afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/sri-lankan-health-experts-stress-there-no-evidence-cannabis-boosts-immunity-against-novel|title=Sri Lankan health experts stress there is no evidence that cannabis boosts immunity against the novel coronavirus|date=February 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> A fake [[Fox News]] article also claimed that [[Cannabidiol|CBD oil]] was a potential cure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2020/03/19/coronavirus-scam-alert-beware-fake-fox-news-text-messages-promising-a-cbd-oil-cure/|title=Coronavirus Scam Alert: Beware Fake Fox News Articles Promising A CBD Oil Cure|last=Brewster|first=Thomas| name-list-format = vanc |website=Forbes|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Thailand====\n\nClaims that Vitamin D pills could help prevent the coronavirus circulated on social media in Thailand.<ref name=20200227afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-vitamin-d-effective-preventing-novel-coronavirus-infection|title=Health experts say there is no evidence vitamin D is effective in preventing novel coronavirus infection|date=February 27, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Thai media website stated that ''[[andrographis paniculata]]'' could boost the immune systems and relieve symptoms of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|title=Thai health experts say there is no evidence the 'green chiretta' herb can prevent the novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-06|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408110538/https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA widely shared post on Facebook claimed that Italian doctors who were infected with COVID-19 were treating patients as normal in Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/video-actually-shows-scene-mexican-television-series-aired-2010|title=This video actually shows a scene from a Mexican television drama|date=April 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually [[Chlorine dioxide]], a chemical used in some industrial applications as a bleach that may cause life-threatening reactions and even death) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref name=newsweek1487069>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref name=npr814550474>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz | name-list-format = vanc | title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200309theguardian>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren | name-list-format = vanc | title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref name=theverge21177998>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref name=\"alex jones\"/> The FDA would later threaten Jones with legal action and seizure of several silver-based products if he continued to promote their use against coronavirus.<ref name=politico178629>{{cite news|last=Owermohle |first=Sarah | name-list-format = vanc | title=FDA warns Alex Jones over false coronavirus claims| date=April 9, 2020| access-date=April 9, 2020 | work=Politico| url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/09/fda-warns-alex-jones-over-false-coronavirus-claims-178629}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref name=newsweek1492044>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200313pinknews>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe hypothesis of Stanford military historian Victor Davis Hanson, that the coronavirus was circulating in California in fall 2019, was widely shared but debunked by genetic analysis.<ref name=20200410slate>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/04/coronavirus-circulating-california-2019-bunk.html|title=No, You Did Not Get COVID-19 in the Fall of 2019|first=Jane C.|last=Hu | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 10, 2020|website=Slate}}</ref>\n\n====Venezuela====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref name=20200305efectococuyo>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n===American===\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the [[Hoover Institution]], who in a series of articles consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus, misapplied and misconstrued Darwinian evolutionary theory in regards to the pandemics, and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac | name-list-format = vanc |website=The New Yorker|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions in Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320euractiv>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref name=npr818192535>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City, gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref name=20200326nymag>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Presidential====\n{{see also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref name=20200225huffpost>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200226buzzfeednews>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=theverge21153035>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been spreading in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref name=theatlantic607348>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref name=npr804628081>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palc | name-list-format = vanc a|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] was false, that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number\",<ref name=usatoday4961519002>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson| name-list-format = vanc |website=USA Today|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=nbcnews1151006>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak was exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it was safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent| name-list-format = vanc |website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied that he had made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, contrary to footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House accused media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus to destabilize the administration.<ref name=bbc51667670>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment; the first case of community spread of the virus had been confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]], with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the rate for seasonal flu.<ref name=msnbc7944608558>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200225statnews>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\", after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him this process would take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to regulatory bodies requiring multiple rounds of tests before vaccines being approved for the public's use.<ref name=20200303washingtonpost>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref name=20200306politifact>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref name=20200312khn>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320cnnA>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara | name-list-format = vanc |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |access-date=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref name=20200320cnnB>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref name=go69716324>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23/><ref name=20200323military>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23/> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref name=20200323cnn>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo | name-list-format = vanc |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref name=nbcnews1167166>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200323buzzfeednews>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] (GM) and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\" when the companies were not producing ventilators at the time. The [[Associated Press]] estimated it would take at least several months for the carmaker companies to change their factories' production abilities.<ref name=20200323apnews>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope | name-list-format = vanc |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |access-date=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> However, Trump ordered General Motors to produce ventilators under the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 27 and it was announced on April 8 that GM would produce 30,000 ventilators for the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] for $489.4&nbsp;million by the end of August, with production to start the week of April 12 and the first 6,132 ventilators being delivered by June 1. It was the first Defense Production Act contract for ventilators and GM confirmed it was not profiting from it.<ref name=20200408cnbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/gm-to-build-30000-ventilators-for-us-for-489point4-million.html|publisher=CNBC|title=GM to build 30,000 ventilators for national stockpile for ,89.4&nbsp;million|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Ford partnered with [[General Electric]] and converted its auto plant in [[Rawsonville, Michigan]] to ventilator production in early April and promised to deliver 50,000 by July 4, scaling up production to 7,000\u20137,200 a week.<ref name=20200330clickondetroit>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/30/ford-partners-with-ge-to-produce-50000-ventilators-in-100-days-amid-michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak/|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020|title=Ford partners with GE to produce 50,000 ventilators in 100 days amid Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Click On Detroit}}</ref><ref name=20200406cbsnews>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ford-rawsonville-plant-michigan-ventilator-factory/|publisher=CBS|title=Ford converts Michigan auto plant into ventilator factory, promising 50,000 devices by July 4|date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilian===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref name=bbc52080830>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=aljazeera2003301816>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref name=vox21195469>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese===\n====Mishandling of crisis====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] publishing data from [[Ai Fen]] on December 30, 2019, revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref name=20200105theguardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 20, the Chinese National Health Commission announced that human-to-human transmission of the coronavirus had already occurred.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kuo |first1=Lily |title=China confirms human-to-human transmission of coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/20/coronavirus-spreads-to-beijing-as-china-confirms-new-cases |access-date=19 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> Later research published on January 29, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=creaders2181398>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref name=20200127thedailybeast>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref name=yahoo00163380>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref name=20200217cnn>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Origin of virus====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/>\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/><ref name=20200318cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost/><ref name=20200328voanews>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref name=scmp3076792>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In addition, articles from [[CounterPunch|''Counterpunch'']],<ref name=20200320counterpunch>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/20/fighting-covid-19-in-cuba-china-and-the-united-states/|title=Fighting COVID 19 in Cuba, China and the United States|date=March 20, 2020|website=CounterPunch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Asia Times]]'',<ref name=20200317asiatimes>{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/china-locked-in-hybrid-war-with-us/|title=China locked in hybrid war with US|last=Escobar|first=Pepe| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|website=Asia Times Online|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> as well as the Chinese scientist [[Zhong Nanshan]] have brought up speculations that the virus may not have originated in China.<ref name=scmp3077442>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3077442/coronavirus-pathogen-could-have-been-spreading-humans-decades|title=Coronavirus 'may have been quietly spreading long before pandemic'|date=March 29, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref name=20200325reuters>{{cite news |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom | name-list-format = vanc |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost/> which criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/>\n\n====Statistics on fatalities====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other health complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=20200327telegraph>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau \u2013 Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Some articles<ref name=20200327japantimes>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref name=metabunk237642>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuban===\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper ''[[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]]''.{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Iranian===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means\".<ref name=\"independent-corona\"/><ref name=france2420200322/>\n\n===Mexican===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\"/><ref name=20200402slate>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Russian===\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced the findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkmen ===\n[[Reporters Without Borders]] reported that the [[government of Turkmenistan]] had banned the word \"coronavirus\" and that people could be arrested for wearing masks or discussing the pandemic.<ref name=\"Banned Use Of The Word\">{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |access-date=April 1, 2020 |publisher=NPR  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401090543/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=npr824611607>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' : Coronavirus Live Updates |publisher=NPR |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The organization later corrected their report, clarifying that the word itself was not banned, but maintained that it had been removed from informational brochures and that the government was restricting information about the virus and providing \"very one-sided information\".<ref name=20200331rsf>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan &#124; Reports Without Borders|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Chronicles of Turkmenistan'', state media did not begin reporting on the measures that had been taken until March 25.<ref name=20200402nytimes>{{cite news |last1=Kramer |first1=Andrew E. |title='The Fields Heal Everyone': Post-Soviet Leaders' Coronavirus Denial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/world/asia/coronavirus-denial-post-soviet.html |access-date=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The BBC quoted an anonymous Turkmen citizen who stated that citizens may get into trouble for suggesting that the coronavirus is already on Turkmenistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52186521|title=Why has this country reported no virus cases?|first=Abdujalil|last=Abdurasulov| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 7, 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> The BBC article also states that the Turkmen government is working to control a possible outbreak.\n\n==Scams==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref name=un1058381>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Many financial companies, like [[Wells Fargo]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/jump/enterprise/coronavirus-response |title=COVID-19: We're here for you - Wells Fargo |publisher=Wells Fargo |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[LoanDepot]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://start.loandepot.com/assets/int-email/disaster/COVID19ServicingCommunicationv6.0.pdf |title=COVID-19 Information |publisher=LoanDepot |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> have posted similar warnings on their websites.\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref name=vox21164745>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison| name-list-format = vanc  |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref name=yahoo171111975>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n===Bat soup===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received abuse and threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=20200301washingtonpost>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200203latimes>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast, scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|access-date=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===''Simpsons'' prediction===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref name=20200303afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref name=chicagotribune20200229>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras| name-list-format = vanc |website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Corona beer misassociation===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref name=prnewswire301012225>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw/><ref name=theatlantic607240>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al| name-list-format = vanc |website=Barron's|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.\n\n===Hospital conditions===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about inadequacies in working-conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1= Carville |first1= Olivia |last2= Court |first2= Emma |last3= Brown |first3= Kristen V | name-list-format = vanc |title= Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website= Bloomberg | date= March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200401businessinsider>{{cite web |last1= Collman |first1= Ashley |title= Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url= https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website= Business Insider |date= April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil/>\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated{{by whom|date=April 2020}} as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref name=20200401nationalobserver>\n{{cite web\n|url= https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll\n|title= Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first= Caroline|last= Orr| name-list-format = vanc \n|date= April 1, 2020|website= National Observer|access-date= April 2, 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Return of wildlife===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" />\n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref name=20200319ktvb>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry Jr |first=Terry | name-list-format = vanc  |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned {{citation needed span|date=April 2020|[[China News Service]]|reason=National Geographic links to Xinhua, not China News Service}} debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref name=thehill488286>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[humpback whale]]s allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref name=20200405hindustantimes>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=April 5, 2020|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Lions freed on the streets===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in Moscow was passed around as if it were true.<ref name=bbc52118949>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===UK\u00a320 banknote===\nA tweet started an internet meme that [[Bank of England]] [[Bank of England \u00a320 note|\u00a320 banknote]]s contained a picture of a 5G mast and the SARSCoV-2 virus.  Facebook and YouTube removed items pushing this story, and fact checking organisations established that the picture is of [[Margate Lighthouse]] and the \"virus\" is the staircase at the [[Tate Britain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/online/5g-coronavirus-20-note/|title=\u00a320 notes don't have a secret message about 5G and coronavirus|first=Grace|last=Rahman| name-list-format = vanc |website=Full Fact}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/banknotes/polymer-20-pound-note The new \u00a320 note] The Bank of England</ref><ref>[https://turnercontemporary.org/support-us/what-can-i-do-with-my-old-20-note/ New \u00a320 note to feature Margate's Turner Contemporary] Turner Contemporary</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n* [https://www.politifact.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus] at [[Politifact]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Misinformation]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{More medical citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|False information about coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\n'''Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' consists of [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] and [[disinformation]] that emerged regarding the origin, scale, prevention and treatment surrounding the [[COVID-19]] disease and the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ensuing pandemic]] related to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online about origin and scale |date=January 30, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GUAR>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation | date=January 31, 2020 | access-date=February 3, 2020 | first=Josh | last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202141231/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum | archive-date=February 2, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Lowy>{{Cite news|first=Natasha|last=Kassam| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/disinformation-and-coronavirus|work=The Interpreter|publisher=Lowy Institute|title=Disinformation and coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=RunningList>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |title=Here's A Running List Of Disinformation Spreading About The Coronavirus |website=Buzzfeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206212717/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/coronavirus-disinformation-spread |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disinformation and [[misinformation]] can be spread through social media,<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |title=Social Media Posts Spread Bogus Coronavirus Conspiracy Theory |first=Jessica |last=McDonald | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 24, 2020 |work=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102802/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/social-media-posts-spread-bogus-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/ |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> text messages,<ref name=\"FTTextMsg\">{{cite web|author=Hannah Murphy, Mark Di Stefano & Katrina Manson|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34b6df5a-ea4a-471f-8ac9-606580480049|title=Huge text message campaigns spread coronavirus fake news|date=March 20, 2020|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=FriendsAunt>{{cite news|first=Mihir|last=Zaveri| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-text-messages-national-quarantine.html|title=Be Wary of Those Texts From a Friend of a Friend's Aunt|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[state media]] of countries such as China, [[Iran]] and [[Turkmenistan]],<ref name=Lowy/><ref name=\"presstv\">{{cite journal|last=Frantzman|first=Seth| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iran's regime pushes antisemitic conspiracies about coronavirus|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=March 8, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310213820/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iran-News/Irans-regime-pushes-antisemitic-conspiracies-about-coronavirus-620212|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/04/did-turkmenistan-really-ban-the-word-coronavirus/|title=Did Turkmenistan Really Ban the Word 'Coronavirus'?|last=Putz|first=Catherine| name-list-format = vanc |website=thediplomat.com|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> and they may be propagated by celebrities, politicians, or other prominent public figures.<ref name=20200408theguardian>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/apr/08/influencers-being-key-distributors-of-coronavirus-fake-news |title= Influencers among 'key distributors' of coronavirus misinformation |first=Jim |last=Waterson | name-list-format = vanc |date= April 8, 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan {{!}} Reporters without borders|date=March 31, 2020|publisher=Reports Without Borders|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><section begin=\"Intro\" /> Medical misinformation about ways to prevent, treat, and self-diagnose coronavirus disease has circulated on social media.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Robert H. |last1=Shmerling |title=Be careful where you get your news about coronavirus |url=https://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/be-careful-where-you-get-your-news-about-coronavirus-2020020118801 |website=Harvard Health Blog |access-date=March 25, 2020 |date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> Some false claims may be commercial scams offering at-home tests, supposed preventives, and \"miracle\" cures.<ref name = \"Beware\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/coronavirus-covid-19-fake-tests-cures|title=Covid-19: beware online tests and cures, experts say|last=Knight|first=Victoria| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 31, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"alex jones\">{{cite news|last1=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first1=Luis|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse | name-list-format = vanc |title=Alex Jones Is Told to Stop Selling Sham Anti-Coronavirus Toothpaste|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143913/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/nyregion/alex-jones-coronavirus-cure.html|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] has declared an \"infodemic\" of incorrect information about the virus, which poses risks to global health.<ref name=Lowy/><section end=Intro/>\n\nSome misinformation and disinformation claimed the virus was a [[bio-weapon]] with a patented [[vaccine]], a [[population control]] scheme, or the result of a [[Espionage|spy operation]].<ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\"/><ref name=RunningList/><ref name=\"vox_misinfo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=How tech companies are scrambling to deal with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin |last2=Heilweil |first2=Rebecca | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=February 10, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some of these misinformation and conspiracy theories may have state involvement.<ref name=\"presstv\"/><ref name=\"20200312theguardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/12/conspiracy-theory-that-coronavirus-originated-in-us-gaining-traction-in-china |title='American coronavirus': China pushes propaganda casting doubt on virus origin |first=Lily |last=Kuo |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |title=Coronavirus: Russia pushing fake news about US using outbreak to 'wage economic war' on China, officials say |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |via=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223223639/https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/article/3051939/coronavirus-russia-pushing-fake-news-about-us-using |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some world leaders have also downplayed the threat of the virus and disseminated misinformation.<ref name=bolsonaro>{{cite web|first=Uri |last=Friedman | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/bolsonaro-coronavirus-denial-brazil-trump/608926/ |title=Bolsonaro Leads the Coronavirus-Denial Movement |work=The Atlantic |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"stat\">{{cite web |last1=Thielking |first1=Megan |title=Experts warn Trump's misinformation about coronavirus is dangerous |url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/26/trump-mixed-messages-on-coronavirus/ |website=STAT |access-date=April 5, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><section end=Intro/>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Combative efforts==\n\nOn February 2, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) described a \"massive infodemic\", citing an over-abundance of reported information, accurate and false, about the virus that \"makes it hard for people to find trustworthy sources and reliable guidance when they need it.\" The WHO stated that the high demand for timely and trustworthy information has incentivised the creation of a direct WHO 24/7 myth-busting hotline where its communication and social media teams have been monitoring and responding to misinformation through its website and social media pages.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite report | vauthors=((World Health Organization)) | year=2020 | title=Novel Coronavirus (&lrm;2019-nCoV)&lrm;: situation report, 13 | publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | hdl=10665/330778 | hdl-access=free }}</ref><ref name=un1056672>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |title=Coronavirus: UN health agency moves fast to tackle 'infodemic'; Guterres warns against stigmatization |date=February 4, 2020 |website=UN News |access-date=February 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205080207/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1056672 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |title=WHO Says There's No Effective Coronavirus Treatment Yet |publisher=Yahoo! Finance |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206043018/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/says-theres-no-effective-coronavirus-200035999.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The WHO specifically debunked several claims as false, including the claim that a person can tell if they have the virus or not simply by holding their breath; the claim that drinking large amounts of water will protect against the virus; and the claim that gargling salt water prevents infection.<ref name=20200317cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|title=One dangerous coronavirus 'self-check test' is circulating on social media. Here's why you should avoid it.|last=Elassar|first=Alaa| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317050148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/us/coronavirus-myths-debunking-holding-breath-10-seconds-trnd/index.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter and Google said they were working with WHO to address \"misinformation\".<ref name=20200206nytimes>{{Cite news |last=Richtel |first=Matt | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |title=W.H.O. Fights a Pandemic Besides Coronavirus: an 'Infodemic' |date=February 6, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 7, 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206224226/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-misinformation-social-media.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a blogpost, Facebook stated they would remove content flagged by global health organizations and local authorities that violate its content policy on misinformation leading to \"physical harm\".<ref name=20200201reuters>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |title=As coronavirus misinformation spreads on social media, Facebook removes posts |date=February 1, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206071606/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-facebook-idUSKBN1ZV388 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Facebook is also giving free advertising to WHO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|title=Facebook announces how it plans to help fight the coronavirus|website=Inverse|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204741/https://www.inverse.com/innovation/facebook-is-giving-the-world-health-organization-free-ads-to-combat-the-coronavirus|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of February, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] removed over one million products claimed to cure or protect against coronavirus, and removed tens of thousands of listings for health products whose prices were \"significantly higher than recent prices offered on or off Amazon\", although numerous items were \"still being sold at unusually high prices\" as of February 28<ref>.{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|title = Amazon culls one million fake coronavirus products|work = BBC News|date = February 28, 2020|access-date = March 1, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200301082532/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-51675183|archive-date = March 1, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nMillions of instances of COVID-19 misinformation have occurred across a number of online platforms.<ref>{{cite arXiv |title= The COVID-19 Social Media Infodemic |first1= Matteo |last1= Cinelli |first2= Walter |last2= Quattrociocchi |first3= Alessandro |last3= Galeazzi |first4=Carlo Michele |last4=Valensise |first5= Emanuele |last5= Brugnoli |first6= Ana Lucia |last6=Schmidt |first7= Paola |last7= Zola |first8=Fabiana |last8=Zollo |first9=Antonio |last9=Scala | name-list-format = vanc |date= March 10, 2020 |class= cs.SI |eprint= 2003.05004 }}</ref> Other [[fake news]] researchers noted certain rumors started in China; many of them later spread to Korea and the United States, prompting several universities in Korea to start the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= 'Fact before rumors' campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 26, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 31, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |first=Cha|last=Meeyoung| name-list-format = vanc |author-link=Cha Meeyoung |date= March 24, 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Donga Science |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= March 25, 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |access-date= March 30, 2020 |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nThe media has praised Wikipedia's coverage of COVID-19 and its combating the inclusion of misinformation through efforts led by the [[meta:Wiki Project Med Foundation|Wiki Project Med Foundation]] and the English-language Wikipedia's [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Medicine|WikiProject Medicine]], among other groups.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wired.com/story/how-wikipedia-prevents-spread-coronavirus-misinformation/ | title = How Wikipedia Prevents the Spread of Coronavirus Misinformation | first=  Noam | last = Cohem | date = March 15, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://slate.com/technology/2020/03/coronavirus-wikipedia-policies.html | title = The Coronavirus Is Stress-Testing Wikipedia's Policies | first= Stephan | last= Harrison | name-list-format = vanc | date = March 19, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Salon (magazine)|Salon]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium.MAGAZINE-why-wikipedia-is-immune-to-coronavirus-1.8751147 | title = Why Wikipedia Is Immune to Coronavirus | first = Omer | last = Benjakob | date = April 8, 2020 | access-date = April 11, 2020 | work = [[Haaretz]] }}</ref>\n\nMany local newspapers have been severely affected by losses in advertising revenues from coronavirus; journalists have been laid off, and some have closed altogether.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hsu |first1=Tiffany |last2=Tracy |first2=Marc | name-list-format = vanc |title=Local News Outlets Dealt a Crippling Blow by This Biggest of Stories |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/business/media/coronavirus-local-news.html |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany newspapers with [[paywall]]s lowered them for some or all of their coronavirus coverage.<ref name=\"Paywalls\">{{cite news |last1=Jerde |date=March 12, 2020 |first1=Sara |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Adweek}}</ref><ref name=\"newspaywalls\">{{cite web |last1=Kottke |first1=Jason |title=Media Paywalls Dropped for COVID-19 Crisis Coverage |url=https://kottke.org/20/03/media-paywalls-dropped-for-covid-19-crisis-coverage |website=kottke.org |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Many scientific publishers made scientific papers related to the outbreak [[open access]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-255\">{{cite press release |url=https://wellcome.ac.uk/press-release/sharing-research-data-and-findings-relevant-novel-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |title=Sharing research data and findings relevant to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |work=wellcome.ac.uk |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> Some scientists chose to share their results quickly on [[preprint]] servers such as [[bioRxiv]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-256\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-research-preprint-servers/ |title=Coronavirus Research Is Moving at Top Speed \u2013 With a Catch |work=Wired |last1=Rogers |first1=Adam |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 13, 2020 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>\n\n==Conspiracy theories==\n\n[[Conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories]] have appeared in both social media and mainstream news outlets, and are heavily influenced by geopolitics.<ref name=al-watsm/> ''[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]'' reported that mainstream outlets which had spread conspiracy theories included domestic and overseas Russian state media ([[Channel One Russia]] and [[RT (TV network)|RT]] ), the British tabloid the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', and conservative media in the United States.<ref name=al-watsm>{{cite web|last=Sharma|first=Gouri | name-list-format = vanc | date=March 5, 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/conspiracy-theories-coronavirus-200303170729373.html|title=Why are there so many conspiracy theories around the coronavirus?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Bioengineered virus===\nIt has been repeatedly claimed that the virus was deliberately created by humans.\n\n''[[Nature Medicine]]'' published an article arguing against the conspiracy theory that the virus was created artificially. The high-affinity binding of the virus' [[peplomer]]s to human [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) was shown to be \"most likely the result of [[natural selection]] on a human or human-like ACE2 that permits another optimal binding solution to arise\".<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Andersen KG, Rambaut A, Lipkin WI, Holmes EC, Garry RF | title = The proximal origin of SARS-CoV-2 | journal = Nature Medicine | volume = 26 | issue = 4 | pages = 450\u2013452 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32284615 | doi = 10.1038/s41591-020-0820-9 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9?fbclid=IwAR0cOVC4i9wyLuODURmxAxWWGOUm9RyzHmzTBA98jI_SR-ou8v-8_MLJgP4 | doi-access = free }}</ref> In case of [[genetic manipulation]], one of the several [[Reverse genetics|reverse-genetic]] systems for [[betacoronavirus]]es would probably have been used, while the genetic data irrefutably showed that the virus is not derived from a previously used virus template.<ref name=\"NM\"/> The overall molecular structure of the virus was found to be distinct from the known coronaviruses and most closely resembles that of viruses of bats and [[pangolins]] that were little studied and never known to harm humans.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-not-human-made-in-lab.html |title=The coronavirus did not escape from a lab. Here's how we know|first=Jeanna|last=Bryner | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=[[Live Science]]| access-date =March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' quoted virus expert and global co-lead coronavirus investigator Trevor Bedford: \"There is no evidence whatsoever of genetic engineering that we can find\", and \"The evidence we have is that the mutations [in the virus] are completely consistent with natural evolution\".<ref name=\"FT5\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | title=Coronavirus was not genetically engineered in a Wuhan lab, says expert | first=Clive | last=Cookson| name-list-format = vanc  | date=February 14, 2020 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | newspaper=[[Financial Times]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214112755/https://www.ft.com/content/a6392ee6-4ec6-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 | archive-date=February 14, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Bedford further explained, \"The most likely scenario, based on genetic analysis, was that the virus was transmitted by a bat to another mammal between 20\u201370 years ago. This intermediary animal\u2014not yet identified\u2014passed it on to its first human host in the city of Wuhan in late November or early December 2019\".<ref name=\"FT5\" />\n\n===Chinese biological weapon===\n\n====United States====\n{{further|Cyberwarfare in the United States|Propaganda in the United States}}\nIn January 2020, [[BBC News]] published an article about coronavirus misinformation, citing two January 24 articles from ''[[The Washington Times]]'' that claimed the virus was part of a Chinese biological weapons program, based at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV).<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"bbc51271037\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online |date=January 30, 2020 |access-date=February 3, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204163412/https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037 |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' later published an article debunking the conspiracy theory, citing US experts who explained why the WIV was unsuitable for bioweapon research, that most countries had abandoned bioweapons as fruitless, and that there was no evidence that the virus was genetically engineered.<ref name=\"20200129washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |title=Experts debunk fringe theory linking China's coronavirus to weapons research |date=January 29, 2020 |website=The Washington Post |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131185716/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/01/29/experts-debunk-fringe-theory-linking-chinas-coronavirus-weapons-research/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, financial news website and blog [[ZeroHedge]] suggested without evidence that a scientist at the WIV created the COVID-19 strain responsible for the coronavirus outbreak. Zerohedge listed the full contact details of the scientist supposedly responsible, a practice known as [[doxing]], by including the scientist's name, photo, and phone number, suggesting to readers that they \"pay [the Chinese scientist] a visit\" if they wanted to know \"what really caused the coronavirus pandemic.\"<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |title=Markets blogger Zero Hedge suspended from Twitter after doxxing a Chinese scientist |last=Peters |first=Jay | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214044/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/31/21117663/twitter-zero-hedge-suspended-platform-manipulation-policy-doxxing-coronavirus |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Twitter later permanently suspended the blog's account for violating its platform-manipulation policy.<ref name=20200131bloomberg>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |title=Zero Hedge Permanently Suspended From Twitter for 'Harassment' |last=Datoo |first=Siraj | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Bloomberg |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202214859/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-01/zero-hedge-permanently-suspended-from-twitter-for-harassment |archive-date=February 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, ''[[Buzzfeed News]]'' reported on an internet meme of a link between the logo of the WIV and \"[[Umbrella Corporation]]\", the agency that created the virus responsible for a [[zombie apocalypse]] in the ''[[Resident Evil]]'' franchise. Posts online noted that \"{{sic|Racoon}}\" (the main city in ''Resident Evil'') was an anagram of \"Corona\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\" /> [[Snopes]] noted that the logo was not from the WIV, but a company named Shanghai Ruilan Bao Hu San Biotech Ltd (located some {{convert|500|mi}} away in Shanghai), and that the correct name of the city in Resident Evil was \"Raccoon City\".<ref name=\"SNOPES\">{{cite web | url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/resident-evil-umbrella-coronavirus/ | title=Is the 'Umbrella Corporation' Logo Oddly Similar to a Wuhan Biotech Lab's? | first=Dan | last=Evon | name-list-format = vanc | date=January 29, 2020 | access-date=February 10, 2020 | website=[[Snopes]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, US Senator [[Tom Cotton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]) and [[Francis Boyle]], a law professor, suggested that the virus may have been a Chinese bioweapon;<ref name=\"cotton\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | title=Chinese ambassador on Cotton coronavirus comments: 'It's very harmful to stir up' unsubstantiated rumors | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | first=Zack | last=Budryk | name-list-format = vanc | access-date=February 11, 2020 | date=February 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210153906/https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/482228-chinese-ambassador-on-cotton-coronavirus-comments-its-very-harmful | archive-date=February 10, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> multiple medical experts have indicated there is no evidence for this.<ref name=\"fact checking\">{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |title=Fact-checking Tom Cotton's claims about the coronavirus |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219234740/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/18/politics/coronavirus-cotton-fact-check/index.html |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Conservative political commentator [[Rush Limbaugh]] said on ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]''\u2014 the most popular radio show in the US\u2014that the virus was probably \"a [[ChiCom]] laboratory experiment\" and that the Chinese were using the virus and the media hysteria surrounding it to bring down Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/rush-limbaugh/rush-limbaugh-coronavirus-effort-get-trump|title=Rush Limbaugh: \"The coronavirus is an effort to get Trump\"|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|title= Rush Limbaugh claims Chinese are 'trying to weaponize' coronavirus to 'bring down' Trump|date= February 25, 2020|access-date= February 25, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162810/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/rush-limbaugh-claims-chinese-are-trying-to-weaponize-coronavirus-to-bring-down-trump|archive-date= February 29, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, the White House asked scientists and medical researchers to rapidly investigate the origins of the virus to address both the current spread and \"to inform future outbreak preparation and better understand animal/human and environmental transmission aspects of coronaviruses.\"<ref name=go68807304>{{cite web| date=February 6, 2020| title=White House asks scientists to investigate origins of coronavirus| url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| access-date=February 28, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208032258/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-asks-scientists-investigate-origins-coronavirus/story?id=68807304| archive-date=February 8, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> American magazine ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' said that Xi Jinping's \"political agenda may turn out to be a root cause of the epidemic\" and that his [[Belt and Road Initiative]] has \"made it possible for a local disease to become a global menace\".<ref name=al-watsm />\n\nThe ''Inverse'' reported that \"Christopher Bouzy, the founder of Bot Sentinel, conducted a Twitter analysis for Inverse and found [online] bots and [[Internet troll|trollbots]] are making an array of false claims. These bots are claiming China intentionally created the virus, that it's a biological weapon, that Democrats are overstating the threat to hurt Donald Trump and more. While we can't confirm the origin of these bots, they are decidedly pro-Trump.\"<ref name=inverse>{{cite news |title=Bots are waging a coronavirus disinformation campaign on social media |url=https://www.inverse.com/mind-body/coronavirus-usa-2020 |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConservative commentator [[Josh Bernstein (talk show host)|Josh Bernstein]] claimed that the Democratic Party and the \"medical deep state\" were collaborating with the Chinese government to create and release the coronavirus to bring down Donald Trump. Bernstein went on to suggest that those responsible should be locked in a room with infected coronavirus patients as punishment.<ref name=\"bernstein\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|title= Josh Bernstein: The Coronavirus Outbreak Is a Democratic and Chinese Conspiracy Against Trump|access-date= March 12, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312173241/https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/josh-bernstein-the-coronavirus-outbreak-is-a-democratic-and-chinese-conspiracy-against-trump/|archive-date= March 12, 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=usatoday5065736002>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Matthew |title=Fact check: Coronavirus did not spread in the US because of an anti-Trump conspiracy |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/17/fact-check-coronavirus-spread-not-anti-trump-conspiracy/5065736002/ |access-date=March 31, 2020 |work=USA Today |issue=2 |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Falwell Jr.]], the president of [[Liberty University]], promoted a conspiracy theory on [[Fox News]] that North Korea and China conspired together to create the coronavirus.<ref name=fox-falwell>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|title=Fox guest Jerry Falwell Jr. speculates that North Korea \"got together with China\" to create coronavirus|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317093144/https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/fox-guest-jerry-falwell-jr-speculates-north-korea-got-together-china-create|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also said that people were overreacting to the coronavirus outbreak and that Democrats were trying to use the situation to harm President Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last= Heim |first= Joe | name-list-format = vanc |title= Liberty University President Jerry Falwell Jr. says in-person classes to continue |date= March 13, 2020 |access-date= March 15, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |quote= 'It\u2019s just strange to me how so many are overreacting,' Falwell said, comparing media coverage of the novel coronavirus to coverage of earlier epidemics. 'It makes you wonder if there\u2019s a political reason for that. Impeachment didn\u2019t work, and the Mueller report didn\u2019t work, and Article 25 didn\u2019t work. And so maybe now this is their next attempt to get Trump.' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317141436/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/liberty-university-president-jerry-falwell-jr-says-in-person-classes-to-continue/2020/03/13/70b23a58-654e-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html |archive-date= March 17, 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n\nConservative MP [[Tobias Ellwood]], chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]], publicly questioned the role of the Chinese Army's Wuhan Institute for Biological Products and called for the \"greater transparency over the origins of the coronavirus\".<ref name=20200229telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Ellwood|first=Tobias | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|title=Transparency will convince the world China is a friend|date=February 29, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=March 3, 2020|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000503/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/29/transparency-will-convince-world-china-friend/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has also been reported that a member of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]], a government committee tasked with dealing with crisis, has stated while government intelligence does not dispute that the virus has a zoonotic origin, it also does not discount the idea of a leak from a Wuhan laboratory, saying that \"Perhaps it is no coincidence that there is that laboratory in Wuhan.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://asiatimes.com/2020/04/wuhan-lab-virus-leak-no-longer-discounted-cobra/ |title=Wuhan lab virus leak 'no longer discounted': Cobra |first= Dave |last= Makichuk | name-list-format = vanc |work=Asia Times|date=April 6, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====India====\nAmidst a rise in [[Sinophobia]], there have been conspiracy theories reported on India's social networks that the virus is a state-supported \"a bioweapon that went rogue\" and also fake videos alleging that Chinese authorities are killing citizens to prevent its spread.<ref name=scmp3075445>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075445/coronavirus-anti-chinese-conspiracy-theories-go-viral|title=Coronavirus: anti-Chinese conspiracy theories go viral in India|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Ukraine====\nAccording to the ''[[Kyiv Post]]'', two common conspiracy theories online in Ukraine are that American author [[Dean Koontz]] predicted the pandemic in his 1981 novel ''[[The Eyes of Darkness]]'', and that the coronavirus was a bioweapon leaked from a secret lab in Wuhan.<ref name=20200318kyivpost>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/coronavirus-misinformation-goes-viral-in-ukraine.html|title=Coronavirus misinformation goes viral in Ukraine|date=March 18, 2020|website=Kyiv Post|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===US biological weapon===\n====Russia====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by Russia|Propaganda in the Russian Federation|Russia\u2013European Union relations#Allegations of Russian intimidation and destabilisation of EU states}}\nOn February 22, US officials alleged that Russia is behind an ongoing disinformation campaign, using thousands of social media accounts on Twitter, Facebook and [[Instagram]] to deliberately promote unfounded conspiracy theories, claiming that the virus is a biological weapon manufactured by the [[CIA]] and the US is waging economic war on China using the virus.<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\">{{Cite news |last=Glenza |first=Jessica | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |title=Coronavirus: US says Russia behind disinformation campaign |date=February 22, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051450/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-russia-disinformation-campaign-us-officials |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3051939\"/><ref name=yahoo171730161>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |title=US accuses Russia of huge coronavirus disinformation campaign |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Kate |last=Ng | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224090721/https://news.yahoo.com/us-accuses-russia-huge-coronavirus-171730161.html |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acting assistant secretary of state for Europe and [[Eurasia]], [[Philip T. Reeker|Philip Reeker]], said that \"Russia's intent is to sow discord and undermine US institutions and alliances from within\" and \"by spreading disinformation about coronavirus, Russian malign actors are once again choosing to threaten public safety by distracting from the global health response.\"<ref name=\"guardian-rus-disinfo\" /> Russia denies the allegation, saying \"this is a deliberately false story\".<ref name=bbc51599009>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |title=Coronavirus: Russia denies spreading US conspiracy on social media |date=February 23, 2020 |publisher=BBC |access-date=February 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225053306/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51599009 |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US-based ''[[The National Interest]]'' magazine, although official Russian channels had been muted on pushing the US biowarfare conspiracy theory, other Russian media elements do not share the Kremlin's restraint.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\">{{Cite news |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |title=Some in Russia Think the Coronavirus Is a U.S. Biological Weapon |last=Episkopos |first=Mark | name-list-format = vanc |date=February 7, 2020 |work=[[The National Interest]] |access-date=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223172332/https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/some-russia-think-coronavirus-us-biological-weapon-121731 |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Zvezda'', a news outlet funded by the Russian Defense Ministry, published an article titled \"Coronavirus: American biological warfare against Russia and China\", claiming that the virus is intended to damage the Chinese economy, weakening its hand in the next round of trade negotiations.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> Ultra-nationalist politician and leader of the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]], [[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], claimed on a Moscow radio station that the virus was an experiment by [[the Pentagon]] and pharmaceutical companies. Politician [[Igor Nikulin (politician)|Igor Nikulin]] made rounds on Russian television and news media, arguing that Wuhan was chosen for the attack because the presence of a BSL-4 virus lab provided a cover story for the Pentagon and CIA about a Chinese bio-experiment leak.<ref name=\"TNI-russia\" /> An EU-document claims 80 attempts by Russian media to spread disinformation related to the epidemic.<ref name=reuters2020-03-18>{{cite news |title=Russia deploying coronavirus disinformation to sow panic in West, EU document says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |agency=Reuters  |date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319222849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21518F |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] news agency was active publishing stories claiming that the virus was invented in Latvia, that it was used by [[Communist Party of China]] to curb [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protests in Hong Kong]], that it was introduced intentionally to reduce the number of elder people in Italy, that it was targeted against the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow Vests]] movement, and making many other claims. Sputnik branches in countries including Armenia, Belarus, Spain, and in the middle east came up with customized versions of these stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/sputnik-coronavirus-could-be-designed-to-kill-elderly-italians/|title=Sputnik: Coronavirus Could be Designed to Kill Elderly Italians|date=March 25, 2020|website=EU vs DISINFORMATION|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Iran====\n\n{{further|Propaganda in Iran}}\nAccording to ''[[Radio Farda]]'', Iranian cleric Seyyed Mohammad Saeedi accused US President [[Donald Trump]] of targeting [[Qom]] with coronavirus \"to damage its culture and honor\". Saeedi claimed that Trump is fulfilling his promise to hit Iranian cultural sites, if Iranians took revenge for the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|US airstrike]] that killed of [[Quds Force]] Commander [[Qasem Soleimani]].<ref name=radiofarda30449087>{{Cite news|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|title=Iran Cleric Blames Trump For Coronavirus Outbreak in Religious City|date=February 22, 2020|work=[[Radio Farda]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223170405/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-cleric-blames-trump-for-coronavirus-outbreak-in-religious-city/30449087.html|archive-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIranian TV personality Ali Akbar Raefipour claimed that the coronavirus was part of a \"hybrid warfare\" programme waged by the United States on Iran and China.<ref name=bbc51677530>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Misinformation and false medical advice spreads in Iran |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |work=BBC News |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301202336/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51677530 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nBrigadier General Gholam Reza Jalali, head of Iranian Civil Defense Organization, claimed that the coronavirus is likely a biological attack on China and Iran with economic goals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|title=Civil Defense Chief: Coronavirus Likely Biological Attack against China, Iran|date=March 3, 2020|agency=[[Fars News Agency]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304231742/http://en.farsnews.ir/newstext.aspx?nn=13981213000410|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=toi-civildefense>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|title=Virus is biological attack on China and Iran, Iranian civil defense chief claims|date=March 4, 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173532/https://www.timesofisrael.com/virus-is-biological-attack-on-china-and-iran-iranian-civil-defense-chief-claims/|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hossein Salami]], the head of [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC), claimed that the coronavirus outbreak in Iran may be due to a US \"biological attack\".<ref name=20200305alarabiya>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|title=Coronavirus may be US 'biological attack': IRGC head Hossein Salami|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306204737/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/05/Coronavirus-may-be-US-biological-attack-IRGC-head.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Several Iranian politicians, including [[Hossein Amir-Abdollahian]], [[Rasoul Falahati]], [[Alireza Panahian]], [[Abolfazl Hasanbeigi]] and [[Gholamali Jafarzadeh Imanabadi]], also made similar remarks.<ref name=20200316iranwire>{{Cite news|url=https://iranwire.com/en/features/6815|title=The Lie that Triggered Khamenei's 'Biological Attack' Conspiracy Theory|date=March 16, 2020|work=IranWire}}</ref> \nHowever, Iran's deputy health minister [[Reza Malekzadeh]] rejected the biological warfare theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaA>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|title=Coronavirus: Iran's deputy health minister rejects biological warfare theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317205520/https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2020/03/14/Coronavirus-Iran-s-deputy-health-minister-rejects-biological-warfare-theory.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFormer Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] sent a letter to the [[United Nations]] on March 9, claiming that \"it is clear to the world that the mutated coronavirus was produced in lab\" and that COVID-19 is \"a new weapon for establishing and/or maintaining political and economic upper hand in the global arena.\"<ref name=20200309washingtonexaminer>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|title='Biologic war': Former Iranian president says coronavirus was 'produced in laboratories'|date=March 9, 2020|agency=[[Washington Examiner]]|access-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311071331/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/biologic-war-former-iranian-president-says-coronavirus-was-produced-in-laboratories|archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyatollah [[Hashem Bathaie Golpayegani]] claimed that \"America is the source of coronavirus, because America went head to head with China and realised it cannot keep up with it economically or militarily.\"<ref name=20200319alarabiya>{{Cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2020/03/19/Video-Senior-Iranian-cleric-who-died-from-coronavirus-blamed-US-for-outbreak |title=Video: Senior Iranian cleric who died from coronavirus blamed US for outbreak |date=March 19, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\n{{further|Cyberwarfare by China|Propaganda in China|Chinese information operations and information warfare}}\nAccording to London-based ''[[The Economist]]'', plenty of conspiracy theories exist on China's internet about COVID-19 being the CIA's creation to keep China down.<ref name=20200208economist>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |title=China's rulers see the coronavirus as a chance to tighten their grip |date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200229034330/https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/08/chinas-rulers-see-the-coronavirus-as-a-chance-to-tighten-their-grip |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[NBC News]] however has noted that there have also been debunking efforts of US-related conspiracy theories posted online, with a WeChat search of \"Coronavirus is from the U.S.\" reported to mostly yield articles explaining why such claims are unreasonable.<ref name=nbcnews1151291>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/coronavirus-rumors-misinformation-swirl-unchecked-china-n1151291|title=Coronavirus rumors \u2013 and misinformation \u2013 swirl unchecked in China|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to an investigation by [[ProPublica]], such conspiracy theories and disinformation have been propagated under the direction of [[China News Service]], the country's second largest state-owned media outlet controlled by the [[United Front Work Department]].<ref name=20200326propublica>{{Cite news|last=Kao|first=Jeff| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-built-a-twitter-propaganda-machine-then-let-it-loose-on-coronavirus|title=How China Built a Twitter Propaganda Machine Then Let It Loose on Coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|work=[[ProPublica]]|access-date=March 31, 2020|last2=Li|first2=Mia Shuang}}</ref> ''[[Global Times]]'' and [[Xinhua News Agency]] have similarly been implicated in propagating disinformation related to COVID-19's origins.<ref name=20200405telegraph>{{Cite news|last=Dodds|first=Laurence| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2020/04/05/china-floods-facebook-instagram-undeclared-coronavirus-propaganda/|title=China floods Facebook with undeclared coronavirus propaganda ads blaming Trump|date=April 5, 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=April 5, 2020|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nMultiple conspiracy articles in Chinese from the SARS era resurfaced during the outbreak with altered details, claiming that SARS is biological warfare conducted by the US against China. Some of these articles claim that [[BGI Group]] from China sold genetic information of the Chinese people to the US, with the US then being able to deploy the virus specifically targeting the [[genome]] of Chinese individuals.<ref name=setn677313>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u9577\u6307\u7a31\u300c\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u662f\u7f8e\u570b\u6295\u653e\u75c5\u6bd2\u300d\u3000\u7db2\u53cb\u50bb\u7206\u773c|url=https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219211548/https://www.setn.com/News.aspx?NewsID=677313|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, Chinese military news site Xilu published an article detailing how the virus was artificially combined by the US to \"precisely target Chinese people\".<ref name=xilu1000010001>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd24\u4e2a\u5173\u952e\u86cb\u767d\u88ab\u66ff\u6362\uff0c\u53ef\u7cbe\u51c6\u653b\u51fb\u534e\u4eba|url=http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|access-date=February 7, 2020|work=\u897f\u9646\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211022551/http://www.xilu.com/20200126/1000010001119697.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}} The article was removed after early February.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSome articles on popular sites in China have also cast suspicion on US military athletes participating in the Wuhan [[2019 Military World Games]], which lasted until the end of October 2019, and have suggested that they deployed the virus. They claim the inattentive attitude and disproportionately below-average results of American athletes in the games indicate they might have been there for other purposes and they might actually be bio-warfare operatives. Such posts stated that their place of residence during their stay in Wuhan was also close to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]], where the first known cluster of cases occurred.<ref name=szhgh221836>{{cite web|language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u6b66\u6c49\u8fd9\u573a\u761f\u75ab\uff0c\u5fc5\u987b\u5f97\u9760\u89e3\u653e\u519b\uff1f|url=http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|access-date=February 21, 2020|publisher=\u7ea2\u6b4c\u4f1a\u7f51|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221185358/http://www.szhgh.com/Article/opinion/zatan/2020-01-30/221836.html|archive-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, this conspiracy theory was endorsed by [[Zhao Lijian]], a spokesperson from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" >{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Ching-Tse |title=China's foreign ministry accuses US military of bringing virus to Wuhan |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3896257 |work=Taiwan News |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=thehill487308>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=China, pushing conspiracy theory, accuses US Army of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/487308-china-pushing-conspiracy-theory-us-army-bringing-coronavirus-wuhan |newspaper=The Hill |access-date=March 13, 2020|date=March 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Didi |title=China accuses US of bringing coronavirus to Wuhan |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/china-accuses-us-of-bringing-coronavirus-to-wuhan-c9rrfbrs7 |work=The Times |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the US government summoned Chinese Ambassador [[Cui Tiankai]] to Washington DC over the coronavirus conspiracy theory.<ref name=20200314alarabiyaB>{{Cite news|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|title=US summons China's ambassador to Washington over coronavirus conspiracy theory|date=March 14, 2020|work=[[Al Arabiya English]]|access-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316012205/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/world/2020/03/14/US-summons-China-s-ambassador-to-Washington-over-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Arab world====\n\nAccording to Washington DC-based nonprofit [[Middle East Media Research Institute]], numerous writers in the Arabic press have promoted the conspiracy theory that COVID-19, as well as SARS and the swine flu virus, were deliberately created and spread by the US to sell vaccines against these diseases, and it is \"part of an economic and psychological war waged by the US against China with the aim of weakening it and presenting it as a backward country and a source of diseases\".<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |title=Arab Writers: The Coronavirus Is Part Of Biological Warfare Waged By The U.S. Against China |date=February 6, 2020 |publisher=[[Middle East Media Research Institute]] |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209043001/https://www.memri.org/reports/arab-writers-coronavirus-part-biological-warfare-waged-us-against-china |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iraqi political analyst Sabah Al-Akili on [[Aletejah TV|Al-Etejah TV]], Saudi daily [[Al Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al-Watan]] writer Sa'ud Al-Shehry, Syrian daily [[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|Al-Thawra]] columnist Hussein Saqer, and Egyptian journalist Ahmad Rif'at on Egyptian news website Vetogate, were some examples given by MEMRI as propagators of the US biowarfare conspiracy theory in the Arabic world.<ref name=\"MEMRI-arab-disinfo\" />\n\n====Philippine====\n\nA Filipino Senator, [[Tito Sotto]], played a bioweapon conspiracy video in a February 2020 Senate hearing, suggesting that the coronavirus is biowarfare waged against China.<ref name=\"nypost-rubio\">{{Cite news|last=Rubio|first=Marco| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Marco Rubio: Russia, China and Iran are waging disinformation war over coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304233343/https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/russia-china-and-iran-are-waging-disinformation-war-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=philstar1990332>{{Cite news|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|title=Bioweapon conspiracy video creeps into Senate coronavirus hearing|date=February 4, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310163521/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/04/1990332/bioweapon-conspiracy-video-creeps-senate-coronavirus-hearing|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n\n[[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Constituent Assembly]] member Elvis M\u00e9ndez declared that the coronavirus was a \"bacteriological sickness created in '89, in '90 and historically\" and that it was a sickness \"inoculated by the ''[[gringo]]s''\". M\u00e9ndez theorized that the virus was a weapon against Latin America and China and that its purpose was \"to demoralize the person, to weaken to install their system\".<ref name=20200307somostuvoz>{{cite web|url=http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|title=Constituyente Elvis M\u00e9ndez: \"El coronavirus lo inocularon los gringos\"|last=Web|first=Master| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 7, 2020|website=Somos Tu Voz|language=es|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318065112/http://www.somostuvoz.net/destacado/constituyente-elvis-mendez-el-coronavirus-lo-inocularon-los-gringos/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Muslim===\n\n{{further|2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|Islamophobia}}\nIn India, Muslims have been blamed for spreading infection following the emergence of cases linked to a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious gathering.<ref name=newsweek1496011>{{cite journal|title=India's Coronavirus Outbreak Stokes Islamophobia as Muslims blamed for spreading infection|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.newsweek.com/indias-coronavirus-outbreak-stokes-islamophobia-muslims-blamed-spreading-infection-1496011|access-date=April 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are reports of vilification of Muslims on social media and attacks on individuals in India.<ref name=firstpost8231371>{{cite journal|first=Pinak Pani|last=Datta| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus outbreak sparks racist attacks on people from North East, stokes Islamophobia on social media|journal=[[Firstpost]]|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-sparks-racist-attacks-on-people-from-north-east-stokes-islamophobia-on-social-media-8231371.html}}</ref> Claims have been made Muslims are selling food contaminated with coronavirus and that a mosque in Patna was sheltering people from Italy and Iran.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nishita|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=A Cluster Of Coronavirus Cases Can Be Traced Back to a Single Mosque And Now 200 Million Muslims Are Being Vilified|journal=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=April 3, 2020|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat}}</ref> These claims were shown to be false.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Priyanka|last=Jha| name-list-format = vanc |title=No, foreign nationals from Italy, Iran weren't hiding in Patna mosque to avoid coronavirus testing|journal=[[Firstpost]]|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.altnews.in/were-50-foreigners-from-itlay-iran-and-china-hiding-in-mosque-due-to-corona-virus-detained-in-bihar-kurji/}}</ref> In the UK, there are reports of far-right groups blaming Muslims for the coronavirus outbreak and falsely claiming that mosques remained open after the national ban on large gatherings.<ref name=20200405theguardian>{{cite journal|first=Nazia|last=Parveen| name-list-format = vanc |title=Police investigate UK far-right groups over anti-Muslim coronavirus claims|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 5, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/police-investigate-uk-far-right-groups-over-anti-muslim-coronavirus-claims/}}</ref>\n\n===Antisemitic===\n\n{{further|Antisemitic canard}}\nIran's [[Press TV]] asserted that \"Zionist elements developed a deadlier strain of coronavirus against Iran\".<ref name=\"presstv\"/>\nSimilarly, various Arab media outlets accused Israel and the United States of creating and spreading COVID-19, [[avian flu]], and [[SARS]].<ref name=jpost617021>{{cite journal|title=Arab media accuse US, Israel of coronavirus conspiracy against China|journal=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=February 9, 2020|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301063057/https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Arab-media-accuse-US-Israel-of-coronavirus-conspiracy-against-China-617021|archive-date=March 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Users on social media offered a variety of theories, including the supposition that Jews had manufactured COVID-19 to precipitate a global stock market collapse and thereby profit via [[insider trading]],<ref name=forward441421>{{cite journal|first=Irene|last=Connelly| name-list-format = vanc |title=Online anti-Semitism thrives around coronavirus, even on mainstream platforms|journal=[[The Forward]]|url=https://forward.com/news/441421/anti-semitic-coronavirus-response-thrives-online-even-on-mainstream/}}</ref> while a guest on Turkish television posited a more ambitious scenario in which Jews and Zionists had created COVID-19, avian flu, and [[Crimean\u2013Congo hemorrhagic fever]] to \"design the world, seize countries, [and] neuter the world's population\".<ref name=20200314timesofisrael>{{cite journal|first=Eric|last=Cortellessa| name-list-format = vanc |title=Conspiracy theory that Jews created virus spreads on social media, ADL says|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|date=March 14, 2020|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133541/https://www.timesofisrael.com/conspiracy-theory-that-jews-created-virus-spreads-on-social-media-adl-says/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli attempts to develop a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] prompted mixed reactions. Grand Ayatollah [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] denied initial reports that he had ruled that a Zionist-made vaccine would be [[halal]],<ref name=jpost621230>{{cite news|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi| name-list-format = vanc |title=Iranian cleric denies approving use of coronavirus vaccine from Israel|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Iranian-cleric-denies-approving-use-of-coronavirus-vaccine-from-Israel-621230|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and one Press TV journalist tweeted that \"I'd rather take my chances with the virus than consume an Israeli vaccine\".<ref name=jpost620900>{{cite news|title=Would a Zionist coronavirus cure be Halal? Iranian cleric says yes|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Is-Zionist-coronavirus-cure-Halal-Iranian-cleric-says-yes-620900|date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A columnist for the Turkish ''[[Yeni Akit]]'' asserted that such a vaccine could be a ruse to carry out [[Compulsory sterilization|mass sterilization]].<ref name=jpost621393>{{cite news|last=Edmunds|first=Donna Rachel| name-list-format = vanc |title=Coronavirus is a Zionist plot, say Turkish politicians, media, public|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Antisemitism/Coronavirus-is-a-Zionist-plot-say-Turkish-politicians-media-public-621393|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn alert by the US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] regarding the possible threat of far-right extremists intentionally spreading the coronavirus mentioned blame being assigned to Jews and Jewish leaders for causing the pandemic and several statewide shutdowns across the US.<ref name=go69737522>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|first=Josh|last=Margolin| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[ABC News]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Spy operation===\n\nSome people have alleged that the coronavirus was stolen from a Canadian virus research lab by Chinese scientists. [[Health Canada]] and the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] said that conspiracy theory had \"no factual basis\".<ref name=nofact/> The stories seem to have been derived<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\"/> from a July 2019 news article<ref name=escorted/> stating that some Chinese researchers had their security access to a [[National Microbiology Laboratory|Canadian Level 4 virology facility]] revoked in a [[RCMP|federal police]] investigation; Canadian officials described this as an administrative matter and said that \"there is absolutely no risk to the Canadian public.\"<ref name=escorted>{{cite news |last1=Pauls |first1=Karen Pauls |title=Chinese researcher escorted from infectious disease lab amid RCMP investigation |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=July 14, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206011635/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/chinese-researcher-escorted-from-infectious-disease-lab-amid-rcmp-investigation-1.5211567 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThis article was published by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] (CBC);<ref name=\"buzz_doxx\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |title=A Pro-Trump Blog Doxed A Chinese Scientist It Falsely Accused Of Creating The Coronavirus As A Bioweapon |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210034232/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/a-pro-trump-blog-has-doxed-a-chinese-scientist-it-falsely |archive-date=February 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> responding to the conspiracy theories, the CBC later stated that \"CBC reporting never claimed the two scientists were spies, or that they brought any version of the coronavirus to the lab in Wuhan\". While pathogen samples were transferred from the lab in [[Winnipeg]], Canada to Beijing, China, on March 31, 2019, neither of the samples was a coronavirus, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] says that the shipment conformed to all federal policies, and there has not been any statement that the researchers under investigation were responsible for sending the shipment. The current location of the researchers under investigation by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] is not being released.<ref name=nofact>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |title=Online claims that Chinese scientists stole coronavirus from Winnipeg lab have 'no factual basis' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208134329/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/china-coronavirus-online-chatter-conspiracy-1.5442376 |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |title=Chinese translation: \u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u4ece\u6e29\u5c3c\u4f2f\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5ba4\u4e2d\u7a83\u53d6 \u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u7f51\u7edc\u4f20\u8a00'\u6ca1\u6709\u4e8b\u5b9e\u6839\u636e' |last=Yates |first=Karen |last2=Pauls |first2=Jeff | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |time=January 27, 2020 |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201040447/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E7%A7%91%E5%AD%A6%E5%AE%B6%E4%BB%8E%E6%B8%A9%E5%B0%BC%E4%BC%AF%E5%AE%9E%E9%AA%8C%E5%AE%A4%E4%B8%AD%E7%AA%83%E5%8F%96-%E5%86%A0%E7%8A%B6%E7%97%85%E6%AF%92%E7%9A%84%E7%BD%91%E7%BB%9C%E4%BC%A0%E8%A8%80-%E6%B2%A1%E6%9C%89%E4%BA%8B%E5%AE%9E%E6%A0%B9%E6%8D%AE-1.5448165 |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200128factcheck\">{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |title=Coronavirus Wasn't Sent by 'Spy' From Canada |first=Saranac Hale |last=Spencer | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Factcheck.org |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130160015/https://www.factcheck.org/2020/01/coronavirus-wasnt-sent-by-spy-from-canada/ |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the midst of the coronavirus epidemic, a senior research associate and expert in biological warfare with the [[Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies]], referring to a [[NATO]] press conference, identified suspicions of espionage as the reason behind the expulsions from the lab, but made no suggestion that coronavirus was taken from the Canadian lab or that it is the result of bioweapons defense research in China.<ref name=20200129besacenter>{{cite web |url=https://besacenter.org/perspectives-papers/china-biological-warfare/ |title=China and Viruses: The Case of Dr. Xiangguo Qiu |last=Shoham | name-list-format = vanc |first=Dany |publisher=Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic Studies |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Population control scheme===\n\nAccording to the BBC, Jordan Sather, a conspiracy theory [[YouTuber]] supporting the [[QAnon|far-right QAnon conspiracy theory]] and the [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vax]] movement, has falsely claimed the outbreak was a population control scheme created by [[Pirbright Institute]] in England and by former [[Microsoft]] CEO [[Bill Gates]]. This belief is held mostly by [[Paleolibertarianism|right-wing libertarians]], [[New World Order (conspiracy theory)|NWO conspiracy theorists]], and [[Christian fundamentalism|Christian Fundamentalists]].<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\"20200123buzzfeednews\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |title=QAnon Supporters And Anti-Vaxxers Are Spreading A Hoax That Bill Gates Created The Coronavirus |last=Broderick |first=Ryan | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 23, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130075624/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/qanon-supporters-and-anti-vaxxers-are-spreading-a-hoax-that |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accidental leakage===\nA number of allegations have emerged on the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology#Concerns as source|link]] between the virus and [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV), among these is that the virus was an accidental leakage from WIV.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web | website=BBC News China | url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | title=[TRANSLATED] Wuhan Pneumonia: \"Wuhan Virus Research Institute\" in the eyes of the outbreak and fake news storm | date=February 5, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216162120/https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/chinese-news-51388024 | archive-date=February 16, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2017, US molecular biologist [[Richard H. Ebright]], expressed caution when the WIV was expanded to become mainland China's first [[biosafety level 4]] (BSL\u20134) laboratory, noting previous escapes of the SARS virus at other Chinese laboratories.<ref name=\"nature\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cyranoski D | title = Inside the Chinese lab poised to study world's most dangerous pathogens | journal = Nature | volume = 542 | issue = 7642 | pages = 399\u2013400 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28230144 | doi = 10.1038/nature.2017.21487 | bibcode = 2017Natur.542..399C | doi-access = free }}</ref> While Ebright refuted several conspiracy theories regarding the WIV (e.g. bioweapons research, that the virus was engineered), he told BBC China that this did not represent the possibility that the virus can be \"completely ruled out\" from entering the population due to a laboratory accident.<ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\nIn February 2020, it has been alleged that the first person infected may have been a researcher at the institute named Huang Yanling.<ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\" /> Rumours circulated on Chinese social media that the researcher had become infected and died, prompting a denial from WIV, saying that she was a graduate student enrolled in the Institute until 2015 and is not the patient zero.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whiov.ac.cn/tzgg_105342/202002/t20200216_5500201.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u58f0\u660e |date=February 16, 2020 |work=Wuhan Institute of Virology }}</ref><ref name=\"scmp0216_huangyanling\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3050872/chinese-research-lab-denies-rumours-links-first-coronavirus |title=Chinese research lab denies rumours of links to first coronavirus patient |date=16 February 2020|first=Jun |last= Mai | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> In April, the conspiracy theory started to circulate around on Youtube and got picked up by conservative media, ''National Review''.<ref name=20200403nationalreview>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/coronavirus-china-trail-leading-back-to-wuhan-labs/ |title= The Trail Leading Back to the Wuhan Labs |first= Jim |last=Geraghty | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|work=National Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/04/14/as-the-coronavirus-spreads-conspiracy-theories-are-going-viral-too/|title=As the Coronavirus Spreads, Conspiracy Theories Are Going Viral Too|website=Foreign Policy|date= 14 April 2020|first=Elise |last=Thomas | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' (SCMP) reported that one of the WIV's lead researchers, [[Shi Zhengli]], was the particular focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media alleging that her work on bat-based viruses was the source of the virus; this led Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\". When asked by the SCMP to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | first=Stephen | last=Chen | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 6, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207210442/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | archive-date=February 7, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref name=caixinglobal101512828>{{cite web | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | first1=Yang | last1=Rui | first2=Feng | last2=Yuding | first3=Zhao | last3=Jinchao | first4=Matthew | last4=Walsh | name-list-format = vanc | date=February 7, 2020 | access-date=February 8, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219215801/https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | archive-date=February 19, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Immunologist [[Vincent Racaniello]] stated that virus leaking theory \"reflect a lack of understanding of the genetic make-up of Sars-CoV-2 and its relationship to the bat virus\". He states that the bat virus researched in the institution \"would not have been able to infect humans \u2013 the human Sars-CoV-2 has additional changes that allows it to infect humans.\"<ref name=\"scmp0411\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3079391/bat-virus-bioweapon-what-science-says-about-covid-19-origins |title=Bat virus? Bioweapon? What the science says about Covid-19 origins |date=11 April 2020|first=Simone |last= McCarthy|first2=Stephen |last2=Chen | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, the US [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], General [[Mark A. Milley|Mark Milley]], in response to questions about the virus being manufactured in a lab, said \"... it\u2019s inconclusive, although the weight of evidence seems to indicate natural. But we don\u2019t know for certain.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/14/covid-19-origin-lab-general-mark-milley |title=US military chief: 'Weight of evidence' that Covid-19 did not originate in a lab |first=Julian |last=Borger | name-list-format = vanc |date= 14 April 2020 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> Days later, multiple media outlets confirmed that U.S. intelligence officials were investigating the possibility that the virus started in the WIV.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |title=U.S. intel community examining whether coronavirus emerged accidentally from a Chinese lab |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/china/u-s-intel-community-examining-whether-coronavirus-emerged-accidentally-chinese-n1185371 |website=NBC News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren P. |title=U.S. Intelligence Sifts Evidence for Origins of Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-intelligence-sifts-evidence-for-origins-of-coronavirus-11587077170 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gazis |first1=Olivia |title=U.S. intelligence community still investigating origins of COVID-19 outbreak, including whether it was a lab accident |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-covid-19-origins-investigation-wuhan-lab-accident/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Campbell |first1=Josh |title=US explores possibility that coronavirus spread started in Chinese lab, not a market |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/15/politics/us-intelligence-virus-started-chinese-lab/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===Age===\nDespite sufficient data gathered in regards of case fatality rates by age group,<ref name=\"covidstats\">{{cite web|url=https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus#what-do-we-know-about-the-risk-of-dying-from-covid-19|title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) \u2013 Statistics and Research}}</ref> rumours of young people with no premorbidities dying of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus were circulating social media and were even published by large daily newspapers.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52041709|title=Chloe Middleton: Woman, 21, died with 'no underlying health issues'|website=BBC|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"express\">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1260123/Chloe-Middleton-coronavirus-death-UK-latest-Facebook-video-COVID-19-symptoms|title=Heartbreak as healthy 21-year-old dies from coronavirus \u2013 'It's not just a virus'|website=Express|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> However, many of these media reports have proven to be false or misrepresented upon closer inspection - such cases included news about a 21-year old spanish football coach Francisco Garcia<ref name=\"yahoosport\">{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/spanish-football-coach-francisco-garcia-163153573.html|title=Spanish football coach Francisco Garcia dies of coronavirus aged 21|website=Sports Yahoo|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> and British 21-year old woman Chloe Middleton.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20200329015127/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/chloe-middleton-death-21-year-old-not-recorded-nhs-covid-19-related|title=Chloe Middleton: death of 21-year-old not recorded as Covid-19|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"spiked\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2020/03/27/chloe-middleton-the-coronavirus-death-that-wasnt/|title=Chloe Middleton: the coronavirus death that wasn't|website=Spiked|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>{{MEDCN|date=April 2020}}<!--implication that young people without co-morbidities can't die-->\n\n===Nurse whistleblower===\n\nOn January 24, a video circulated online appearing to be of a nurse named ''Jin Hui''<ref name=\"theinitium20200130\">{{cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|title=\u6cdb\u79d1\u5b78\uff1a\u95dc\u65bc\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u768420\u500b\u50b3\u8a00\uff0c\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u771f\u54ea\u4e9b\u662f\u5047\uff1f|website=The Initium|date=January 30, 2020|language=Chinese|first1=Peiqi|last1=Luo|first2=Yingkai|last2=Liao| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202120919/https://theinitium.com/article/20200130-repost-pansci-2019ncov-misinformation/|archive-date=February 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Hubei]] describing a far more dire situation in Wuhan than purported by Chinese officials. The video claimed that more than 90,000 people had been infected with the virus in China, the virus can spread from one person to 14 people and the virus is starting the second mutation.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |title=Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube struggle with coronavirus hoaxes |last=Ghaffary |first=Shirin | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 31, 2020 |website=Vox |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208004124/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/1/31/21115589/coronavirus-wuhan-china-myths-hoaxes-facebook-social-media-tiktok-twitter-wechat |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The video attracted millions of views on various social media platforms and was mentioned in numerous online reports. However, the BBC noted that contrary to its English subtitles in one of the video's existing versions, the woman does not claim to be either a nurse or a doctor in the video and that her suit and mask do not match the ones worn by medical staff in Hubei.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /> The video's claim of 90,000 infected cases is noted to be 'unsubstantiated'.<ref name=\"bbc_misinfo\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n===Alleged leak of death toll===\n\nOn February 25, ''[[Taiwan News]]'' published an article, claiming [[Tencent]] accidentally leaked the real numbers of death and infection in China. ''Taiwan News'' suggests the ''Tencent Epidemic Situation Tracker'' had briefly showed infected cases and death tolls many times higher of the official figure, citing a Facebook post by 38-year-old Taiwanese beverage store owner ''Hiroki Lo'' and an anonymous Taiwanese [[netizen]].<ref name=taiwannews3871594>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|title=Tencent may have accidentally leaked real data on Wuhan virus deaths|first=Keoni|last=Everington | name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Taiwan News]]|date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200217020907/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3871594|archive-date=February 17, 2020|access-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The article was referenced by other news outlets such as ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and widely circulated on Twitter, Facebook, 4chan, sparked a wide range of conspiracy theories that the screenshot indicates the real death toll instead of the ones published by health officials.<ref name=bloommag /> Justin Lessler, associate professor at the Bloomberg School of Public Health, claims the numbers of the alleged \"leak\" are unreasonable and unrealistic, citing the case fatality rate as far lower than the 'leaked information'. A spokesman of Tencent responded to the news article, claiming the image was doctored, and it features \"false information which we never published\".<ref name=inews1411992>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |title=A massively shared story about the 'real' Coronavirus death toll is fake: Here's how we know |date=February 11, 2020 |website=iNews |last=Sharma |first=Ruchira | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191409/https://inews.co.uk/news/coronavirus-death-toll-story-fake-china-virus-explained-1411992 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKeoni Everington, author of the original news article, defended and asserted the authenticity of the leak.<ref name=\"bloommag\" /> Brian Hioe and Lars Wooster of ''New Bloom Magazine'' debunked the theory from data on other websites, which were using Tencent's database to generate custom visualizations while showing none of the inflated figures appearing in the images promulgated by ''Taiwan News''. Thus, they concluded the screenshot was digitally fabricated.<ref name=\"bloommag\">{{cite web |url=https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |title=TAIWAN NEWS PUBLISHES COVID-19 MISINFORMATION AS EPIDEMIC SPREADS |first=Brian |last=Hioe |first2=Lars |last2=Wooster | name-list-format = vanc |website=New Bloom Magazine |date=February 12, 2020 |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229191408/https://newbloommag.net/2020/02/12/coronavirus-taiwan-news/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation against Taiwan===\n\n{{further|Cross-Strait relations}}\nOn February 26, 2020, Taiwanese [[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] reported that large amounts of misinformation had appeared on Facebook claiming [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|the pandemic in Taiwan]] had lost control, the Taiwanese Government had covered up the total number of cases, and that President [[Tsai Ing-wen]] had been infected. The Taiwan fact-checking organization had suggested the misinformation on Facebook shared similarities with [[mainland China]] due to its use of [[simplified Chinese]] and mainland China vocabulary. The organization warns the purpose of the misinformation is to attack the government.<ref name=cna2020022604>{{cite news|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/202002260428.aspx|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u8b20\u8a00\u591a \u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3\u63073\u5927\u5171\u540c\u9ede|date=February 26, 2020|agency=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]] |language=zh-tw}}</ref><ref name=taipeitimes2003731764>{{cite news |title=Virus Outbreak: Chinese trolls decried for fake news |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |work=Taipei Times |date=February 28, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301114540/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2020/02/28/2003731764 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200229reuters>{{cite news |title=Taiwan accuses China of waging cyber 'war' to disrupt virus fight |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |agency=Reuters |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160250/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-taiwan/taiwan-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-total-at-39-idUSKBN20N09C |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Taiwan's [[Ministry of Justice Investigation Bureau]] warned that mainland China was trying to undermine trust in factual news by portraying the Taiwanese Government reports as fake news. Taiwanese authorities have been ordered to use all possible means to track whether the messages were linked to instructions given by the Communist Party of China. The PRC's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] denied the claims calling them lies and said that Taiwan's [[Democratic Progressive Party]] was \"inciting hatred\" between the two sides. They then claimed that the \"DPP continues to politically manipulate the virus\".<ref name=20200303reuters>{{cite news |first1=Yimou |last1=Lee |first2=Ben |last2=Blanchard | name-list-format = vanc |title='Provocative' China pressures Taiwan with fighters, fake news amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 5, 2020 |quote=\"We have been told to track if the origins are linked to instructions given by the Communist Party, using all possible means,\" the official said, adding that authorities had increased scrutiny on online platforms, including chat rooms. |date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305160849/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-taiwan-china/provocative-china-pressures-taiwan-with-fighters-fake-news-amid-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN20Q08M |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', China has used organized disinformation campaigns against Taiwan for decades.<ref name=washingtonpost3400200>{{cite web |last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=Russia's disinformation campaign in the U.S. has nothing on China's efforts in Taiwan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/russias-disinformation-campaign-in-the-us-has-nothing-on-chinas-efforts-in-taiwan/2020/01/08/3400200a-231a-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html |work=The Washington Post |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNick Monaco the research director of the Digital Intelligence Lab at Institute for the Future analyzed the posts and concluded that the majority appear to have come from ordinary users in China not the state. However, he criticized the Chinese government making to decision to allow the information to spread beyond China's [[Great Firewall]] which he described as \"malicious.\"<ref name=npr814709530>{{cite web |title=With Odds Against It, Taiwan Keeps Coronavirus Corralled |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/814709530/with-odds-against-it-taiwan-keeps-coronavirus-corralled |publisher=NPR |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Taiwan News'', nearly 1 in 4 cases of misinformation are believed to be connected to mainland China.<ref name=taiwannews3904042>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3904042|title=One-fourth of coronavirus misinformation in Taiwan comes from Chinese trolls: CIB|website=Taiwan News|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020 the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] announced that it was partnering with the Taiwan FactCheck Center to help combat misinformation about the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Chen |last1=Yun-yu |first2=Matthew |last2=Mazzetta | name-list-format = vanc |title=AIT partners with local group to combat COVID-19 disinformation |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202003270016 |website=focustaiwan.tw |publisher=Focus Taiwan |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Misrepresented World Population Project map ===\n\nIn early February, a decade-old map illustrating a hypothetical viral outbreak published by the World Population Project (part of the [[University of Southampton]]) was misappropriated by a number of Australian media news outlets (and British tabloids ''The Sun'', ''Daily Mail'' and ''Metro'')<ref name=\":4\" /> which claimed the map represented the 2020 coronavirus outbreak. This misinformation was then spread via the social media accounts of the same media outlets, and while some outlets later removed the map, the BBC reported that a number of news sites had yet to retract the map.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|author=Reality Check team|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|title=How a misleading coronavirus map went global|date=February 19, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219013538/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51504512|archive-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Decline in cellphone subscriptions===\nThere was a decrease of nearly 21 million cellphone subscriptions among the three largest cellphone carriers in China, which led to the spread of misinformation that this is evidence for millions of deaths due to the coronavirus in China.<ref name=laj-dicu/> However, the decline in cellphone subscriptions is actually attributed to people cancelling phone services as a result of a downturn in the social and economic life during the outbreak.<ref name=laj-dicu>{{cite web |last1=Lajka |first1=Arijeta |title=Drop in cellphone users in China wrongly attributed to coronavirus deaths |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8717250566 |website=AP NEWS |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Medical misinformation==\n{{main|List of unproven methods against COVID-19}}\n<!--This article is becoming longer by the day. Please try to add new content in the :List of unproven methods against COVID-19\" page instead of doing so here-->\nWidely circulated posts on social media have made many unfounded claims of methods against coronavirus. Some of these claims are scams, and some promoted methods are dangerous and unhealthy.<ref name=WHO_myths/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Andrew |title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> For misinformation that is a direct claim of a method to prevent, diagnose, or treat COVID-19, see [[List of unproven methods against COVID-19]]. This section deals only with other misinformation or prevent/diagnose/treat claims with wider social consquences.\n\n===COVID-19 recovery===\nIt has been wrongly claimed that anyone infected with COVID-19 will have the virus in their bodies for life. While there is no curative treatment, infected individuals can recover from the disease, eliminating the virus from their bodies; getting supportive medical care early can help.<ref name=WHO_myths/>\n\n===Vaccine pre-existence===\nIt was reported that multiple social media posts have promoted a conspiracy theory claiming the virus was known and that a vaccine was already available. [[PolitiFact]] and [[FactCheck.org]] noted that no vaccine currently exists for COVID-19. The patents cited by various social media posts reference existing patents for genetic sequences and vaccines for other strains of coronavirus such as the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|SARS coronavirus]].<ref name=20200123politifact>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |title=No, there is no vaccine for the Wuhan coronavirus |first=Tom |last=Kertscher | name-list-format = vanc |website=Politifact |date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=February 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207133056/https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/jan/23/facebook-posts/there-outbreak-china-wuhan-coronavirus-there-not-v/ |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200124factcheckA\" /> The WHO reported as of February 5, 2020 that amid news reports of \"breakthrough\" drugs being discovered to treat people infected with the virus, there were no known effective treatments;<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |title=WHO: 'no known effective' treatments for new coronavirus |date=February 5, 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=February 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205155653/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-treatments-who-idUSKBN1ZZ1M6 |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> this included antibiotics and herbal remedies not being useful.<ref name=aljazeera2002020934>{{cite news |title=Dispelling the myths around the new coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html |access-date=February 8, 2020 |publisher=Al Jazeera |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206033735/https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/02/dispelling-myths-coronavirus-outbreak-200202093426388.html?utm_source=website&utm_medium=article_page&utm_campaign=read_more_links |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[COVID-19 vaccine|Scientists are working to develop a vaccine]], but as of March 18, 2020, no vaccine candidates have completed clinical trials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocaine===\nCocaine does not protect against COVID-19. Several viral tweets purporting that snorting [[cocaine]] would sterilize one's nostrils of the coronavirus spread around Europe and Africa. In response, the [[French Ministry of Health]] released a public service announcement debunking this claim, saying \"No, cocaine does NOT protect against COVID-19. It is an addictive drug that causes serious side effects and is harmful to people\u2019s health.\" The [[World Health Organisation]] also debunked the claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|title=Sorry to the French People Who Thought Cocaine Would Protect Them From Coronavirus|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |website=Pedestrian.TV|access-date=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311082415/https://www.pedestrian.tv/news/french-government-cocaine-coke-coronavirus-hoax/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ethnic resistance/susceptibilty===\n\nThere have been claims that specific [[ethnicities]] are more or less vulnerable to COVID-19. COVID-19 is a new [[zoonotic]] disease, so no population has yet had the time to develop [[population immunity]].{{medcn|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeginning on February 11, reports, quickly spread via Facebook, implied that a Cameroonian student in China had been completely cured of the virus due to his African genetics. While a student was successfully treated, other media sources have noted that no evidence implies Africans are more resistant to the virus and labeled such claims as false information.<ref name=20200212afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|title=Black people aren't more resistant to novel coronavirus|date=February 12, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216141447/https://factcheck.afp.com/black-people-arent-more-resistant-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenyan Secretary of Health [[Mutahi Kagwe]] explicitly refuted rumors that \"those with black skin cannot get coronavirus\", while announcing Kenya's first case on March 13.<ref name=20200313cnn>{{cite news|title=Minister rejects false rumors that 'those with black skin cannot get coronavirus' as Kenya records first case|first1=Mia|last1=Alberti|first2=Bethlehem|last2=Feleke| name-list-format = vanc |publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319003805/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-13-20-intl-hnk/h_daa3fbd19db18fdbb4be569a9613fe96|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This myth was cited as a contributing factor in the disproportionately high rates of infection and death observed among African Americans.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poston |first1=Ben |last2=Barboza |first2=Tony |last3=Jennings |first3=Angel | name-list-format = vanc |title=L.A. releases first racial breakdown of coronavirus fatalities; blacks have higher death rate|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-07/l-a-releases-first-racial-breakdown-of-coronavirus-fatalities-african-americans-have-higher-death-rate}}</ref><ref name=usatoday2961323001>{{cite news|last=Barfield Berry |first=Deborah | name-list-format = vanc  |title=Black people dying from coronavirus at much higher rates in cities across the USA | newspaper=USA Today |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/04/07/who-dying-coronavirus-more-black-people-die-major-cities/2961323001/}}</ref>\n\nThere have been claims of \"Indian immunity\": that the people of India have more immunity to the COVID-19 virus due to living conditions in India. This idea was deemed \"absolute drivel\" by Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS). He said that there was no [[population immunity]] to the COVID-19 virus yet, as it is new, and it is not even clear whether people who have recovered from COVID-19 will have lasting immunity, as this happens with some viruses but not with others.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |work=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] claimed that the virus was genetically targeted at Iranians by the USA, and this is why it is [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|seriously affecting Iran]]. He did not offer any evidence.<ref name=\"independent-corona\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Iran's leader suggests US cooked up 'special version' of virus to target country |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-us-target-country-special-version-covid19-a9417206.html |work=The Independent |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=france2420200322>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200322-iran-s-supreme-leader-khamanei-refuses-us-help-to-fight-coronavirus-citing-conspiracy-theory |title=Iran's Khamanei refuses US help to fight coronavirus, citing conspiracy theory |date= March 22, 2020|publisher=France 24 }}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 xenophobic blaming by ethnicity===<!--not sure if this doesn't belong with some of the nationally-based blaming above-->\nCOVID-19-related [[xenophobic]] attacks have been made against people the attacker blamed for COVID-19 on the basis of their ethnicity. The [[Asian Australian Alliance]] did a survey on attacks against Asian Australians in April 2020; 81% of victims said they believed the attack against them was related to the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Naaman |title=Survey of Covid-19 racism against Asian Australians records 178 incidents in two weeks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/17/survey-of-covid-19-racism-against-asian-australians-records-178-incidents-in-two-weeks |work=The Guardian |date=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[White supremacist]] groups have blamed COVID-19 on non-whites and advocated deliberately infecting minorities they dislike, such as Jews.<ref>{{cite web |title=World - as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19 - News - msn |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/as-world-struggles-to-stop-deaths-far-right-celebrates-covid-19/ |website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n<!--On the basis of historical examples, there have been warnings about discriminating by immunity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olivarius |first1=Kathryn |title=The Dangerous History of Immunoprivilege |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/opinion/coronavirus-immunity-passports.html |website=The New York Times |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>-->\n\n===5G===\nThe theories linking 5G mobile phone networks to COVID-19 were described as the \"worst kind of fake news\" by Professor Steve Powis, national medical director of [[NHS England]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\"/> Viruses cannot be transmitted by [[radio waves]]. COVID-19 is spreading in many countries which do not have 5G networks.<ref name=WHO_myths/>\n\nIn February 2020, [[BBC News]] reported that conspiracy theorists on social media groups alleged a link between coronavirus and [[5G]] mobile networks, claiming that [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Wuhan]] and [[Diamond Princess outbreak]]s were [[Wireless device radiation and health|directly caused by electromagnetic fields and the introduction of 5G and wireless technologies]]. Some conspiracy theorists also alleged that the coronavirus outbreak was [[cover-up]] for a 5G-related illness.<ref name=\"bbc-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|title=Coronavirus: Fake news is spreading fast|work=[[BBC]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Rory|last=Cellan-Jones| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317062547/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51646309|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Thomas Cowan, a [[Alternative medicine|holistic medical practitioner]] who trained as a physician and operates on probation with [[Medical Board of California]], alleged that coronavirus is caused by 5G, based on the claims that [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|African countries were not affected significantly by the pandemic]] and Africa was not a 5G region.<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\"/><ref name=\"cbc-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595|title= Viral video claiming 5G caused pandemic easily debunked|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date= March 23, 2020 |first1=Katie |last1=Nicholson |first2=Jason |last2=Ho |first3=Jeff |last3=Yates| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-date= March 26, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326125553/https://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/fact-check-viral-video-coronavirus-1.5506595}}</ref> Cowan also falsely alleged that the viruses were wastes from cells that are poisoned by electromagnetic fields and historical viral pandemics coincided with the major developments in radio technology.<ref name=\"cbc-5g\"/> The video of his claims went viral and was recirculated by celebrities including [[Woody Harrelson]], [[John Cusack]], and singer [[Keri Hilson]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Satariano |first1=Adam |last2=Alba |first2=Davey | name-list-format = vanc |title=Burning Cell Towers, Out of Baseless Fear They Spread the Virus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/10/technology/coronavirus-5g-uk.html |work=The New York Times |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The claims may also have been recirculated by an alleged \"coordinated disinformation campaign\", similar to campaigns used by the [[Internet Research Agency]] in Saint Petersburg, Russia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Ryan |title=5G Virus Conspiracy Theory Fueled by Coordinated Effort |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-09/covid-19-link-to-5g-technology-fueled-by-coordinated-effort |access-date=12 April 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The claims were criticized on social media and debunked by [[Reuters]],<ref name=\"reuters-5g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|title=False claim: 5G networks are making people sick, not Coronavirus|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320023007/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-coronavirus-5g/false-claim-5g-networks-are-making-people-sick-not-coronavirus-idUSKBN2133TI|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'',<ref name=usatoday2873731001>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/ |title= Here's why 5G and coronavirus are not connected |last=O'Donnell |first=Bob | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 21, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213438/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2020/03/21/did-5-g-cause-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/2873731001/}}</ref> [[Full Fact]]<ref name=20200313fullfact>{{cite web |url=https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/ |title= These claims about the new coronavirus and 5G are unfounded |last=Krishna |first= Rachael | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Full Fact]] |access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160841/https://fullfact.org/online/coronavirus-5G/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[American Public Health Association]] executive director [[Georges C. Benjamin]].<ref name=\"newsweek-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-video-suggests-5g-internet-causes-coronavirus-people-are-falling-it-1493321|title= Youtube Video Suggests 5G Internet Causes Coronavirus and People Are Falling For It|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=March 19, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Kelly|last=Wynne | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=\"huffington-5g\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|title=No, Keri Hilson, 5G Did Not Cause Coronavirus|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|first=Taryn|last=Finley| name-list-format = vanc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232700/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/keri-hilson-5g-did-not-cause-coronavirus_n_5e6f8ba7c5b6dda30fce0348|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter telecommunications masts in several parts of the United Kingdom were the subject of arson attacks, British Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] said the theory that COVID-19 virus may be spread by [[5G]] wireless communication is \"just nonsense, dangerous nonsense as well.\"<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS 5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says] Reuters Technology News, April 4, 2020</ref> [[Vodafone UK|Vodafone]] announced that two Vodafone masts and two it shares with [[O2 (UK)|O2]] had been targeted.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/06/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-telecom-tower-fires/|title=5G-coronavirus conspiracy theory spurs rash of telecom tower arson fires|website=Fortune}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, 2020 at least 20 mobile phone masts in the UK had been vandalised since the previous Thursday.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims>{{Cite news|title=At least 20 UK phone masts vandalised over false 5G coronavirus claims|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/06/at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last2=Hern|first2=Alex}}</ref> Because of slow rollout of 5G in the UK, many of the damaged masts had only 3G and 4G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> Mobile phone and home broadband operators estimated there were at least 30 incidents of confronting engineers maintaining equipment in the week up to April 6.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/> There have been eleven incidents of attempted arson at mobile phone masts in the Netherlands, including one case where \"Fuck 5G\" was written, as well as in Ireland and Cyprus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2330065-brand-bij-vier-zendmasten-heel-sterk-vermoeden-van-brandstichting.html|title=Brand bij vier zendmasten: 'Heel sterk vermoeden van brandstichting'|date=April 10, 2020|work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting]]|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=live|language=nl}}</ref><!-- FT article not paywalled --><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fildes|first1=Nic|last2=Di Stefano|first2=Mark|last3=Murphy|first3=Hannah | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.ft.com/content/1eeedb71-d9dc-4b13-9b45-fcb7898ae9e1|title=How a 5G coronavirus conspiracy spread across Europe|work=Financial Times|date=16 April 2020|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Facebook has deleted multiple messages encouraging attacks on 5G equipment.<ref name=guardian-at-least-20-uk-phone-masts-vandalised-over-false-5g-coronavirus-claims/>\n\nEngineers working for [[Openreach]] posted pleas on anti-5G Facebook groups asking to be spared abuse as they are not involved with maintaining mobile networks.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies>{{Cite news|title=Broadband engineers threatened due to 5G coronavirus conspiracies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/03/broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies|last=Waterson|first=Jim| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Mobile UK said that the incidents were affecting attempts to maintain networks that support home working and provide critical connections to vulnerable customers, emergency services and hospitals.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/> A widely circulated video shows people working for broadband company Community Fibre being abused by a woman who accuses them of installing 5G as part of a plan to kill the population.<ref name=guardian-broadband-engineers-threatened-due-to-5g-coronavirus-conspiracies/>\n\nYouTube announced that it would reduce the amount of content claiming links between 5G and coronavirus.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory>{{Cite news|title=YouTube moves to limit spread of false coronavirus 5G theory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory|last=Hern|first=Alex| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 5, 2020|access-date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Videos that are conspiratorial about 5G that do not mention coronavirus would not be removed, though they might be considered \"borderline content\", removed from search recommendations and losing advertising revenue.<ref name=guardian-youtube-to-suppress-content-spreading-coronavirus-5g-conspiracy-theory/> The discredited theories had been promoted by British conspiracy theorist [[David Icke]] in videos (subsequently removed) on YouTube and Vimeo, and an interview by [[London Live]] TV network, prompting calls for action by [[Ofcom]].<ref name=bbc52198946>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52198946  Leo Kelion, \"Coronavirus: YouTube tightens rules after David Icke 5G interview\", ''BBC News'', 7 April 2020]. Retrieved April 7, 2020</ref><ref name=extremetech308888>{{Cite web|url=https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/308888-youtube-says-it-will-remove-5g-misinformation-as-frightened-people-burn-cell-towers|title=YouTube Says It Will Remove 5G Misinformation After People Burn Cell Towers \u2013 ExtremeTech|website=extremetech.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 2020, [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda\u00ed]] were investigating fires at 5G masts in [[County Donegal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal>{{Cite news|title=Garda\u00ed suspect fires at 5G masts were deliberate after coal found|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal-5073466-Apr2020/|last=Maguire|first=Stephen| name-list-format = vanc |date=13 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020|work=[[TheJournal.ie]]}}</ref> Garda\u00ed and fire services had attended the fires the previous night in an attempt to put them out.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal/> Although Garda\u00ed were awaiting results of tests they were treating the fires as deliberate.<ref name=tj-5g-masts-set-on-fire-donegal/>\n\nThere were 20 suspected arson attacks on phone masts in the UK over the [[Easter]] 2020 weekend.<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\">{{cite news |title=Mast fires surge in the UK over Easter weekend amid 5G-coronavirus conspiracy theories |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/world/mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-994035.html |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=14 April 2020}}</ref> These included an incident in [[Dagenham]] where three men were arrested on suspicion of arson, a fire in [[Huddersfield]] that affected a mast used by emergency services and a fire in a mast that provides mobile connectivity to the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Birmingham]].<ref name=\"ie-mast-fires-surge-in-the-uk-over-easter-weekend-amid-5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theories\"/>\n\n===Vegetarian immunity===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}<!--this seems to be more complex tahn just a claim that if you dont' eat meat you will not get infected-->\nClaims that [[vegetarian]]s are immune to coronavirus spread online in India, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|access-date=March 3, 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}} Eating meat does not have an effect on COVID-19 spread, except for people [[zoonosis|near where animals are slaughtered]], said Dr. Anand Krishnan, professor at the Centre for Community Medicine of the [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] (AIIMS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Vegetarian food, Indian immunity won\u2019t prevent Covid-19, says Anand Krishnan |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/coronavirus-cases-cure-symptoms-precautions-aiims-6314643/ |website=The Indian Express |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Fisheries, Dairying and Animal Husbandry Minister Giriraj Singh said that the rumour had significantly affected industry, with the price of a chicken falling to a third of pre-pandemic levels. He also described efforts to improve the hygiene of the meat supply chain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Non-vegetarian food does not cause COVID-19, says Minister |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/non-vegetarian-food-does-not-cause-covid-19-says-minister/article31003791.ece |work=The Hindu |date=6 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n===Alcohol (ethanol and poisonous methanol)===\nContrary to some reports, drinking alcohol does not protect against COVID-19, and can increase health risks<ref name=WHO_myths/> ([[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption|short term]] and [[Long-term effects of alcohol|long term]]). [[Drinking alcohol]] is [[ethanol]]; other [[alcohols]], such as [[methanol]], which causes [[methanol poisoning]], are acutely poisonous, and may be present in badly-prepared alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beauchamp GA, Valento M | title = Toxic Alcohol Ingestion: Prompt Recognition And Management In The Emergency Department | journal = Emergency Medicine Practice | volume = 18 | issue = 9 | pages = 1\u201320 | date = September 2016 | pmid = 27538060 }}</ref>\n\nIran has reported incidents of methanol poisoning, caused by the false belief that drinking alcohol would cure or protect against coronavirus;<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/> [[Alcohol in Iran|alcohol is banned in Iran]], and [[bootleg alcohol]] may [[Bootleg alcohol#Safety|contain methanol]].<ref name=\"slate-methanol\"/> According to Iranian media, nearly 300 people have died and over a thousand have become ill due to [[Methanol toxicity|methanol poisoning]], while [[Associated Press]] gave figures of around 480 deaths with 2,850 others affected.<ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\"/> Iranian social media had circulated a story from British tabloids that a British man and others had been cured of coronavirus with [[whiskey]] and honey,<ref name=\"independent-methanol\"/><ref name=mirror21418662>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/coronavirus-first-brit-who-caught-21418662 |title=Coronavirus: British man who caught virus 'beat flu with glass of hot whisky' |work=The Mirror |date=February 3, 2020 }}</ref> which combined with the use of alcohol-based<!--not just ethanol!--> [[hand sanitizer]]s as disinfectants, led to the false belief that drinking high-proof alcohol can kill the virus.<ref name=\"independent-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/iran-coronavirus-methanol-drink-cure-deaths-fake-a9429956.html |title= Coronavirus: Hundreds dead in Iran from drinking methanol amid fake reports it cures disease |first=Bel |last=Trew| name-list-format = vanc  |work=[[The Independent]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"slate-methanol\">{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/hundreds-die-iran-drinking-bootleg-alcohol-methanol-coronavirus-cure-social-media.html |title= Hundreds Die in Iran From Bootleg Alcohol Being Peddled Online as Fake Coronavirus Remedy |first=Elliot |last=Hannon | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ap-nytimes-methanol\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html |title= In Iran, False Belief a Poison Fights Virus Kills Hundreds |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 28, 2020|archive-date=March 28, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200328174609/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/27/world/middleeast/ap-ml-virus-outbreak-iran-a-deadly-drink.html}}</ref>\n\nSimilar incidents have occurred in Turkey, with 30 [[Turkmens|Turkmenistan citizens]] dying from methanol poisoning related to coronavirus cure claims.<ref name=20200325cnnturk>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnnturk.com/video/turkiye/9-kisi-daha-saf-alkolden-oldu |title=9 ki\u015fi daha saf alkolden \u00f6ld\u00fc |date=March 25, 2020 |website=[[CNN T\u00fcrk]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref name=hurriyet41473161>{{cite web |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/katil-sahte-alkol-41473161 |title= Katil: Sahte alkol |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |last=Ayd\u0131n |first=\u00c7etin | name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 28, 2020 |language=Turkish}}</ref>\n\n===Efficacy of hand sanitiser, \"antibacterial\" soaps===\nClaims that [[hand sanitiser]] is merely \"antibacterial not antiviral\", and therefore not effective against the coronavirus, have spread widely on Twitter and other social networks, not only in the US but also elsewhere. While the effectiveness of sanitiser depends on the specific ingredients, most hand sanitiser sold commercially{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} does destroy the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|title=Those Viral Posts Claiming Hand Sanitiser Doesn't Kill Coronavirus Are Wrong & Here's Why|last=Crellin|first=Zac | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|website=Pedestrian.TV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305012603/https://www.pedestrian.tv/health/does-hand-sanitiser-sanitizer-kill-coronavirus-antiviral-antibacterial-viral-tweet/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Hand sanitizer]] is recommended against COVID-19,<ref name=WHO_myths/> though unlike soap, it is not effective against all types of germs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Show Me the Science \u2013 When & How to Use Hand Sanitizer in Community Settings |author=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/show-me-the-science-hand-sanitizer.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Washing in soap and water for at least 20 seconds is recommended by the US Centers for Disease Control as the best way to clean hands in most situations. However, if soap and water are not available, a hand sanitizer that is at least 60% alcohol can be used instead, unless hands are visibly dirty or greasy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/disinfecting-your-home.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |language=en-us |date=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=When and How to Wash Your Hands|author= Centers for Disease Control |url=https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html |website=www.cdc.gov |language=en-us |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> The US CDC and the Food and Drug Administration recommend plain soap; there is no evidence that \"[[antibacterial soap]]s\" are any better, and limited evidence that they might be worse long-term.<ref>{{cite web |author=Center for Drug Evaluation and Research |title=Q&A for Consumers: Hand Sanitizers and COVID-19 |url=https://www.fda.gov/drugs/information-drug-class/qa-consumers-hand-sanitizers-and-covid-19 |website=FDA |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Antibacterial Soap? You Can Skip It, Use Plain Soap and Water |url=https://www.fda.gov/consumers/consumer-updates/antibacterial-soap-you-can-skip-it-use-plain-soap-and-water |website=FDA |author=Office of the Commissioner |language=en |date=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Public use of face masks===\nSeveral governments and institutions have initially dismissed the use of face masks by the general population, often with misleading or incomplete information about the efficacy of masks.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\">{{cite web |title=Through all the misinformation, what is the truth of wearing face masks? |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18385472.misinformation-truth-wearing-face-masks/ |website=The National }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=T. A. |title=\"I Was Looking at Them in the Wrong Way\": Mask Misinformation and the Failure of the Elites |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/mask-misinformation-and-the-failure-of-the-elites |website=Vanity Fair |date=April 2020}}</ref> Professor Zeynep Tufekci, writing in ''The New York Times'', suggests that the authorities dismissed mask usage by the general public in their messaging to manage shortages of supplies rather than confronting the reality of the situation.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web |last1=Tufekci |first1=Zeynep |title=Why Telling People They Don\u2019t Need Masks Backfired |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/opinion/coronavirus-face-masks.html |website=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> She remarks that the public received contradictory pieces of information about the usage of face masks, unlike other measures such as hand washing and social distancing.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nEven though there is no evidence that non-medical masks are an effective means of respiratory protection, there is some evidence they may reduce the transmission of viruses.<ref name=\"thenational.scot\"/> For instance, Harvard epidemiologist Bill Hanage said about masks that \"You're not wearing them to stop yourself getting infected, but to stop someone else getting infected.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=T. A. |title=\"I Was Looking at Them in the Wrong Way\": Mask Misinformation and the Failure of the Elites |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/mask-misinformation-and-the-failure-of-the-elites |website=Vanity Fair |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Helicopter spraying===\nIn some Asian countries, it has been claimed that one should stay at home on particular days when helicopters spray disinfectant over homes for killing off COVID-19; no such spraying is taking place.<ref name=20200326afpA>{{cite news |title=False claim circulates online that certain countries in Asia are using helicopters to spray 'COVID-19 disinfectant' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330085147/https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-online-certain-countries-asia-are-using-helicopters-spray-covid-19|archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320afp>{{cite news |title=Indian authorities refute 'fake' advisory which claimed disinfectant would be sprayed across India to tackle COVID-19 |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408121452/https://factcheck.afp.com/indian-authorities-refute-fake-advisory-which-claimed-disinfectant-would-be-sprayed-across-india|archive-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Mosquitos===\nIt has been claimed that [[mosquitos]] transmit coronavirus. There is no evidence that this is true; coronavirus spreads through small droplets of saliva and snot.<ref name=WHO_myths/> Colder northern-hemisphere countries have had COVID-19 spread long before the first mosquitos of spring emerge.\n\n===Cruise ships safety from infection===\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map per Capita.svg|thumb|upright=1.8|Claims by cruise-ship operators notwithstanding, there are many cases of coronaviruses in hot climates; some countries on the [[Caribbean]], the [[Mediterranean]], and the [[Persian Gulf]] are severely affected.]]\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships}}\nIn March 2020, the ''[[Miami New Times]]'' reported that managers at [[Norwegian Cruise Line]] had prepared a set of responses intended to convince wary customers to book cruises, including \"blatantly false\" claims that the coronavirus \"can only survive in cold temperatures, so the Caribbean is a fantastic choice for your next cruise\", that \"[s]cientists and medical professionals have confirmed that the warm weather of the spring will be the end of the [c]oronavirus\", and that the virus \"cannot live in the amazingly warm and tropical temperatures that your cruise will be sailing to.\"<ref name=\"nmt-cardona\">{{cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|title=Leaked Emails: Norwegian Pressures Sales Team to Mislead Potential Customers About Coronavirus|last1=Cardona|first1=Alexi C.|date=March 11, 2020|work=Miami New Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312003229/https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/coronavirus-norwegian-cruise-line-leaked-emails-show-booking-strategy-11590056|archive-date=March 12, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFlu is seasonal (becoming less frequent in the summer) in some countries, but not in others. While it is possible that the COVID-19 coronavirus will also show some seasonality, it it not yet known.<ref name=\"newsweek-02-11-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|title=Could Coronavirus Really Be Killed by Hot Weather? Scientists Weigh In|last1=Gander|first1=Kashmira|date=February 11, 2020|magazine=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145434/https://www.newsweek.com/could-coronavirus-really-killed-hot-weather-scientists-weigh-1486709|archive-date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Ravinder Kanda, senior lecturer in evolutionary genomics at Oxford Brookes University, U,.K., told Newsweek: \"Little is known about the seasonal dynamics of this particular virus\u2014we cannot take it for granted that the warmer weather will simply drive the virus out of existence.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"time-gunia\">{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|title=Will Warmer Weather Stop the Spread of the Coronavirus? Don't Count on It, Say Experts|last1=Gunia|first1=Amy|date=February 28, 2020|magazine=Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309112416/https://time.com/5790880/coronavirus-warm-weather-summer/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=Dr. Nancy Messionnier of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, warned against assuming the number of cases will slow as the weather warms. \"I think it\u2019s premature to assume that,\" she said during a call with reporters on February 12. \"We haven\u2019t been through even a single year with this pathogen.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"fox-farber\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|title=Will the coronavirus die out as the weather warms?|last1=Farber|first1=Madeline|date=February 20, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173144/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-die-out-warm-weather-trump|archive-date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020|quote=\"We hope that the gradual spring will help this virus recede, but our crystal ball is not very clear. The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus, and we know respiratory viruses are often seasonal, but not always. For example, influenza (flu) tends to be seasonal in the U.S., but in other parts of the world, it exists year-round. Scientists don\u2019t fully understand why even though we have been studying [the] flu for many years,\" Dr. William Schaffner, the medical director of the National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, told Fox News in an email.}}</ref>{{medical citation needed|date=April 2020}} The COVID-19 coronavirus spread along international air travel routes, including to tropical locations.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Venkatesh S, Memish ZA | title = SARS: the new challenge to international health and travel medicine | journal = Eastern Mediterranean Health Journal = La Revue De Sante De La Mediterranee Orientale = Al-Majallah Al-Sihhiyah Li-Sharq Al-Mutawassit | volume = 10 | issue = 4-5 | pages = 655\u201362 | date = 25 January 2004 | pmid = 16335659 | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref> [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|Outbreaks on cruise ships]], where an older population lives in close quarters, frequently touching surfaces which others have touched, were common.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Browne A, Ahmad SS, Beck CR, Nguyen-Van-Tam JS | title = The roles of transportation and transportation hubs in the propagation of influenza and coronaviruses: a systematic review | journal = Journal of Travel Medicine | volume = 23 | issue = 1 | pages = tav002 | date = January 2016 | pmid = 26782122 | doi = 10.1093/jtm/tav002 | url = https://academic.oup.com/jtm/article/23/1/tav002/2635586 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mallapaty S | title = What the cruise-ship outbreaks reveal about COVID-19 | journal = Nature | volume = 580 | issue = 7801 | pages = 18 | date = April 2020 | pmid = 32218546 | doi = 10.1038/d41586-020-00885-w }}</ref>\n\nIt seems that COVID-19 can be transmitted in all climates.<ref name=WHO_myths>{{cite web |title=Myth busters |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters |website=www.who.int |publisher=World Health Organization |language=en}}</ref> It has seriously affected many warm-climate countries. For instance, [[Dubai]], with an [[Climate of Dubai|year-round average daily high of 28.0 Celsius (82.3\u00b0F)]] and [[Dubai International Airport|the airport said to have the world's most international traffic]], has had [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates|thousands of cases]].\n\n===Country-specific===\n\n====Australia====\n\nA warning, claiming to be from the [[Australia Department of Health]] said that coronavirus  spreads through petrol pumps  and that everyone should wear gloves when filling up petrol in their cars.<ref name=20200325afpA>{{cite news |title=Australia's Department of Health did not issue a warning that 'using petrol pumps can spread COVID-19' |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331182810/https://factcheck.afp.com/australias-department-health-did-not-issue-warning-using-petrol-pumps-can-spread-covid-19|archive-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Twitter post claimed that scientists from the \"Australian Medical University\" had developed a vaccine for the coronavirus. It accepted 0.1 [[Bitcoin]] as payment for a vaccination kit and promised shipping in 5\u201310 days. It was later removed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|title=Social media awash with fake treatments for coronavirus|last=Taylor|first=Andrew | name-list-format = vanc |date=2020-03-28|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123958/https://www.smh.com.au/national/social-media-awash-with-fake-treatments-for-coronavirus-20200326-p54e9q.html|archive-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Brazil====\nIn Brazil, a video was widely shared claiming that vinegar was more effective than hand sanitiser against the coronavirus. That was disproved, as \"there is no evidence that [[acetic acid]] is effective against the virus\" and, even if there was, \"its concentration in common household vinegar is low\".<ref name=20200304abril>{{cite web|url=https://saude.abril.com.br/blog/e-verdade-ou-fake-news/alcool-em-gel-nao-evita-infeccao-por-novo-coronavirus-e-fake/|title=\u00c1lcool em gel n\u00e3o evita infec\u00e7\u00e3o por novo coronav\u00edrus? \u00c9 fake!|last=Pinheiro|first=Chlo\u00e9 | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 4, 2020|language=pt-br|trans-title=Hand sanitiser does not prevent infection by coronavirus? Fake!|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nChloroform and ether based drug [[:pt:Cheirinho-da-lol\u00f3|''lol\u00f3'']] was said to cure the disease in messages spread in Brazil. Other so called cures in messages spreading in Brazil were avocado and mint tea, hot whiskey and honey, essential oils, vitamins C and D,<ref name=otempo2307041>{{cite web|url=https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|title=\u00c9 fake news: lol\u00f3 n\u00e3o cura coronav\u00edrus e representa risco \u00e0 sa\u00fade|first=Rafaela|last=Mansur| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 6, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307135307/https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/e-fake-news-lolo-nao-cura-coronavirus-e-representa-risco-a-saude-1.2307041|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> fennel tea (supposedly similar to the medicine [[Tamiflu]], according to a false e-mail attributed to a hospital director) and cocaine.<ref name=20200304uol>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|title=Lol\u00f3, coca\u00edna, ch\u00e1: nada disso mata coronav\u00edrus, e dicas de cura s\u00e3o falsas|author=Lucas Borges Teixeira|date=March 4, 2020|language=pt|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182615/https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere/ultimas-noticias/2020/03/04/lolo-cocaina-cha-nada-disso-mata-coronavirus-e-dicas-de-cura-sao-falsas.htm|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\nA fake [[Costco]] [[product recall]] notice circulated on social media purporting that Kirkland-brand bath tissue had been contaminated with COVID-19 [sic] due to the item being made in China. No evidence supports that SARS-CoV 2 can survive for prolonged periods of time (like what might happen during shipping) on surfaces, and Costco has not issued such a recall.<ref name=20200313afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/costco-not-recalling-bath-tissue-due-novel-coronavirus-contamination|title=Costco is not recalling bath tissue due to novel coronavirus contamination|date=March 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-can-stay-infectious-for-days-on-surfaces/2020/03/12/9b54a99e-6472-11ea-845d-e35b0234b136_story.html|title=Coronavirus can stay infectious for days on surfaces. But it's still okay to check your mail.|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====China====\n\nVarious national and party-held Chinese media heavily advertised an \"overnight research\" report by [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] and Shanghai Institute of Materia Medica, [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]], on how {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}, an herb mixture from [[traditional Chinese medicine]] (TCM), can effectively inhibit the novel coronavirus. The report has led to a purchase craze of {{lang|zh-Latn|shuanghuanglian}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wee |first1=Sui-Lee |title=In Coronavirus, China Weighs Benefits of Buffalo Horn and Other Remedies |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 15, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206125038/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/world/asia/coronavirus-traditional-chinese-medicine.html |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince its third version, the COVID management guidelines from the [[National Health Commission]] recommends using TCM to treat the disease.<ref name=bbc51485559>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6cbb\u7597\uff1a\u8bb2\u7a76\u5b9e\u8bc1\u7684\u897f\u533b\u548c\u81ea\u6211\u5b9a\u4f4d\u7684\u4e2d\u836f |url=https://www.bbc.com/zhongwen/simp/science-51485559 |website=BBC News |date=February 14, 2020 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Treating the novel coronavirus: the empirical Western medicine and the self-positioning Chinese medicine}}</ref> In Wuhan, the local authorities have pushed for a set of TCM prescriptions to be used for every case since early February.<ref name=cctv200125>{{cite web |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u533b\u6765\u4e86\uff018\u4e2a\u9632\u6cbb\u201c\u534f\u5b9a\u65b9\u201d \u8f85\u52a9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u80ba\u708e |url=http://news.cctv.com/2020/01/25/ARTIce5OB5W3sORPe90dPEJh200125.shtml |website=CCTV News |access-date=February 15, 2020 |trans-title=Here comes Chinese medicine! 8 \"agreed-on prescriptions\" help prevent and treat the new coronavirus pneumonia}}</ref><ref name=epochtimes11842894>{{cite web |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8981\u6c42\u6240\u6709\u60a3\u8005\u5fc5\u987b\u5403\u4e2d\u836f \u7f51\u6c11\u8d28\u7591 |url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/20/2/4/n11842894.htm |website=Epoch Times |access-date=February 15, 2020 |date=February 4, 2020 |trans-title=Wuhan wants all patients put on TCM; Netizens question}}</ref> One formula was promoted at the national level by mid February.<ref name=sina2164147>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2020-02-17/doc-iimxxstf2164147.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u53d1\u5e03 {{!}} \u56fd\u5bb6\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\uff1a\u6e05\u80ba\u6392\u6bd2\u6c64\u5bf9\u6cbb\u7597\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u6709\u7597\u6548|work=Chinanet|publisher=Sina News|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine: The \"lung-clearing detoxing decoction\" is effective against COVID-19}}</ref> The local field hospitals were explicitly TCM-oriented. According to state-owned media, as of March 16, 2020, 91.91% of all Hubei patients have used TCM, with the rate reaching 99% in field hospitals and 94% in bulk quarantine areas.<ref name=xinhuanet1125720410>{{cite news |script-title=zh:ICU\u5185\u5916\u7684\u4e2d\u897f\u533b\u5408\u4f5c\u2014\u2014\u4e13\u5bb6\u8c08\u4e2d\u533b\u836f\u5728\u6297\u51fb\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u4e2d\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u4f5c\u7528 |language=zh-Hans |trans-title=Co-operation between Chinese and Western medicine inside and outside of the ICU \u2013 experts talk about the vital role of TCM in the fight against COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/politics/2020-03/16/c_1125720410.htm |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims originating from China circulated, stating that saline solutions could kill the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|title=Saline solution kills China coronavirus? Experts refute online rumour|date=2020-01-24|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401153714/https://factcheck.afp.com/saline-solution-kills-china-coronavirus-experts-refute-online-rumour|archive-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Estonia====\nOn February 27, 2020, the Estonian Minister of the Interior [[Mart Helme]] stated at a government press conference that the [[common cold]] had been renamed as the coronavirus and that in his youth nothing like that existed. He recommended wearing warm socks and mustard patches as well as spreading goose fat on one's chest as treatments for the virus. Helme also said that the virus would pass within a few days to a week just like the common cold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|title=VIDEO {{!}} Mart Helme: k\u00fclmetushaigus on n\u00fc\u00fcd siis \u00fcmber ristitud koroonaviiruseks. Mingit h\u00e4daolukorda Eestis pole|last=Vasli|first=Karoliina| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 27, 2020 |website=[[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]] |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311135111/https://www.delfi.ee/news/paevauudised/eesti/video-mart-helme-kulmetushaigus-on-nuud-siis-umber-ristitud-koroonaviiruseks-mingit-hadaolukorda-eestis-pole?id=89066557date=2%20March%202020|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Greece====\nDespite the coronavirus outbreak, on March 9, the [[Church of Greece]] announced that the [[Holy Communion]], in which churchgoers eat pieces of bread soaked in wine from the same chalice, would continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite news | first1=Michele |last1=Kambas |first2=George |last2=Georgiopoulos | name-list-format = vanc | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | agency=Reuters | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174830/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | archive-date=March 12, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] stated that the Holy Communion \"cannot be the cause of the spread of illness\", with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the wine was without blemish because it represented the blood and body of Christ, and that \"whoever attends Holy Communion is approaching God, who has the power to heal\".<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\"/>\n\nNew Democracy MP Elena Rapti also said that she was going and that if there was deep faith, the Communion was healing.<ref name=\"ref 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|title=Corona-Panik nur f\u00fcr Ungl\u00e4ubige?|last=Aswestopoulos|first=Wassilis| name-list-format = vanc |website=heise online|language=de|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310205222/https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Corona-Panik-nur-fuer-Unglaeubige-4678649.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Church furthermore refused to restrict Christians from taking the Holy Communion.<ref name=dw52742226>{{cite web|publisher=Deutsche Welle|title=Inside Europe: Greek Orthodox Church weighs in on coronavirus|date=March 13, 2020|url=https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181239/https://www.dw.com/en/inside-europe-greek-orthodox-church-weighs-in-on-coronavirus/av-52742226|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In public statements, several clerics urged worshippers to continue taking part in the Holy Communion, justifying it by saying that Jesus never got sick,<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | name-list-format = vanc | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=euractiv.com | date=March 9, 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ |access-date=March 18, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318181234/https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | archive-date=March 18, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> while the Bishop of Piraeus Seraphim announced that only those who took part in masses without true faith could be affected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> There were furthermore reports that the CoVid 19 hotline was informing concerned believers that there was no risk of contagion at the sacrament.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, causing a sharp reaction by the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/> Eleni Giamarellou, a professor of infectious diseases at the University of Athens, announced that there was no danger, and that she was accepting communion with faith in God, so she could not become infected.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/> The Greek Association of Hospital Doctors criticized these professionals for putting their religious beliefs before science.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\"/>\n\nIt was also reported that a right-wing populist party leader of the party [[Greek Solution]], [[Kyriakos Velopoulos]], sells a hand cream via his TV shop, which supposedly would completely kill COVID-19, although the alleged miracle drug is not approved by medical authorities.<ref name=\"ref 1\"/>\n\n====India====\nPolitical activist [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure COVID-19.<ref name=indiatimes73952691>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=firstpost8111021>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] criticised politicians incautiously spreading such misinformation without an evidence base.<ref name=20200303ndtv>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|publisher=NDTV|access-date=March 5, 2020|date=March 3, 2020|quote=\"Q: In a situation like this when we need scientific solution to a medical crisis, when you get in our country for examples, political leaders saying things like co''[sic]'' dung or cow urine can be beneficial in fixing something like coronavirus, do we end up taking a step back after such statements, as we need to deal with the issue in a modern scientific manner. <br/>A: I completely agree, I think all the public figures including politicians need to be extra careful when it comes to making such statements, because they have such a huge following. Its really important for them to say things that are based on some scientific evidence and rationing''[sic; probably \"reasoning\" typo]''.... when it comes to the claims of cures of this infection we should be extremely careful about our statements and it should be made by the people who know what they\u2019re talking about. And has to be baked''[sic]'' by evidence\"}}</ref> Dr Shailendra Saxena of the [[Indian Virological Society]] stated that there is no evidence that cow urine has any anti-viral effect, and eating cow dung might even create a new [[zoonosis]].<ref name=BBC_tea>{{Cite news|last=team| name-list-format = vanc |first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>{{medcn|date=April 2020}}<!--not clear if doc is a subject expert-->\n\nParliamentarian [[Ramesh Bidhuri]] of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] claimed that experts say using [[Namaste]] as a greeting prevents transmission of COVID-19, but using Arabic greetings like [[Adab (gesture)|Adab]] and [[As-salamu alaykum]] does not prevent it as they direct air into the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|title=Coronavirus: Saying aadab sends infected air into the mouth, claims BJP leader Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Scroll.in|access-date=March 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317065950/https://scroll.in/video/955329/coronavirus-saying-aadab-sends-infected-air-into-the-mouth-claims-bjp-leader-ramesh-bidhuri|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=deccanherald811390>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|title=Experts have said namaskar, not adaab or assalamu alaikum, will help prevent coronavirus, says BJP MP Ramesh Bidhuri|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=March 15, 2020|date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192721/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/experts-have-said-namaskar-not-adaab-or-assalamu-alaikum-will-help-prevent-coronavirus-says-bjp-mp-ramesh-bidhuri-811390.html|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading an \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during [[Janata curfew]], a stay-at-home curfew enforced in India, went viral on social media.<ref name=20200320hindustantimes>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it's fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=March 20, 2020 }}</ref> The notion that the vibrations generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref name=thenewsminute120844>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that 'clapping may kill virus', PIB debunks}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[Amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on 'clapping vibrations destroy virus potency' after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=March 23, 2020 }}</ref> Misinformation has spread that the lifetime of SARS-CoV-2 is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew would break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |author=Ratna |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |access-date=March 22, 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of COVID-19 cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/>\n\nIn India, fake news circulated that the [[World Health Organization]] warned against eating cabbage to prevent coronavirus infection.<ref name=20200331afp>{{cite news |title=WHO did not warn against eating cabbage during the COVID-19 pandemic |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402070033/https://factcheck.afp.com/who-did-not-warn-against-eating-cabbage-during-covid-19-pandemic|archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The poisonous fruit of the [[Datura]] plant as a preventive measure for COVID-19 resulted in eleven people being hospitalized in India. They ate the fruit, following the instructions from a [[TikTok]] video that propagated misinformation regarding the prevention of COVID-19.<ref name=thenewsminute122136>{{cite news |title=11 in AP hospitalised after following TikTok poisonous 'remedy' for COVID-19 |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/11-ap-hospitalised-after-following-tiktok-poisonous-remedy-covid-19-122136 |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com}}</ref><ref name=thehindu31282688>{{cite news |last1=Reporter |first1=Staff |title=Twelve taken ill after consuming 'coronavirus shaped' datura seeds |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/twelve-taken-ill-after-consuming-coronavirus-shaped-datura-seeds/article31282688.ece |access-date=April 9, 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=April 7, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nAn \"anti-coronavirus\" mattress was advertised as being anti-fungal, anti-allergic, dustproof and waterproof and that it could fight the coronavirus.<ref name=\":0CVP\">{{Cite news|last=team|first=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|date=March 25, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nClaims of neem leaves or ''[[Azadirachta indica]]'' as remedies for COVID-19 were circulated in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|title=No scientific evidence neem can cure COVID-19 infection - Experts|website=[[Bernama]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408122745/https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1825466|archive-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndian politician [[Chakrapani (politician)|Swami Chakrapani]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body could cure coronavirus. He also stated that only Indian cows must be used.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=The Times of India|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that a 30 year-old Indian textbook lists aspirin, anti-histamines and nasal spray as treatments for COVID-19. The textbook actually talks about [[coronaviruses]] in general, as a family of viruses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/hoax-circulates-online-old-indian-textbook-lists-treatments-covid-19|title=Hoax circulates online that an old Indian textbook lists treatments for COVID-19|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====Italy====\nThere are claims that wearing shoes at one's home is the reason behind the spread of the coronavirus in Italy.<ref name=20200409afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-refute-misleading-claim-wearing-shoes-indoors-main-reason-hike-covid-19-infections|title=Hoax circulates online that people wearing shoes indoors triggered hike in COVID-19 cases in Italy|date=April 9, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====Nigeria====\nFollowing the first reported case of COVID-19 in Nigeria on February 28, untested cures and treatments began to spread via platforms like [[WhatsApp]].<ref name=qz1810219>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|title=Nigeria's biggest battle with coronavirus will be beating misinformation|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi| name-list-format = vanc |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162841/https://qz.com/africa/1810219/nigerias-coronavirus-case-may-spark-wave-of-fake-news-and-fears/|archive-date=February 29, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> There were also claims that chloroquine was used to cure over 12,000 COVID-19 patients.<ref name=20200221afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/anti-malaria-drug-has-proven-effective-treating-coronavirus-has-not-cured-12552-patients |title=Anti-malaria drug has proven effective in treating coronavirus but has not cured 12,552 patients &#124; AFP Fact Check |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Pakistan====\nReligious and scientific misconceptions related to the coronavirus was widespread in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Only 38% Pakistanis can recall state helpline for coronavirus: report |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/282463-only-38-pakistanis-can-recall-state-helpline-for-coronavirus-report |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.geo.tv}}</ref> According to a survey research conducted by [[Ipsos]], 82% of people in Pakistan believed that performing [[wudu]]/ablution five times a day will keep them protected from contracting Coronavirus. Meanwhile 67% polled believed that jamaat (congregation prayer) cannot become a source of infection<ref name=\"thenews/1\">{{cite news |title=88pc Pakistanis aware of COVID-19 implications: poll |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/643643-88pc-pakistanis-aware-of-covid-19-implications-poll |access-date=13 April 2020 |work=www.thenews.com.pk |language=en}}</ref> and 48% people believed that shaking hands cannot infect anyone since it is [[Sunnah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2020/04/myths-pakistanis-believe-wuzu-protects-you-from-covid/|title=Myths: Pakistanis believe wuzu protects you from COVID {{!}} SAMAA|publisher=Samaa TV|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Philippines====\nPosts on social media claimed that volcanic ash from the eruption of the [[Taal Volcano]] on January 12, 2020 in the Philippines was the cause of low infection rates in the country, stating that it could kill the virus and had \"anti-viral\" and \"disinfectant qualities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|title=World Health Organization refutes misleading claim that volcanic ash can kill coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408104634/https://factcheck.afp.com/world-health-organization-refutes-misleading-claim-volcanic-ash-can-kill-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClaims from the Philippines circulated that sap from [[Tinospora|''tinospora crispa'']] plants could serve as an antibiotic against the coronavirus when used as an eye drop. It also made the claim that the coronavirus is from the skin and crawls to the eyes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|title=Philippine health experts dismiss misleading online claim that tinospora crispa plants can treat novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-05|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408105720/https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-health-experts-dismiss-misleading-online-claim-tinospora-crispa-plants-can-treat-novel|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere were also claims that an anti-viral injection was developed as a cure in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/philippine-authorities-warn-anti-viral-injection-has-not-yet-been-approved-treating-covid-19|title=Philippine authorities warn anti-viral injection has not yet been approved for treating COVID-19|date=April 15, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nSouth Korean \"conservative populist\" Jun Kwang-hun told his followers that there was no risk to mass public gatherings as the virus was impossible to contract outdoors. Many of his followers are elderly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khatouki |first1=Christopher |title=Clandestine Cults and Cynical Politics: How South Korea Became the New Coronavirus Epicenter |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |access-date=March 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313065620/https://thediplomat.com/2020/03/clandestine-cults-and-cynical-politics-how-south-korea-became-the-new-coronavirus-epicenter/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus at the [[River of Grace Community Church]] after followers had salt-water sprayed into their mouths under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref name=scmp3075421>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=March 16, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=upi9881584365>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|agency=United Press International|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were also fake news of discovery of a vaccine against COVID-19.<ref name=20200325afpB>{{cite news |title=This photo shows a COVID-19 test kit developed by a South Korean company |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company |access-date=April 3, 2020 |work=AFP Fact Check |date=March 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327125546/https://factcheck.afp.com/photo-shows-covid-19-test-kit-developed-south-korean-company|archive-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Senegal====\nOn Facebook, a widely shared post claimed that 7 Senegalese children had died because they had received a COVID-19 vaccine. No such vaccine exists, although some are in clinical trials.<ref name=20200408afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/senegalese-children-did-not-die-coronavirus-vaccine-which-does-not-yet-exist|title=Senegalese children did not die from a coronavirus vaccine (which does not yet exist)|date=April 8, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====Sri Lanka====\n\nA claim that [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] could protect against the coronavirus appeared on Youtube, along with a petition to legalize cannabis in Sri Lanka.<ref name=20200219afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/sri-lankan-health-experts-stress-there-no-evidence-cannabis-boosts-immunity-against-novel|title=Sri Lankan health experts stress there is no evidence that cannabis boosts immunity against the novel coronavirus|date=February 19, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> A fake [[Fox News]] article also claimed that [[Cannabidiol|CBD oil]] was a potential cure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2020/03/19/coronavirus-scam-alert-beware-fake-fox-news-text-messages-promising-a-cbd-oil-cure/|title=Coronavirus Scam Alert: Beware Fake Fox News Articles Promising A CBD Oil Cure|last=Brewster|first=Thomas| name-list-format = vanc |website=Forbes|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Thailand====\n\nClaims that Vitamin D pills could help prevent the coronavirus circulated on social media in Thailand.<ref name=20200227afp>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-vitamin-d-effective-preventing-novel-coronavirus-infection|title=Health experts say there is no evidence vitamin D is effective in preventing novel coronavirus infection|date=February 27, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Thai media website stated that ''[[andrographis paniculata]]'' could boost the immune systems and relieve symptoms of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|title=Thai health experts say there is no evidence the 'green chiretta' herb can prevent the novel coronavirus|date=2020-02-06|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408110538/https://factcheck.afp.com/thai-health-experts-say-there-no-evidence-green-chiretta-herb-can-prevent-novel-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA widely shared post on Facebook claimed that Italian doctors who were infected with COVID-19 were treating patients as normal in Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/video-actually-shows-scene-mexican-television-series-aired-2010|title=This video actually shows a scene from a Mexican television drama|date=April 13, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nSome [[QAnon]] proponents, including Jordan Sather, and others, have promoted gargling \"[[Miracle Mineral Supplement]]\" (actually [[Chlorine dioxide]], a chemical used in some industrial applications as a bleach that may cause life-threatening reactions and even death) as a way of preventing or curing the disease. The Food and Drug Administration has warned multiple times that drinking MMS is \"dangerous\" as it may cause \"severe vomiting\" and \"acute liver failure\".<ref name=\"bleach\">{{cite news|last=Sommer|first=Will| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|title=QAnon-ers' Magic Cure for Coronavirus: Just Drink Bleach!|date=January 28, 2020|newspaper=[[Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 14, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223501/https://www.thedailybeast.com/qanon-conspiracy-theorists-magic-cure-for-coronavirus-is-drinking-lethal-bleach|archive-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] promoted a [[colloidal silver]] solution sold on his website, as a remedy for coronavirus COVID-19; [[naturopath]] Sherrill Sellman, a guest on his show, falsely stated that it \"hasn't been tested on this strain of the coronavirus, but it's been tested on other strains of the coronavirus and has been able to eliminate it within 12 hours.\"<ref name=newsweek1487069>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|title=TELEVANGELIST SELLS $125 'SILVER SOLUTION' AS CURE FOR CORONAVIRUS|last1=Moyler|first1=Hunter|date=February 12, 2020|work=Newsweek|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215044054/https://www.newsweek.com/televangelist-show-guest-promotes-silver-solution-cure-coronavirus-1487069|archive-date=February 15, 2020|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The US Food and Drug Administration and New York Attorney General's office both issued cease-and-desist orders against Bakker, and he was sued by the state of Missouri over the sales.<ref name=npr814550474>{{cite news| first=Matthew S.| last=Schwartz | name-list-format = vanc | title=Missouri Sues Televangelist Jim Bakker For Selling Fake Coronavirus Cure| publisher=NPR| date=March 11, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312105326/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/11/814550474/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure| archive-date=March 12, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200309theguardian>{{cite news| last=Aratani| first=Lauren | name-list-format = vanc | title=New York attorney general to televangelist: stop touting product as coronavirus cure| newspaper=The Guardian| date=March 9, 2020| access-date=March 16, 2020| url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313205221/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/09/jim-bakker-letitia-james-coronavirus-product-stop-promoting| archive-date=March 13, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe New York Attorney General's office also issued a cease-and-desist order to radio host [[Alex Jones]], who was selling silver-infused toothpaste that he falsely claimed can kill the virus and had been verified by federal officials,<ref name=theverge21177998>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|title=Alex Jones ordered to stop selling fake coronavirus cures|last=Porter|first=Jon| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 13, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135410/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21177998/new-york-attorney-general-alex-jones-infowars-coronavirus-cures-prevention|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> causing a Jones spokesman to deny the products had been sold for the purpose of treating any disease.<ref name=\"alex jones\"/> The FDA would later threaten Jones with legal action and seizure of several silver-based products if he continued to promote their use against coronavirus.<ref name=politico178629>{{cite news|last=Owermohle |first=Sarah | name-list-format = vanc | title=FDA warns Alex Jones over false coronavirus claims| date=April 9, 2020| access-date=April 9, 2020 | work=Politico| url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/09/fda-warns-alex-jones-over-false-coronavirus-claims-178629}}</ref>\n\nAnother televangelist, [[Kenneth Copeland]], claimed on Victory Channel during a programme called \"Standing Against Coronavirus\", that he can cure television viewers of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} directly from the TV studio. The viewers had to touch the television screen to receive the spiritual healing.<ref name=newsweek1492044>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|title=Conservative pastor claims he \"healed\" viewers of coronavirus through their TV screens|last=Lemon|first=Jason| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020|website=Newsweek|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316135415/https://www.newsweek.com/conservative-pastor-claims-he-healed-viewers-coronavirus-through-their-tv-screens-1492044|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200313pinknews>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|title=This anti-LGBT+ televangelist tried to heal people of the coronavirus through their televisions|date=March 13, 2020|website=PinkNews|access-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150419/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/13/kenneth-copeland-anti-lgbt-televangelist-coronavirus-covid19-heal-virus-pandemic/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrested actor Keith Lawrence Middlebrook for selling a fake COVID-19 cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/celebrity/actor-keith-middlebrook-arrested-by-fbi-for-allegedly-peddling-bogus-coronavirus-cure/ar-BB11LQpX?ocid=ientp|title=Actor Keith Middlebrook arrested by FBI for allegedly peddling bogus coronavirus cure|publisher=MSN|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe hypothesis of Stanford military historian Victor Davis Hanson, that the coronavirus was circulating in California in fall 2019, was widely shared but debunked by genetic analysis.<ref name=20200410slate>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/technology/2020/04/coronavirus-circulating-california-2019-bunk.html|title=No, You Did Not Get COVID-19 in the Fall of 2019|first=Jane C.|last=Hu | name-list-format = vanc |date=April 10, 2020|website=Slate}}</ref>\n\n====Venezuela====\nIn February 2020, {{ill|Mar\u00eda Alejandra D\u00edaz|es}}, a member of the [[2017 Constituent National Assembly|Venezuelan Constituent Assembly]], promoted a recipe that she claimed would cure COVID-19. The recipe consisted of ingredients often purported to prevent and cure colds, including [[Cymbopogon|lemon grass]], [[Sambucus|elder]], ginger, black pepper, lemon and honey. D\u00edaz also described the virus as a bioterrorism weapon.<ref name=20200305efectococuyo>{{cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/cocuyo-chequea/coronavirus-te-medicinal/|title=\u00bfEl coronavirus se puede curar con un t\u00e9 de plantas? #DatosCoronavirus|date=March 5, 2020|website=[[Efecto Cocuyo]]|language=Spanish|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n===American===\n\nAccording to Washington Post, the US Republican government members were largely influenced by series of articles by [[Richard Epstein|Richard A. Epstein]] of the [[Hoover Institution]], who in a series of articles consistently played down the scale of the epidemics, ridiculed the \"panic\" being spread by \"progressives\", made a number of incorrect statements about the SARS-CoV-2 virus, misapplied and misconstrued Darwinian evolutionary theory in regards to the pandemics, and predicted \"about 500 deaths at the end\" of the epidemics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/the-contrarian-coronavirus-theory-that-informed-the-trump-administration|title=The Contrarian Coronavirus Theory That Informed the Trump Administration|last=Chotiner|first=Isaac | name-list-format = vanc |website=The New Yorker|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral members of the [[U.S. Senate]]\u2014particularly [[Richard Burr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[North Carolina|NC]]) and [[Kelly Loeffler]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]])\u2014have come under [[2020 Congressional insider trading scandal|scrutiny for sales of large amounts of stocks]] before the financial markets crashed due to the outbreak, sparking accusations that they had insider knowledge from closed-door briefings, while many of them publicly downplayed the risks posed by the health crisis to the U.S. public.<ref name=hal-st>{{cite web |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |title=Stock trades by Senate Intelligence Committee chair after coronavirus briefings trigger investigation |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-20/stock-trades-by-lawmakers-who-got-coronavirus-briefings |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=vis-al2>{{cite web |last1=Visser |first1=Nick |title=At Least 2 GOP Senators Dumped Millions in Stock After Coronavirus Briefings |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/stock-sales-gop-senators-coronavirus_n_5e741524c5b63c3b648d8374 |website=HuffPost |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=bl-hd>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=How damning are Richard Burr's and Kelly Loeffler's coronavirus stock trades? Let's break it down. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/richard-burrs-kelly-loefflers-suspiciously-well-timed-stock-trades-during-coronavirus-examined/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320euractiv>{{cite web |last1=Lawton |first1=Sarah |title=As COVID-19 cases grew, US Senators sold off stocks and downplayed risks |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/global-europe/news/as-covid-19-cases-grew-us-senators-sold-off-stocks-and-downplayed-risks/ |website=Euractiv |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> For instance, an audio recording from February 27 revealed that Burr ([[Senate Intelligence Committee]] chairman) gave dire warnings to a small group of well-connected constituents in private, contrasted in severity to his public statements and not known to the public, that the virus is \"much more aggressive in its transmission than anything that we have seen in recent history,\" advising against travel to Europe (13 days before official warnings, 15 days before the ban), saying that schools will be likely be closed (16 days before the closure), and suggesting that the military might be mobilized (learned three weeks later from the recording).<ref name=npr818192535>{{cite web |last1=Mak |first1=Tim |title=Weeks Before Virus Panic, Intelligence Chairman Privately Raised Alarm, Sold Stocks |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192535/burr-recording-sparks-questions-about-private-comments-on-covid-19 |publisher=NPR |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bill de Blasio]], the mayor of New York City, gave wrong instructions during a [[photo op]] public [[3-1-1]] call.<ref name=20200326nymag>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/bill-de-blasio-had-his-worst-week-as-new-york-city-mayor.html|title=When New York Needed Him Most, Bill de Blasio Had His Worst Week As Mayor|last=Freedlander|first=David| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 26, 2020|website=Intelligencer|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Presidential====\n{{see also|Veracity of statements by Donald Trump}}\nUS President [[Donald Trump]] and his top economic adviser [[Larry Kudlow]] have been accused of spreading misinformation about the coronavirus. On February 25, Trump said, \"I think that whole situation will start working out. We're very close to a vaccine.\"<ref name=20200225huffpost>{{cite news |title=Larry Kudlow Claims Coronavirus 'Contained' In U.S. as CDC Warns of Likely Spread |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/larry-kudlow-coronavirus-misinformation_n_5e556f11c5b64c1d5620ddb1 |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200226buzzfeednews>{{cite news |title=Trump's Biggest Supporters Think the Coronavirus Is a Deep State Plot |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/trump-supporters-coronavirus-deep-state-qanon |work=BuzzFeed |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=theverge21153035>{{cite news |title=Trump's reckless coronavirus statements put the entire US at risk |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/25/21153035/coronavirus-response-trump-vaccine-covid19-cdc-who-health-crisis |work=The Verge |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vox-mis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21154253/trump-ebola-tweets-coronavirus|title=Trump is facing a coronavirus threat. Let's look back at how he talked about Ebola|date=February 26, 2020|work=Vox}}</ref> At the time, [[SARS-CoV-2]] had been spreading in the United States undetected for weeks,<ref name=theatlantic607348>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|title=The Official Coronavirus Numbers Are Wrong, and Everyone Knows It|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 3, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307000203/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-really-have-coronavirus/607348/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and new vaccine development may require a minimum of a year to prove safety and efficacy to gain regulatory approval.<ref name=npr804628081>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|title=Timetable for a Vaccine Against the New Coronavirus? Maybe This Fall|publisher=NPR|first=Joe|last=Palc | name-list-format = vanc a|date=February 12, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303155745/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/02/12/804628081/timetable-for-a-vaccine-against-the-new-coronavirus-maybe-this-fall|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on March 4, Trump also claimed that the [[Mortality rate|death rate]] published by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] was false, that the correct fatality rate was less than 1 percent, and said, \"Well, I think the 3.4 percent is really a false number\",<ref name=usatoday4961519002>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|title=Coronavirus death rate is 3.4%, World Health Organization says, Trump says 'hunch' tells him that's wrong|first=David|last=Jackson| name-list-format = vanc |website=USA Today|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211222/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/05/coronavirus-trump-disputes-world-health-organization-death-rate/4961519002/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |title=Trump says he has a hunch about the coronavirus. Here are the facts \u2013 YouTube |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310145305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SwqV0VHR4-E |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=nbcnews1151006>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|title=Trump has many hunches about the coronavirus. Here's what the experts say.|publisher=NBC News|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306162252/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/just-my-hunch-trump-contradicts-health-experts-coronavirus-n1151006|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that the potential impact of the outbreak was exaggerated by Democrats plotting against him, and that it was safe for infected individuals to go to work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|title=Opinion {{!}} Trump's latest coronavirus lies have a galling subtext|first=Greg|last=Sargent| name-list-format = vanc |website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306034904/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/05/trumps-latest-coronavirus-lies-have-galling-subtext/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Walters|first=Joanna| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|title=Trump calls WHO's global death rate from coronavirus 'a false number'|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 5, 2020|last2=Aratani|first2=Lauren |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305151056/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/trump-coronavirus-who-global-death-rate-false-number|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In a later tweet, Trump denied that he had made claims regarding infected individuals going to work, contrary to footage from the interview.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Coronavirus Press Conference USA.jpg|thumb|240px|President [[Donald Trump]] and members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] brief the media]]\nThe White House accused media of intentionally stoking fears of the virus to destabilize the administration.<ref name=bbc51667670>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|title=Media 'using virus to topple Trump' \u2013 White House|date=February 28, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229162842/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51667670|archive-date=February 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Stat News'' reported that \"President [[Cabinet of Donald Trump|Trump and members of his administration]] have also said that US containment of the virus is 'close to airtight' and that the virus is only as deadly as the seasonal flu. Their statements range from false to unproven, and in some cases, underestimate the challenges that public health officials must contend with in responding to the virus.\"<ref name=stat /> Around the same time that the \"airtight\" claim was made, SARS-CoV-2 was already past containment; the first case of community spread of the virus had been confirmed, and it was spreading faster than [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]], with a [[case fatality rate]] at least seven times the rate for seasonal flu.<ref name=msnbc7944608558>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|title=U.S. unready to deal with potential coronavirus spread|publisher=MSNBC|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303192803/https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/u-s-unready-to-deal-with-potential-coronavirus-spread-79446085581|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|title=Coronavirus may spread faster than WHO estimate|website=Medical News Today|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304134154/https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-may-spread-faster-than-who-estimate|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=20200225statnews>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|title=New China coronavirus data buttress fears about high fatality rate|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302010337/https://www.statnews.com/2020/02/25/new-data-from-china-buttress-fears-about-high-coronavirus-fatality-rate-who-expert-says/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, Trump told the media that he had heard that a [[COVID-19 vaccine]] would be available in \"a matter of months\", with \"a year [being] an outside number\", after Trump attended a discussion where his senior health official [[Anthony Fauci]] told him this process would take \"a year to a year and a half\" (at a minimum, Fauci later said). During that discussion, Trump repeatedly quizzed the leaders of pharmaceutical companies on the time needed to produce vaccines, stating \"I like the sound of a couple of months better\". The length of time required is due to regulatory bodies requiring multiple rounds of tests before vaccines being approved for the public's use.<ref name=20200303washingtonpost>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump's baffling coronavirus vaccine event |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/03/trumps-baffling-coronavirus-vaccine-event/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Trump blamed the [[Barack Obama administration]] for making \"a decision\" that delayed [[COVID-19 testing]] by the Trump administration. The policy in question had never been modified by the Obama administration, despite plans to do so. The policy's [[Project Bioshield Act|overall legal roots date to 2004]], before the Obama administration. Under the umbrella of [[Emergency Use Authorization]]s, the old policy stated that laboratory-developed tests \"should not be used for clinical diagnoses without FDA's approval, clearance, or authorization during an emergency declaration\". However, this policy was historically treated as a recommendation and generally unenforced, with no clear legal authority of the FDA in this area. The Trump administration continued to require laboratories to apply to the FDA for approval, but allowed the laboratories to test while the FDA processed the applications.<ref name=20200306politifact>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |title=False: Donald Trump stated on March 4, 2020 in a meeting at the White House: \"The Obama administration made a decision on testing that turned out to be very detrimental to what we're doing\" on the coronavirus. |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/06/donald-trump/trump-wrongly-blames-obama-limits-coronavirus-test/ |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, Trump over-promised on the availability of COVID-19 testing in the United States, claiming that: \"Anybody that wants a test can get a test.\" Firstly, there were criteria needed to qualify for a test; recommendations were needed from doctors or health officials to approve testing. Secondly, the lack of test supplies resulted in some being denied tests even though doctors wanted to test them.<ref name=20200312khn>{{cite news |url=https://khn.org/news/donald-trumps-wrong-claim-that-anybody-can-get-tested-for-coronavirus/ |title=Donald Trump's Wrong Claim That 'Anybody' Can Get Tested For Coronavirus |last=Valverde |first=Miriam | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 12, 2020 |work=[[Kaiser Health News]] |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200320cnnA>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |last2=Subramaniam |first2=Tara | name-list-format = vanc |title=Trump made 33 false claims about the coronavirus crisis in the first two weeks of March |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/fact-check-trump-coronavirus-false-claims-march/index.html |access-date=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Trump falsely claimed that the drug [[chloroquine]] was approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] as a treatment for COVID-19. This led the FDA to state that it had not approved any drugs or therapies for COVID-19. While Trump claimed that \"we're going to be able to make that drug available almost immediately\", the leader of the FDA stated that the drug would still need to be tested in a \"large, pragmatic [[clinical trial]]\" on subjects infected with COVID-19.<ref name=20200320cnnB>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While Trump promoted chloroquine as a potential \"game changer\", Fauci stated that positive results thus far were still based on \"anecdotal evidence\" and not \"definitive\" evidence from clinical trials.<ref name=go69716324>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Anne |last2=Phelps |first2=Jordyn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Fauci throws cold water on Trump's declaration that malaria drug chloroquine is a 'game changer' |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fauci-throws-cold-water-trumps-declaration-malaria-drug/story?id=69716324 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Trump also remarked that re-purposing existing drugs for COVID-19 is \"safe\" and \"not killing people\" (chloroquine is a form of treatment for malaria, while its derivative hydroxychloroquine is a form of treatment for lupus or arthritis), however most drugs may cause [[side effects]].<ref name=VerganoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Potentially serious side effects from chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine include [[irregular heartbeat]]s, [[tinnitus]], [[blurred vision]], [[muscle weakness]] or \"mental changes\".<ref name=VerganoMarch23/><ref name=20200323military>{{cite news |last1=Kime |first1=Patricia |title=Drug Touted as COVID-19 Treatment Has Troubling Side Effects, Experts Say |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/03/23/drug-touted-covid-19-treatment-has-troubling-side-effects-experts-say.html |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[military.com]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Overdoses of these drugs have been documented in scientific literature, including fatal overdoses.<ref name=VerganoMarch23/> Demand for chloroquine in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] sharply increased after Trump's comments, with three people overdosing by March 23.<ref name=20200323cnn>{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |first2=Bukola |last2=Adebayo | name-list-format = vanc |title=Nigeria records chloroquine poisoning after Trump endorses it for coronavirus treatment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/23/africa/chloroquine-trump-nigeria-intl/index.html|access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> A married couple in their 60s living in the [[state of Arizona]] ingested a fish tank cleaner product containing chloroquine phosphate; the man died while the woman survived in critical condition. The woman stated that they intended to self-medicate against the coronavirus after hearing Trump tout the potential benefits of chloroquine during a public briefing.<ref name=nbcnews1167166>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Erika |last2=Hillyard |first2=Vaughn | name-list-format = vanc |title=Man dies after ingesting chloroquine in an attempt to prevent coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/man-dies-after-ingesting-chloroquine-attempt-prevent-coronavirus-n1167166 |access-date=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200323buzzfeednews>{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Brianna |title=A Man Died After Self-Medicating with a Drug Trump Promoted As A Potential Treatment for the Coronavirus |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/briannasacks/man-died-chloroquine-phosphate-coronavirus |access-date=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Trump addressed a shortage of [[ventilator]] supply in the United States, claiming that carmaker companies [[General Motors]] (GM) and [[Ford]] \"are making them right now\" when the companies were not producing ventilators at the time. The [[Associated Press]] estimated it would take at least several months for the carmaker companies to change their factories' production abilities.<ref name=20200323apnews>{{cite news |last1=Krisher |first1=Tom |last2=Yen |first2=Hope | name-list-format = vanc |title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump hype on auto industry and ventilators |url=https://apnews.com/17868870ddfc526c6c7f454d651b6d7f |access-date=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> However, Trump ordered General Motors to produce ventilators under the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 27 and it was announced on April 8 that GM would produce 30,000 ventilators for the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] for $489.4&nbsp;million by the end of August, with production to start the week of April 12 and the first 6,132 ventilators being delivered by June 1. It was the first Defense Production Act contract for ventilators and GM confirmed it was not profiting from it.<ref name=20200408cnbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/gm-to-build-30000-ventilators-for-us-for-489point4-million.html|publisher=CNBC|title=GM to build 30,000 ventilators for national stockpile for ,89.4&nbsp;million|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Ford partnered with [[General Electric]] and converted its auto plant in [[Rawsonville, Michigan]] to ventilator production in early April and promised to deliver 50,000 by July 4, scaling up production to 7,000\u20137,200 a week.<ref name=20200330clickondetroit>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/30/ford-partners-with-ge-to-produce-50000-ventilators-in-100-days-amid-michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak/|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020|title=Ford partners with GE to produce 50,000 ventilators in 100 days amid Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Click On Detroit}}</ref><ref name=20200406cbsnews>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ford-rawsonville-plant-michigan-ventilator-factory/|publisher=CBS|title=Ford converts Michigan auto plant into ventilator factory, promising 50,000 devices by July 4|date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilian===\n\n[[File:Jair Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|Brazilian president [[Jair Bolsonaro]] repeatedly attempted to downplay the pandemic and even tried to force Brazilian states to revoke social isolation measures]]\nWhen the outbreak began in Brazil, many Brazilian states, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], which is the hotspot of the outbreak in Brazil, imposed harsh social isolation measures that included the shutdown of schools and non-essential business. Fearing an economic crash caused by those measures and the collapse of popular approval, the Brazilian Government, led by far-right president [[Jair Bolsonaro]], started to promote denialism of COVID-19's lethality, downplaying the disease by claiming that it was just a \"little Flu\" and accusing the media of promoting panic and hysteria.<ref name=bolsonaro />\n\nBolsonaro openly attempted to force sub-national governments (both states and municipalities) into revoking the social isolation measures by launching a campaign called \"o Brasil n\u00e3o pode parar\" (Brazil Can't stop), which received massive backlash from both the media and the public and was blocked by a court order.<ref name=bbc52080830>{{cite news|last=Watson |first=Katy | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52080830 |title=Coronavirus: Brazil's Bolsonaro in denial and out on a limb |work=BBC News |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=aljazeera2003301816>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Cowie  | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/indepth/features/deny-defy-bolsonaro-approach-coronavirus-brazil-200330181645501.html&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQyM8BCEAwBQ&usg=AOvVaw2_LFMc5Zd8yIztZChUZKyg&ampcf=1 |title=Deny and defy: Bolsonaro's approach to the coronavirus in Brazil |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome analysts have noted that Bolsonaro's positions mimic the early positions of U.S. president [[Donald Trump]], who also tried to downplay the pandemic before adopting harsher measures.<ref name=vox21195469>{{cite web|first=Alex |last=Ward | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/30/21195469/coronavirus-usa-china-brazil-mexico-spain-italy-iran&ved=0ahUKEwiU3qnRhcboAhUXIbkGHVtIBuQQxfQBCDYwAw&usg=AOvVaw0DiuDCpjq5DJvxsE_0khld |title=Coronavirus: How Trump and other world leaders who denied the threat endangered us |date=March 30, 2020 |publisher=Vox |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chinese===\n====Mishandling of crisis====\n[[File:Xi jinping and Li keqiang.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] general secretary [[Xi Jinping]] (left) and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] Premier [[Li Keqiang]]]]\n[[Whistleblower|Whistleblowing]] from various Chinese doctors, including [[Li Wenliang]] publishing data from [[Ai Fen]] on December 30, 2019, revealed that Wuhan hospital authorities were already aware that the virus was a SARS-like coronavirus and patients were already placed under quarantine.<ref>{{Citation|title=Wuhan doctor who was punished for trying to warn of coronavirus succumbs to the disease|date=February 6, 2020|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304083225/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/02/06/wuhan-doctor-punished-trying-warn-coronavirus-dies-infection/|archive-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Wuhan Health Commission still insisted that the illness spreading in Wuhan at the time was not SARS on January 5, 2020.<ref name=20200105theguardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|title=Mystery illness in Chinese city not Sars, say authorities|website=The Guardian|date=January 5, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109170148/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/05/mystery-illness-to-strike-chinese-city-is-not-sars-say-authorities-wuhan|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, the Chinese [[National Health Commission]] said that they had no \"clear evidence\" of human-to-human transmissions.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|title=Paper on human transmission of coronavirus sets off social media storm in China|date=January 31, 2020|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205122018/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3048460/paper-human-transmission-coronavirus-sets-social-media-storm|archive-date=February 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 20, the Chinese National Health Commission announced that human-to-human transmission of the coronavirus had already occurred.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kuo |first1=Lily |title=China confirms human-to-human transmission of coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/20/coronavirus-spreads-to-beijing-as-china-confirms-new-cases |access-date=19 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> Later research published on January 29, 2020 indicated that among officially confirmed cases, human-to-human transmission may have started in December of the previous year, and the delay of disclosure on the results until then, rather than earlier in January, was met with criticism towards health authorities.<ref name=\"SCMPH2H\" /> [[Wang Guangfa]], one of the health officials, said that \"There was uncertainty regarding the human-to-human transmission\",<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|title=\u536b\u5065\u59d4\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u6210\u5458\u738b\u5e7f\u53d1\u56de\u5e94\"\u53ef\u9632\u53ef\u63a7\"\uff1a\u5e76\u65e0\u4e0d\u59a5 \u5916\u754c\u5b58\u5728\u8bef\u89e3_\u817e\u8baf\u65b0\u95fb|website=new.qq.com|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201074528/https://new.qq.com/omn/20200201/20200201A03EDU00.html|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but he was infected by a patient within 10 days of making the statement.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=creaders2181398>{{cite web|url=http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|title=\u4e0a\u592e\u89c6\u79f0\u75ab\u60c5\u53ef\u63a7 \u4e2d\u5171\u4e13\u5bb6\u81ea\u5df1\u4e2d\u62db\u88ab\u9694\u79bb \u2013 \u4e07\u7ef4\u8bfb\u8005\u7f51|website=news.creaders.net|access-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302172357/http://news.creaders.net/china/2020/01/21/2181398.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, the ''Daily Beast'' reported the editor of state-owned People's Daily tweeted an image of a [[Modular building|modular container building]] used for marketing purposes by Henan K-Home Steel Structure Co., Ltd. and not of the actual hospital. The tweet stated that the 1st building of the [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] had been completed in 16 hours. Some claim this post is part of the Chinese government's misinformation campaign to hype certain aspects of the government's response.<ref name=20200127thedailybeast>{{cite news |title=The Chinese Government Is Spreading Coronavirus Disinformation |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/coronavirus-disinformation-being-spread-by-chinese-government-to-convince-foreigners-its-doing-a-good-job |work=The Daily Beast |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\nThe tweet was later removed and replaced with a video of the modular container buildings being assembled at [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] again stating the first building had been completed in 16 hours.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=zlj517 |number=1221828307144134656 |date=March 22, 2020 |title=Lijian Zhao}}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2020, China's [[paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Party general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] published an article which claimed he had been aware of the epidemic since January 7, 2020 and issued an order to contain the spread of the disease during a meeting on that day. However, a record of that same meeting released beforehand shows that there was zero mention of the epidemic throughout.<ref name=yahoo00163380>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|website=Yahoo! Japan News|date=February 16, 2020|title=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u300c1\u67087\u65e5\u306b\u611f\u67d3\u5bfe\u7b56\u6307\u793a\u300d\u306f\u865a\u507d\u304b|access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216131334/https://news.yahoo.co.jp/byline/endohomare/20200216-00163380/|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live|quote=According to the issue of Chinese Communist Party Central Magazine \"[[Qiushi]]\" printed on February 15, Xi Jinping wrote, in the February 3rd meeting he claimed he had already warned about the novel coronavirus pneumonia on the January 7th meeting. However, there are no record of such in neither the February 3 meeting minute nor the January 7 meeting minute. Which indicate this is a retrospectively made excuse and Xi Jinping have made a lie.}}</ref><ref name=20200217cnn>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Did Xi Jinping know about the coronavirus outbreak earlier than first suggested?|date=February 17, 2020|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=February 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219052546/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/asia/china-coronavirus-xi-jinping-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Origin of virus====\n\nIn response to the outbreak Chinese government officials launched a coordinated [[disinformation]] campaign seeking to spread doubt about the origin of the coronavirus and its outbreak.<ref name=RoginPost>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|title=China's coronavirus propaganda campaign is putting lives at risk|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 18, 2020|author-link=Josh Rogin|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319145226/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/18/chinas-coronavirus-propaganda-campaign-is-putting-lives-risk/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat>{{cite news|first1=Ben|last1=Westcott|first2=Steven|last2=Jiang | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 13, 2020|title=Chinese diplomat promotes conspiracy theory that US military brought coronavirus to Wuhan|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182148/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/13/asia/china-coronavirus-us-lijian-zhao-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A review of Chinese state media and social media posts in early March 2020, conducted by the ''Washington Post'', found that anti-American conspiracy theories circulating among Chinese users \"gained steam through a mix of unexplained official statements magnified by social media, censorship and doubts stoked by state media and government officials.\"<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Conspiracy theorists blame U.S. for coronavirus. China is happy to encourage them.|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=March 5, 2020|first=Gerry|last=Shih| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318050859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/conspiracy-theorists-blame-the-us-for-coronavirus-china-is-happy-to-encourage-them/2020/03/05/50875458-5dc8-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> U.S. Department of State officials,<ref name=AFPDangerous>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|title=US summons Chinese ambassador over 'dangerous and ridiculous' coronavirus conspiracy theory|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=March 16, 2020|first=Shaun|last=Tandon| name-list-format = vanc |access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125651/https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/03/16/us-summons-chinese-ambassador-dangerous-ridiculous-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory/|archive-date=March 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as University of Chicago political science professor [[Dali Yang]], an authority on Chinese politics, have stated that the  \"Chinese campaign\" appears intended to deflect attention away from the Chinese government's mishandling of the crisis.<ref name=ShihChinaEncourage/>\n\nAt a press conference on March 12, 2020, two spokesmen for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs ([[Zhao Lijian]] and [[Geng Shuang]]) promoted the conspiracy theory that the coronavirus had been \"bio-engineered\" by Western powers; and suggested that the U.S. government, specifically the U.S. Army, had spread the virus.<ref name=\"Taiwan News March 2020\" /><ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> No evidence supports these claims.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/><ref name=20200318cnn>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Trump and Beijing agree on the coronavirus crisis: It's someone else's fault|publisher=CNN|first=James|last=Griffiths| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318173526/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/17/asia/trump-chinese-virus-tweet-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Zhao also pushed these conspiracy theories on Twitter, which is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in mainland China]] but is used as a [[public diplomacy]] tool by Chinese officials, who use the platform to promote the Chinese government and defend it against criticism.<ref name=CNNChineseDiplomat/> China's ambassador to South Africa also amplified these claims on Twitter.<ref name=RoginPost/><ref name=20200328voanews>{{Cite news|last=Yuwen|first=Cheng| name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/us-pushes-back-against-russian-chinese-iranian-coronavirus-disinformation|title=US Pushes Back Against Russian, Chinese, Iranian Coronavirus Disinformation|date=March 28, 2020|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=Zhan|first2=Qiao}}</ref> Some Chinese state media had propagated the speculation that the virus may have spread in Italy before the Wuhan outbreak, after Italian doctor Giuseppe Remuzzi mentioned reports of strange pneumonia cases in November and December, he later said his words were twisted.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Italian doctor is now key to China's efforts to sow confusion over the coronavirus's origins |url=https://qz.com/1823417/italy-now-key-to-china-coronavirus-origin-propaganda-efforts/ |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=Quartz}}</ref><ref name=scmp3076792>{{cite news |last1=Ho |first1=Matt |title=Italian professor repeats warning coronavirus may have spread outside China last year |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3076792/italian-professor-repeats-warning-coronavirus-may-have-spread |access-date=March 25, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> In addition, articles from [[CounterPunch|''Counterpunch'']],<ref name=20200320counterpunch>{{Cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/20/fighting-covid-19-in-cuba-china-and-the-united-states/|title=Fighting COVID 19 in Cuba, China and the United States|date=March 20, 2020|website=CounterPunch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Asia Times]]'',<ref name=20200317asiatimes>{{Cite web|url=https://asiatimes.com/2020/03/china-locked-in-hybrid-war-with-us/|title=China locked in hybrid war with US|last=Escobar|first=Pepe| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 17, 2020|website=Asia Times Online|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> as well as the Chinese scientist [[Zhong Nanshan]] have brought up speculations that the virus may not have originated in China.<ref name=scmp3077442>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3077442/coronavirus-pathogen-could-have-been-spreading-humans-decades|title=Coronavirus 'may have been quietly spreading long before pandemic'|date=March 29, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn \"intentional disinformation campaign\" by China was discussed among the [[Group of Seven]] (G7),<ref name=20200325reuters>{{cite news |first1=Arshad |last1=Mohammed |first2=David |last2=Brunnstrom | name-list-format = vanc |title=Pompeo says G7 discussed China's coronavirus 'disinformation' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-heath-coronavirus-pompeo-china/pompeo-says-g7-discussed-chinas-coronavirus-disinformation-idUSKBN21C2N9 |agency=Reuters |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> and the Chinese efforts were condemned by the U.S. Department of State,<ref name=RoginPost/> which criticized Chinese authorities for spreading \"dangerous and ridiculous\" conspiracy claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/> The U.S. summoned China's ambassador to the United States, [[Cui Tiankai]], to issue a \"stern representation\" over the Chinese government's claims.<ref name=AFPDangerous/>\n\n====Statistics on fatalities====\n\nOn March 27, 2020, doubts were raised about the accuracy of Chinese data relating to the official death toll of 2,535 in Wuhan as Chinese news outlet [[Caixin]] published photos of a truck unloading 2,500 boxed [[funeral urn]]s arriving from Hankou [[funeral home]] and a further 3,500 boxed funeral urns inside Jingya Hall. People collecting ashes faced large wait times because of poor communication, a lack of enough staff and the quantity of ashes that had to be searched to locate the correct box. It is alleged that this shows that many people who have died with COVID-19 symptoms but were not tested and those who have died of other health complications due to an overloaded medical system have been excluded from any official death counts.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/stacks-of-urns-in-wuhan-prompt-new-questions-of-virus-s-toll | title=Stacks of Urns in Wuhan Prompt New Questions of Virus's Toll | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sharon | last1=Chen | first2=Dandan | last2=Li | first3=Claire| last3=Che | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref name=20200327telegraph>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/27/doubts-surface-chinese-virus-death-toll-thousands-urns-spotted/ | title=Doubts surface over Chinese virus death toll after thousands of urns spotted in Wuhan | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 28, 2020 | first1=Sophia | last1=Yan | first2=Nicola| last2=Smith | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> It is unclear how many funeral urns have any relation to COVID-19 victims. Official records show that in 2019 there were around 14,000 cremations in Wuhan per quarter,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mzj.wuhan.gov.cn/tjxx/387166.jhtml | title=Wuhan Civil Affairs Bureau \u2013 Quarterly Report of Civil Affairs Statistics for the 4th Quarter of 2019 | date=March 13, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref> with 13,856 cremations reported for the 4th Quarter in Wuhan.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Some articles<ref name=20200327japantimes>{{cite newspaper| url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/27/asia-pacific/science-health-asia-pacific/china-corona-toll/ | title=Stacks of urns in Wuhan prompt new questions about virus's toll | newspaper=[[Japan Times]] | date=March 27, 2020 | access-date=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> appearing in late March, however, initially reported an incorrect figure of 56,007 cremations in Wuhan for the 4th Quarter. This was based on a misunderstanding of how the Wuhan Civil Affairs data is reported, with quarterly figures representing the cumulative total of the year-to-date, rather than the quarter in question.<ref name=metabunk237642>{{cite web | url=https://www.metabunk.org/threads/wuhan-funeral-urns-as-an-indicator-of-death-rate.11175/#post-237642 | title=Wuhan Funeral Urns as an Indicator of Death Rate | date=March 31, 2020 | access-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Cuban===\nIn Cuba, Cuban president [[Miguel D\u00edaz Canel]] claimed on Twitter that Cuban [[Interferon alfa-2b]] was being used to treat and cure COVID-19 in China, linking to an article written by state-owned newspaper ''[[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]]''.{{ref|a}} The Chinese embassy in Cuba also made similar claims. Several Latin American news outlets<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvn-2.com/mundo/caribe/Medicamento-cubano-usado-China-coronavirus_0_5528447147.html|title=Medicamento cubano es usado en China contra el coronavirus|date=March 8, 2020|website=TVN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico-digital.com/2020/03/19/solicitan-a-la-presidente-que-considere-ingreso-de-medicina-cubana/|title=Solicitan a la presidente que considere ingreso de medicina cubana|work=El Peri\u00f3dico|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> relayed the story, which was also relayed on social media, and the claims were eventually translated to Portuguese and French.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://factual.afp.com/el-antiviral-cubano-interferon-alfa-2b-se-usa-en-china-para-tratar-enfermos-del-nuevo-coronavirus|title=El antiviral cubano Interfer\u00f3n Alfa 2B se usa en China para tratar a enfermos del nuevo coronavirus, pero no es ni una vacuna ni una cura|date=March 18, 2020|website=AFP Factual}}</ref> In reality, the interferon was made by a Chinese company, in China, using Cuban technology, and it was under clinical trials in China as a potential cure, but it was not actively being used as such, as the claims suggested.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Iranian===\n[[File:Ali Khamenei in 2020 Friday Prayer 06.jpg|thumb|Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] has suggested the U.S. government is responsible for the spread of coronavirus.]]\nIran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] said that the U.S. created \"a special version\" of the virus that is \"specifically built for Iran using the genetic data of Iranians which they have obtained through different means\".<ref name=\"independent-corona\"/><ref name=france2420200322/>\n\n===Mexican===\nMexico's federal government has been slow to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic as of late March 2020, with a great deal of criticism.<ref name=\"poor-coronavirus\">{{cite news |title=Mexican governor prompts outrage with claim poor are immune to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/mexican-governor-miguel-barbosa-prompts-outrage-with-claim-poor-are-immune-to-covid-19 |work=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] has continued to hold rallies, be tactile with crowds, and downplay the threat of coronavirus to Mexicans' health and to the Mexican economy.<ref name=\"obrador=coronavirus\"/><ref name=20200402slate>{{cite news |title=AMLO Goes off the Rails |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/coronavirus-amlo-mexico-president.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Russian===\nThe European Union watchdog group [[EUvsDisinfo]] reported that Russia was pushing what they believe was false information related to the [[SARS-CoV-2]] pandemic through \"pro-Kremlin outlets\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://euvsdisinfo.eu/the-kremlin-and-disinformation-about-coronavirus/|title=The Kremlin And Disinformation about Coronavirus|website=EUvsDisinfo|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Russian presidential spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] denounced the findings.<ref>{{cite web |title='Russophobic': Kremlin Denies Evidence of Russian COVID-19 Disinformation Campaign |url=https://www.polygraph.info/a/kremlin-blames-russophobia-for-report-on-russian-coronavirus-disinfo/30498024.html |website=polygraph.info |access-date=March 31, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Turkmen ===\n[[Reporters Without Borders]] reported that the [[government of Turkmenistan]] had banned the word \"coronavirus\" and that people could be arrested for wearing masks or discussing the pandemic.<ref name=\"Banned Use Of The Word\">{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |access-date=April 1, 2020 |publisher=NPR  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401090543/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=npr824611607>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824611607/turkmenistan-has-banned-use-of-the-word-coronavirus |title=Turkmenistan Has Banned Use of the Word 'Coronavirus' : Coronavirus Live Updates |publisher=NPR |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The organization later corrected their report, clarifying that the word itself was not banned, but maintained that it had been removed from informational brochures and that the government was restricting information about the virus and providing \"very one-sided information\".<ref name=20200331rsf>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/coronavirus-limits-turkmenistan|title=Coronavirus off limits in Turkmenistan &#124; Reports Without Borders|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to ''Chronicles of Turkmenistan'', state media did not begin reporting on the measures that had been taken until March 25.<ref name=20200402nytimes>{{cite news |last1=Kramer |first1=Andrew E. |title='The Fields Heal Everyone': Post-Soviet Leaders' Coronavirus Denial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/world/asia/coronavirus-denial-post-soviet.html |access-date=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The BBC quoted an anonymous Turkmen citizen who stated that citizens may get into trouble for suggesting that the coronavirus is already on Turkmenistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-52186521|title=Why has this country reported no virus cases?|first=Abdujalil|last=Abdurasulov| name-list-format = vanc |date=April 7, 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> The BBC article also states that the Turkmen government is working to control a possible outbreak.\n\n==Scams==\n\nThe UN WHO has warned of criminal scams involving perpetrators who misrepresent themselves as representatives of the WHO seeking personal information from victims via email or phone.<ref name=un1058381>{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |title=UN health agency warns against coronavirus COVID-19 criminal scams |publisher=United Nations |date=February 29, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308013146/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/02/1058381 |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] has warned consumers not to click on links in suspicious emails or give out personal information in emails, text messages or phone calls claiming to be representatives from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams |title=COVID-19 Consumer Warnings and Safety Tips |publisher=Federal Communications Commission |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Many financial companies, like [[Wells Fargo]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/jump/enterprise/coronavirus-response |title=COVID-19: We're here for you - Wells Fargo |publisher=Wells Fargo |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[LoanDepot]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://start.loandepot.com/assets/int-email/disaster/COVID19ServicingCommunicationv6.0.pdf |title=COVID-19 Information |publisher=LoanDepot |access-date=April 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> have posted similar warnings on their websites.\n\nCybersecurity firm [[Check Point]] stated there has been a large increase in [[phishing]] attacks to lure victims into unwittingly installing a computer virus under the guise of coronavirus-themed emails containing attachments. Cyber-criminals use deceptive domains such as \"cdc-gov.org\" instead of the correct \"cdc.gov\", or even [[domain spoofing|spoof the original domain]] so it resembles specific websites. Over 4,000 coronavirus-related domains have been registered.<ref name=vox21164745>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |title=Coronavirus email scams are trying to cash in on your fear |work=vox.com |first=Sara |last=Morrison| name-list-format = vanc  |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306153955/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/5/21164745/coronavirus-phishing-email-scams |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPolice in New Jersey, United States reported incidents of criminals knocking on people's doors and claiming to be from the CDC. They then attempt to sell products at inflated prices or otherwise scam victims under the guise of educating and protecting the public from the coronavirus.<ref name=yahoo171111975>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |title=Coronavirus: Sinister people are knocking on doors claiming to be part of official disease response, police warn |work=The Independent |via=[[Yahoo! News]] |first=Andrew |last=Griffin | name-list-format = vanc |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172735/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-sinister-people-knocking-doors-171111975.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLinks that purportedly direct to the [[Johns Hopkins University]] coronavirus map, but instead direct to a false site that spreads [[malware]] have been circulating on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hackers are using coronavirus concerns to trick you, cybersecurity pros warn |date=March 15, 2020 |first=Wallace |last=Witkowski | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[MarketWatch]] |url= https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120751/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/hackers-are-using-coronavirus-concerns-to-trick-you-cybersecurity-pros-warn-2020-03-12 |archive-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html|title=Hackers made their own coronavirus map to spread malware, feds warn |work=The Miami Herald |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021637/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article241171546.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n===Bat soup===\nSome media outlets, including ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and [[RT (TV network)|RT]], as well as individuals, disseminated a video showing a Chinese woman eating a bat, falsely suggesting that it was filmed in Wuhan and connecting it to the outbreak.<ref name=\"20200127foreignpolicy\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Palmer | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Wuhan Virus |date=January 27, 2020 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=February 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203090706/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-wuhan-virus/ |archive-date=February 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200130theguardianB /> However, the widely circulated video contains unrelated footage of a Chinese travel [[vlogger]], Wang Mengyun, eating bat soup in the island country of [[Palau]] in 2016.<ref name=20200127foreignpolicy /><ref name=\"20200130theguardianB\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |title=Bat soup, dodgy cures and 'diseasology': the spread of coronavirus misinformation |first=Josh |last=Taylor | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 30, 2020 |website=The Guardian |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208030512/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/31/bat-soup-dodgy-cures-and-diseasology-the-spread-of-coronavirus-bunkum |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"20200129news\">{{cite web |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |title=Chinese influencer Wang Mengyun, aka 'Bat soup girl' breaks silence |first=Marnie |last=O'Neill | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 29, 2020 |website=news.au |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208145637/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/food/food-warnings/chinese-influencer-wang-mengyun-aka-bat-soup-girl-breaks-silence/news-story/63ef0cec5b6d448d1843e2e1bcadb14d |archive-date=February 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"fx-bso\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |title=Coronavirus: Outrage over Chinese blogger eating 'bat soup' sparks apology |last=Gaynor |first=Gerren Keith | name-list-format = vanc |date=January 28, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204201417/https://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/coronavirus-chinese-blogger-eats-bat-soup |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wang posted an apology on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]],<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> in which she said that she had received abuse and threats,<ref name=20200129news /> and that she had only wanted to showcase [[Palauan cuisine]].<ref name=20200129news /><ref name=fx-bso /> The spread of misinformation about bat consumption has been characterized by [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobic and racist sentiment]] toward Asians.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=20200301washingtonpost>{{cite web |last1=Romm |first1=Tony |title=Millions of tweets peddled conspiracy theories about coronavirus in other countries, an unpublished U.S. report says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309040454/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/02/29/twitter-coronavirus-misinformation-state-department/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=20200203latimes>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Suhauna |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |website=Los Angeles Times |date=February 3, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205072802/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast, scientists suggest that the virus originated in bats and migrated into an intermediary host animal before infecting people.<ref name=al-watsm/><ref name=bru-14bc>{{cite web|first1=Hilary|last1=Brueck|access-date=March 7, 2020|title=14 bogus claims about the coronavirus, including a fake coconut-oil cure and a false link to imported packages|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2|website=Business Insider|date=February 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206102658/https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-myths-red-meat-bleach-antibiotics-and-sesame-oil-2020-2/|archive-date=February 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===''Simpsons'' prediction===\nClaims that ''[[The Simpsons]]'' had predicted the coronavirus pandemic in 1993, accompanied by a doctored screenshot from the show (where the text \"Corona Virus\" was layered over the original text \"Apocalypse Meow\", without blocking it from view), were later found out to be false, with the claim being widely spread on social media.<ref name=20200303afp>{{cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/image-simpsons-was-digitally-altered-make-it-look-it-predicted-novel-coronavirus|title=An image from The Simpsons was digitally altered to make it look like it predicted the novel coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|website=AFP Fact Check}}</ref><ref name=chicagotribune20200229>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-ent-simpsons-predicts-coronavirus-20200229-q6ekedk665bzvlrgdcvdgm6eqy-story.html|title=Did 'The Simpsons' really predict the coronavirus outbreak? Twitter thinks so|first=Christi|last=Carras| name-list-format = vanc |website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===Corona beer misassociation===\nA poll was released showing that 38% of American beer-drinkers have refused to drink [[Corona (beer)|Corona-brand beer]].<ref name=prnewswire301012225>{{cite press release|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/5wpr-survey-reveals-38-of-beer-drinking-americans-wouldnt-buy-corona-now-301012225.html?mod=article_inline|title=5WPR Survey Reveals 38% of Beer-Drinking Americans Wouldn't Buy Corona Now|publisher=5W Public Relations|date=February 27, 2020|agency=PR Newswire}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|first=Kate|last=Gibson| name-list-format = vanc |date=March 1, 2020|title=Survey finds 38% of beer-drinking Americans say they won't order a Corona|publisher=CBS News|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306171055/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cornavirus-corona-beer-they-have-nothing-to-do-with-each-other/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This statistic is not considered a reliable indication of an American belief that drinking the beer causes the virus, even though assumptions have been made along this line in the media and among the public.<ref name=bar-astw/><ref name=theatlantic607240>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|title=What the Dubious Corona Poll Reveals|last=Mounk|first=Yascha| name-list-format = vanc |date=February 28, 2020|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312073643/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/about-corona-poll/607240/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There is no direct link between the virus and the beer brand,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=bar-astw>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|title=Americans Say They Won't Drink Corona Beer Because of Coronavirus. Sales Are Up 5% Anyway.|last=Root|first=Al| name-list-format = vanc |website=Barron's|access-date=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307220916/https://www.barrons.com/articles/americans-say-they-wont-drink-corona-because-of-coronavirus-but-sales-are-up-5-51583610529|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> but rather, both names draw upon the Latin ''corona'', meaning 'crown'.\n\n===Hospital conditions===\nU.S. hospitals have been silencing doctors and other staff, threatening to fire them if they publicly speak about inadequacies in working-conditions and lack of equipment.<ref name=bl-sil>{{cite web |last1= Carville |first1= Olivia |last2= Court |first2= Emma |last3= Brown |first3= Kristen V | name-list-format = vanc |title= Hospitals Tell Doctors They'll Be Fired If They Speak Out About Lack of Gear |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/hospitals-tell-doctors-they-ll-be-fired-if-they-talk-to-press |website= Bloomberg | date= March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=20200401businessinsider>{{cite web |last1= Collman |first1= Ashley |title= Hospitals are threatening to fire health workers who speak to the media during the coronavirus outbreak |url= https://www.businessinsider.com/coroanvirus-hospital-health-workers-speaking-to-media-threatened-lose-job-2020-4 |website= Business Insider |date= April 1, 2020}}</ref> The Washington State Nurses Association states that there is an effort by hospitals to preserve their image.<ref name=bl-sil/>\n\nSome conservative figures{{Who|date=April 2020}} in the United States downplayed the scale of the pandemic, stating that it has been exaggerated{{by whom|date=April 2020}} as part of an effort to hurt President Trump. Some people pointed to empty hospital parking lots as evidence that the virus has been exaggerated. Despite the empty parking lots, many hospitals in New York City and other places experienced thousands of COVID-19-related hospitalizations.<ref name=20200401nationalobserver>\n{{cite web\n|url= https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/04/01/analysis/right-wing-conspiracy-theories-go-mainstream-amid-mounting-covid-19-death-toll\n|title= Right-wing conspiracy theories go mainstream amid mounting COVID-19 death toll|first= Caroline|last= Orr| name-list-format = vanc \n|date= April 1, 2020|website= National Observer|access-date= April 2, 2020\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Return of wildlife===\nDuring the pandemic, many false and misleading images or news reports about the environmental impact of the coronavirus pandemic were shared by [[clickbait]] journalism sources and social media.<ref name=\"natgeo\" />\n\nA viral post that originated on [[Weibo (company)|Weibo]] and spread on Twitter claimed that a pack of elephants descended on a village under quarantine in China's [[Yunnan]], got drunk on corn wine, and passed out in a tea garden.<ref name=20200319ktvb>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/verify/verify-did-elephants-get-drunk-on-corn-wine-while-humans-were-social-distancing/277-0c48ef63-33ec-478f-be6a-4ebdeb4b0299 |title=Verify: Did elephants get drunk on corn wine while humans were social distancing? |last=Spry Jr |first=Terry | name-list-format = vanc  |publisher=KTVB |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The state-owned {{citation needed span|date=April 2020|[[China News Service]]|reason=National Geographic links to Xinhua, not China News Service}} debunked the claim that the elephants got drunk on corn wine and noted that wild elephants were a common sight in the village; the image attached to the post was originally taken at the Asian Elephant Research Center in Yunnan in December 2019.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/ |title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life |author=Daly, Natasha |work=National Geographic |date=March 20, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing reports of reduced pollution levels in Italy as a result of lockdowns, images purporting to show swans and dolphins swimming in [[Venice]] canals went viral on social media. The image of the swans was revealed to have been taken in [[Burano]], where swans are common, while footage of the dolphins was filmed at a port in [[Sardinia]] hundreds of miles away.<ref name=\"natgeo\" /> The Venice mayor's office clarified that the reported water clarity in the canals was due to the lack of sediment being kicked up by boat traffic, not due to a lack of water pollution that was initially reported.<ref name=thehill488286>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown of India]], a video clip purporting to show the extremely rare [[Malabar large-spotted civet|Malabar civet]] (a [[critically endangered]], possibly [[Extinction|extinct]] species) walking the empty streets of [[Meppayur]] went viral on social media. Experts later identified the civet in the video as actually being the much more common [[small Indian civet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/spotted-malabar-civet-coronavirus/|title=Was a Rare Malabar Civet Spotted During COVID-19 Lockdown?|website=Snopes.com|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Another viral Indian video clip showed a pod of [[humpback whale]]s allegedly returning to the [[Arabian Sea]] offshore from [[Mumbai]] following the shutdown of shipping routes; however, this video was found to have actually been taken in 2019 in the [[Java Sea]].<ref name=20200405hindustantimes>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/fact-check-does-viral-video-show-whales-swimming-at-bombay-high-here-s-the-truth/story-zEOP8acFmCXrK39s4VGJaK.html|title=Fact Check: Does viral video show whales swimming at Bombay High? Here's the truth|date=April 5, 2020|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Lions freed on the streets===\nA social media joke suggesting that lions had been freed to keep people off the streets in Moscow was passed around as if it were true.<ref name=bbc52118949>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/stories-52118949/coronavirus-how-can-you-stop-the-spread-of-misinformation|title=Coronavirus: How can you stop an 'infodemic'?|website=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===UK\u00a320 banknote===\nA tweet started an internet meme that [[Bank of England]] [[Bank of England \u00a320 note|\u00a320 banknote]]s contained a picture of a 5G mast and the SARSCoV-2 virus.  Facebook and YouTube removed items pushing this story, and fact checking organisations established that the picture is of [[Margate Lighthouse]] and the \"virus\" is the staircase at the [[Tate Britain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/online/5g-coronavirus-20-note/|title=\u00a320 notes don't have a secret message about 5G and coronavirus|first=Grace|last=Rahman| name-list-format = vanc |website=Full Fact}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/banknotes/polymer-20-pound-note The new \u00a320 note] The Bank of England</ref><ref>[https://turnercontemporary.org/support-us/what-can-i-do-with-my-old-20-note/ New \u00a320 note to feature Margate's Turner Contemporary] Turner Contemporary</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[Buck passing]]\n* [[List of conspiracy theories]]\n* [[SARS conspiracy theory]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n: 1.{{note|a}}''Granma'' is owned by the ruling political party in Cuba, the Communist Party of Cuba.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters World Health Organization: Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters]\n* [https://www.politifact.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus] at [[Politifact]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Misinformation related to the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Communication of falsehoods]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in China]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fake news]]\n[[Category:Medical-related conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Misinformation]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistory]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Disinformation operations]]\n", "name_user": "JMonkey2006", "label": "safe", "comment": "Replaced some biased language", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misinformation_related_to_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "Bipin Chandra Pal", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian academic and politician}}\n{{about|the Indian nationalist leader|the Indian historian|Bipin Chandra}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Bipin Chandra Pal\n|image         = Bipin-Chandra-Pal.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1858|11|07|df=y}}\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1932|05|20|1858|11|07|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = Poil, [[Habiganj Sadar|Habiganj]], [[Sylhet region|Sylhet District]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]] \n|death_place   = Calcutta (now [[Kolkata]]), British India\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Calcutta]]\n|movement      = [[Indian Independence movement]]\n|party         = [[Indian National Congress]] \n|organization  = [[Brahmo Samaj]] \n|occupation    = Politician<br>Writer<br>[[Indian independence movement|Indian independence movement activist]]<br>Orator<br>Social reformer\n|signature     = Bipin Chandra Pal Signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Bipin Chandra Pal''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a8 \u099a\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09b0 \u09aa\u09be\u09b2}}, [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]]: {{font|\ua81b\ua824\ua819\ua824\ua818 \ua80c\ua818\ua806\ua816\ua806\ua81e \ua819\ua823\ua81f|font=Surma|size=18px}}, {{audio|Bipin chandra pal.ogg|pronunciation}}; 7 November 1858 \u2013 20 May 1932) was an [[Indian nationalist]],  writer, orator, social reformer and [[Indian independence movement|Indian independence movement activist]]. He was one third of the [[Lal Bal Pal]] triumvirate.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ashalatha |first1=A. |first2=Pradeep |last2=Koropath |first3=Saritha |last3=Nambarathil | title = Social Science: Standard VIII Part 1 | chapter = Chapter 6 \u2013 Indian National Movement | work = Government of Kerala \u2022 Department of Education | publisher = State Council of Educational Research and Training (SCERT) | year = 2009 | pages = 72 | chapter-url = https://www.itschool.gov.in/pdf/Std_VIII/Social%20Science/SS_VIII_Engpart1.pdf | accessdate = 13 October 2011}}</ref> Pal was one of the main architects of the [[Swadeshi movement]]. He stood against the [[Partition of Bengal (1905)|partition of Bengal]] by the colonial British government.\n\n==Early life and background==\nBipin Chandra Pal was born in the village of [[Habiganj Sadar Upazila#Administration|Poil]], [[Habiganj District|Habiganj]], [[Sylhet region|Sylhet District]], [[Bengal Presidency]] of British India, in a [[Hindu]] [[Bengali Kayastha]] family.<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia Of Indian War Of Independence (1857\u20131947)|quote=Bipin Chandra Pal (1858\u20131932) a patriot, nationalist politician, renowned orator, journalist, and writer. Bipin Chandra Pal was born on 7 November 1858 in Sylhet in a wealthy Hindu Kayastha family|author=M.K. Singh|year=2009|page=130|publisher= Anmol Publications}}</ref> His father was Ramchandra Pal, a [[Farsi|Persian]] scholar, and small landowner. He studied and taught at the Church Mission Society College (now the [[St. Paul's Cathedral Mission College]]), an affiliated college of the [[University of Calcutta]].<ref name=Alumni>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stpaulscmcollege.org/alumni-association.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925080918/http://www.stpaulscmcollege.org/alumni-association.html|url-status=dead|title=List of distinguished alumni|archivedate=25 September 2012|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> His son was [[Niranjan Pal]], one of the founders of [[Bombay Talkies]]. His son-in-law was the [[Indian Civil Service|ICS]] officer, [[S. K. Dey]], who later became a union minister. His another son-in-law was freedom fighter [[Ullaskar Dutta]] who married Lila Dutta.\n\nAs revolutionary as he was in politics, Pal was the same in his private life as well. After his first wife died, he married a widow and joined the [[Brahmo Samaj]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/features/bipin-chandra-pal-as-much-a-revolutionary-in-politics-as-in-his-private-life/146215/|title=Bipin Chandra Pal: As much a revolutionary in politics, as in his private life|date=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112004218/https://theprint.in/features/bipin-chandra-pal-as-much-a-revolutionary-in-politics-as-in-his-private-life/146215/|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n[[File:Bipin Chandra Pal 1958 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Pal featured on a 1958 [[Indian stamp]].]]\nPal is known as the ''Father of Revolutionary Thoughts'' in India and was one of the freedom fighters of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=69M3Bqe-WRc|title=Bipin Chandra Pal|date=19 May 2014|work=youtube}}</ref> Pal became a major leader of the Indian National Congress. At the Madras session of Indian National Congress held in 1887, Bipin Chandra Pal made a strong plea for repeal of the Arms Act which was discriminatory in nature. Along with [[Lala Lajpat Rai]] and [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]] he belonged to the [[Lal Bal Pal|Lal, Bal, Pal]] trio that was associated with revolutionary activity. [[Aurobindo Ghosh]] and Pal were recognised as the chief exponents of a new national movement revolving around the ideals of [[Purna Swaraj]], [[Swadeshi]], boycott and national education. His programme consisted of Swadeshi, boycott and national education. He preached and encouraged the use of Swadeshi and the boycott of foreign goods to eradicate poverty and unemployment. He wanted to remove social evils from the form and arouse the feelings of nationalism through national criticism. He had no faith in mild protests in the form of non-cooperation with the British colonialists. On that one issue, the assertive nationalist leader had nothing common with [[Mahatma Gandhi]]. During the last six years of his life, he parted company with the Congress and led a secluded life. Sri Aurobindo referred to him as one of ''mightiest prophets of nationalism''.Bipin Chandra Pal made his efforts to remove social and economic ills. He opposed caste system and advocated widow  remarriage. He advocated 48 hours of work week and demanded for the hike in wages of workers. He expressed his disdain for Gandhi's ways, which he criticised for being rooted in \u201cmagic\u201d instead of \u201clogic\u201d.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAs a journalist, Pal worked for ''Bengal Public Opinion'', [[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|''The Tribune'']] and ''New India'', where he propagated his brand of nationalism.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://studentsmorningstar.com/Books.aspx|title=Total History & Civics|last=Sequeira|first=Dolly|publisher=Morning Star (A unit of MSB Publishers Pvt. Ltd)|year=2018|isbn=|location=India|pages=53}}</ref> He wrote several articles warning India of the changes happening in China and other geopolitical situations. In one of his writings, describing where the future danger for India will come from, Pal wrote under the title \"Our Real Danger\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Uneasy neighbours : India and China after 50 years of the war|last=Madhav|first=Ram|publisher=New Delhi: Har-Anand Publications|year=2014|isbn=978-81-241-1788-0|location=|pages=10, 11, 12}}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\">\nLal Bal Pal.jpg|[[Lala Lajpat Rai]] of [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]] of [[Maharashtra]], and Bipin Chandra Pal (right) of [[Bengal]], the triumvirate were popularly known as [[Lal Bal Pal]], changed the political discourse of the [[Indian independence movement]].\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|Bipin Chandra Pal}}\n* {{Citation\n | surname1 = Owen\n | given1 = N\n | year = 2007\n | title = The British Left and India\n | url =\n | publisher = Oxford University Press\n | isbn= 978-0-19-923301-4\n}}\n* {{cite book |editor-last1=Lenman |editor-first1=Bruce |editor-last2=Marsden |editor-first2=Hilary |date=2005 |title=Chambers Dictionary of World History |location=London |publisher=Chambers Harrap |isbn=978-0-550-10094-8 |via=[[Credo Reference]]}}\n*{{Citation|last=Pal|first=Bipin Chandra|title=Nationality and Empire|url=|volume=|pages=|year=1916|publisher=Thacker, Spink & Co / Low Price Publications|isbn=81-7536-274-X|given1=}}\n\n{{India House}}\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n{{Bengal Renaissance}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pal, Bipin Chandra}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Habiganj District]]\n[[Category:Bengali people]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Bengal]]\n[[Category:India House]]\n[[Category:Brahmos]]\n[[Category:St. Paul's Cathedral Mission College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of Central Legislative Assembly of India]]\n[[Category:Revolutionaries from West Bengal]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian academic and politician}}\n{{about|the Indian nationalist leader|the Indian historian|Bipin Chandra}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Bipin Chandra Pal\n|image         = Bipin-Chandra-Pal.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1858|11|07|df=y}}\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1932|05|20|1858|11|07|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = Poil, [[Habiganj Sadar|Habiganj]], [[Sylhet region|Sylhet District]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]] \n|death_place   = Calcutta (now [[Kolkata]]), British India\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Calcutta]]\n|movement      = [[Indian Independence movement]]\n|party         = [[Indian National Congress]] \n|organization  = [[Brahmo Samaj]] \n|occupation    = Politician<br>Writer<br>[[Indian independence movement|Indian independence movement activist]]<br>Orator<br>Social reformer\n|signature     = Bipin Chandra Pal Signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Bipin Chandra Pal''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a8 \u099a\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09b0 \u09aa\u09be\u09b2}}, [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]]: {{font|\ua81b\ua824\ua819\ua824\ua818 \ua80c\ua818\ua806\ua816\ua806\ua81e \ua819\ua823\ua81f|font=Surma|size=18px}}, {{audio|Bipin chandra pal.ogg|pronunciation}}; 7 November 1858 \u2013 20 May 1932) was an [[Indian nationalist]],  writer, orator, social reformer and [[Indian independence movement|Indian independence movement activist]]. He was one third of the [[Lal Bal Pal]] triumvirate.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ashalatha |first1=A. |first2=Pradeep |last2=Koropath |first3=Saritha |last3=Nambarathil | title = Social Science: Standard VIII Part 1 | chapter = Chapter 6 \u2013 Indian National Movement | work = Government of Kerala \u2022 Department of Education | publisher = State Council of Educational Research and Training (SCERT) | year = 2009 | pages = 72 | chapter-url = https://www.itschool.gov.in/pdf/Std_VIII/Social%20Science/SS_VIII_Engpart1.pdf | accessdate = 13 October 2011}}</ref> Pal was one of the main architects of the [[Swadeshi movement]]. He stood against the [[Partition of Bengal (1905)|partition of Bengal]] by the colonial British government.\n\n==Early life and background==\nBipin Chandra Pal was born in the village of [[Habiganj Sadar Upazila#Administration|Poil]], [[Habiganj District|Habiganj]], [[Sylhet region|Sylhet District]], [[Bengal Presidency]] of British India, in a [[Hindu]] [[Bengali Kayastha]] family.<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia Of Indian War Of Independence (1857\u20131947)|quote=Bipin Chandra Pal (1858\u20131932) a patriot, nationalist politician, renowned orator, journalist, and writer. Bipin Chandra Pal was born on 7 November 1858 in Sylhet in a wealthy Hindu Kayastha family|author=M.K. Singh|year=2009|page=130|publisher= Anmol Publications}}</ref> His [[Sylhetis|Sylheti]] father was Ramchandra Pal, a [[Farsi|Persian]] scholar, and small landowner. He studied and taught at the Church Mission Society College (now the [[St. Paul's Cathedral Mission College]]), an affiliated college of the [[University of Calcutta]].<ref name=Alumni>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stpaulscmcollege.org/alumni-association.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925080918/http://www.stpaulscmcollege.org/alumni-association.html|url-status=dead|title=List of distinguished alumni|archivedate=25 September 2012|accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> His son was [[Niranjan Pal]], one of the founders of [[Bombay Talkies]]. His son-in-law was the [[Indian Civil Service|ICS]] officer, [[S. K. Dey]], who later became a union minister. His another son-in-law was freedom fighter [[Ullaskar Dutta]] who married Lila Dutta.\n\nAs revolutionary as he was in politics, Pal was the same in his private life as well. After his first wife died, he married a widow and joined the [[Brahmo Samaj]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/features/bipin-chandra-pal-as-much-a-revolutionary-in-politics-as-in-his-private-life/146215/|title=Bipin Chandra Pal: As much a revolutionary in politics, as in his private life|date=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112004218/https://theprint.in/features/bipin-chandra-pal-as-much-a-revolutionary-in-politics-as-in-his-private-life/146215/|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n[[File:Bipin Chandra Pal 1958 stamp of India.jpg|thumb|Pal featured on a 1958 [[Indian stamp]].]]\nPal is known as the ''Father of Revolutionary Thoughts'' in India and was one of the freedom fighters of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=69M3Bqe-WRc|title=Bipin Chandra Pal|date=19 May 2014|work=youtube}}</ref> Pal became a major leader of the Indian National Congress. At the Madras session of Indian National Congress held in 1887, Bipin Chandra Pal made a strong plea for repeal of the Arms Act which was discriminatory in nature. Along with [[Lala Lajpat Rai]] and [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]] he belonged to the [[Lal Bal Pal|Lal, Bal, Pal]] trio that was associated with revolutionary activity. [[Aurobindo Ghosh]] and Pal were recognised as the chief exponents of a new national movement revolving around the ideals of [[Purna Swaraj]], [[Swadeshi]], boycott and national education. His programme consisted of Swadeshi, boycott and national education. He preached and encouraged the use of Swadeshi and the boycott of foreign goods to eradicate poverty and unemployment. He wanted to remove social evils from the form and arouse the feelings of nationalism through national criticism. He had no faith in mild protests in the form of non-cooperation with the British colonialists. On that one issue, the assertive nationalist leader had nothing common with [[Mahatma Gandhi]]. During the last six years of his life, he parted company with the Congress and led a secluded life. Sri Aurobindo referred to him as one of ''mightiest prophets of nationalism''.Bipin Chandra Pal made his efforts to remove social and economic ills. He opposed caste system and advocated widow  remarriage. He advocated 48 hours of work week and demanded for the hike in wages of workers. He expressed his disdain for Gandhi's ways, which he criticised for being rooted in \u201cmagic\u201d instead of \u201clogic\u201d.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAs a journalist, Pal worked for ''Bengal Public Opinion'', [[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|''The Tribune'']] and ''New India'', where he propagated his brand of nationalism.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://studentsmorningstar.com/Books.aspx|title=Total History & Civics|last=Sequeira|first=Dolly|publisher=Morning Star (A unit of MSB Publishers Pvt. Ltd)|year=2018|isbn=|location=India|pages=53}}</ref> He wrote several articles warning India of the changes happening in China and other geopolitical situations. In one of his writings, describing where the future danger for India will come from, Pal wrote under the title \"Our Real Danger\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Uneasy neighbours : India and China after 50 years of the war|last=Madhav|first=Ram|publisher=New Delhi: Har-Anand Publications|year=2014|isbn=978-81-241-1788-0|location=|pages=10, 11, 12}}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\">\nLal Bal Pal.jpg|[[Lala Lajpat Rai]] of [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]] of [[Maharashtra]], and Bipin Chandra Pal (right) of [[Bengal]], the triumvirate were popularly known as [[Lal Bal Pal]], changed the political discourse of the [[Indian independence movement]].\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|Bipin Chandra Pal}}\n* {{Citation\n | surname1 = Owen\n | given1 = N\n | year = 2007\n | title = The British Left and India\n | url =\n | publisher = Oxford University Press\n | isbn= 978-0-19-923301-4\n}}\n* {{cite book |editor-last1=Lenman |editor-first1=Bruce |editor-last2=Marsden |editor-first2=Hilary |date=2005 |title=Chambers Dictionary of World History |location=London |publisher=Chambers Harrap |isbn=978-0-550-10094-8 |via=[[Credo Reference]]}}\n*{{Citation|last=Pal|first=Bipin Chandra|title=Nationality and Empire|url=|volume=|pages=|year=1916|publisher=Thacker, Spink & Co / Low Price Publications|isbn=81-7536-274-X|given1=}}\n\n{{India House}}\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n{{Bengal Renaissance}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pal, Bipin Chandra}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Habiganj District]]\n[[Category:Bengali people]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Bengal]]\n[[Category:India House]]\n[[Category:Brahmos]]\n[[Category:St. Paul's Cathedral Mission College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of Central Legislative Assembly of India]]\n[[Category:Revolutionaries from West Bengal]]\n", "name_user": "223.225.32.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life and background:Removal of uncitated information.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bipin_Chandra_Pal"}
